window.__QUIZ_SUBJECT__=[{"id": "theory>Literature>2000>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLA  ROTIMI :   The Gods Are Not to be Blame    Comment on the significance of the prologue in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The prologue is the brief overview of the background events that portray the course of action in the entire play. In the prologue the major characters and  their characterization major to the audience. The characters include Odewale as {baby}; King Adetusa and Queen Ojuola {Odewale's parents}, Baba Funke; { the blind soothsayer}; Ogun Priest; Gbonka {the king's messenger} ; Aderopo etc.     The prologue is used to emphasize Baba Funke, the blind soothsayer presuppostion/prediction as regards Odewale's and how his survival will have disastrous effect on his parents  and the village as a whole. The prologue also made mention of the attack of the Ikolus on the people of kutuje and its consequental effects.      Subsequently, the prologue mentions the advent of the deadly plague into the land of Katuje eleven  years after the crowning of Odewale as the king of Kutuje after assisting  the people of Kutuje to suppress Ikulos.     The prologue also introduce dance, songs, mime, commentary on the play  in order to enrich the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLA  ROTIMI :   The Gods Are Not to be Blame    \"She died as she lived, royally\". Is the statement true of Queen Ojuola?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Queen Ojuola is queen/ wife to both king Adetusa and king Odewale in succession. Unknown to her and with the consent of the gods, she doubles as Odewale's mother and wife. She is a woman of admirable character, to an extent that even king Odewale beseech the gods to grant him some of the goodness of her heart.      She is a very supportive wife throughout the play. She tries to settle the issue between Odewale and Aderopo amicably. However, destiny takes its full course and she ends up marrying her own son and bearing him children.      Having realized the tragic turn out of events, she knows that the only way to get rid of the pain, shame and disgrace is to end  it all. Thus, she died as she lived royally.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "EFUSA T. SUTHERLAND : The Marriage of Anansewa    \"Oh father, there is cunning in your head   You are to be feared\" . To what extent is Anansewa's assessment of Ananse's character justified?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This statement is as a result of Anansewa's realization that her father has mapped out plans to sell her into marriage for his own benefit. Ananse displays a lot of cunning in his ambition. He makes his daughter some photograph and tours the country with them to seek the interest of four wealthy chiefs in his daughter.       Ananse makes Anansewa type a letter full of praises to each of the suitors to re-assure each chief of her availabilty. He plans an outdoor marriage ceremony for Anansewa in order to make her eligible for marriage. When he realizes that the four chiefs intend to come to perform head-drink ceremony on the same day, he persuades Anansewa to pretend to be dead. In order to execute this plan successfully,he tricks his mother and sister into a huried departure from his house.       His cunning ways pay off as he discovers that chief - Who - is - Chief is the best suitor for his daughter.  Anansewa follows all these schemings of her father closely and is dazzled by them, hence the statement that there is cunning in her father's head.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "EFUSA T. SUTHERLAND : The marriage of Anansewa    Discuss the events culminating in the funeral arrangements for Anansewa in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Due to being unable to  pay her school fees. Anansewa is sent out of school. Ananse her father devices a means to raise money to feed himself, improve his social status, pay Anansewa's fees and get a suitable husband for his daughter.       Ananse tours the country in search of suitors with his daughter's pictures. He follows up his tours by sending letters in appraisal of his daughter to the cheifs. He plans and executes the marriage ceremony of Anansewa as a way of making her eligible for marriage. However, when he discovers that the four suitors are all coming the same day, he plans to fake funeral which culminates in the funeral arrangements for Ananse in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "GEORGE BERNARD SHAW: Arms and the Man    Compare and contrast the characeters of Louka and Raina in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In comparison, Louka and Raina are pulchritudinous young women who are ambitious. While Louka looks forward to marrying someone above her who will elevate her from servant status,Raina dreams of a husband like Sergius who represents all that chivalry stands for;and who is upper class like her.       Louka is very confident like Raina.She does not have inferiority complex.She demonstrated her confidence when she calls Raina by her name for the first time ever. While Raina often acts her part of being of aristocratic birth and one that has inherited certain ideas of conduct which publicly frowns at insincerity and lying, Louka is never satisfied with her part as servant and combines jealousy, hate and wit to get what she wants.         In spite of all these, Louka can be seen as seen as a practical woman that is determined to break class barriers and acheive social acceptance and personal dignity in contrast to Raina who is conceited and idealistic but capable of adopting a less than idealistic stand on her love relationship with Bluntschdi.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "GEORGE BERNARD SHAW: Arms and the Man    Discuss the treatment of love in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The play examine love  from two perspectives. The idealistic and practical. The idealistic is represented by the Raina  relationship while the practical or the realistic is seen in both Raina-Bluntschli and Louka-Sergius relatinships. The ideal love as portrayed by Raina and Sergius is depicted as pretentions, hpocritical and materialistic.       At opening of the play, Raina is presented as an innocent and naive girl who is full of romantic ideas of love. At the end, we see her as an experiencd, mature and realistic girl who is able to refuse her mother match-making based on wealth and status. She declares, \"I am not here to be sold to the highest bidder\".      It is in this tranformation of Raina that Shaw's view of love is presented.  The other view of love as practical, realistic and satisfying is presented by the  Louka - Sergius and Raina - Bluntschli's relationship. It is on Raina's realization that love is not solely built on romantic ideas but on understanding and truth that she fall in love with Captain Bluntschli.      Similarly, the Louka Sergius relationship portrays the same indepth affection  as Sergius stops to find true love in Louka who also succeeds in briding the class gaps. There is also parental love.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLDSMITH: She Stoops to Conquer    Compare and contrast the characters of Mr. and Mrs. Hardcastle.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Mr. and Mrs. Hardcastle are the parents of Miss Hardcastle. Both parents always have altercations in many issues such as vices of the city life and their attitudes towards Tony Lumpkin.     In terms of contrast, Mr. Hardcastle enjoys his old fashioned houses and has a poor opinion of city life while Mrs. Hardcastle is always blaming her husband for denying her the opportunity to see the latest fashions; thus, she keeps up to her neighbour who goes to London every winter for a month's polishing.              Mr Hardcastle has a high sense of humour and patience which allows him to tolerate Tony's pranks while Mrs. Hardcastle is scheming  self - centred and materialistic as found in her treatment of Constance Neville.           While Mr Hardcastle is satisfied with his past achievements based on his aristocractic background, Mrs. Hardcastle is restless and disturbed in her aspirations to become an aristocract. Their mode of assessment goes a long way in unravelling an aspect of their character. Mr. Hardcastle's rational and objective assesement of Tony Lumpkin contrasts sharply with Mrs Hardcastle's irrational and subjective assesement of him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLDSMITH: She Stoops to Conquer    Discuss Tony Lumpkin as a comic hero", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony, the son of Mrs. Hardcastle  by a former marriage, has been brought up as a spoilt child by a doting mother who maintains that he is a tender weakling. Because he has a good fortune, his mother believes he does not need any formal eductaion. As  a comic hero, Tony could be assessed from the perspective of his role in birthing situations that are comic as well as his own ability to create humour and laughter.       Tony creates an impression of being in love with Constance Neville when in Mrs. Hardcastle's presence. This makes it easy for Neville to have her freedom to marry Hastings eventually.      Tony uses language to enrich the play by revealing an aspect of his split character when he is drunk. The journey to Aunt Pedigree also brings about comedy as Tony deceives his mother by going in circles in the neighbourhood.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the poet convey the tragedy of prison life in \"Letters to Martha 17\" ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poet descibes the psychological impact of prison restrictions on a prisoner. The small cell in which he is kept restricts both his physical movement and field of vision. The poet, Brutus portrays these tragedy through the use of some several figurative devices such as ; Imagery of sufferings, hostility  and confinement. It is illustrated in the lines of        \"walks on bleak hostility\"       \"The low ceiling of the prison\"        \" A rose and florescent light that blot out light from the outside.  There is also the images of freedom and the power of imagination such as  \"The complex  aeronautics / of the birds\"  \"The grateful, unimpended  motion of the clouds\".  The poet also make use of Rhetorical question . The use of rhetorical questions which emphasze the deprivation of the writer's feels in prison. These question reveal the desperation  and dejection felt by  the poet.  In all, Dennis Brutus shows that prison life is terrible in South Africa.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the poetic devices used in \"Nightfall in Soweto\" and Letters to Martha 17\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the two poems a number of poetic devices are employed to drive the message home. These poetic devices include Metaphor, Personfication, diction,and repetition.  Metaphor: In \"Nightfall in Soweto\", the poet's desires to set a wider field of vision is expressed by the word \"upwards \" in the mind turns upwards\"line8.  The cruel treatment of Blacks in Soweto is presented metaphorically  by the following lines. \" to be run down by the marauding beast [lines 19 and 20], \" man has become prey\" [line 18].   Personification: This device is used to symbolized the cutailment of freedom in both poems. In \"Nightfall in Soweto\", \"Nightfall\" is personified to represent not only hostility, but also fear, violence, horror and repression.  Diction: Both poems are presented in a language that brings out their respective meanings clearly and simply. In Letter to Martha 17, words like dreaded, and ravaging depicts horror and destruction while \"sleeping\" is suggestive to the general \"fear\" felt by the Blacks at the approach of the night.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the dramatic elements in \"Mending Wall\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem centres majorly on the theme of realtionship - the need to mantain good neighbourliness. Man needs to review his relationship with others as part of the progress he makes in civilization. The poet uses the dramatic elements to heighten the readers' appreciation of the meaning of the poem..  There is the use of conflict in the dramatic element of the poem. There is not only conflict of character but also beliefs  and interests. The conflict is played out by the neighbour's concept of \"good fences makes good neighbours\" as aopposed to the speaker's more progressive and accomodating attitude which in conformity with nature.      There is also the use of characerization. The neighbour is described as conservative and old fashioned..  The use of language in the poem can not be over emphasize. The language of the poem is highly conversational and colloquial, showing the simplicity of the character.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss Keats' attitude to the Urn in \"Ode on a Grecian Urn\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Urn, which is an art work, represent the timelessness of art, for it has survived  the ravages  of time.  The poet's  enthusiasm for and administration of this art work  are expressed in apt languages.  For example, the description of the Urn as \"Unravished\", sets the tone for his effusions as he examines  and comments on the variety of images etched on it. His excitement are conveyed by rhetotical question as in \" What struggle to Escape\"         In the subsequent stanza, the poet conclude that the Urn, with its engravings, represents eternity and, therefore, symbolizes beauty and truth.But Keat attitude to the Urn is certainly not one of unqualified admiration. The Urn being a work of imagination transcends time and Keats appreciates this aspects of its beauty. However, he equally calls attention through his careful choice of words, another aspect of the Urn. Its silence and quietnes, the arrested freshnes of its figures, the Urn being \"a cold pastoral\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CAMARA LAYE: The African Child    What aspect of Laye's father's personality are revealed in the gold smelting ceremony?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The aspects of Laye's father's personality may be noted as they concern the gold smelting ceremony are that he makes constant communion with his ancestors for aspiration and creativity through the snake which as a guiding spirit through out the novel, he always portrays his god - like quality which is manifested in his ability to transform ordinary matter into something extra - ordinary beautiful, manifestation of his vanity in love of praise and sensitivity to music.  He makes ritualistic communion with the snake.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CAMARA LAYE: The African Child    Discuss the significance of Laye's encounter with snakes", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The first encounter which is the first episode in the story reveals Laye's ignorance of the nature of snakes. The encounter takes place between the author, as a five - year - oldboy and the snake outside the father's workshop before the mother, and the apprentice  {Damany}. It demonstrates the community's dread for snakes.       The child, unaware of the danger the snake can pose, plays with it, putting a reed into his mouth. The snake swallows the full length of the reed until the child's  fingers almost enter the mouth of the snake . He is whisked away by one of his father's servant.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ELECHI AMADI: The Concubine    Discuss the contributions of Adaku and Wonuma to the failure of the marriage between Ekwueme and Ahurole.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ekwueme and Ahurole largely supported by their mother mothers: Adaku and Wonuma, work against the sucess of their marriage. Adaku is Ekwueme's mother, Ekwueme remains her only child for almost twelve years. Adaku's attachment to Ekwueme makes Ekwueme dependent on her. This affects his maturity to a full man. Adaku's close relationship with her son, Ekwueme affects his relationship with other women .     Wonuma on the other hand is Ahurole's mother. Wonuma brings out the idea of love potion to solve her daughter's matrimonial problems . This marks the turning point in the relationship between Ekwueme  and Ahurole. Wonuma teaches her daughter the styles to use in administering the love potion which will not arouse any suspicion  With the strong support of her mother , Ahurole administers the love potion and Ekwueme reacts to it negatively by running mad.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ELECHI AMADI: The Concubine    Comment on the character and role of Wodu Wakiri in The Concubine.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Wakiri is a very good composer and a dance. He is also a melodious singer. He sings Soprano. The villagers says he had a voice as clear as sound of Igele.   He is welcome everywhere he goes because he is always amusing people and he consider no occasion serious. The only occasion he appeared serious and worried is when his best friend, Ekwueme, goes berserk i.e, runs mad.  Wakiri provides comic belief in a village dominated by grief and tension arising from tragic event. He brightens people's mood and livens their dull moments. He contributes significantly to the social life of the village. He is a member of the four - man party that went for the marriage negotiations of Ahurole to Ekwueme carrying the 'single' calabash of wine needed for the openings talk. Wakiri plays a prominient and crucial role during the crisis of Ekwueme. He is one of the young men who brings Ekwueme backs to his father's compound.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "GEORGE ORWELL:  Animal Farm    Discuss three vices or weaknessess in human society that Orwell satirizes in Animal Farm.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Notable among the vices satirized by in the novel are egocentrism, narcissim or discrimination, selfishness and depotism or ruthlessness.  Discrimination or Narcissism: This occurs in form of discrimination between genders, among ethnic groups, nations or even between one race and the other . The pigs demonstrate this narcissits tendency on their part when they claim to be superior to all other animal in the farm.  Selfishness: This is demonstrated by Napeleon, squealer and most pigs. They ascribed to themselves all the goodies, brunties, largesse and all choicest foods and drinks in the farms without taking others into consideration.  Depotism:  This is demonstrated in the novel by Napoleon and his nine ferocious dogs who constitute themselves as his guards.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "GEORGE ORWELL:  Animal Farm    How does Napoleon systematically amend the original laws of Manor Farm?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The original law prohibits the animals to adopt man's way such as walking on two legs, wearing clothes, sleeping in bed, drinking alcohol and killing other animals. They decided to adopt them as constitution by which they will live together forever.      However, the revolution is betrayed immediately Napoleon takes over power . He embark on systematic destruction of  the principle of Animalism as entrenched in the animals commandments.      Napoleon discards the ideas of being addressed  \"Comrade\" and prefers to be addressed as a \"leader\". This is against maxism \"All animls are equal\". Also Napoleon begins to sleep in bed. The original law is now restructed by squealer as \"No animal shall sleep in bed with sheet\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ROBERT LOUIS STEVENSON: Treasure Island    With close reference to the text, discuss the visits of the Black Dog and Pew  to Billy Bones at the Benbow Inn, bringing out their effects on him.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Billy is shocked to see Black dog, they talk, quarrel, and fight. Black dog is wounded on the left shoulder and he runs away while Billy Bones faints. Billy Bones faints from weariness, resulting from heavy drinking and loss of appetite. Dr. Liversey comes and attends to Billy.     Blind pew visit Billy Bones on one cold afternoon after the burial of Jim's father. He grips Jim's hand and orders Jim to take him to Billy Bones, thrreatening to break Jim's arm if he does not obey. Billy Bones is shocked to see Blind Pew.      The blind man's hands over the \"Black Spot\" to Billy and leaves immediately. Billy reads the \"Black Spot\" - \"You have till ten O' clock tonight\". Billy jumps and puts his hand on his wrote and falls. Billy Bones dies out of shock upon receiving the \"Black Spot\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2000>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ROBERT LOUIS STEVENSON: Treasure Island  Examine the character and role of any two of the following in Treasure Island:  a. Billy Bones  b. Jim Hawkins  c. Ben Gunn", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "a. Billy Bones:  Billy Bones is an old man, who, in an attempt from his former mates, seeks temporary shelter at Benbow Inn. He is a tall, strong and rough with a scar across his bright cheek.      His actions betray a  restlessess of mind and an inner psychological turmoil that speak of a deep - seated fear in him which from time to time is outwardly manifested in uncouth gestures, wicked songs and terrible outburst of temper. He consumes copious amount of alcohol to the point of unconsciouness which also highlights his desperate intention to drown his fears and get a grip of his emotions. He thus bring into the plot a new dimension : one of fear,restlessness and dread, especially, of the unknown, a theme which recurs in the novel.  b. Jim Hawkins : He is a young boy living with his parents at Benbow Inn. He is host to Billy Bone and during the voyage to Treasure Island, he serves in the ship as a ship boy.     On board Hispaniola, Jim is the first to realize treachery and brutality of the pirates. He discovers the brutal side of Silver's character beneath the veneery of friendliness, especially in his murder of Tom and his incitement of mutiny.  c. Ben Gunn: He is a pathetic character in whose situation we see man's inhumanity to his fellow man. He represent the dark side of humanity and epitomizes the danger of treachery involved in undertaking adventures of fortune. It is through Ben Gunn that the pirates' desired are thwarted and rendered futile.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLA ROTIMI : The Gods are not to Blame    How does Ola Rotimi sustain the tragic interest in The Gods are not to Blame.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The tragic interest in the play is suatained through the use of a number of devices: suspense, language, flashblack etc.   - suspense: The ignorance of his parentage and the townpeople equally ignorants of Odewale's identity, the tragedy is played out to the very end.  - language: The language by itself shed light to the tragedy and foreshadows Odewale's doom through the use of imagery and proverb.  - flashback: In the use of flashback, the mystery surrounding Adetusa's death and the cause of the plague is revealed", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLA ROTIMI : The Gods are not to Blame    How does the playwright unravel the mystery of King Adetusa's death?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The mystery surrounding King Adetusa's death can be illustrate thus:  - The plague initiates the conflicts and introduces the tragic atmosphere in the play  - The oracle complicates matter by announcing that the plague is a result of a \"curse in the land\" which has to do with murder of Adetusa. The death leads to the search for the murderer.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "EFUA T. SUTHERLAND: The Marriage of Anansewa    With close reference to the text show how Chief - who - is  Chief - maarries Anansewa", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "INTRODUCTION:   A poor but ambitious widower sends the photographs of his only child, Anansewa, to four differnt wealthy chiefs with whom he  individuallly concludes engagment rites. He does this because he lives in penury and cannot pay his daughter's school fees. And to achieve this aim Ananse brings to play this cunningness tricks.  Point to note:  i. Anansewa is driven out of school, Ananse can no longer pay her school fees  ii.He convinces four chiefs to marry his daughter   iii. Ananse prevails upon Anansewa to accede to his plans to get money by giving her away to highest bidder.  iv. In response, the four chiefs prepare individually for the actual marriage  v. The plan which seems to be working runs into a hitch as all the four chiefs seperatly send messages to Ananse fixing the day for the head - drink of Anansewa  vi. To avoid being exposed and embarrassed, he tricks Aya, {his mother} and Ekuwa {his aunt} into leaving for Nanka their home town.  vii. Anansewa pretends to be dead and this enable Ananse to determine which of the four suitors honestly loves Anansewa.  viii. The plans pays off as the various suitors sends funeral / cashgifts  ix. In the end Ananse achieve his aims of securing a good husband for his daughter.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "EFUA T. SUTHERLAND : The Marriage of Anansewa    Examine the use of language in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Language is used to reveal character, for example. Ananse's cunning is revealed in the flamboyance of the letter he writes to the suitors. It is meant to flatter and deceive each of the four chiefs. His refusal to explicitly state the \"object of your interest\" also brings out the cunning and evasiveness.    The diction is effective in bringing out the mood in the play. The players reference to \"oh, life is a struggle .... life is a pain in this world \" exposes Ananse poverty's which is further highlighted in Ananse's remarks.  \"It's rain combining with life to beat your father down\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "GEORGE BERNARD SHAW : Arms and the Man    Assess the contribution[s] of Nicola to the development of the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Nicola, a servant in the house of the Petkoffs, contribues  a lot to the development of the play. In his role as servant he has acquired thorough knowledge and understanding of the life of Petkoffs and is in a position to pass judgement and make critical comments on their public and private. lives.     Nicola further contributes to the plot. In his return of Bluntschill's bag, he sets the stage for the series of conflicting comments and cross references noted in the mystery the old coat. The reader is thus set for the unraveling of the plot and the resolution of the mystery behind Major Petkoff's coat.     Nicola also contribute to the development of the theme of love in the play. In his relationship with Louka he accentuates another level of love.  Louka is bethroned to him but it is clear the relationship lacks lustre sensual elements.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "GEORGE BERNARD SHAW: Arms and the Man    Comment on marriage and status as portrayed in Arms and the Man.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The relationship between marriage and social class can evidently be seen in Raina who begins the play fully believing in class marriage but ends the play content with her \"chocolate cream soldier\" regardless of his wealth or social class.       In the play, marriage is presented as good but that people abuse the institution by mere illusions and fantacies, for  example the primary motive of Rainah's marriage to Sergius is based on the erroneous belief that Sergius is a hero whom she could be proud of.     Bernard Shaw thinks of marriae not as a means of satisfying the personal desireof individual men and women, nor as a means of strengthening family ties but as the means of bringing birth a new better generation. Marriage, in Arms and the Man, is seen as a universal phenomenon but it comes in different forms and its perceived in different ways by different people.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLSMITH : She Stoops to Conquer    Examine the relationship between parents and their children in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The two families in the play, the Hardcastles and the Marlow. They appear to be knit but there is evidence that the parents differ from their children. The children are fashion conscious and they are non conformists. In the end both children and their parents are forced to make compromises which eventually gives the children the upper hand.  i. Mrs Hardcastle attempt to force a marriage between Tony and Constance for her selfish aim of retaining control over Miss Neville's inheritance misfires  ii. Mr Hardcastle tries to impose young Marlow on Kate as husband to strengten his friendship with Sir Charles, but in the end Kate marries Marlow out of love.  iii. Mrs Hardcastle pampering of Tony in an attempt to win his love rather makes him wayward, a wastrel, a drunkard, one ignoring home, school and church.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLSMITH : She Stoops to Conquer    What  is the significance of the \"Ale house\" scene in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Ale house is the inn frequented by Tony Lumpkin where he spends more of his time. The mistake of one night originates from the Ale house with Tony being the initator of the error. By misdirecting Hastings and Marlow into his stepfather's house as inn, Tony initoiates the conflicts and heightens the humor in the play      The Ale house introduces the character and provides a focal point  for the comedy.  The Ale house represent Tony's world where he is more relaxed and his  natural tendencies are fully played.  Tony's song in the Ale house exposes his disregard for education and religion. For him \"Good liquor.....gives genius a better discerningg\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the poet treat the theme of adventure in \"Stanley meets Mutesa\" ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poet describes the difficult and hazardous expendition of stanley, the white ambassador, embarks upon with his African retinue, to meet Metusa an African {Buganda} king.  The journey is  made under extreme weather conditions - the day is very hot and the night extremely cold, and infested with mosquitoes.  The carrier's physical and psychological condition are described in a language that conveys their pitiful state. They are dirty and clothed in \"tattered rags\". The journey itself stressful and long, their suffering is compounded by the weight of the heavy loads they carry and men are increasingly pestered by flies. Their spirit and hopes are rise and fall in the sun from day to day.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the effective use of imagery in \"Salute to the Elephant\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poet uses different types of imagery. Each of the images used describes one quality of the elephant or the other.  Images of fear; this is convey by word like \" tremor\", which the awesomeness of the animal. It creates an image of disgust and point of its strenght. The image of destruction  is used. This is used to describe the elephant as a demon, who tears a man like a garment and snaps tree branches into pieces. There is also the image of wealth; the elephant is a possessor of a \"saving basket money\" which confirms its economic value. Reference is also made to the elephant as death, through the image of death.     Also there is the image of movement; this is expressed by reference to \"walks with a staggering gait\", \"trading ponderously\", \"walks slowly as if relunctantly \" which brings out the elephant majesty and awesomeness.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the moral significnce of the poem \"Mending Wall\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem decries the creation of artificial barriers in human communication and sees such barriers as unnatural. The periodic mending of the wall which the two neighbours engage in confirms that nature itself is opposed to their actions. There is therefore a perceptiven as well as a moral problem presented in the poem.    A religious interpretation can be given to the poem. The walls between the neighbours symbolizes absence of love which is a clear violation of the christian teaching of \"love thy neighbour as thy self\". In this context, good neighbourliness symbolizes human interaction, love, peace and understanding which the two characters have denied themselves", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the poet's mood in \" An Irish Airman Foresees His Death\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem is a reflective poem in that the speaker, an airman and soldier by choice, weighs his career on the balance and finds that he has never served himself nor his country men well by joining his compatriots to fight during the first world war. He can only see that he is heading towards death and no matter the oucome of the war the circumstances of his people, the poor Kiltartan, are not going to improve.      The lines which expresses speaker's indifference regarding his relation with his enenmy he doe not hate and the English he does  not love, deepen his mood from sadnees to despair, as he realises that his fighting the war has not and is not likely to benefit his poor country . His admission that he alone is responsible for his choice of career.               \"A lonely impulse of delight               Drove to this turmult in the clouds\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CAMARA LAYE : The African Child.    Discuss the presentation of traditional life in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Traditional life is presented with aural of mysticism out, the supernatural, festivity, communalism and fecundity. In the first instance, it is defined by traditional rituals shaped by spirits and lesser deities and finds expression in tottems, culture and customs. It is manifested in the significance amd position of the little snake, the supernatural powers of Laye's mother,the visit to the marabouts; the crocodile as Laye's mother totem and magical potions his fathers uses in incantation.      Traditional life is also thrives on checks and  balances and the operation of societal laws. Culprits are punished as the law is upheld. Himorana is severely flogged for breaking the bond of love and protection that should operate in a closely - knit family.  Traditional life is characterized  by the celebrations, ceremonies and festivals. In some situations traditional ceremonies assume epic proportions. This is seen in the circumcision ceremony where every member of society participates. It becomes a communal festival and everyone contribute to its succes.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CAMARA LAYE : The African Child.  Discuss the presentation of family relationship  in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Family relationship in the  novel centre around communal life and living in the society. In the novel Laye presents his family as a closely - knit unit where personal concern and individaulism are replaced by a more accomodating, wholesome and humane attitude to members of the society .      The bond of kinship ties is also evident in Laye's visit to Tindican and Kouroussa where the cordial relationship between him and his uncless as well as his grandmother demonstrates the African spirit of protection and hospitality .   This spirit of warmth and togetherness is also reflected at Tindican and Kouroussa. There is mutual affection and tenderness between Laye and his grandmother. There is the hospitality and companionship shown to him by uncle Lansana as well as the good natured disposition of his younger brother who is, in his tender care, would tell interesting stories of birds and animals to Laye.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ELECHI AMADI : The Concubine    How are African marriage ceremonies and funeral rites portrayed in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According the plot of the novel, the author see these ceremonies; funeral rites, child naming, marriage ceremonies as time - consuming, extremely extravagant, in many cases energy sapping.  points to note:  i. Marriages are arranged by the parents on both sides e.g, Ekwueme's parents meets Ahurole's  ii. Sometimes marriage can involve appeasing the gods or even binding the furious ones e.g, the sea - king in Ekwueme and Ihuoma's case.  iii. The communities are completely involve in marriage ceremonies - starting from the age groups of the couples to the elders of the society.  Funeral rites on the other hand , Emenike's burial is the responsibility of the Omokachi community and not that of Emenike's  family members alone. The whole community is therefore involved in the various stages of the burial rites.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "With reference to at least four incidents, show how The Concubine  portrays an undiluted African traditional life.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel is set in the distant past of an Igbo community and culture when there was no echoes of any foreign influence.  There is interactions between gods and the community, everything is directed by the gods of the land . Every activities has its own gods and priest. illness, injuries - physical and mental - are treated with herbs after traditional diagnosis by divination.: Emenike's injury, Madume's toe injury , Ekwei's madness, Ahurole's problems with her agwu are just examples.       Time is measured by shadow's length and sun's journey to Chiohi. The fear and respect for the gods ancestral spirit dictate the conscience of individuals, hence crime is a taboo and very rare. Disputes, quarrel and conflicts are setlled by council of elders not individuals.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "GEORGE ORWELL: Animal Farm    Discuss Orwell's use of irony in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Irony stand from a subtle comment or situation in which is said is or the expected outcome is the opposite of what is intended or expected.  The writer uses irony to laugh at the folly of the animals in their belief that there lives would become better after the overthrow of the Jones. The irony is extended in the wideness of the pigs and the gullibility of the other animals. Examples:    Napoleon's announcement that Sunday afternoon work is voluntary but anyone who does not votunteer will have his ration reduced by half {chapter 6}, Squealer's insistence that pigs are brain workers who deserve to consume milk and apple, Squealers makes fine speeches which he underscores the \" joy of service and disunity of labour\" but the animals find aspiration in Boxer's strength and never failing of \"I will work harder\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "GEORGE ORWELL: Animal Farm    With close reference to the text, show how Animal Farm appeals the reader's imagination", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Animal Farm is a very imaginative work of arts in which animals are made to act like human beings.It is a political satire that has stood the test of time. The use of imagery in the novel can be seen from the following.  The publicity/ public relations gimmicks used by Squealer, Napoleon's chief spokesman  The political debates - whether the windwill should be bulit or not, large carrots as against grass.  The two different battles with human beings  The alteration of the constitution of Animal farm and Squealers accident.  The buliding of the windwill is organized in such a way that the smaller animals do small jobs, while the pigs one breaks stone, haul planks and plough the field .", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ROBERT LOUIS STEVENSON: Treasure Island    What makes Treasure Island interesting?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel is about sea voyage that is undertaken in an old  but refurblished ship, the Hispaniola, the purchase of which is undertaken by a novice. In the same manner the supposed Captain who is to man the ship, is not the one that recruits the crew. Trelawney collects old sea dogs, a group of criminal and sea pirates , that are bloody - thirsty and Dr.  Livesey - the ship's medical doctor '. Jim Hawkins - a very young boy, Long John Silver - the ship's cook and a most wicked pirate and a host of others. The roles assigned these characters collectively and individaully and the manner in which they perform them for interesting reading.       R.L Stevenson explores anxious themes that generate interest in the novel. The theme of adventure is one. A voyage and by sea to a very remote and unknown Island, their only guide been an awkward drawn map with red mark to locate the exact location of the buried treasure which is the object of their  mission.     There are the themes honour, patroitism and good governane which are associated with the good men - Trelawney, Smollet, Livesey, Jim Hawkins, etc. These men pilot the Hispaniola successfully to and fro under the able leadership of captain Smollett and Trelawney.     Another area of interest is the language of the author. The simplicity of the language for most part of the novel enters into the spirit and life of a small boy, the narrator makes the novel attractive to young readers who him as one of their own talking to them in the language they easily understand.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2001>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Write notes on any two of the following:   i. The Apple Barrel,  ii. Spyglass   iii. The black spot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Apple Barrel :   The incident occurs on board the Hispaniola as it approaches Treasure Island.  Jim Hawkins has gone to help himself with an apple from the apple barrel only to find out that it is virtually empty that he has to jump in, if he is to get any. Inside the barrel, and being    rocked almost to sleep, he fortutiously hears the voice of Long John Silver plotting with Dick and Israel hand to kill Captain Smollett and others and take over the ship. Jim therefore takes the opportunity to inform Dr. Livesey and others who successfully defend themselves and leave the Hispaniola for the mutiners  The Spyglass  The spyglass is the tallest hill on Treasure Island, rising to a height of three to four thousand feet.The spyglass is also an instrument used by Billy Bones when he goes out early in the morning to take in fresh air. The reader's first awareness of the spyglass is through Jim Hawkins who, after Billy Bones death precipated by the fight the black dog at the Admiral Benbow Inn, finds the key to Billy Bone's sea which contain a book and paper which is a Treasure Island specifying its geographical location, including the glass where the treasure is hidden.  The Black Spot:   The black spot is first mentioned by Billy Bones as the attempt to recover from a stroke caused by a fight with black at the Admiral Benbow Inn. Pleading for a drinkn and  being told by Jim Hawkins that Dr. Livsesey has ordered total abstinence and rest for at least a week. Billy Bones despairingly says \"they'd have the black spot on me by then\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI : The Black Hermit    Compare and contrast the character and the role of Jane and Thoni in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The two characters Jane and Thoni represent two different forces in society - westernihzation and traditional respectively. Thoni is the traditional woman who at death of her husband is prepared to be inherited by Remi, the younger brother of her late husband.      Thoni heightens the tragic atmosphere in the play in her misgivingsand uncertainties about Remi's return and the prospect  of continuitty of their relationship . Her frustration and disillusionment is tied to the overall discontent in African society at independence.     Jane is the modern day woman.  She dwells in the city and is exposed  to western values. By going to night clubs, dancing the waltz and living a premarital life with Remi, she sharply contrast Thoni who longs for a  husband and the glories of motherhood in a simple traditional enviroment.      On the other hand, Thoni is the non - questioning, passive and docile woman. She accepts situation as it is and only complain in private to her mother - in - law. She blames her situation on fate and seeks divine assistance for its correction . She is quiet and given to the prophetic in her psychic ruminations on outcome of her marriage to Remi.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI : The Black Hermit    How does Ngugi present religion in the play ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the plot development of the play, the playwright uses the pastor as the representative of christainity, and it is through his actions that the reader, for the most part, comes to assess the validity of the chriatain faith in Africa. Christainity is presented as a life - denying and non -  functional in the African enviroment. In Nyobi's conversation with the pastor after her compliance with elder's decision, the unattractive side of christainity is seen. With its emphasis on the spiritual over the natural, it makes little provision for the humanity of the individual. In the face of adversity and discomfort the pastor can only offer the promises of heaven as a solution to earthly problems.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA : The Lion and the Jewel    Discuss the character and role of Sadiku in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Sadiku, is the senior wife of Baroka, the Bale of lluginle. She was the youngest wife of the great Okiki, Baroka's father, and at his  death, Okiki's son, Baroka, inherited her.     As the senior wife of Baroka, she occupies a respectable position in the palace. She is the favourite of the Bale and is often consulted before any decision is taken on important issues.  She is given the priviledge and accorded the honour of being \"go - between\" of the Bale in the wooing of Sidi, a role she performs grudgingly.       Sadiku accentuates the theme of generation gap.  The contrast between the ideals and belief of the old and the young generation is reflected in her role in the play. Sadiku's traditional approach to love, her acceptance of her position in Baroka's home and her function as \"go - between\" illustrate the features of old generation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Discuss the conflict between modernism and traditionalism in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the play, Lion and the Jewel, there is conflict between African and European values and ways of life.     In Lakunle's encounter with Sidi, the conflict in their attitude to love and marriage is seen . Lakunle's approach to love is based on the chivalry and romance of the 18th century where the suitor  her suitor pursues the lady, romantisizes  and speaks poetry to her. The woman must walk hand in hand with her suitor on the streets with painted lips and high - heeled shoes.      The opposing views in their of the culture and customs of the people indicate another area of conflict. While traditional sees the payment of bride price as a sign of love, being a virgin and and respect for the bride, Lakunle sees it as \"buying a heifer off the market stall\", a means through which woman lose their civil liberties and becomes chattles and mere property.     To Sidi the non payment of bride pricw will bring her sham. \"They will say no virgin\" To Lakunle it is a \"savage custom, barbaric, outdated and accursed \" a means of slaming our heritage before the World.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "RICHARD SHERIDAN: The Rivals    Discuss the use of dramatic irony in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The playwright use of dramatic irony is attributed to the following: Lydia's perception of Jack Absolute as Ensign Beverly as she fails to appreciate his double identity. Mrs Malaprop inability to appreciate the fact that Jack Absolute is Ensign Beverly, and in the circumstance unwittingly assists him in love plans. Jack Absolute's deception of Mrs Malaprop who is ignorant of his double identity and thus insult and mocks her to her face without her realising that he is Ensign Beverly.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "RICHARD SHERIDAN: The Rivals    How does the playwright's characterization contribute to the development of the play ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There is a comic character, Mrs Malaprop, who in her attempts to live up to an imaginary sophisticated London standard of living and her misuse of words to cover her vulgarity and lack of education, heightens the comedy.      As part of characterization Julia is seen as failure to Lydia. She is more realistc, practical and down - to - earth character whose initiatves prevail at the end of the play.     There is contrast in characters to illustrate meaning. This for instance is seen in Sir Anthony and Captain Absolute on one hand which contrasts with the lack of sophistication and refinement in Bob Acres on the other. This contrast illustrates the distinction in social status, background and education of the characters and hightlights the social structure of 18th century England.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T. S. ELIOT: Murder in Cathedral    Comment on the role of the chorus in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The chorus sets the mood of fear and uncertainty in the play. This is achieved by what seems the natural reaction of the poor women expecting more trouble at the return of Arcbishop of Canterbury.     The chorus also contributes to language enrichment through it use of imagery and biblical allusions. This image is woven around the endless cycle of time and it depicts in metaphysical terms the relationship between man, time, eternity and God.     The chorus also has a prophetic intuition in their visionary fear of the Archbishop's impending death, especially in the presence of the four knights at canterbury. The chorus affirms this intuition in the metaphor of the line \" I have seen these things in a shaft of sunlight\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T. S. ELIOT: Murder in Cathedral    Discuss the dramatic significance of  Tempters in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The tempters represent four aspects of the conflict that Archbishop has to overcome. They are not characters in the conventional sense, but external  manifestations of his inner conflict..        The first temptation enyokes sensuality - love for pleasure, athletics, music, good company,gaiety and romance.  The second tempters presenst a more attractive proposition - political power which Becket had once relinquished upon his appointments as Archbishop, an act brought him into conflict with the king.    Becket's third temptation is more subtle. He is offered the opportunity to use power of the church in secular ways and thus pitch the church against the state   The final temptation is the most subtle as it presents a proposition he has thought about  - glories  of sainthood for self satisfaction, \"to be able to rule from the tomb and be high in heaven.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How successful is the use of imagery in  We have come home", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There is the image of warrior who goes to war in anticipation of returning with captives as proof of succes or victory. This image illustrates the plight of the African student who travels overseas to engage in rigorous studies, \"bloodless war\" and anticipates a return home with certificates as evidence of success.     There is yet aonther, the image of death and suffering noted in \"burial\", \"wreaths\", and \"the death march\". All these suggest an environment that suffocates progress because values are mixed up . In the resulting confusion, life and death becomes synonymous, time is suspended and \"there is no acquintance with tomorrow\".    There is also image of night and the dark sun which suggest a lack of light, purpose and direction, and absence of the vital and regenerative element of life.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the style and theme of \"Abiku.\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Thematically, the poem has three part structure, the first part calls Abiku's attention to its identification  marks, which should force it to stay and live like a normal child. In the second part there is description of the homestead, which though poor and lowly has been a home to may other children. The third part make a direct appeal to Abiku to desist from fulfiling its cycle of birth and death.     As for the style, there is image of supernatural that runs through the poem. The child is conceived as spirit; it is linked to its kindred spirits, ad it has power of initiating a cycle of birth and death.     Finally, there is imaged of the bondsman, who, by virtue of its scars is forced to \"step in and say say\" as it has already been recognized.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the theme and style of  \"Is my Team Ploughing?\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem exposes the conscience of a man who has either had a hand in the person's death or who, by virtue of that death, is psychologically disturbed over the amorous relationship that has developed between him and the persona's lover. The poem could be interpreted in two levels : first a mystical conversation or interchange between a dead man , the peresona, and hid one time friend, in which the persona confronts his friend about the truth of their relationship, society's activities and his relationship with his former lover.     The use of dialogue in the interchange between the persona and his friend is effective for it reveals character, enhances plot and highlight themes .Using the question and answer techniques, the reader is given insight into the relationship that exist between two friends before persona's death.     There is also the use of reminiscences as the persona recalls his activities on earth: the ploughing session in the fields the entertainment on the football pitch and the pains of departiure, especially of continuity in various aspect of life regardless of the persona's experiece.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How is atmosphere conveyed in \"Elegy Written in a Country Churchyard?\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Through the use of diction, imagery, symbolism  and figurative language, the atmosphere of death is vividly conveyed.     In the first stanza of the poem, the poet uses imagery  to set the mood of finality that depicts an end to an ongoing activity. This state of finality is reflected i n the significance of the images of \"curfew\", \"the lowing herd\" and the \"plowman\" who, in their various activities, indicate an end of action, a span of life as it were.    The diction amplifies the state of sadness and grief in the poet's use of contrast and repetition. There is repetition of \" no more\" to emphazise finality of action as in : \"no more shall rouse them from then lowly bed\" and \"for them no more the blazzing heart shall burn\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE : Anthills of Savannah    What view of contemporary African society is treated in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. Chinua Achebe presents African society under a military administration. The armed forces men, the kakistocract {military} take  up the mantle of leadership of pioneering the affairs of the state.  ii. Institutionalization of corruption. The leaders are the most corrupt phenomenom in the society. He is a megalomaniac dictator fashinoed on such deruptible characters as Idi Amin  and the self - styled \"Emperor Bokassa.  iii. The blood  thirstines  of the ordinary people is frightrning. This is revealed in the execution of the four armed robbers .  iv The ordinary people acquiesce in corruption and injustce.  v. There are no means for the ordinary man to seek redress.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE: Anthills of Savannah    Comment on the narrative technique used in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. The narrative technique used in the novel is a combination of the first person and the third person narrative techniques in a peculiar way, and this makes it complex. This accrues to the fact the result of the plot from different perspectives.  ii. The narrative techniques enanble the author to present a clear picture of the society's moral decadence without seeming too intrusive.  iii. The novel consist of three narrators. Each narrators gives his/her view of the events from different perspective of theirs.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AYI KWEI ARMAH: The Beautiful Ones Are not Yet Born    Comment on the style of the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel reveals the prevalent corruption in political and governmental circles of the Post - Independence Ghana. The Author sees Ghana socio - eco - political society as a decadent society where corruption and decay permeate  all aspets of life.       The Author also adopts the omniscient narrative technique. He presents the events from his point of view shape and evaluates  the material to suit his team, and creates characters to act in accordance with development of the theme.     He also uses language in another aspect of the style. The most part of the language is Caustic and vitrolic in its  referance  to bodily secretions, pungent, odour  and enviromental decay.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AYI KWEI ARMAH: The Beautiful Ones Are not Yet Born    Discuss on the character of Mana the teacher, bringing out their development of the plots.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Teacher can be examined on two levels in the novel. He is a character who is annoyed at the corruption he sees around him and who takes refuge in solitude  to avoid being corrupted.       Psychologically, Teacher's exposits a man deeply troubled and disturbed over his inability to get to the top. The calmness that surrounds his life is a direct contrast to his inner turmoil. As he has hatred for corruption , he longs for those good things of life can only be acquired through corrupt means. He is  a pardoxical fgure that illustrates contrast  between appearance and reality.     Maanan represents a structural link in the novel, the link between past and present. she represents the expectations of society and her resultant derangement is an indication of post - independence disillusuioment and disappointment in Africa.      She represents the destruction of womanhood in Africa by crurel and selfish politicians .      Maanan also epitomizes the ordinary Ghananian woman, filled with unbounded aspirations and dreams for the improvement of society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THOMAS HARDY: Tess of the d'Urbervilles    Comment on the view that Tess is a victim of society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Hardy uses the novel to express his abhorrence of a dogmatism that makes theory and abstract ideals more important than compassion and loving kindness.   The dogmatism and rigidity of the church is its attitude to the baptism  and burial of poor sorrow; the danger of love such as Angel's which is \"ethereal to a fault, imaginative to impracticality\" a love that creates \"an ideal presence that conveniently drops the defects of the real as Angel does not fall in love with Tess, but with a dream, a fantasy, which he believes to be Tess.      Futhermore,the irresponsibilty of Jack Dubeyfield who at Parson Tringham's insinuations of his link with the supposed nobel d'Urbervilles gets drunk and cannot take the cart to the market next day gives impetus to Tess tragic story. This prompts her taking prince to the market, its death and her sense of guilt which drives her into the clutches of Alec.      In addition, Alec's seduction of Tess is the one single action from which her misfortunes emanate. Alec is the archetype of the victorian villain, devilish in thoughts and action who unscrupulously robs Tess of her innocence.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THOMAS HARDY: Tess of the d'Urbervilles    Comment on the author's use of symbolism in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel highlight the conflicts between rustic simplicity and conventional morality, the peasant class and the aristcracy. It could als be interpreted to mean the destruction of the peasantry by the rising burgeoise and aristcracy. In essence the forces of modernism destroy the rural life.     The house, Prince is symbolic of traditionalism and represent the  family means of  sustenance and its death from the accident with the mail cart shows the destruction of traditionalism by the forces of modernism.  In like manner, the destruction of Tes by Alec shows the destruction of peasantry by the rising burgeoise.      Tess portrait is both real and symbolic. Hardy provides abundant references to her beauty and attractiveness in the references to her mouth and lips.  Tess is both individual and representative, human and symbolic. As an individual she personifies all that Hardy finds mostly love in women - loyalty, courage, tenderness, came for others, and willingness to sacrifice everything and suffer all for love. As a symbol she represents all women everywhere, exploited and then rejected, victims of society whose values are demonstratably fals and heartless victim, often of cruel and ruthless men.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe    Discuss Crusoe's relationship with Xury and man Friday in Robinson Crusoe.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Crusoe's personal relationship with other characters in the novel is affected by his economis perception of the society. He treats other characters in terms of their commodity value. The clearest case is that of Xury, the moorish boy who helped him to escape from slavery and on another occassion offered to prove his devotion by sacrificing his own life.      Crusoe properly resolves \"to love him ever after\" and promises \"to make him a great man\" . But when they encounter Portuguese captain, who offers Crusoe sixty piece of eight, he cannot resist the bargain, and sells Fury into slavery.       Crusoe relation with Friday is similarly egocentric. On first meeting him, he does not ask him his name,  but gives him one. Even in language Crusoe is a strict utilitarian man.   The relationship between Crusoe and Friday apart form illustrating the primacy of the economic motive in Crusoe also highlights the imperialist theme. It shows the master - servant characteristic of the colonizer and the colonized and the dominating oppresive and controlling influence is noted as Crusoe remarks in a little time, i began to speak to him and teach him to speak to me and i first made him know his name should be  Friday which was the day i saved his life ... I likewise taught him to say master and then let him know that was to be my name....\"  Crusoe regard his relationship with Friday as ideal.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2002>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe    Comment on the treatment of religion in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i.  Crusoe illustrates the norm of the religious fable, after the pattern of the  old morality play. There is  a real tension between God's purpose and Crusoe's very human impulses a tension that illustrates the conflict between God and evil of man's soul  ii. Crusoe certainly exhibits frequents sign of intimate knowledge of Bible. He quotes some twenty verses of the Bible in the first part of the text alone, besides making several breif refrences and he seeks divine guidance by opening the Bible at random.  iii. There is also the tendency from puritan point of view, to see every item in his personal experience as potentially rich in moral and spiritual meaning. As such a lot of events in the narrative are seen as divine pointers in this regard,  his solitary sojourn on the Island is God's punishment fo Crusoe's great sins.", "marks": "20", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit     Discuss the significance of the supernatural in The Black Hermit", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the play, the supernatural refers to practices, events or circumstances that are not immediately comprehensible. This can be seen in the following:  a.  The death of Ngobi's first son is attributed to a cause on the family.  b. Remi's failure to unite his people is perceived by society as the effect of black magic used on him by the neighbhouring tribes.  c. Remi's refusal to marry Thoni, his leaving for the city and adoption of christainity are perceived as abnormal and therefore attributed to the supernatural  d. Ngome's death as a result of his conversion to christainity is attributed to gods.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit     Discuss the use of irony in  the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The use of irony in the play can be evaluated through Remi's character. There are inconsistences in Remi's character which focused him to act in way that are ironic.  Refusing to inherit Thoni, he seeks refuge in  the city. The impression created is that of a modern individual  who cannot aloow himself to be ensnared by negatvie tradition as he perceives them, yet on his return and her eventual suicide, Remi demonstrates  an intensity, of love for Thoni that is baffling.      Another irony of situation is noted inThoni's suicide. After waiting so long for Remi's return with all the promises and hopes it holds for the future, Thoni commits suicide at the first note of Remi's rejection of her.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Discuss the use of symbolism in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The title of the play itself is symbolic. It brings to light aspect of the characters of Baroka and Sidi, who are likened to the lion of Jewel resppectively. Boroka symbolizes a lion in terms of his agility, strength cunningness and craftiness, while Sidi's beauty associates her with a precious jewel.     There is also the  symbolism of characters. Lakunle, for instance, represents the half baked educated. African who sees his knowledge of books as a solution  to the African predicament. He condemns his identity and casts aspersions on the customs of his people. In his dress, speech and refusal to pay the bride price,   he cut a picture of the so - called modern man.      There is symbolism of mime \"The lost traveller\" . This exposes Lakunle derailment for the ways of his tribe and indirectly calls for a reunion with his cultural identity. Significantly, his falling into the river immediately after this scene is a cultural baptism.     There is also the symbolism of language. Lakunle's poetic language and his use of high - sounding words express his preoccupation with the books; Sidi's use of simple prose and diction that express her uncertainties about Lakunle's  point of view shows her a naive and innocent girl, while, Boroka's use of proverb places him firmly at home within his tradition and highlight and knowledge of the World.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Discuss the significance of bride price in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The payment of the bride price raises question about womanhood in Africa. Lakunle infers that it is symbolic not only of a backward custom but its subjects the woman to marital bondage for she is, as it were, \"tied to her husband dirtied heels\". She is his property, a mere chattle because she had been \"paid for\"and, in turn, has the responsibilty of \"bringing forth children by the gross\". The bride price is a major barrier to a reconcillation of the traditional and the modern. It Sidi from committing herself to Lakunle's proposals as she sees his romantic speeches as a means of avoiding the payment of the bride. She evetually succumbs to the ballet presumably in anticipation of the ballet's payment of the bride price.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T. S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    Comment on the view that Thomas Becket is a martyr", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In different ways, we are given an early impression of Thomas characters and situation - a man sturbborn, determined and proud.  a. His encounter with the fourth tempter shows - awareness, knowledge of his own character, strength and weakness . He realizes he could be regarded as being supernaturally proud in delibrately choosing an option that could lead to death and supernatural glory. His compassion for the chorus' despair makes him ready to act on instnct not for self - aggrandisement but becuse he would thus the fufilling the will of God.  b. His first words in the play are low keyed and admirable. His calmness and resoect for the ordinary people contrast with the priest's dismissal of them as foolish and babbling. His very first word is \"peace\", he has come to cause trouble.  c. He shows calmness and courage in his first meeting with knight and rebuts their accusations and insult; he expresses his argument clearly and is not provoked by their taunting to return to France.  d. Despite his personal danger,he remains conscious about his pastoral role and attempt to confront and enlightened the chorus and so reveals them as their sufferings and doubt.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T. S. ELIOT: Murder in the Catheral     Discuss the reasons given by the knights for killing the Archbishop and their significance in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the knights' murder of the ArchBishop, they addressed the audience in their attempts to justify their reasons for his death. Baron William de Traci says that their action was done purely out of patroitism. In essence, they had nothing personal against him. On the contrary they had alot of respect for him. They acknowledge the fact that their actions is bloody and confessed they are only able to carry out the 'pretty stiff job' after indulging in alcohol. In his defence, Hugh de Marvile, the second knight, recounts the clash the king and Thomas. The kings wants to untie the state under one central administration and sees in Thomas administrator. To ensure political stability, the king wants the offices of Chancellor and Archbishop to be united. Unfortunatley, Thomas resigns his appointment as Chancellor after being appointed Arcbishop as he claims the two offices are incompatible. This action displeases the king as Thomas was deemed to place himself above the king's authority.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "R. B. SHERIDAN:  The Rivals    Discuss the character and role of Lydia Languish in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Lydia Languish symbolizes a romantic lover in the play. She thus given to romantic illusions , day, dreaming and fantacy. She writes a letter to herself in her frustrations over Beverly's love and she reads sentimental novels. She is presented as a sentimental young woman, whose emotional sensibilities are aroused and sharpened by her deep love for Beverly. She is a committed and devoted lover, one whose love is devoid of materialism as she is prepared to the poor Ensign Berverly inspite of her position.      She is however not a strong willled character as she lacks the will to upbrade Beverly for his deception upon the discovery of his doubled identity and she allows herself to be constantly bullied by her aunt, Mrs Malaprop. In her relationship with Beverly she accentuates to the theme of romance in the play. She represent the other side of womanhood , the ideal and the fanciful, in contrast to the practical down - to - earth, and realistic Julia.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "R. B. SHERIDAN:  The Rivals    How does mistaken identity contribute to the development of the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Mistaken identity is seen in Lydia and Malaprop's misconception of the character of Absolute. while Lydia sees him as Beverly, the romantic lover, Malaprop's sees  as Jack Absolute,the son of Sir Absolute.  i. The misconceptions brings out the romantic sides of Lydia's character as she daydreams and romanticizes her relationship with Beverly.  ii. Mistaken identity impinge on the theme of love in the play as it is the basis of the relationship between Lydia and Beverly  iii. It also contributes to the theme of appearance and reality as it reveals the misconceptions of Lydia and Malaprops in their perception of Beverly. In this way the irony in the play is intensify  iv. It also contributes to the humour in the play especially in the relationship between Absolute and Malaprops. Through this technique Malaprop is unwittingly deceived and used as a go-  between in the Lydia - Absolute relationship.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the use of language in \"Ours to plough, not to Plunder\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There is an abundant use of personification in the poem. The personification of the earth serves to elicit feelings of tenderness from man and thus buttresses the point that if we view the earths as another human being, then we would accept the need to handle it with care. There is the symbolic use of dimple on the face of the earth in line three.This further confirms the human features of the earth as beautiful warranting its treatment with care and concern      Through the use of possessive pronoun \"our\" in relation to the earth Osundare successfully communicates the need to jealously guard the earth as a prized possession . There is use of contrast in the title of the poem . The earth is ours to \"plough\"  not to \"plunder\". The contrast between the two illustrates the differences between the creative use of the earth and its wanton destruction.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the use of irony in \"No Coffin, no Grave\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The particular type of irony used is the situational irony examples include the references to the unconventional  way in which the politician dies and is buried. The irony lies in whayt is not said, as well as said. For example, we are told the politician is without a coffin/without a grave where scanvengers perform his autopsy. The \"stuffering rifle\" that snufs off his life is said to do a \"gun salute\" while his mourners are his bullet - ridden car and his vehicle licese plate.  His death is ironical he had planned a haven - to - be - project , an expensive and flamboyant burial for himself in his gold - laden cofin which would be laid \"under the jacaranda tree beside his palace\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the development of the theme of  \"A Valediction: Forbidding Mourning\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem makes a comparison between spiritual love that is platonic and sensual love that is earthly. It seeks to demonstrate the superiority of spiritual love over the sensual and by an ordered earthly. It seeks to demonstrate the superiority of spiritual love over the sensual and by an ordered and systematic progression of thoughts coupled with a logical structure the theme of the poem is presented     The second stanza of the poem introduces spiritual love as a contrast to sensual love . Its superiority is suggested not only by the diction used to describe it but also the images associated to it. The use of conceit and other images in subsequent stanzas serves to demonstrate the fact that physical seperation does not affect spiritual love.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the view that  \"Two look at Two\" is a poem about nature.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "It is indeed valid and sound to argue that the poem is about nature. Aside the pair of lovers all other references concern  nature - the woods with its animals, its trees and stones. These provide the setting or the engagement  of the lovers with the aniamal world represented by the doe and the buck.   In the poem nature is represented as a great reconciler. By bringing down the artificial wall, it allows the lovers to confront  their animal counterparts and learn from them the lesson of tolerance. Nature is also presented as a soother of passions. The lovers find the woods beginning in their romantic adventure.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE: Anthills of the Savannah    Discuss the theme of friendship in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There are various levels of friendship in the novel. The author sees the running of government by a cabal of friends as very dangerous. It could generate rancour and unnecessary pettiness in the government . Then he looks at the genuine friendship like Ikem and Chris, Beatrice and Elewa. Chris defies His Excellency's order to dismiss Ikem thereby putting his position and life at risk in the name of friendship. Beatrice stands at Elewa's side in her moment of grief after Ikem's disappearance.      Also, those in the lower class too exhibit nobility, sincerity and selflessness in their relationship . Emmanuel, the student leader and Braimoh, the taxi driver, are prepared to sacrifice their entire life for the cause they believe in.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE: Anthills of the Savannahh    Comment on the character and role of Beatrice in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Beatrice, the fifth daughter of a headmaster, is named Nwanyibuife after her baptism. A graduate in English with honours from London University, she is, in the words of her boyfriend, Chris, \" a perfect embodiment of my ideal woman, beautiful without being glamorous, peaceful but very strong. \" She becomes senior Assistant secretary in the ministry of Finance in General Sam's government.      Beatrice is perceptive and is quick to notice Chris' resentment of Ikem . She notes with a tinge pof the prophetic that there is \"plenty of trouble ahead of you two\" and calls them into awareness of their responsibilty in correcting the anomalies of the state. Her attitude to love is frank and", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AYI KWEI ARMAH: The Beautiful Ones Are Not Yet Born    Discuss the character and role of Koomson in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Koomson represents the corrupt African who has learnt to \"drive fast\". He is a former school mate and friend to the man. He is ambitious. He is a man who has quickly and cleverly learns the rules of the game and in the eyes of Oyo has succeeded in life, for despite the fact that \"accidents would happen, Joe Koomson has learnt to drive\" He is associated with the image of the latrrine which reveals his rotteness,filth and decay. Just like the users of the latrine, he too leaves his odour on government policies. He accentuates the theme of appearance and reality, for inspite of  is glamour and opulence, he is nothing but a fool and cowardly who flatulates in moment of crisis.He depicts instability in African politics and the deadly risks associated with it, for when the government is overthrown.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AYI KWEI ARMAH: The Beautiful Ones Are Not Yet Born    Discuss the significance of the encounter between the man and the timber merchant in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The timber merchant could not comprehend the man's refusal to accept bribe. The scene brings out vividly society perception of corruption. It shows the esteem in which the morally upright are held in society. Like the timber merchant, a host of other characters including the man's wife and his mother in law insult the ,man for his stance against corruption. The man's encounter with the timber merchant brings out the man's attempt to steer clear of corruption. In his refusal to accept bribe, he demonstrates a willingness to be free of the rot in society. It brings out another aspect of the man's character - his consistency  and uncertainty about the moral righteousness of his stance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THOMAS HARDY: Tess of the d'Urbervilles    Discuss the contribution of Tess' parents to her tragedy in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jack Durbeyfield, Tess' father, sets the tragedy in motion. After his conversation with Parson Tringham, and his apparent discovery of his noble lineage, he goes into delusion grandeur. He refers to himself as Sir John and gets so drunk that he cannot take the cart to the market the next morning. Tess has the responsibility the responsibility, which leads to Prince's death in the accident with the mail cart.       With the prince's death and the loss of the family's source of income, Tess' sense of guilt allows her to be persuaded by her parents to claim Kinship with the d'urbervilles and this leads to the loss her virginity to Alec the single act from which all her subsequent troubles emanate.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THOMAS HARDY: Tess of the d'Urbervilles    Discuss the role of Alec in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Alec represents the rising burgeoisie and capitalist, young attractive and bouyant but cold, impersonal and ruthless. Alec is a contributing factor to Tess' demise.     Alec's relationship with Tess shows the destruction of the peasantry by the forces of modernism. It indicates a collision between traditional agrarian lifestyle and the emerging capitalist tendencies. He represents a dark past of Tess, a past she wants buried and forgotten but which return to plague her.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe    Discuss the influence of religion on Robinson Crusoe in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The influence can been from two major perspectives.  Firstly, there is the view that depicts Crusoe as a religious  man whose life is guided  by providence. This view accounts for his righteous morals on his actions, his daily reflections and meditations on the Bible , his perception of himself as the biblical prodigal son and his gratitude to God for his rescue from his Island.    Through his experiences on the Island he learn to trust and worship God and to give glory to him.He calls upon God in times of distress, reads his Bible  and offers prayers of thanksgiving for his deliverance.      On the contrary, is the view that depicts Crusoe's attachment to religion as hypocritical. Crusoe reflects the puritanical view of religion in the novel. He refers to religion and uses the Bible for his convenience. He quickly forgets the vows and oaths he makes in times of danger as soo as the danger is over.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2003>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe    Discuss the character of Robinson Crusoe in novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Robinson Crusoe is the hero in the novel. There are two sides to Crusoe's character which contrast each other. On one  hand, he is seen as:  a. He is presented as religious. He calls upon God in times of trouble, reads his Bible and offers prayer of thanksgiving to Him.  b. He is intelligent and creative. Against the odds on an unhabited Island, Crusoe's instinct  for survival enables him to successfully adapt to his enviroment.  On the other hand, there is the unattractive side  of Crusoe.  i.  He is a contemptous and proud. He treats Friday with cadascavim and imposes his culture, which he sees as superior to his.  ii. He is self centred and inconsiderate. Driven by his desire of economic independence, he ventures abroad against the wishes of his parents.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Discuss the theme of tradition and change in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The theme of tradition and change is Soyinka's \"The lion and the Jewel\" develop primary as a result of the clash of interest between the character of Chief Baroka that symbolises \"the lion\" and of course represent tradition and the character of Lakunle that symbolises modernity and influence of western culture on other culture.  Soyinka depicts the character of Lakunle, a progressive school teacher that represent modern life in the society whose influence is bound to effect change through his words and mode of dressing. He wears Western clothing, and he had been educated in a British School and nurtures the desire to turn his village ilujinle into a modern city like Lagos.  He proclaimed his love to sidi and promises to turn her into a modern wife who would have equal rights with her husband. Lakunle despises the custom of paying of bride price as awful, barbaric, out of fashion, archaic and humiliating but sidi upheld her beliefs that bride price is the pride of a maiden who is still a virgin that she insists that she would not marry Lakunle unless he pays her bride price.  The character of Chief Baroko, represents the strength of traditions in the play. He opposes modernity and extremely concerned himself with preserving the traditional way of the village. He paid off a surveyor not to route train tracks through ilujinle, thereby robbing off the village the link to the modern world.  The photographer in the play can also be considered as the influence of change. It is as a result of Sidi's portrait in the magazine that made her to actualize her self as an element of change and this makes her to be refer to as the jewel of the village.  In the end, Soyinka closely-knit traditional society with its norms and value and tradition prevails over modernity when Chief Baroka disflowered sidi and wins her hand in marriage.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel  Discuss the use of song and dance in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Songs and dance are seen as means of transmitting information in a community where there is no form of civilisation or modern appliances. Also, it is a means of entertainment for the bored village youths who have no taste of the modern youths who have so many appliances and modern instruments to entertain themselves at all times. In \"The Dance of the Lost Traveller\",  four girls kissed on the ground, forming the wheels of the poor. Lakunle adjusts their position and sits in air in the middle. He pretends to drive the \"car\". The girls dance the stall. They shudder, and drop their faces onto their laps. He pretends to try to restart the \"car\". He gets out and checks the \"wheels\" and also winches at them. He tries to start the \"car\", fails and takes his things for a trek. The songs and dance enhance the theatrical performance of the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit     Discuss the attempts of the Elders to bring Remi home and its significance", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Discuss the attempts of the elders to bring Remi home and its significance   The elders of Marue met  In Act I,scene II to discuss crucial matters affecting their tribe. Such as them not benefitting from independence. Instead, it has brought them heavier and heavier taxation. They grieved on the fact that their tribe isn't being represented in the current government. They then conclude at the meeting that their salvation would be in Remi.     Remi,a youth of the Maura tribe who schooled in the city and return to his village as a political and social leader for his people in the government of a newly independent country. He departed from home having been prevailed by his  father and the elders of the village to marry the widow of his brother,recently killed in an accident. After the ceremony, he flees the reality of the marriage as he absconds to the city and refuses to return. The elders believe when he return, he would lead their tribe back to strength and influence. They agreed to use charm to break his resistance. Therefore, the elect elder travel to the city to plead with Remi and to skillfully drop the charm in his room.  However, the significance of their attempt shows that the people belief in supernatural forces which depicts that their view towards traditions and custom is highly upheld. Also, their attempt sheds  light on their desire to have someone from their own tribe who will represent and speak for their interest.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit   Discuss the character and role of Ngoni in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Ngugi's The Black Hermit, Nyobi is one of the major character in the play. She represent an ideal African woman as she serves as custodian of tradition or as a guardian in the play. For instance, when Remi absconded to the city and left his inherited wife;Thoni, She took her under her care and began taking care of her. That her pastor even encouragea her that God had brought Thoni to her care in order for her to lead her to Christianity.  Nyobi like every other character in Ngugi' \" The black Hermit \" is caught between tradition and modernity. Her commitment to the church and her allegiance to the gods and the culture of her people make her runs to them in difficult time. For instance she agrees and blesses the charm the elect elder who was sent to the city to bring Remi back to the village. At same wise, she seeks the counsel of the pastor and pleaded that the pastor should also visit Remi in the City. Also she is presented through her use of language as firmly rooted in the culture of her people. Although, she is not portrayed  as a strong willed character in the play,nevertheless she didn't withhold  her criticism towards Remi of been the caused of Thoni' death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "RICHARD B. SHERIDAN: The Rivals    Discuss the conflict between Lydia and Mrs. Malaprop in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Richard B. Sheridan's \"the Rivals\" tells an impenetrable love affair of a seventeen year old book obsessed girl, Lydia Languish, who is under the guardianship of her aunt; Mrs Malaprop. These infricacy are Lydia Languish delusion built on various romantic novels she has, and desires to marry for love and into poverty. It is in this light that she came into clash of interest with her aunt.    Lydia Languish finds the idea of eloping with a poor soldier, Ensign Beverly to be adventurous, she doesn't know that captain Jack Absolute; a ranking office in the military has disquised into \"Ensign Beverly\".   Mrs Malaprop is against lydia's choice of poor suitor and demands she marries whomever she suggests to her. Mrs Malaprop endorses Jack absolute among other suitors such as Bob Acres and Sir Lucius O'Trigger. Lydia understands what is at stake as she is bound to lose two third of her inheritance if she marries without her aunt's consent.  Deceit, disguise and scheme trial the plot of this comedy of manner until the resolution of conflict.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "RICHARD B. SHERIDAN: The Rivals  Discuss the character of Captain Absolute in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The character of Captain Absolute in R. B Shendian's \"The rivals\", is presented as a character with double identity in the play. His character strengthens the theme of mistaken identify or disquise as the case may be. He is the son of Sir Anthony Absolute, a wealthy aggressive authoritarian father. He is a captain in the British Army. He cunningly tricked his father from imposing his dictatorial views and threat on him. It is father has arranged a marriage for him to aid his personal social status and also threatens to disinherit him should him reject his offer.  He is charming, witty and brave that he tricks lydia into believing he is a poor Ensign Beverly in order to take advantage of her romantic disposition.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>7>i", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    Discuss any this literary devices used in the play:    The Chorus", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "T.S Eliot employ the use of chorus to depicts danger, fear and agitation in the play. The chorus in murder in cathedral is composed of a group of women of canterbury.  At first the chorus delivers a sense of foreshadowing as they approach the cathedral they foretell that danger awaits but certainly not for them. \"There is not danger for us, and there is no safety in the cathedral T.S Eliot uses the chorus to warn the audience that danger is coming by providing an abridge of the past.  It is also through Eliot use of chorus by the women of canterbury that the audience is enlightened that the archbishop, Thomas Becket has been away for seven years and is now returning to canterbury.    On Thomas Becket return, the women of the chorus fear for his safety and beg him to leave canterbury, then it became apparent that the (Thomas Becket) is to die they then resigned to fate.    After the death of the Archbishop, the chorus made the audience to know that martyr had been made in canterbury.    T.S Eliot made use of the chorus to mirror the feelings that every person would have in reaction to Becket's death and uses it to provide a link between the various segments of the play.", "marks": "8.5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>7>ii", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    Discuss any this literary devices used in the play:  The Interlude", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Eliot use of the interlude in his Murder in the Cathedral serves as an opportunity for Thomas Becket's, the tragic and a self reflection on his Fate to die. The interlude is written in prose and delivered on christmas morning by the tragic hero who talks about the duality of celebrating both christ's birth on earth and his passion and death. Through his sermon, Becket expresses his anxieties and his determination to die a martyr as he abandons himself to be a pure instrument of God. The sermon with a farewell since he doesn't think he will ever preach to them again.  Eliot uses the interlude to depict the tragic hero's turning point submitting himself humbly to the will of God.", "marks": "8.5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>7>iii", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "iii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    Discuss any this literary devices used in the play:  Imagery", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "T.S Eliot deploys the use of quite a number of imagery in his play \" murder in Cathedral \". First is the use of Biblical imagery through which Becket defines his destiny – his martyrdom. Thomas Becket links the Christmas Birth and Passion / Death together to express the full meaning of martyrdom.   Eliot tactfully presents the imagery of light and darkness. This elements vividly represent the struggle between the two powers that is occurring within the play. Light and dark imagery is used throughout the play to show the disparities between Church and State. The state (King Henry II and those in his ruling class) is generally presented by dark imagery that portrays a somber and serious mood. The church on the other hand, is portrayed with a lightness that leans toward the idea that godly rule is to be desired.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    Murder in the Cathedral is a tragic play. Do you agree?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "T. S Eliot \"Murder in the Cathedral\" meets the qualities put forth by Aristotle's definition of a tragic play. According to Aristotle: a tragedy is the imitation of an action that is serious and also having magnitude, complete in itself. Consisting an exciting emotion of pity and fear presenting a reversal of fortune of a renewed person.  Basically, the draws of Aristotle's idea of tragedy is the tragic pleasure of pity and fear the audience feel watching the tragic play and these were the characteristics of T-S Eliot's \"Murder in the Cathedral\".  The use of chorus in the play sets the dark tone of restive, fear; danger and agitation in the play. The protagonist and the tragic hero is defeated by his own tragic flaws of pride. His ideal are in stark contrast to the King Henry's as his request to access the church courts are refused.  Eliot uses the four tempter to reflect Beckett's inner conflicts, his love for pleasure his ambition for power, the coalition to become greater and the desire for immortality through martyrdom. He then rid himself of these temptation to attain moral integrity.    The dramatic conflict that qualities Eliot \"Murder in the Cathedral\" as a tragic play occurs between Beckett and the King Henry and this conflict of interest lead to the killing of the Archbishop Thomas Beckett for his betrayal to the thing as it was fore mentioned that they were close friends before his exile to france for seven years.  The purgation of emotions of the audience at the end of the play also qualifies \"Murder in the Cathedral\" as a tragic play. Despite the Archbishop's weakness, sympathy is given towards his brutal death.  Therefore, Eliot's \"Murder in the Cathedral\" is a tragic play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on Cheney-Coker's use of language in the poem \"Freetown\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Though freetown is the title of the poem, it is also the state capital of Sierra-leone, a British Ex-colony. The poem begins with an apostrophe'. Africa I have long been away from you\". The poet, sly cheney coker had had to flee his country when his then President Siaka Steven ruled with an iron fist and people who had dissent views were threat to the country, hence, coker went on exile in the 1970s. Back to the poem, the persona freely expresses his thought on his country, race and people in simple poetic expressions. He compared his wandering to the fulani, a nomadic tribe who move about with their cattle.  The persona expresses his disgust in \"the shame of your race as womb of the Earth\" (line 9).  Africa is seen as the origin of all human race among whom Africans bear the shame of poverty, deprivation and under development.  He further takes a sarcastic swipe at his female compatriots! \"My sisters who plaster their skins with the white cosmetics/to look whiter than the snows of Europe\". The use of language from the excerpt shows the loss of African's identity as they strive to be who they are not. Africans inhumanity to fellow Africans is criticized in line 24  \"Creole masters leading native races\"  This line refers specifically to the situation in freetown, where the half.  Caste descendants of the slaves freed and settled on the land, look down on the original inhabitants of the country and refer to them in derogatory terms as the natives\". The language of cheney-coker's \"freetown\" is direct and denotative.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the character of Ulysses in the poem", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Afred Lord Tennyson' Ulysses\". The open lines of the poem introduce us to the persona of the poem as a king who gains nothing from just sitting on the throne, around Fire  with his wife and making laws to the people. This presents him as a person who has a strong propensity for adventure.  \" It little profits that an idle king,/By this still hearth, among these barren crags,/Match'd with an aged wife, I mete and dole/Unequal laws unto a savage race,/That hoard, and sleep, and feed, and know not me.\" Line 1-5  Ulysses expresses his intense dissatisfaction and boredom on his island home of Ithaca.Although his journeys have had share of joy and sorrow on him.   _\"I cannot rest from travel: I will drink/Life to the lees \". Ulysses is also presented as one who is trusting that he left the affairs of the state into the guidance of his son. He is also portrayed as an experienced and knowledge person that through his journeys,he had encountered different characters, climates, etc and he has been reverend by them all.  Finally, Ulysses; being a practical realist, expresses the fact that he's getting older and doesn't have a lot of time left, so he wants to get busy living rather than busy dying. The poem concludes with his resolution to \"strive, to seek, to find, and not to yield.\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2004>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the use of imagery in \"Ode to the West Wind\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Percy Bysshe Shelley' \" Ode to the West Wind\" shows the correspondence between the inner and the outer world of the poet. It tells the poet's intention to become a force that may bring the change and rejuvenation in man's life.   However, the poet deployment  of imagery of nature through the west wind as an agent accentuate  his excellent use of imagery in the poem as it progresses from the beginning till the end. The poem commences with the imagery of the earth;the earth is mostly associated with the femininity-fertility, rebirth, and stability. It then shifts  its attention to the imagery of the air; the air is the source of communication because it carries thoughts far away. It is a symbol of inspiration and creativity. Although,it destroy, it also encourage new life as well as hope. Thus, the detail descriptions of the imagery of air create a sensory experience of the poet's inspiration for the creation of such a poetry that may go far beyond his reach and bring the change and revolution far and wide. The third  imagery is that of water. Water is associated with the ability to feel and the intuition to know. Finally, the imagery of fire.The fire is usually the image of hopelessness, destruction and death. However,it works as a preserver as well. The fire is immediate in its action thus represents action orientation.  Notably, there is a fifth element that represent the spirit of a poet-prophet figure. Metaphorically described as the 'West Wind'. The west wind as the fifth element represents a force that could dominate even the most powerful elements----earth, air, fire, and water. The persona of the poem wants to be both the west wind itself and the objects the west wind spreads in order to  bring some revolution among the mankind.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit.    Discuss the character of Thoni in the play, bringing out its significance.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James Ngugi's The Black Hermit is a play that highlights various problems and challenges the newly formed African countries faced after gaining independence.  The character of Thoni as presented in the play symbolises an African woman who obeys the traditions of the Marua tribe and remained faithful and committed to marry Remi; the younger brother of her late husband. Even when Remi rejected her and abscounded to the city, she patiently and faithfuly awaits his return. She refuses her mother-in-law's advice to take another husband but her commitment to the relationship fueled her refusal.  However, Thoni's inability to remain unwavering at challenging moment like Remi's refusal to live with thus her decision to commit suicide.  Thoni's character in the play helps to highlights the theme of traditionalism in the play. And her unyielded love relationship with Remi contributes to the development of the plot and unfolded other aspect of the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JAMES NGUGI: The Black Hermit.  To what extent do the characters realise their ambitions in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The church and tribe feel let down at the actions of Remi which falls short of expectations as the man among them to lead them, promote their customs and traditions and hence unit its member. Unfortunately, Remi's action further disintegrated the tribe.  Thoni's ambition to settle down with Remi remains a mirage as Remi flees to the city. She commits suicide in the course of time due to this rejection.  Jane's ambition to hold on to Remi and probably manouvered him to marry her is not attained as Remi returns to the village much to the amazement of Thoni. She feels betrayed and vents her anger on him.  Furthermore, Omange's political ambitions are not realized due to the lack of support from Remi and his contrastive views on politics. He is also frustrated by the division and disunity in the tribe.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Consider the dramatic significance of the first meeting between Lakunle and Baroka.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The first meeting of the two suitors of Lakunle has multiple significances to the play. Baroka the old suitor shows up suggests action continues as it were before his coming as he does not want to be the \"Chief Baseje\" meaning one who spoils or ruins things. Deep down however, besides being a competitor to Lakunle, both men are always at loggerheads because of some dirty old secrets. This scene is an Exposition as various deeds of the Baale are revealed to the audience and sidi who do not have the information.  Lakunle exposes how Baroka foiled the plan of the colonial masters to construct a railway line into the village.  Baroka, for the fear of civilization and its antecedents consequences diverted the rail line to a neighbouring village after giving heavy bribes to the construction workers.  Baroka's fear is that is ilujinle becomes civilized like lagos for example, he would lose the grip he holds on the village. This information was relayed to Lakunle by his father and it is one if the reasons he detests Baroka. As far as he is concerned, Baroka is his greatest stumbling block in turning. The village into a great city where men will pay no bride price, women will cook with modern kitchen equipment and so on. Besides the instruments of flashback and exposition which dominate this scene, the two men also flaunt their capacities in winning sidi, the jewel.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel  Compare and contrast the characters and roles of Sidi and Sadiku in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Sidi is the \"Jewel\" in the play and she represents the present generation while sadiku, the eldest wife of Baroka represents the older generation. In similarity, both women are manipulated as pawns in the hand of a skilful chess player: Baroka. The two women are victims of patriarchal society as men in the play view than as possession which should be taken. Sidi, though she clings tightly to her views on the compulsory payment of bride price and would not yield to the whims of the educated school teacher, lakunle, she admires her beautiful pictures splashed on the pages of the magazine which the city photographer brings. This shows sidi as an evolving character who bridges the past with the future. Unlike sadiku who is predominantly classical. She views women as weaker beings who do not match the prowess of men especially is issues relating to marriage. Sadiku is stark illiterate alongside her husband who exploits her gullibility in claiming sidi for himself. A sharp contrast between the two women is that while sidi has a mature and independent mind to vehemently refuse her two suitors, Baroka and Lakunle, Sadiku is naive, uneducated, weak willed and very gullible. Another similarity in these two characters is their unbridled tongues which form their strongest character defects. Baroka knows his wife would not keep his supposed impotence a closely guarded secret. Sidi also fails to wisely manage the information but chooses otherwise to taunt the Baale.  There is no much difference between the old woman sadiku and sidi at the end as Baroka had successfully exploited their weakness in achieving his aim.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral    How does the chorus contribute to the action of the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In T. S Eliot \"Murder in Cathedral\", the chorus contributed largely to the element of tragedy and actions in the play. The chorus that composed by the ordinary women of canterbury is used to first delivers a sense of communication an encapsulation of the past to the audience. It is through the chorus that the audience became aware that the tragic hero; Thomas Beckett has been away for seven years and is now returning to canterbury.  The chorus also serves as a sense of foreshadowing; as it reveals the danger that awaits at the cathedral. The women of the chorus fear for the safety of the archbishop and beg him to leave canterbury but when it becomes apparent that he will die they resigned to the tragic hero's fate.  The chorus reflected the emotions of the audience and the action of the play; the fear, regret and faith of the women of the chorus mirrors the feelings that an everyday person would have in reaction to Thomas' death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "T.S. ELIOT: Murder in the Cathedral  Discuss the view that Thomas' martyrdom is self-imposed", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Thomas Becket of the T. S Eliot's \"Murder in the Cathedral\" is the tragic hero of the play.  According to Aristotles in his poetics a tragic hero of a tragic play must evoke a sense of pity or fear within the audience, stating that \"the change of fortune presented\" must not be from \"bad to good\" but reversely from \"good to bad\" such that misfortune is visited upon this tragic hero\" not through vices or depraivity but by some \"error of judgement\", this error or hamartia refers to a flaw in the character of the hero that leads to his downfall or misfortune.  Therefore, the view that the death of Thomas Becket as a self-imposed martyrdom is an assertion.  First is the temptation scenes in the play that clearly reveals the mind of Thomas as portrayed by the tempters in the play which serves as externalisation of his thoughts. Thomas's quest for \"saintly glory\" is realized when the fourth tempter tempted him, he became apparent towards the situation at hand and the genuiness of the direction of his thoughts shocked him. The tempter confirms his desire for sainthood through his conversation.  In support to the revelation of Thomas Becket's flow of thoughts during the visit of the tempters is his sermon on christmass morning gives a confirmation of his longings for martydom as he refers to some of the biblical character that gave up their lives for the sake of peace. Through the interlude in the play, Thomas insisted that a martyr is not merely one who dies for christ, instead the true martyr is one who has become the instrument of God who has lost his will in the will of God thereby has found freedom in his submission to God. The closing of his sermon also ascertain the self-imposed martydom when he said \"I do not think I shall ever preach to you again\" - The statement alludes the potential of his impending death and martydom.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "RICHARD B. SHERIDAN: The Rivals    Discuss the theme of mistaken identity in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This is the most dominant theme in the play which enhances the play's comedy of manners. Captain Absolute disquises as an Ensign Beverly to win the affection of Lydia who has developed fantasy for a lover of low birth through her romance novel. This mistakenly identity further heighten the plot of the story as Bob Acres, another suitor of lydia detests \"Beverly\" and challenges him to a duel while ignorant of the fact that captain Absolute is the Beverly. In another instance of impersonation, and mistaken identity, Sir Lucius O'Trigger, an irishman and another suitor of lydia believes he is corresponding with her but unknowingly, lucy a scheming maid of Mrs Malaprop delivers lucius letters to Mrs Malaprop. False hope, aspirations, fantasy and love are raised ignorantly by several characters until the end of the play when the real identities of the names are unveiled: Captain Absolute is the fantasised \"Beverly\" and Mrs Malaprop finds out her supposed admirer does not really exist.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "RICHARD B. SHERIDAN: The Rivals  Comment on the relationship between Julia and Faulkland.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The character of Julia in the play symbolises a moral core, she is a beautiful and moderate orphan betrothed to faulkland by her father before his death. She loves Faulkland and tolerates his excesses. However, Faulkland is very jealous and worries she is being unfaithful even after she had professed her love to him. Towards the end of the play, he devises a plan: he tells her he has gotten into a fight and is to flee the country. He expects her to decline as a confirmation of his ceaseless doubts but Julia agrees to flee with him and marry him. This erased the doubts he has and opened up to her that he is only testing her. Julia is upset by this distrust and angrily calls off their engagement. Faulkland's plan had achieved the opposite of what he intended. The two characters further strengthen the theme of arranged marriage in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the elements of culture in J. P. Clark's \"Abiku\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Abiku in African traditional belief is a child who dies several times after birth and still keeps coming to the world to punish his mother based on affiliation with his or her \"kindred spirits\". Particularly common in the yoruba mythology, the Abiku child is one of sorrow who derives pleasure in the affliction of his mother who has watched him die at her hands on multiple occasions. The elements of culture in the poem shows measures adopted to understand and unravel counter - measures that are applicable in dealing with the Abiku child. For example, it is shown in line two that Abiku lives in \"Baobab tree\".  Nocturnal birds that signify evil omens such as the \"bats\" and the \"owls\" are also used to represent Abiku. As a means of discouraging Abiku from dying, some parts of his body are inflicted with injuries to make him \"deformed\" to his kindred spirit and also to identify him should he come again. \"We know the knife-scars / serrating down your back and front / like beak of the sword fish / And both of your ears, notched\".  The excerpt above from the poem shows Abiku's cars are notched to compel him as a bondsman to his family and never depart again. Communal disposition to Abiku is often fierce to as he viewed as a cruel child who only makes his mother's joy transient. This societal stereotype is premeditated: Compel him to stay.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the theme of \"No Coffin, No Grave\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The theme of vanity is central to the poem. The poem recounts the end of a dictator, who dies a cruel and miserable death without a coffin or grave despite the great national resources at his disposal while alive. The line three of the poem shows how \"scavengers performed the postmorten\".  The poem shares historical peculiarities with several African leaders who were brutal, nothless and dictatorial but death has a way of teaching the vanity of power, wealthy position and influence when it comes knocking.  The persona uses lofty sarcasm to mock the dead ruler who was obviously killed. \"In front of night club\". As a national leader who is expected to be given a gun salute, the gun shot the ruler got was his \"state burial anyway\". All the expensive possessions he had acquired, obviously from looted public funds lie waste as the \"car knelt\", the red plate wept, wrapped itself in blood of it's master\". Towards the ending of the poem, the persona reveals the kind of burial the ruler had desired for himself\" . . . In a gold-laden coffin/like a VIP/under the Jacaranda tree beside his palace/ a shelter for his grave/ and much beer for the funeral party\". . . All these lofty dreams were unachieved as his body rots. The vanity of power and affluence.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the theme of permanence and change in \"Is my team Ploughing\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "A. E Housman's \"is my team ploughing\" is a realistic poem that recounts a vital lesson of the way the world works. The poet's use of question and answer technique in the poem accentuate the theme of permanence and change in the poem. Every stanza of the poem starts and ends with quotation marks which indicate that they are from the voice of the speaker perceived as one from the grave while words without quotation marks are responses from the friend.  The theme of permanence which is somewhat the central purpose of the poem accentuate the simplest terms of life that life goes on that deaths do not cause permanent disturbance in everyone lives. Although certain situation may change but they will gain back momentum in time.  Stanza two of the poem strengthens the assertion of change . . .\"Aye, the horses trample, the harness jingles now\" No change though you lie under, the land Tou used to plough\". Also line 13 and 14, \"Age, the ball is still-flying the lads play heart and soul\". The speakers quest to know the changes that occur in his absence made a huge impact and empowers the theme of change as it portrays the speaker's lover of having a less emotion and concern towards the speaker as she is seems to have forgotten him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE: Anhills of the Savannah    Discuss the significance of His Excellency's Cabinet meeting", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Achebe's \"Anthills of the savannah\" is a socio-political novel that set the fictitious nation of kangan. The story begins with the cabinet meeting that reveals the current political situation in this newly unprepared nation of British rule, the hopes and dreams of democracy have been quashed by a force military dictatorship government of Sam.  Sam is a sterm career soldier who becomes the president of Kangan and being a soldier whose aim is to fight against external aggressor of his country. Sam succeeds the former leader who was toppled with the help of his friends: Chris Oriko and Ikem Oshodi. Sam surrounds himself with his childhood friends with the hope of getting good counsel from them.  However, Sam soon gets intoxicated with power and becomes what his friend chris calls \"Baby Monster\". Sam adopts \"president for life\" and \"His Excellency\" appellations.  The activities in his cabinet meetings portrays him as a bully. The cabinet members spend their sessions with him in fear, anxiety and intimidation.  Significantly, the cabinet meeting also reveals the incapability of Sam of providing leadership the country needs, he tolerates no dissenting voice and maintains an air of supremacy over all. Cabinet members scamper for safety at the sound of his voice and inadvertently, he is surrounded by men pleasing sycophants.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "CHINUA ACHEBE: Anhills of the Savannah  Comment on the character and role of Chris Oriko", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Chris Oriko of Achebe's \"Anthills of the Savannah\" is one of the three intimate friends in the novel besides Sam and Ikem. Chris is the Minister of Information appointed by a friend turned dictator-Sam. The crucial ministry he heads manages and disseminate information particularly as it concerns the government and people of Kangan. Out of public interest and patriotism, he had supported the ousting of a government to pave way for his friend Sam whom he thought would bring sanity into governance. He actively plays the role of an arbitrator between sam and ikem Osodi. Osodi is the Editor-in-Chief of the National Gazette which is under Chris' ministry. Ikem, a vocal critic, Journalist and public speaker never hides his disdain for the dictatorial tendency of their Friend Sam who now desires the title of \"President for life\". Chris understands this as a very dangerous game and tries to warn Ikem and also pacify sam, though he detests the emerging dictator in sam. His Excellency, Sam later orders Chris to sack Ikem but almost for the time, chris stood his ground: Sam should do it himself.  This daring act from Chris makes Sam to term the action as a conspiracy against him by his two friends. In this view, chris tries to protect his interest by ensuring the safety of his own life, his girlfriend; Beatrice and Ikem. After the sudden murder of Ikem by state police, chris tries to flee with his family and Elewa; Ikem's pregnant wife. While on the news, the news filters in that sam has been toppled. An argument arose between a militia and chris which leads to his being shot.  Chris exudes the character of a human rights activist, a loyal friend and a voice for the oppressed.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe    How does Crusoe survive on the island before Friday's arrival?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Daniel Defoe's \"Robinson Crusoe\" is an epistolary, confessional and didactic novel, an autobiography of the title character Robinson Crusoe. It is a realistic Fiction of a literary genre as it recounts the vigorousity, perseverance, courageous and resilience character traits of the protagonist, Robinson crusoe.  Robinson Crusoe leaves England and a home which provides him with all the material comfort which he can desire in order to satisfy his thirst for adventure. He had a shipwrecked on an inhabited island with very few resources at his disposal yet his survival on the island depends on how resourceful he is in handling challenges of feeding, shelter and clothing. Before friday's arrival on the island; friday.    He caters for his feeding through several journeys to the wrecked ship and salvages all edible such as bread, liquor, cheese, sweet etc. He grows rice and discovers turtles as a source of meat for him. Also, he improvises pots, baskets and ovens to facilitates the collection of food and cooking.  Crusoe solves the challenge of shelter as he sleeps several night on tree tops, he later pitches a tent, converts cave into a home, all with the quest of providing secured shelter for himself.  Before Friday arrives the island, Crusoe retrieves as many clothes as possible from the ship including shoes and head clothes, he convert animal skin to sew jacket and to make boot.  Finally, Crusoe survival skills includes is unwavering faith in God and divine intervention, he reads the Bible and kept a faith that against all odds he survives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2005>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "DANIEL DEFOE: Robinson Crusoe  Bring out the Signifiance of Robinson Crusoe's First Voyage?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Robinson Crusoe as a young and impetuous wanderer, defiled his parents and went to sea. He ignores his father wishes for him to become a lawyer and runs away to secure free passage to london on the first of september, 1651. Not too long, misfortune begins in form of rough weather. The ship he boarded is forced to land at Tarmouth.  The significance of Crusoe first voyage is the fact that his friend learns about the circumstances under which he left his family and becomes angry, tell him not to have come to sea and for this reasons they parted ways. Crusoe could not stand the humiliation of going back home makes his way to london, boarded another ship (voyage) headed to Guiana.  Also, the first voyage strengthens the theme of adventure and brings out the resilience character trait in crusoe. His quest for adventure is non-competible even in the face of tribulation and misfortune he remain unwavering to his mission to be a seafaring man.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty      Discuss the effect of war on the people of Urukpe", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "It is expected that whatever involves violence can only bring injury, pain, sadness and loss. The people of Urukpe are not exempted when war befalls them. One of the people the war really affects is Aku. She is neglected and scorned in the society so bad that she could hardly move out of her house due to fear of being attacked by the people who were already traumatised and hard-hearted as a result of the war.        The war also makes Brigadier Major Ali's job of maintaining peace more difficult. The war also affects Chief Toje's rubber business, which leads to the fight between him and Oshievire because the latter's business continued to boom.         Aku has to suffer for three years with her child, during the time her husband was sent to prison. Due to hunger and poverty caused by war, Aku finally succumbs to Toje's sexual advances with the hope of him providing her with money and other things that will aleviate her suffering through the war.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty      Examine the role of Major Ali in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Major Ali S . Idris is the Brigadier Major otherwise called a military governor of the army in Urukpe. All through the novel, he portrays habits of a morally upright man. He aims at humanity in all his actions towards the people who need him in Urukpe.        Major Ali constantly carries out his duties without being biased and he properly addresses issues before taking decisions. This is shown when he refuses to believe all that was  said about Oshievereeven though he could do nothing about the latter's plight. Instead he sends guards to Aku's house to watch over her and her child when he feels she is in danger.       He also executes a soldier who killed another man during a quarrel. Ali believes that even if he has to hurt people in carrying out his role, what is right must always be upheld. He is an upright man who can withstand any opposing force while carrying out his duty.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    \" A man is never Ugly\" Using this statement as your starting point, examine the relationship between men and women in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Joys of Motherhood is a story which illustrates the biased relationship which exists between men and women in the eastern part of the country. In this novel, men arre considered superior human s whom must be respected, pampered and served by a feminine gender. It doesn't matter whether the man is ugly, poo, rootless or uncaring, a woman still has to worship at his feet.         Nnu ego suffers this gender discrimination greatly in her first husband (Amatokwu's) house and shee continued enduring in Nnaife's house. It is alright for a man (Amatokwu) to marry a second wife while the first wife is neglected but when the wife complains, she is rebuked. A woman who also give birth to a female child is useless because she can't poduce a male child that will contin ue the family lineage.          Nnaife kept marrying more wives even though he realise he can't feed them all, at the detrimeent of the wellbeing of the woman and their children. No one dares question their authority which will make women suffer at the end.         However, Buch portrays th error in this culture when the male children Nnu ego bore were successful but ended up being useless. Nnu Ego was cared for by her female children during her aged years while her male children abandoned her. The shows that the saying ' a man is never ugly'  according to the story, it is wrong because the acts of most men in the book are beastly and inhumane.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    How does Nnu Ego's experiences in Amatokwu's house advance the plot of the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Being the apple of her father, Nwokocha Agbadi's eyes, Nnu Ego was married to Amatokwu in an elaborate way, the people of Ibuza remember for very long time. She got married but was unable to concieve, which led to scorn and hatred from her husband. In Ibuza, a barren women is as good as useless.       In no time, Nnu Ego was given a separate hut while while Amatokwu brought home another woman to share his hut as a wife. The second wife concieved and bore a son which was like fuelling the fire that was Nnu Ego's maltreatment in Amatokwu's house. Her husband insulted her the more and Nnu Ego's sorrow increased.      The second wife takes in again and was in labour when Nnu Ego picked up the first child and decided to breastfeed him. Amatokwu sees her, hits her repeatedly and snatches the baby from her. He accused her of trying to kill the child due to her bitterness.       Nwokocha Agbadi rises to the occassion and takes his daughter away from Amatokwu's house, to stop her suffering.      The life of Nnu Ego in Amatokwu's house is the starting point of Nnu Ego's life of suffering which continues till the end of the story.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    What does wright's childhood experience with his family reveal about him?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Richard Wright is the hero in the prose, Black Boy. Life was shaped by his experiences and what he witnessed right from childhood. At the tender age of four, Wright set's fire to his grandmother's house knowingly and that was just his wrong doings.        Wright didn't just start doing this, due to his thoughts alone but by happenings around him. He was the product of a broken home where his  mother who was around wasn't healthy enough to take good care of him. His grandmother was too strict with her beliefs while his mother was constantly ill. As a result, he became a reserved child who prefers reading in solitude than playing with his peers. He believes he wants to be accepted for who he is because his decisions of being an athiest has been cause of disapproval for him all the time.       Wright is surrounded by unsatisfied and judgemental family members, racially segregated and violent society. With this he became violently resistant and ruthless.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy      Examine the causes of violence in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel, Black Boy is characterised by fights, violence and brutality. The reasons for all these is not far-fetched because all quarrels are between blacks and whites. In Southern America, discrimination of the black when treated as such, but when some blacks like Richard show disapproval they are beaten up.         Whites also kill blacks at will without being persecuted. A good instance is when uncle Hoskins was murdered by whites who were jealous of his profitable saloon. Bob was also killed when some wives thought he was having an affair with a white girl.         The racism caused so much problem in the book that two black men can even become enemies. An example is the fight that broke out between Harrison and Richard.           Every violent act recorded in the book, Black Boy is one way or the other connected to racial discrimination.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: A Man for All Seasons    Comment on the friendship between Silas Marner and Williams Dane.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Duke of Norfolk in \" A Man For All Seasons\" is Moore's friend. He is a simple-minded man who acts upon what he knows and is easily swayed by what others say, sometimes contrary to what he believes. He supports Moore so many times especially when Cromwell tries to invove him in the plans to implicate Moore wrongly. An example is when the Duke dismisses the point that Moore recieved the cup as a bribe, further pointing out that Moore already gives the cup out when he realised it was a bribe.         However despite the Duke's friendship with Moore, Moore is too stupid to know what is going on around him which eventually led to Comwell encouraging him to betray Moore's friendship.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    What role does fate play in the development of the plot?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Sir Thomas Moore can be described as an unbending and disciplined man. No matter the situation, Moore always stands by his principles of moral upstanding and clear conscience. Moore's refusal to sign the oath of parliament's Act of supremacy even to the point of death shows that he cannot turn his back to what is right. This leads to the conflict between Sir Thomas Moore and the authorities.         Though Moore does not speak when he is not asked and neither does he force his opinions on others, people like Comwell and Rich seeks his downfall till they succeed. King Henry plans to divorce his wife in order to mary Anne but More thinks it is improper. Moore being a man of his words refuses to change his opinions till he is implicated and sentenced to death.         Thomas Moore's character in opposition to the norms of the authorities portray conflict between moral standards and a corrupt filled government.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY    How does Rubadiri present the destructive force of the thunderstorm in \"  African Thunderstorm\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "David Rubadiri pictures the violent nature of thunderstorms in his poem. He describes how the storm starts from the west (in line 1) suddenly and swiftly with so much face that anything in its way is blown away or broken. The storm is likened to the destructive nature of locust in a farmland and the violence a mad man displays which makes everyone stay clear off him.       In verse two, David describes how objects are moved from their places and the introduction of lightnings which accompany thunderstorms. The lightnings wreak havoc by making houses go up in flames. Then the downpour begins.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    What does Clarke find fascinating about the dancer in \"Agbor dancer\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poet in \"Agbor Dancer\" describes a dancer with steps that are so mesmerizing that one can't help staring. The speaker is fascinated about how the dancer is so absorbed in her dance, moving with different dancesteps to the ancestral rhythm of the drums. The speaker seems interested in the skill displayed by the writer in dancing sync with the drum which symbolises her culture and her interest in it.          In line 1-3, the speaker describes the process the dancer goes through before she settles in the \"ancestral core\" where she dwells with rhythmic interpretation of the sounds. She is so deep in it that it engulfs her whole being beyond what mouth and pens can describe. The lines explain better . 'Limbs like fresh foilage in the sun' (line 5), line 12 '.... her heart a descent', line 13 '... quick to her fingertips' and line 14 '... and to es...'       The speaker wishes to join her in the deep exploration and pleasure she gets in the her culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the use of poetic devices in \"The Solitary Reaper\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Silas Marner is the protagonist in the book 'Silas Marner'. Williams Dane is a friend of Silas whom the latter trusts so much. Silas thinks he has a friendship worth keeping with William but William ends up stabbing him in the back. William frames Silas by placing his knife in the Deacon's drawer and taking the money contained in it. With this, Silas is accused of stealing the money and murder of the deacon.       William also displays his cruelty when he succesfully tampers with the drawing lot which as a result confirms that Silas is guilty. When Silas leaves his home town and settles in Raveloe due to this betrayal, William doen't hesitate in getting married to Silas' fiancee, Sarah.       Though Silas holds William in high esteem, William shows habits of wickedness and betrayal of trust. These are characteristics that shouldn't be found in good friends.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on the effectiveness of the houseman's use of imagery in \" To an Athlete Dying Young \".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The sequential arrangement of events in \"To an Athlete Dying Young\" are developed with instances of so many predestined events. The event which leads to Silas' relocation to Raveloe is a doing of fate, because nothing could have been done to prevent it.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Raveloe, Silas suffers another blow dealt by fate when Duncan Cass steals his gold, making the joy he derives from his money disappear within seconds. Fate later bestows good fortune on Silas Marner when a baby crawls into Silas's hut, making Silas have a child to show love to and live with even without getting married.   &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;   Sixteen years later, Eppie is 18 years old and her biological father, Godfrey still hasn't approached Silas to claim her as his . This is fate's way of dealing with Godfrey's promiscuity which leads to the death of his wife. Godfrey and Nancy do not have any child, so Godfrey has to live 16 years of his life without his daughter. When he finally approaches Silas about the paternity of Eppie, she refuses to go with him and continues her stay with Silas.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Discuss the dramatic technique used in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The dramatic techniques used in the book \" Sizwe Bansi is Dead'' are flashback, humour, plot and dramatic monologue.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Flashback used casts the minds of readers back to the beginning before Sizwe Bansi becomes Robert. This is used at the beginning of the book.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Humour is present in the play, an inevitable feature of a satire. A serious issue of a black man living in penury and a tragic life is portrayed in a funny way.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Plot in the book doesn't start from the beginning. Rather the events are arranged in sequence from the end to where it all begins.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There are also lots of instances of dramatic monologue portrayed by styles in the book.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: SIzwe Bansi is Dead    Comment on the theme of the search for identity in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Search for identity in the play 'Sizwe Bansi is Dead' is a common situation most black South Africans have to deal with repeatedly. Their entire lives are contained in a passbook, which can alter their future and determine their fate with simple stamp made by a white man.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is the predicament that befalls Sizwe Bansi who is not allowed to work as stated in his passbook. He wis given a deadline to return to King William's Town, his hometown before a stipulated time. Sizwe and his family are condemned to a life of poverty due to his inability to work. As a way out of his predicament, Sizwe has to forfiet his identity and take up that of a dead man, Robert Zwelinzima.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sizwe, Buntu and Styles struggle to maintain their identities under the oppressive rule of the whites. They take photographs of themselves to preserve their identity and also strive hard to live the best life they can.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE DE GRAFT : Sons and Daughters      \" Our society is sold on money: nothing is worth anything unless it brings money. \" How does this statement reflect an aspect of the conflict in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "'Sons and daughters' is centered majorly on the conflicts which occurs between James Ofosu and his two young children concerning choosing thier fields of study. James feels he has to choose professions for his children because they are not worthy or sensible enough to choose thier careers.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; James Ofosu is a man of strict principles who thinks it is ridiculous to become an artist and dancer, just like Aaron and Maanan have decided to. He constantly argues with his children, saying Aaron and Maanan have to become an engineer and a lawyer respectively. This decision of James is biased because he believes the course 'art' cannot provide the money needed to sustain one's life.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; James doesn't hide his hatred for arts by repeatedly rebuking his children and chasing Awere, an artist out of his house. On the contrary, someone who studied a notable profession (law) ends up displaying a terible immoral act, showing that James has been wrong all along.  The saying\" Our society is sold on money; nothing is worth anything unless it brings money'' which is upheld by James Ofosu in the story is contradicted when Awere, whom James condemned so many times sells one of his painting for two hundred and twenty pounds - an indication that one can earn huge sums of money through art. James eventually gives in and allows Aaron and Maanan study their courses of choice.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE  DE GRAFT; Sons and Daughters      Discuss the character and role of Hannah in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hannah is James Ofosu's wife and the mother of George, Kofi, Aaron and Maanan. Though Hannah is an uneducated person, she thinks well and makes good judgements in situations. Maanan succesfully balances the role of a wife and that of a mother. She tries to convince her husband to allow Aaron and Maanan study the courses they desire but immediately he gets angry, she keeps quiet.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The character of Hannah portrays though it is good to be educated, an uneducated person can also be knowledgeable, disciplined and have good moral standard in the society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Discuss the theme of corruption in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the book 'The Government Inspector' corruption is common in the activities of the Mayor and the supposed inspector Hlestakov. Hlestakov, a foppish civil servant with a wild imagination was mistaken for the inspector that is sent to investigate them.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The corrupt nature of the Mayor who collects bribe from the people and merchants, makes him quickly succumb to the demand of Hlestakov. The Mayor and other members who are guilt-ridden decide to cover up their misdeeds by further showing acts of corruption. This makes Hlestakov become rich in no time, considering the huge sums he recieves.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hlestakov is also a corrupt man because he is an impostor. He pretends to be someone else and with the power vested in that position, he commits all kinds of atrocities before the real inspector arrives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Examine the use of satire in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'Goverment Inspector' is a satirical play which aims at exposing and ridicling the corruption common in the 19th century Russia. The leaders in the book are deceived by a clever boy who deceives them into believing he is the Inspector. Being corrupt and not wanting to be reported by the Inspector, the Mayor provides every demand the Inspector makes.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Satires are humorous and they have exaggerated characters. This is present in the book with the numerous funny scenes shown or displayed. Each character represents a different social ill which Nikolai Gogol wish to point out. Eventually, everyone is rewarded according to his deeds: even the impostor, Hlestakov is caught in the end as a liar and thief; a corrupt man also.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Seasons    Examine the use of poetic devices in ''The Solitary Reaper''", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "'Solitary reaper'  is a ballad by William Wordsworth which captures the beauty of the song a girl sings to herself while cutting grain in the field. The poem contains a lot of poetic devices related to sound, Like the use of onamatopoeia in stanza 2 (Cuckoo-bird).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; William uses alliteration in stanza two. ' More welcome notes to weary bands ' ( 'w' alliterates). '... the silence of the seas' ('s' alliterates). Apostrophe is also present in line 7 where the speaker calls upon soomeone imaginary to listen to the song.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Rhetorical question is used in stanza 3 in two instances to further emphasize William's interest in the melody the lady sings. All these poetic devices point out the lyrical aspect of the poem which is necessary in a ballad.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2006>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Seasons      Discuss the conflict between Sir Thomas More and the authorities", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 'To An Athlete Dying Young', Houseman uses widows, doors and other portals to create imageries in the mind of readers. Doors and windows are used to exit to another side, just as death moves in and out of them. With this, the speaker makes us think the death of the athlete as passing through rather than passing away.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Shrubs and flowers are also used to represent victory, affection and respect for the dead. In lines 11 - 12, 'laurel' represents victory while 'rose' represents respect for the dead.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Home is also used to describe death as moving from a house to a new one. This is explained at the end of the first stanza where the speaker recalls the athlete being carried home on the shoulders of the crowd to be delivered to his own doorstep. The athlete's new town is a peaceful place, but still a graveyard.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    Examine Emecheta's use of irony in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Buchi Emecheta used lots of irony in her book \" Joys of Motherhood\". The title of the book is the first irony represented in the book. All through the novel, the heroine, Nnu Ego never enjoys motherhood. She suffers through pregnancy and toils to take care of her children. At the end she dies miserably despite having rich sons that stayed abroad.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, Adaku who breaks all norms of a typical Igbo woman's lifestyle lives a life of enjoyment and happiness while Nnu Ego who respects her culture and tradition has nothing to show for it at the end.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The male gender which is also held in high esteem in the book ends up being useless and irresponsible. Men like Amatokwu, Nnaife, Oshiaju and Adiamabua show different levels off irresponsibility in the novel.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    What role does superstition play in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Superstition is one of the major tips in Buchi Emecheta's Joys of Motherhood. First, Nnu Ego is considered a reincarnation of a slave who was brutally buried alive with her master's corpse. Ngozi's ( Nnu Ego's first child's) death was also related to the anger of this slave woman who is Nnu Ego's god.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is also superstitious that a girl's father should be the one to choose her huusband just like Agbadi did for Nnu Ego. Another belief is the supremacy of the male gender over the females. Females are considered useless because they can't carry on the family's lineage. Barren women are also considered witches who don't want children in the real world.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Every incident in the novel is related to one superstition or the other. Even death is never considered a natuaral phenomenom which requires some special activities. An instance is the act of burying slaves with their masters. Burials are also considered very important even if the deceased died in an abject poverty. An Example is Nnu Ego and Agbadi's elaborate burial", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    In what way does Toje contribute to Oshevire's tragedy?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Toje is a rich business man who always has things done his own way. His rubber business experiences loss and this makes him negatively jealous of Oshievere who's business boomed during the period. Toje repeatedly finds way to send Oshievere packing because of this and with the use of his corrupt practices and with the help of some corrupt  and incompetent officials. Oshievere is sent to three years imprisonment.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the period of war it is difficult for Oshievere's wife, Aku who has to find means of survival for her child and herself in the absence of her jailed husband. Toje uses the oppurtunity to shower gifts on Aku to get into her pants. Aku who is in desperate need of financial help agrees to have a sexual relationship with Toje. Upon Oshievere's return from prison, salt is added to his injury when he learn that Toje now has carnal knowledge of his wife. The bitterness of Oshievere later leads him to his death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    With reference to the text, discuss the theme war.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'The Last Duty' is a novel which focuses on the effect of war on the citizens of the countries involved. Though violence is never the answer to any problem in societies, the ego, wickedness and impatience of a few stake holders condemn lots of citizens to lives of deprivation, hardship and struggle to survive.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the civil war in Zonda, Simba troops tear apart the relationship between the peaceful lives of the Zondas and the Igbo people. The war also causes Oshievere and Aku to be torn apart due to Toje's wickedness. The war causes not only devastation of farms and residences, mass killing of soldiers and civilians, missing children and rape, but also the invisible psychological wounds it creates in people's lives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Compare and contrast a Silas' life in Lantern Yard and Raveloe.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Silas Marner, while living in Lantern Yard is a devout christian.  He has a fiancee, Sarah, a friend (William) and also holds the church in high esteem. Silas is betrayed by William who creates a lot of incidence that makes Silas to be tagged a thief and a murderer. This humiliation makes Silas Marner leave for Raveloe.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Raveloe, Silas refuses to have any interaction with other people because he still carries about the hurt he feels from the unjust circumstances that led to his exit from Lantern Yard. He stays indoors and gets buried in his job which earns him lots of money. Silas blames God for not justifying his innocence, so he denounces God and stops being a christian.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silas who derives joy in his money becomes depressed again when Dustan Cass steals his money. Unlike in Lantern Yard, Silas is sympathised with during his predicament. With the arrival of Hephzibah in Silas' life , Silas experienced joy once again even to his later days. His neighbours embarrass him and his child and he continues living in a peaceful environment where he is loves.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Examine the use of superstition in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Superstition can be attributed to the inexplainable circumstances which Silas experiences for so many years of his life. The deacon's money mysteriously disappears from the drawer and Silas is found as a murder weapon. With this Silas' planned out life is disputed because he discovers his friend is a traitor as well as his fiance who betrays his trust.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also, it is by chance the baby crawls into Silas' cottage giving him a chance at happiness again after he is robbed of his money. Fate smiles on him again when he now has a child.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All through the book, unforseen events which have certain meanings and outcomes are portrayed.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Discuss the relationship between Richard and his father.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nathan Wright, Richard's father only appears in the book for a short while. Nathan is physically intimidating and he frequently beats Richard - an addition to Richard's life of abuse. He is part of Richard's life for a while before he abandons his fatherly responsibilities and leaves his wife and child.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The departure of Nathan from his home shows that he is weak, simply pathetic. This contributes to the lifestyle Richard lives all through his life.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy     What are the causes of Richard's problem with Aunt Addie?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aunt Addie is one of Ella's sisters, making Richard her nephew. Addie lives at home, Granny in Jackson, Mississipi and she shares Granny's intense religious nature and teaches at a religious school which Richard briefly attends.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard's decision to be an atheist is the main cause of Addie's hatred for him. She believes it is wrong for Richard not to embrace Christianity just like the other members family do. She shares Granny's spite for Richard and tries not to miss any oppurtunity to beat him or humiliate him at home or even in school.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She makes it her mission to make Richard miserable due to her constant method of correcting Richard's bad habits.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss the theme of love in Senghor's  I will pronounce your name .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "'I Will Pronounce Your Name' is a love poem which Senghor uses to celebrate love for Negritude ideology in the form of a young African woman by the name, Naett. Senghor expresses his affection for Naett through the lines of the poem. He makes reference to Naett's beauty in accordance with African culture.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The character of Naett can be considered to represent the African continent. Though Africa is usually degraded, Senghor shows that whatever people think does not demean the beauty of the continent.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Though as Leapold writes, Naette has experienced some level of \"shame\" in being banished from Futa, he decides to become her sorcerer, proclaiming her name. He also promises to immortalize her through spoken words (voice) which the African culture lacks or has been refused to be heard.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on the theme of conflict of cultures in Kobena Acquah's  \"In the Navel of the Soul\" .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The dominant theme in Kobena Acquah's \" In the Navel of the Soul\" is the theme of conflict. The poem illustrates the opposing ideas and finding of traditional practices and activities of experts. In verse1 the midwives with a feeling of their hands detect pregnancy but in verse 2, the experts say otherwise. With their observations and laboratory tods, they declare that the woman is not pregnant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kobena further affirms the midwives' findings in verse 3 that there is indeed development in the woman's womb. Then the speaker shows frustration, disbelief and anger at the words of the experts. She believes there are too many deciets in their findings because even with the evidence clear as day, they still ignore reality and make conclusion from their fixed ideology.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In verse 7, the experts decide that if the midwives feel the woman is pregnant, they are all insane. With this, the speaker decides that if whatever they believe in is really madness, then they are happy being mad because truly, she also feels the movement of a baby in the womb; 'a spirit refusing to be drowned in its own water before birth' (lines 30-31).   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poem illustrates the conflict between African culture, its method and Western culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on Frost's use of symbolism in  \"The Road Not Taken\" .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James Ofosu thinks it is necessary to choose careers for his children who are not interested in the chosen courses, engineering and law. The the job of gaining admission for Aaron and Maanan is put in the hands of lawyer Bonu (James' friend).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While James thinks lawyer Bonu is a trusted friend, it is ironical the lawyer will make amorous advances towards Maanan against everything James thinks of him. James intends to save his daughter from a life of sexual exposure that will be her lifestyle as a dancer but his fears are confirmed not with dancing but with his immoral friend who wants to have sex with her.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the end when James gets wind of lawyer Bonu's intention, he realises how wrong he (James) has been all along, so he allows Aaron and Maanan study their courses of choice.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    How does Houseman present the theme of death in the poem  \"To An Athlete Dying Young\" .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Death, in \"To An  Athlete Dying Young\" is presented in a gentle and peaceful way. Though peaceful and a transition to another world, death is a check on the mortality of the humans. The athlete with so much achievement and great dreams has his life cut short early in life. The speaker ccntinues to speak to the dead athlete though he can no longer hear him. This makes the readers imagine themselves in the athlete's running shoes and consider their mortality and their value for fame and glory.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A large portion of the poem is recited at the funeral where the athlete's remains is brought to his new home.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Discuss the theme of racial discrimination in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sizwe Bansi is Dead is a book which mirrors the hardship black South Africans faced in the hands of the whites. During the apatheid system, pass books were used to violate the human rights of the blacks. The lives of the blacks are cut out by whatever is written in their pass books. They are ordered to go, live, work and survive with the provisions of the passed books.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This affected the lives of so many South African blacks, with Sizwe, Buntu and Styles as typical examples. They were subjects to lives of misery and poverty due to restrictions imposed on them by the authorities. Sizwe's life comes to an end when he takes up the identity of a dead man, Robert Zwelinzima so that he can earn a living in order to take care of his family.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the book, lives of blacks are meaningless and amounts to nothing, the blacks had to struggle through life to maintain an identity while trying to make living worthwhile.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Comment on the use of comedy in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The level of humor in the play, \"Sizwe Bansi is Dead\", causes readers to laugh out loud even in the face of the sad lifestyles blacks live in South Africa. For instance, when Styles tells the story about his days working in a South African food factory he uses hilarious anecdote about the day Henry Ford comes to visit.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The comic part of the book are so entertaining that one can hardly believe that the South Africans can find humour in such severe situations. The authorities are also described in ridiculous ways, adding to the humour in the book.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Discuss the use of irony in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James Ofosu thinks it is necessary to choose careers for his children who are not interested in the chosen courses, engineering and law. The job of gaining admission for Aaron and Maanan is put in the hands of lawyer Bonu (James friend).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While James thinks lawyer Bonu is a trusted friend, it is ironical the lawyer will make amorous advances towards Maanan against everything James thinks of him. James intends to save his daughter from a life of sexual exposure that will be her lifestyle as a dancer but his fears are confirmed not with dancing but with his immoral friend who wants to have sex with her.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the end when James gets wind of lawyer Bonu's intention, he realises how wrong he (James) has been all along, so he allows Aaron and Maanan study their courses of choice.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Examine the relationship between James and his two children, Maanan and Aaron.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aaron and Maanan and the third and last children of James Ofosu respectively. James Ofosu sees his children as not mature enough to make important decisions that concerns their life. He is an unbending and rigid father who doesn't take lightly the questioning of his orders. Though he successfully chose courses for his first and second sons, George and Kofi, Aaron and Maanan prove hard to be controlled.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; James is a father who loves his children by wanting them to pursue professions that will make them successful in life, but he doesn't care about how they feel. Nobody questions his orders but when Aaron and Maanan's educational issue became a serious one, the house of the Ofosu's becomes heated and unpleasant. The relationship between father and children becomes strained and hostile due to the father's controling behaviour and the children's will to be independent and in control of their lives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    How is corruption exposed in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The entire society in the play \"The Government Inspector\", is corrupt. The mayor metes are untold hardship on his people by collecting bribes at the slightest opportunity. The Mayor's sins are so numerous that when he hears of the Inspector's arrival he quickly tries to persuade him not to report him to the authorities. The Inspector who is an impostor readily accepts the bribe offered and asks for more from the Mayor but other characters in the play are ignorant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hlestakov is also corrupt by pretending to be who he is not which is a criminal offence. He also decieves people into giving huge sums of money to cover their crimes, though he has no power to do so. The people also inflate the prices of contracts with the knowledge of the Mayor who is in support of criminal acts.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The drama points out the moral decadence among the people in authority which shouldn't be so. At the end, nemesis catches up with all the corrupt people in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Examine the use of mistaken identity in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The fear of being discovered to be perpetrators of corruption related crimes makes Mayor and other officials be on the look-out of any government representative who comes to the area. Ivan Aleksandrovish Klestakov, an official from St. Petersbourg who has been in the district for two weeks and lodged in an hotel without paying for anything is mistaken for the government Inspector, thinking he has always come to inspect the city secretly.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This makes the Mayor and other officials mistake Ivan for the inspector. They quickly bribe him to cover up all the atrocities that are the norms in the city. Ivan being an equally corrupt man, quickly takes advantage of the situation but he is later discovered.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Seasons    How does Thomas More demonstrate moral uprightness in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Thomas More is an upright man who believes in following the right moral principles. He is the protagonist of the play who has to deal with different opposing factors trying to shake his will but he remains unbending. In the preface of the play, Bolt calls More \"A hero of selfhood\" because More refuses to sacrifice himself, which he denies by his moral conscience, even as he sacrifices his life.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More is man who puts his faith in society's system of judgement - the law. Throughout the play, More is considered a representative of a concept (morality) rather than person. The king therefore seeks consent to his decision to get married to his lover but is dissappointed and bitter when More's morals contradicts the king's actions.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This is the beginning of the end for More, as he is sentenced to death due to his refusal to sign the Act of Supremacy.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2007>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON - AFRICAN POETRY                                         Comment on Frost's use of symbolism in \"The Road Not Taken\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Symbolism helps to add more details to a poem and allows the readers to get literal examples to poems. In the poem \"The Road Not Taken\" making a decision is symbolized as a fork in the road (line1) where there are two directions and one has to be taken. When the speaker is faced with this decision he wants to follow through both roads but life is not like that. Life is full of difficult decisions with close alternatives but one has to think of the advantages one has over the other to make the right decision.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"The Woods\" in the poem signifies ' Indecision' as well as 'yellow leaves' as the season of autumn where leaves fall and decay. All these are the confusing circumstances surrounding the speaker's decision making process which are also present in man's everyday life.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    Discuss three instances of conflict in the novel.``", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The first conflict at the beginning of the book \" Joys of Motherhood' . Nnu Ego is at a point of disagreement with her chi god whom she believes is responsible for the death of her first child, Ngozi. She decides to commit suicide by jumping into the water to meet her chi where she can question her for causing her suffering.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Another conflict in the book is the inadequacies of Nnaife in contrast to Nnu Ego's wish to create a family filled with with love, knowledge and happiness. Nnaife drinks with all his money and marries numerous wives at the expense of a happy famiy which is the dream of Nnu Ego.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Lastly there is conflict between Nnu Ego and her fate. Though Nnu Ego struggles all her life in order to become successful, everything seems to be against her - her father, the government and sadly, her children. She manages to send her male children to school and though they are successful they neglect her and she dies in penury, loneliness and suffering.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joys of Motherhood    Discuss Emecheta's narrative technique in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The narative techniques use in the prose by Buchi Emecheta are characterisation, flashback and irony. Every character in the book represents an aspect of the message meant to be passed. Nnu Ego suffers through life but she has a happy childhood and teenage years when she is showered with love from her father, Agbadi. Other characters also contribute to the themes of discrimination, poverty superstitions etc.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Buchi also uses a perfect flashback which takes us from the beginning of the book where Nnu Ego plans to commit suicide to her background, her first married life and why she wants to kill herself.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is Ironical that the book is titled \"Joys of Motherhood\" when there is no joy in Nnu Ego's giving birth of many children. Though her children became well off, they are too self - centered to take care of their mother.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Comment on the theme of rivalry in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Last Duty centres on lots of disagreements between people and groups with the instances of war and rivalry. Toje, a man who deals in rubber business decides to make Mr. Mukoro Oshievere's life miserable due to the latter's successful earnings concerning his business. Toje eventually succeeds in sending Oshievere to prison due to his wickedness and jealousy for a fellow business man.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Oshievere spends three years in prison and upon his return he discovers that his tormentor now has sexual relationship with his wife, Aku. This is the capper on the jug, because it makes Oshievere terribly bitter.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Minimal rivalry leads to a war that affects every inhabitant of Urukpe who has to suffer through with physical and emotional scars to live with for a long time.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Discuss the role of Omonigbo Rukeme in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Omonigbo Rukeme is an accomplice of Mr London Toje in the process of unjustly jailing Mr. Mukoro Oshievere. Even when he knows that Toje's actons are unjust, he still accepts bribe in order to indict Oshievere in court. However the evidence Rukeme provides is irrelivant and baseless, so it is dismissed. The fair Judicial court refuses to send Oshievere to prison for the two-count charge against him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Discuss the theme of betrayal in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silas Marner is a weaver, a devout christian, Sarah's fiance and William's friend. His life in Lantern Yard is cut out already and peaceful until things take the turn for worse. William whom Silas trusts betrays him by making him labelled as a thief before the church in Lantern Yard. Silas is cast away and also deserts him which leads him to life in Ravelou.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The betrayal of William serves as a conflict which tears Silas apart from his planned out life to that of uncertainty, isolation and sadness in his ealy years at Ravelou.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Which evidences from the novel, show that \" One reaps what one sows\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Silas Marner, though aflicted and betrayed never hurt anyone. He sows to humility, love and good character, so in the end, he becames successful and happy with his little family.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dustan Cass, who is a thief and a gangster ends up dead out in a stone pit near Silas' house immediately after stealing the money.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Geoffrey Cass, who is unfaithful to his wife ends up childless all through his life. With his infidelity he indirectly kills his wife and makes his daughter live in the custody of Silas. Though Geoffrey eventually marries Nancy after his wive's death, their union is not blessed with a child.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Examine the factors that make Richard a distinct personality", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard Wright, the hero of the novel ' Black Boy' is a peculiar character. He is tough and very intelligent. He loves reading, wrriting, thinking and would do all this rather than play with his age mates. He is also an atheist which makes him always at logger heads with his family.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard is determined to live according to his own principles, refusing to accept that blackness, lack of religion and intellectual curiosity makes him inferior or flawed.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He becomes hardened and strong-willed, a liar and a thief due to the circumstances surrounding his childhood and community. He is brought up in a hope which lacks love and affection and is abused a lot by family members and other people in the community who believe in oppressing the blacks Richard eventually accepts himself and lives on.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                      RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Discuss the contribution of Mr.Crane and Mr. Olin to the development of the plot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard Wright, the hero of the novel ' Black Boy' is a peculiar character. He is tough and very intelligent. He loves reading, wrriting, thinking and would do all this rather than play with his age mates. He is also an atheist which makes him always at logger heads with his family.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard is determined to live according to his own principles, refusing to accept that blackness, lack of religion and intellectual curiosity makes him inferior or flawed.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He becomes hardened and strong-willed, a liar and a thief due to the circumstances surrounding his childhood and community. He is brought up in a hope which lacks love and affection and is abused a lot by family members and other people in the community who believe in oppressing the blacks Richard eventually accepts himself and lives on.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: SIzwe Bansi is Dead    Examine the view that life is meaningless for the blacks in South Africa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With a stamp on a black man's passbook by a white man, the black man's life is already cut out for him and has to live by the rules stated in the passbook. This makes life extremely difficult for so many black South Africans.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sizwe Bansi has a stamp on his passbook which forbids him to work. With this Sizwe and his family are reduced to a life of abject poverty. It is also stipulated in the passbook that Sizwe has to  return to his hometown within  a short period of time. In his desperation he has to change his identity to that of Robert Zwelinzima so as to earn a living.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In this book, the lives of blacks mean nothing. Whites order them around and make living hell for them. Blacks like Sizwe, Styles and Buntu now have to struggle really hard before they can make ends meet. They vow to make every moment of their lives count even if the whites don't think so.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ATHOL FUGARD: SIzwe Bansi is Dead    Discuss two dramatic techniques in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  'Sizwe Bansi is Dead' is a satire which aims at exposing the ills of the South African society, especially in the aspect of hostility and discrimination of blacks. One of the dramatic techniques used in the play is flashback. In the first pages of the book Sizwe is already Robert Zwelinzima. In the course of the book Sizwe's story of how he has to change identity was narrated.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Satires require sarcasm, humour and ridiculous characters to make the story live up to its name. There is enough humour to cause laughter though there is terrible maltreatment experienced by the blacks.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Discuss the character and role of Aunt Fosuwa in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aunt Fosuwa is the paternal aunt to George, Kofi, Aaron and Maanan but at times she is best described as an intruder. She meddles in the affairs of her brother (James) with his family. Aunt Fasuwa supports Lawyer Bonu's sexual advances towards Maanan, so when Maanan and her mother want to report the matter to James, she (Aunt Fosuwa) objects.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aunt Fosuwa has low moral standards and she is meddlesome. The private matters of the Ofosu's household is her paramount business, which shouldn't be.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                      JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Discuss the conflict between the two youngest children and their father in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; James Ofosu creates a disagreement between himself and his two youngest children when he enforces a course of study on them. Maanan wishes to become a dancer while Aaron wishes to be an artist (painter) but James refuses, choosing law for Maanan and engineering for Aaron.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This causes heated arguments in the house of the Ofosu's all the time. Lawyer Bonu already secures admission Aaron overseas and is determined to change his course of study on getting to school, without his father's knowledge.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James being the adamant person he is, entrusts the job of grooming Maanan to be a lawyer in the hands of Bonu who has other agenda. James is so strict and trusts his friend so much that if Maanan reports Lawyer Bonu's actions to him (James), James won't believe. At the end, when James sees how wrong he is later frees his children to study their courses of choice.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Discuss the significance of the encounter between the protesters and Hlestakov in the Mayor's House.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A small Russian town headed by a Mayor recieves a letter that a government inspector is coming to their town very soon. This makes the Mayor who is a corrupt man become terrified at how  much trouble it will cause if the Inspector finds out his corrupt acts.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Khlestakov is mistaken as the inspector and he demands huge sum from them to cover up their crimes. The villagers are sick and tired of the Mayor's corruption so they match to the Mayor's house and begs Khlestakov to dismiss the Mayor. Khlestakov is dismayed by the Mayor's corruption and says he deserves to be exiled in chains. Saying all this, he collects more money from the protestors, promising to comply with their request. This makes Khlestakov ask for more money to cover up the crime.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Examine the character of the postmaster and contribution to the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The post-master is a simple-minded person who opens the letters to expose the real face of Klestakov. He alerts the Mayor and its officials about being deceived into paying huge sum of money to a fake government inspector. He further proves his point by intercepting a letter by Hearst to his friend to show that he is not the real inspector but a fake one.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ROBERT BOLT: A Man for All Seasons    Discuss the decline of values in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The decline of values in the play \"A Man for All Seasons\" is an attribute of majority of the characters, who represent the English political system. The only man who stands up for what he believes is More and he ends up paying for it with his life.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The King of England King Henry decides to divorce his wife Catherine but the church is against it. This causes the major conflict in the play. He does everything in his power to punish whoever and whatever stands in his way. An example of this is More who is later sentenced to death.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard Rich is an object of greed, selfishness and wickedness. He soccumbs to temptation of wealth and status, though he later acts humane when he becomes aware of his moral shortcomings in the predicaments of More.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also,Thomas Cromwell who is supposed to uphold what is right, as a lawyer plots against More until he keeps him behind bars. Cromwell has an evil nature and facilitates More's downfall with only a minimum of guilt.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON - AFRICAN DRAMA                                      ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Seasons    Discuss the theme of friendship in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Rubadiri's language shows that the thunderstorm comes softly and swiftly. 'Clouds come hurrying with the wind' (line 2), 'Sharply' (Line 3), \"whirling'' (line 7), 'the winds whistles by' (line 14 and 25).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The thunderstorm is also violent. This is portrayed in line 8-9 (tossing up things on its tail like a mad man chasing nothing), lines 14-15 (madly), line 28 (flying off) and line 30-31 ( as jagged blinding flashes rumble, tremble and crack).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The distruction caused by the thunderstorm is also described in vivid words. Destruction as shown in line 6 (like a plague of locust), line 27 ( clothes were like tattered rags), line 32 (admist the smell of fried smoke) and line 33 (and the pelting march of the storm).", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY                                         Discuss contrast as poetic device in  \" In the Navel of the Soul\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contast all through the poem. First, there are two different groups of people (midwives and experts) who have different ideologies, beliefs and findings. Their methods of findings also differ. The midwives use their hand (get in their fingers upon our navel), which is readily available and easy to use while experts conduct tests to determine their answers and conclusions. \"The urine test they ordered said negative\" (line 5). As a result-+/, their findings and conclusions are different; the midwives say there is a baby growing in the woman's womb while the experts say their test shows she is not pregnant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also, there is contrast in words in some lines. This is seen in line 13-14( the things that are done in your name/ I mean the things that are undone) and lines 21-22 ( we are not sure-No. we are not sure). In the poem there is contrast in culture and words to show the ever opposing beliefs of Africans and the western culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY                                         **What is the poet's attitude to affliction in \"On His Blindness\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"On the Blindness\" is a sonnet written by John Milton, a blind poet. The speaker reflects on his used days and seems concerned about what he hasn't been able to achieve due to his blindness. He is nervous, thinking that if God feels he has not used his talent (ability to write) well, he may be condemned. This can be attributed to the story of Lord and his servant in  Matthew 25 where the Lord dealt out a severe punishment to one of his servants who hid his talent instead of using it ' ... and present I my true account, lest he returning chide' (line 6).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Then the speaker has it in mind to ask if God demands work even from those who don't have their sight, just like a labourer with sight will work in the dark but patience being personified talks to him before he could ask. Patience makes him understand that God is complete and doesn't need work or talents of any kind. Patience further tells him that if he really wants to serve God, he has to accept his yoke because Kings (God) also have people who wait on them and stand in readiness until their actions and services are needed. 'They also serve who only stand and wait'.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON- AFRICAN POETRY                                         Discuss the theme of change in Yeat's \"The Second Coming\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"The Second Coming\" is a poem which gives account of christians' belief that Christ will come again into the world. The worlds is already aware that this is going to occur (some revelation is at hand, surely the second coming is at hand), but it is going to happen when no one expects (Hardly are those words out when a vast image of out of spiritus mundi troubles my sight). This is when the change will occur.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the second coming, the world is going to change from a steady one (that twenty century of stony sleep) into a disturbed and violent one. Lines 1 - 8 describe the disorder that will befall the earth at the approach of Christ. Then when the change occurs it is not going to be as pleasant as it was when Christ was first born in Bethlehem. Humans are therefore admonished to be prepared for the change which is inevitable.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2008>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY                                         Discuss the theme of friendship and betrayal in \"A Man For All Seasons\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Theme of friendship and betrayal in the play \"A Man For All Season\" explains how More, an innocent man ends up being sentenced to death. Rich is a low-functionary with whom More helps establish though More suggests he become a teacher. With this Rich serves as a betrayal for Sir More when he provides himself at More's trial in exchange for a post as the attorney-general in Wales.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;King Henry VIII, the King of England who is regarded as a moral person cares greatly about what More, a man of great moral repute, thinks of him. He decides to put his conscience at ease by forcing More to sanction the King's divorce from Catherine.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Examine the relationship between Aku and Oshevire.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Aku is Oshevire wife and their union is blessed with a child. However their union is cut short when Oshievire is sentenced to three years in prison.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With Aku scorned by the community, the on-going war and the financial calamity that befalls her, Aku gives in to Toje's sexual advances. Aku thinks she will have enough financial security to get through the hard times with her child. Due to Toje's sexual incompetences, Aku had sex with Tojee's niece and this causes a fight to break out between uncle and niece.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On Oshievire's return from prison, he finds out that his matrimonial home has been defiled by the same man who unjustly sends him to prison. This further adds to Oshievire's pain.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Discuss the impact of the war on Toje", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. London Toje, a rubber business man witnesses losses in his business due to the on-going war. War, which never breeds anything good, regardless the circumstance creates psychological damage in Toje to the extent that Toje sees another successful businessman, Oshievire as a threat to him.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Toje proves his wickedness and inhumanity by doing everything possible to put Oshivire behind bars and he is successful. He further asks his (Toje's) wife to himself in his absence.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Though Toje is a ruthless man, the war brings out the more beastly character and also provides suitable avenue for his corruption to be carried out.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joy Of Motherhood    Discuss the significance of the Ona-Agbadi relationship", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ona and Agbadi are the parents of Nnu Ego. Ona as a proud woman is not allowed to marry but can have lovers and bear children who will be owned by her father if thy are males. Agbadi is a powerful hunter who is rich and is one of the pride of Umunna.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Agbadi loves Ona but she refuses to marry him. When he is almost killed by an elephant. Ona spends weeks by his side, nursing him back to earth. With this Agbadi realises that Ona loves him and torments her back. She later becomes pregnant and with Nnu Ego moves in to live with Agbadi after her father's death. Ona dies during child birth while carrying her second child.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joy Of Motherhood    Examine Obi Umunna's influence on Ona", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Obi Umunna is Ona's father. Because he has no son to continue his lineage, he has forbidden Ona to get married. He allows Ona to have lovers who can get her pregnant and he tells her that if she bears a son it will be his but a girl can belong to the child's father.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, when Obi Umunna dies, Ona moves in to live with Agbadi as a wife with Nnu Ego.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Examine the role of Richard's Mother in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ella Wright, Richard's is a woman who believes in severe methods of discipline and she is devout to her children. She is fiercely determined to raise them up successfully after her husband abandons the family.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ella shows a special tolerance and acceptance for Richard, that we do not see in any other character. Ella is constantly sick and suffering but she still shows care for her children. For instance, Ella walks on her weak legs to give Richard a hug when she learns that he will be getting a job in a defiance of Granny and Addie's wishes, suggesting that she takes genuine delight in her son's success.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    With reference to the text discuss the character of Richard as a self-determined person", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richarrd Wright the hero of ' Black Boy' is a self detgermined boynwho knows what he wants and goes for it, not a person that accepts wha life dishes out, with folded arms. He believes in his worth and capabilities - an attitude which constantly puts him at odd with his family.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Richard is young, he is determined to live according to his own principles and willing to live with the consequences. He becomes an athiest which was a crime in the face of Granny an Aunt Addie. He writes and publishes a book \"The Voodo of Hell's Half Acre\" which causes outrage in the family but he doesn't care.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He makes it his mission not to accept any form of discrimination from whites and this put him in a lot of trouble. He educates other blacks that they are not inferior to the whites so shouldn't act like one.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Examine the role of money and gold in the life of Silas in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The changing forces of Silas' life revolves around the bag of money in Lantern Yard and the gold in Ravelou. The miaaing bag of money found empty behin Slias' chest of drawers, turned Silas's life upside down. Slilas had to leave Lantern Yard when he was found guilty, suspended and when his fiancee, Sarah broke up with him. He leaves for Ravelou where he leads an unhappy and isolated life.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After a while in Ravelou, Silas earns a lot of Gold through working and gradually he sees a reason to live for but his happiness was short-lived when Duncan Cass steals his gold. This reduced Silas to a life of Sadness again for a while.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The bag of money and gold shows that wealth is part of a driving force to live in the book.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Examine how William Dane affect the fortune of Silas Marner", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; William Dane is a friend of Silas whom Silas trusts. William betrays Silas by putting the bag of stolen money in latter's chamber. This results in why Silas is labelled a thief. His life is disrupted; he lost his faith, fiancee and was suspended in his church. This makes Silas stgeady life to become disorganized.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;William didn't hesitate to marry Sarah, Silas ex-fiancee. This further proves that he is not a good friend. This single act brought shame and unhappiness Silas and he has to relocate.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Examine the Significance of ''Sizwe's Death''", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \" Sizwe Bansi is Dead\" is a book which clearly narrrates the ordeal of black South Africans in the period of aparthy. The blacks are considered less human and are treated badly by the white Lords in every aspects of their lives. The willingness of the Blacks to maintain their identity becomes difficult in the face of humiliation, poverty, discrimination and inferiority.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sizwe as provided in his passbook, was not allowed to work and has exceeded the time the whites permitted him to use . If caught by the authority he will deported to his hometown, so, he decided to 'die' and take up the identity of Robert Zwelinzima. With his new identity he can work so as to provide for his family and also stay in the country.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This is the type of fate that befalls most of the blacks in their own home land. Their lives are considered irrelevant and made to work long hours of hard labour.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Give an account for the preparations for Ford's visit to the assembly plant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Agbor dancer is used to praise African culture. The dancers step match with rhythm in awesome moves that the mouth and hands cannot explain. It is caprivating as the dancer is filled deeply with its riches and knowledge.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The speaker feels intrigued so much that he yearns to associate himself with the African culture. He wants to get lost in the deep provisions and meanings of its life-changing rhythms just as it does to the Agbor dancer.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Discuss the Character and role of Mr. James Ofusu in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James Ofosu is the head of the Ofosu family. He believes in having the final say on issues and doesn't like it when his orders are questioned. He chooses Medicine and Accounting for George and Kofi respectively and they listened and did exceedingly well in thier fields.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;However, reverse is the case for Aaron and Maanan who wants to become an artist and a dancer respectively. They refuse their father's demand of them to study engineering and law and this infuriates James. A man who isn't used to having his orders questioned had tom deal with this issue of course everyday. He is commanding and demanding.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Afterwards, when he saw Lawyer Bonu, his much trusted friend, trying to kiss Maanan in his (James) house, he reluctantly lets go of his dictatorship and allows Aaron an Maanan pursue the courses of their dreams.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; James represents parents and guidiance who think they have absolute power over their children. However, this era demands that it is the right for someone who wants to start a journey to be able to pick his or her destination.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    To what extent is the play about friendship betrayed", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Betrayal of trust caused the climax in the play ' Sons and Daughters'. James Ofosu trusts Lawyer Bonu so much that he entrusts him the care of his children, especially Maanan. He told Lawyer Bonu to groom Maanan to become a great lawyer like him.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On the contrary, Lawyer Bonu has another task at heart. He wishes to have sex with Maanan. Though Maanan protests, he seems not to understand the clear mesage and keeps trying anyway. At the end , he tries to kiss Maanan in her father's sitting room and it was there, James realizes of a pathetic excuse for a friend Lawyer Bonu is.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Though James trusts lawyer Bonu so much, the latter betray James trust and this single act leads to the climax. James unwillingly succumbs to his children's wish and allow them to make their decisions.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                      NIKOLAI GOGOL: The Government Inspector    Discuss the theme of deception in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Government Inspector centres on the ills in the society, especially the authorities in government. The Mayor and other officials in the town are corrupt, so when they recieve a letter that a government inspector will visit the town very soon, they become scared, thinking of ways to cover up their numerous corrupt activities.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A young civil servant Hlestakov who who was on his way from Petersburg was mistaken for the government Inspector. Hlestakov who sees this opportunity as a way to amass wealth wuickly plays along. The Mayor and other officials bribe him to cover up their crimes and he readily asks for more. The Mayor trying to be on the good side of the inspector invites him to his home and cares for all his needs.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The deception ends when the Mayor got hold of Hlestakov's letter to his friend, containing details of his deception. Hlestakov was exposed and the Mayor feels like a fool, then the real Inspector arrives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 NIKOLAI GOGOL:  The Government Inspector    Compare and contrast Hlestakov and the Mayor", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Mayor and Hlestakov in ' The Government Inspector' are both government workers. The Mayor is the Mayoral head of the district for inspection in the play while Hlestakov is a copy-typist in the Russian civil service.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Both the Mayor and Hlestakov are both corrupt. The Mayor makes life miserable for the people by collecting huge sums from them. With this terrible deeds he hopes to bribe the inspector into silence but he was also decieved and duped by Hlestakov. Hlestakov is also a corrupt man with wild imaginations. He decieves the entire town and collects huge money from them.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hlestakov and the Mayor are bossy and lacks good etiquette. They are both thieves and cheats who are not fit for public service.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Season    Discuss the notion that Sir Thomas More is naive", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sir Thomas More is a naive man because he only believes in what he knows and holds unto it. He doesn't believe in diplomacy and compromise and that eventually leads to his death.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;More is a man who gives up his life because he cannot sacrifice his own commitment to his conscience, which which dictates that he should not turn his back is right or on God. More, regardless of consequences speaks his opinion even at the point of death.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When he realises he was bribed with a silver cup, he gives it out not wanting to be in possession of an object of corruption. More is witty and pragmatic with his love rooted in the law.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;More naivety has no place in the practice of politics in the book, which is killed with corruption,lies, deception and bribery.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Season    Examine the  contribution of Richard to the development of the plot", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard Rich is a character who seeks to advance himself politically and socially, whatever the cost he is the secretary to the team of Sir Thomas More's prosecutor. Rich later ignored More's advice to become a teacher but chose to get the job offered to him by Cromwell.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Though he participated in the plot to imprison More, he later became remorseful and tries to notify More of the consipiracy Cromwell, Chapuys and Matthew have against him. Though he realizes that more is a good man, he isn't daring enough to leave the prosecuting team.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY    Illustrate Senghor's use of figure of speech in the  \"I will Pnounce Your Name\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the poem 'I will pronounce your name' Senghor uses figure of speech like simile, metaphor, personification and onomatopoeia to express himself.   (1) Simile - ... your name is mild like cinamon  (2) Personification - It is the fragrance in which the lemon grove sleeps  (3) Metaphor - It is the fragrance in which the lemon grove sleeps                        - And it resembles the savannah                         - that is the dry tornado, the hard clap of lightning                        - coin of gold, shining coal, you my night  (4) Onomatopoeia - ' words like blooming, clap, fragrance etc  makes the meaning of their sounds.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY    How does J.P Clarke present the theme of cultural alienation in  \"Agbor Dancer\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The dance symbolises the poet's yearning to be identified with the root. He is fascinated with the aspect of his culture which engages the dancers in an act of cultural dance.   The dance contrasts sharply wiuth the poet as the dance signifies her deep knowledge of involvement in her culture and understanding of cutural music. The poet describes the dance as 'maguc maze' with its 'intricate pattern rippling crest after crest'. Early separation from his culture makes the poem to respond to the appeal or communal call this infectuous music creates. His frustration is shown at the end of the post.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the relationship between man and nature in  \"The Solitary Reaper\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "'The solitary reaper' is a poem that gives overwhelming influence that nature exercises a great influence on man. This can be seen freom the presentation of common people like the solitary reaper, forests, birds' songs from nature animals and humans. Aall these have great influence on he poet.   As the poet listens to the 'plaintives numbers' he appears mesmerized. The valley is said to be 'overflowing with sound' and the idea of nightingale being able to sing 'welcome notes' to weary bands of travellers also reflects the power of nature on man.  It has a soothing effect on many unhappy encounters experienced by the poem in life", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2009>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss in detail, three images employed in  \"To His Coy Mistress\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Andrew Marvel, in his poem ' To his Coy Mistress' uses a lot of imagery to make his intentions known to the readers. One of the imageries used is the enternity. The poet uses phrases that creates pictures of enternity in the minds of readers, even though it may not be at his disposal not the lady's. Phrases like 'till the conversion of the Jews(Line 10), an age to every part (Line 17). Here the readers imaginelife without interruption ( death), where everyone has the time in the world to all he wants.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The third imagery is love in a physical way. The poet emphasises intimacy, saying it will be a waste if the lady dies a virgin. Lines 37 - 43 describe the form of closeness he would like to enjoy with the lady to make their relationship worthwhile during their story on earth.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Discuss the dramatic techniques discussed in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Athol Fugard employs a number of dramatic techniques to convey the conditions of black South Africans in an oppressive system. These include:    The use of flashback  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Flashback is a dominant dramatic techniques used in the play. Events unfold through flashback as Styles reflects on the conditions of the black South Africans in Ford Motors. Through this technique, the audience is made aware of the oppressive and the exploitative nature of the apartheid system on the black worker who is kicked out if he dares challenge the white foreman. Sizwe's experiences in the house of Zola are also re-enacted through flashback.    The use of Characters  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fugard's use of a few characters is also an aspect of how he generates interest in the play. There are only three characters, namely; Styles, Sizwe and Buntu and the auction of the play is seen from their perspective. Styles is the dominant character who re-enacts most of the injustices of the white regime and the inhuman treatment the black South African workers receive.    The use of the Dramatic Monologue  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The dramatic monologue is seen as the dominant narrative techique employed by the playwright. Styles' utterances and actions as he plays several roles reveal the evils of aparthed in the plight, as well as the hope of the oppressed blacks.    The use of Symbols  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Several things stand for various ideas. The photographic studio itself represents a place where Styles creats a dream world for the suffering blacks in a situation where their hopes have been shattered by the unjust system. Buntu's house stands for a rehabilitation centre for the bllacks. Cokroaches represent the oppressors whom Styles, who represents his people, is determined to exterminate. Other symbols include the use of the insecticide \"Doom\", and the Cat, which also represent his attempt to overcome oppression, while the Camera offers hoppe. Styles' newspaper headlines open up his mind to the realities and possibilities in and outside his immediate world.    Use of Irony  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Irony is used to reinforce the dehumanising conditon of the Black man. It is ironical that Sizwe has to use a dead man's passport to survive and earn a living in his own native land.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Other dramatic techniques employed in the play include miming and mimicry, use of the epistolary style, the absence of features like acts and scenes and the concentration of the setting in styles' studio.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ATHOL FUGARD: Sizwe Bansi is Dead    Discuss the use of symbols in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The play, symbols are used to represent the various predicaments of black people.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  There is the symbol of the photographic studio which becomes a temporary refuge for blacks who are crippled economically and socially and who indugle their fantasy in taking pictures. Sizwe Bansi, as an asylum seeker, finds this studio a temporary place of refuge.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The \"cockroaches\" symbolize the oppressive white settllers; the \"Doom\" applied by Styles on the cockroaches represents all the ineffective actions taken to free South Africa from racial discrimination.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The \"cat\" is used to remind the blacks that they need a greater force to free themselves from the oppressive regime; the \"passbook\" that the blacks are made to carry is a symbol used to highlight the evils of apartheid. Without a valid passbook characters like Sizwe Bansi are limited in their movement and in securing gainful employment.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Death, itself, is used symbolically to represents rest and peace for the oppressed blacks. The harsh conditions faced by the blacks make them wish to die. There is also Buntu's house which becomes a rehabilitation centre and Buntu himself is made a rehabilitation officer for Sizwe Bansi.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Examine the major conflict in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The conflicts in the play can be seen from different perspectives, ranging from the generation gap involving choice of profession to betrayal of trust and domestic misunderstanding.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  One of the major conflicts in the play is the generational gap involving choice of profession. James Ofosu believes it is his parental responsiblity to choose a career for his children and having chosen for the first two sons, he considers Aaron and Maanan's refusal to accept his choice as an act of disobedience. This conflict results in the strained relationship between him and the two children. It takes Awere's success in painting and Lawyer Bonu's betrayal of trust for James to accept the children's choices.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  There is also domestic conflict which is more pronounced between Mrs. Hannah Ofosu and Aunt Fosuwa than between James and his wife. On the one hand, while aunt Fosuwa disputes over who has responsibilty over the family, Hannah and James are at logger-heads over his friendship with Lawyer Bonu. Again it takes Lawyer Bonu's betrayal of trust to resolve this conflict.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Of the three major conflicts, that between Lawyer Bonu and James though much delayed, is never resolved. It takes Lawyer Bonu's betrayal of trust to establish this conflict.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AFRICAN DRAMA                                 JOE DE GRAFT: Sons and Daughters    Compare and contrast the roles of Hannah and Fasuwa in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  In attitude, roles and disposition, Hannah and Aunt Fosuwa are poles apart. Hannah is James wife while Aunt Fosuwa is his sister. Hannah is portrayed as a dutiful and loving wife and mother. She sees to it that her husband's and children's needs are met. She is capable of discernment. Thus she recognizes that Awere is a good influence on her son and consequently approves Awere's friendship with her children.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  On the other hand, Aunt Fosuwa is depicted as a jealous and envious woman in her relationship with Hannah and her children. While she will not let Hannah enjoy her marriage, her plans regarding Hannah's children and their friends are also ill-motivated. For example, she hats Awere because she feels there is a relationship between Awere and Maanan which will overturn her plans to makee Maanan Lawyer Bonu's second wife.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Hannah, unlike Aunt Fosuwa, believes in the sanctity of marriage and stays with her husband against all odds, while Aunt Fosuwa believes in polygamy, having unsuccessfully married three times. She not only actively encourages Maanan to be Lawyer Bonu's second wife, but also urges Hannah to break her own marriage.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  A perfect role Hannah plays in the play is to show tolerance and understanding in all situations. In spite of James intemperance and set ways, she is able to accomodate him as she does Aunt Fosuwa. Aunt Fosuwa, on the other hand, has no self-discipline in her attitude to marriage and children. She is rather permissive. Her encouragement of Lawyer Bonu's overtures to Maanan emboldens him and leads to the betrayal of James' trust and friendship.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 NIKOLAI GOGOL:  The Government Inspector    Compare the character of the Mayor and Anna Adreyevna.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Mayor is a long serving civil-servant in charge of one of the provinces of St. Petersburg and he is the husband of Anna. They both have a daughter called Marya.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The Mayor is never satisfied with whatever he has but wants more. Anna is like the husband because she is not satisfied with her husband alone and flirts openly with Hlestakov, the so-called Government Inspector. The Mayor never discharges his duties as expectedof an honest civil servant and Anna also does not discharge he duties as faithful wife in the home.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The Mayor lacks scruples. He suggests to the other civil servants that the Inspector's visit notwithstanding, they should maintain the status quo i.e. the collection of bribes should continue as usual. Anna also lacks scruples, she competes with her daughter for Hlestakov.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  They are both ambitious. As the husband is dreaming of becoming a General Anna is dreaming of living in the city. Anna is very inquisitive and asks Hlestakov a lot of questions about city people.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The Mayor becomes flustered at the news of the visit of the government Inspector. Anna, on the other hand, is calm even when she knows her husband is aware of her fliration with the Government Inspector.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  He is selfish. He indulges in self-praise and praises himself to Hlestakov without being aware of it. As an opportunist, he encourages Hlestakov to flirt with his wife because he sees it as an opportunity to be prompted to the rank of General.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 NIKOLAI GOGOL:  The Government Inspector    Examine the three Comic scenes in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  There are many comic scenes in the play. One such scene occurs where Hlestakov has no money to pay for his accumulated bills in the inn, but still threatens the Landlord and the waiter for refusing his demand for more food and not being properly attended to by the inn keeper. When food is eventually served, though he has not paid a single Rouble for it, he still complains about its quality. The comic element in this scene emanates from the absurdity of Hlestakov's behavior.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The scene where Bob and Dob attempt to report the arrival of the expected Government Inspector is equally comic. Both are at their comic best competing to announce the arrival. In their foolish eagerness they  misrepresent Hlestakov as the expected Government Inspector, thus setting the stage for the action of the play.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gogol also creates another comic scene when Yosif, thinking that the Landlord of the inn has reported them to the Mayor for their debts, quickly inform Hlestakov that the Mayor has come to arrest and put them in prison. Ironically, it is the Mayor who believes Hlestakov is the Government Inspector being expected from Petersburg and has come to meet him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is also funny and ridiculous that the Mayor should bribe Hestakov with a \"loan\" of 400 Roubles fearing that he is Govt. Inspectr, while, in fact, Hlestakov is a spendrift and no Govt. Inspector.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet another  comic scene is created where mother and daughter compete for Hletakov's attention under the full glare of the Mayor. They dress to kill and fantasize about him and even quarrel about who is best qualifies to woo him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Also, comic is the scene where the Mayor fantasizes about when his daughter Marya, would get married to Hlestakov. He boasts about it in the province and all the officials go to the Mayor's house with their wives to congratulate him on his soon becoming father-in-law of the Government Inspector. The Mayor cuts a very ridiculous figure as he struts around gloating on his own imagined position and importance.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The last scene in the play after the interception of Hlestakovs' letter by the Postmaster is as comic as all the others. Here all the characters lick their wounds and count their loses as they confess their stupidity in allowing Hlestakov to dupe them.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Season    Examine the play as a conflict between King Henry's Desires and More's Principles.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is quite evident in the drama that the King's heartiest wishes are ones that More cannot endorse. More's stand is that what the King wants to have are against his moral and religious principles.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  On the King's part, he has married a queen who is unable to bear a son and so must be divorced. Meanwhile he has found a younger woman he wishes to marry. The King, to make his self conviction strong, reasons that the setting aside of a church provision to make his marrying his late brother's wife possible is also unlawful. He therefore wants to set matters right by having that marriage annulled.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The King also considers the Pope as a mere archbishop who must not lord it over other people from his church in Rome; England can have its own church and its Archbishop. To succed in implementing his desires, the King must have More's support his Chancellor and friend. More will not co-operate. His reasons are ones by on principle and religion.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More strongly believes that it is wrong to give public approval for the divorce of Queen Catherine and the marriage of the King to Anne Boleyn. The Pope had been persuaded to set aside a biblical injunction on marriage between King henry VII and his brother's widow. Asking the Pope to reverse that is not morally right as far as More is concerned. He also strongly opposes the King's attacks on the abbeys and his policy of reformation.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The King's disregard for the Pope shocks More. He thinks that breaking away from Rome is sacrilegious. He strongly believes that the Pope is God's representative and must not be rebuffed. Therefore, he refuses to swear the Oath in support of the King's desire and does not give reasons. He opposes the Act of Parliament that approves the legitimacy of the King's marriage with Anne Boleyn.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At this point, More and King Henry VII are on a collision course. In the end, the King has his way without More's support. More resigns as Chancellor but he loses his life. If he will not agree with the King, More must die. He dies in the belief that he has lived and stood by his conscience and that he has been true to his moral and religious principles.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA                                 ROBERT BOLT: A Man For All Season    Examine the characters of Sir Thomas More and Master Cromwell.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Professionally, both are legal scholars and important public officers. More is a principled and God-fearing man. This is seen when he refuses to give public approval to Henry's marriage with Anne Boleyn. He also refuses to accept bribe. At home, he is a good family man.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Crownwell, on the other hand, has no moral scruples sand will do anything for position and oney. These contrasting aspects of their characters are played out in the drama. For example, Crownwell's' lack of moral scruples makes him a wiling tool in the hands of the King. To satisfy the King's desire to remarry (which More is opposed to), he viciously implicates More in the bribery scandal and gets him executed in the end.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One other area where More and Cromwell contrast in character is the way they view friendship. While More is sincere and willing to help for a good cause, Crownwell is not. For example, More befriends Rich to improve the young man's moral and career development while Crownwell's friendship with Rich is exploitative and geared towards the acquistion of power, influence and money.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Judging from More's character as it develops in the play, one may consider him as naive even when he stands in great danger of his life and has virtually all his family opposing him. But More lives and dies for his principles. Cromwell, on the other hand, stands on no higher moral ground than his own material comfort which he perseus, vengefully", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY                                     Examine the poet's use of images in the \"Songs of Sorrow I and II\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"Songs\" of sorrow I & II is a pessimistic poem. It is a dirge in which the living blame the ancestors for the hardship and difficulties that their departure has left behind. Much of this meaning is conveyed through several important images used in the poem.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The desolation and helplessness that has occured is presented right at the beginning of \"Songs of Sorrow I\" in the image of the 'Chameleon faces'. The image is appropriate as it conjures up the picture of something that cannot be wiped away or cleaned . It is this castastrophe that is emphasized by the use of this image.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The series of other images closely associated with destruction, destruction and aven death, is used in successive parts of the poem: References can be made to images like the \"sun and rain\" that 'burn' and beat respectively; the gun that can no longer be fired because there are no sons; other plant and animal images such as \"the sharp stumps;\" the falling \"tree\" which also symbolizs the death of Agosu, an important family elder, the \"broken fences\"; the \"snake\", the 'crow' and the \"vulture\" which are all destructive creatures. The \"wilderness\" is not spared in reference to its desolation.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The overwhelming feeling in the poem is that nothing has gone right since the departure of the ancestors and onl suffering remains for survivors like the persona. Even those who travel and return have to confront a life of misery. An entire civilization or way of life represented by \"Kpeti's great household\" is no more. What are left are the broken fences now taken over by entire strangers.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "AFRICAN POETRY                                     Discuss the characteristics and effects of the storm in \" An African Thunderstorm\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 'An African thunderstorm is a highly descriptive poem about the ravages caused by a typical storm.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The two aspects of the storm - its characteristics and its effects are clearly brought out. In respect of his cahracteristics, the storm, as a natural phenomenon, is presented as destructive and fearsome. The wind that blows in its wake \"tosses up things in its tails/like mad man chasing nothing\" or like a plague of locusts\".     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The above two similes emphasize the chaos that is caused. The impression formed is that of some brurte force that is being unleashed. There is a sense on the foreboding as the \"pregnant clouds\" gather to\"perch on hills\". Hell appears to break loose as nothing is spared in the wind's trial. As the accompanying thunder is unleashed and the storm's effects diminsh, this is felt in the onomatopoeia words, \"tremble, \"rumble\" \"crack\" and \"pelting\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The storm's effect on its surroundings are also conveyed in words that appeal to the senses. \"Screams of delighted children\" contrast with the frenzied movement of women carrying their babies on their backs upon sensing danger. Their cloths are torn apart. \"exposing dangling breasts\". Not spared, even, are the trees which \"bend\" to let it pass.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY                                     How effective is Houseman's use of imagery in \"To An Athlete Dying Young''?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem is about the premature death of a young athlete, which sets the poet reflecting on the purpose and meaning of life.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The dominant image is that of the athlete being chaired shoulder-high and basking in the cheers of the spectators as he receives the laurel which is a classical symbol of success.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The above image contrasts with another, the \"road where all runners come\" which is death. Death is presented in other images like \"a stiller town\", which is the cementery where \"silence sounds no worse than cheers; \"home\" which suggests finality, and \"shady night\". All these stand in opposition to the image of the laurel and the rose, which though marking earthly success and beauty, wither so fast.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is remarkable, therefore, that the athlete is described as \"smart lad\" to have died young before beauty and success desert him.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the poem, images are turned upon their heads. For example, the image of the lad being carried \"shoulder high\" as a mark of worldly success is the same image presented of him being carried \"shoulder high\" this time, towards his grave. Similarly, the garland that withers where \"lads wore their honors out\" is described as \"unwithered\" on the head of the \"strength less dead.\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reference can also be made to the image of the \"challenge cup\" which lures athletes into the limelight, \"the market place\". There, if they do not \"retire\" as quickly as the \"smart lad\" they will face, in the language and feeling of the poet, disappointment and disgrace, being 'lads that wore their honors out. Runners whom renown outran/ And the man died before the man\". However, for the \"smart lad\" who dies at the height of his achievement, there is the \"still defended challenge cup\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 2>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY                                     Examine the theme of rejected love in Marvel's \" To his Coy Mistress\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The theme of rejected love is more implied than stated in the poem. What the poem presents, essentially, is a scene where the persona attempts to woo his mistress into having a sexual relationship with him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In stanza after stanza, the persona conjures up different types of images , that do ease his mistress's fears by suggesting that time and distance are not of the essence in their love relationship and he can afford to sit by \"the tide/ Of Humber and complain while she refuses\". \"Till\" the conversation of the Jews\" and he spends countless number of years adoring the physical features of his mistress.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When his mistress does not appear to have been moved, the persona invokes the spectre of death in stanza 2, with \"Time's winged chariot hurrying near\" Other images associated with the grave and decay are made use of, and the mistress is remined of her own mortality and the work that worms willdo to her virginity if she does not give it to his sexual overtures.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Since this may appear to have frightened his mistress enough, the persona argues in the 3rd stanza that now is time for them to consummate their love, for the \"youthful hue/sits on thy skin like morning dew'' and her body and senses seem aroused.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Throughout the poem, though, it is only the persona who speaks, pleads, coaxes and threatens. Not a word is heard from his mistress; yet it is the persona's turns of language use that suggest a rejection of his love by this mistress.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joy Of Motherhood    How important is Mama Abby to Nnu-Ego's survival in the city?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mama Abby is Nnu Ego's neighbour on Little Road, Yaba. She becomes Nnu Ego's mentor when the latter moves to Lagos and serves as a strong pillar of support to her when the going gets tough.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She understands the problems that Nnu Ego goes through. She compares her own predicament to that of Nnu Ego and treats the latter with sympathy and understanding.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mama Abby caters for the physical needs of Nnu Ego and her family. For example, when Oshia is starving Mama Abby and Iyawo Itsekiri step in to save the poor boy from dying of hunger.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mama Abby raises the initial alarm about Oshia's fever. This intervention probably saves his life. She takes Oshia on a trip to the Island to speed up his recovery. She regards Oshia as \"our son\" implying a strong attachment to Nnu Ego's family. Mama Abby is very caring and loving and helps Nnu Ego during critical periods of her life.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mama Abby's support to Nnu Ego even extends to going with her to the Post office and reading letters for her as she does when Nnaife remits money to the family. She also helps her to open a Saving Account. Nnu Ego has complete confidence in Mama Abby and this strengthens the bond between them. When Nnu Ego has to go to the barracks to take delivery of a parcel sent by Nnaife. Mama Abby goes with her and helps her to take delivery of her mail and the remittance of sixty pounds. She is crucial to Nnu Ego's survival in the city.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 BUCHI EMECHETA: The Joy Of Motherhood    Comment on the theme of gender discrimination in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 'The Joy of Motherhood', women are not only barely tolerated they are discriminated against. A woman is supposed to be seen and not heard. Women are regarded as child producing machines only, and not have any rights of their own. That is why a woman is not fulfilled until she gets married and is able to produce children. Where she brings forth female children only, her chance of retaining her position in the man's house is reduced. And where she fails to produce a child, she is regarded as a total house is reduced. And where she fails to produce a child, she is regarded as a total failure. But, when a woman brings forth a male child, she is celebrated, not only by the husband, but by the entire family and the community at large.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nnu Ego epitomizes the disadvantaged position of women in the novel. She is reduced to a housemaid in the house of Amatokwu, her first husband, because of her inability to produce a child. She is relegated to the background and saddled with the task of taking care of the home while her co-wife is showered with attention and accorded special treatment because she has a child.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Nnaife's house, Nnu Ego's hope of womanhood is revived; but this is dashed when Ngozi, her first child, dies and she regards herself as a failed woman. Her joy is resuscitated at the birth of a boy. Nnu Ego feels happy and her relationship with her husband improves.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the husband is conscripted into the army, it is Nnu Ego that is saddled with the responsibility of taking care of the children. Making ends meet is almost a nightmare. Unfortunately, when Nnaife returns from Fernando Po, he chooses to acquire more wives without even consulting her, thereby compounding their financial problems. Nnaife behaves like this because he is a man.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Kehinde Nnu Ego's daughter, refuses to accept the husband chosen for her by her father, Nnaife becomes very annoyed. Rather than face the situation squarely, he chooses to heap the blame on Nnu Ego.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adaku, the other wife is also a victim of gender discriminatio. All her children are female. On reporting a case of indignity suffered by her visitor at the hands of Nnu Ego to Nwakusor, Nnaife's friend, Nwakusor reminds Adaku that the only way a man gets immortalized is by having a son. He says to her: \"I know you have children, but they are girls, who in a few years' time will go and help build another man's immortality\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nnu Ego's claim to the house is based on her bringing forth Adim and Oshia. Ironically, her male children prove irresponsible but her daughters andd their daughters and their husbands are those who give her support financially.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gender discrimination is entrenched in the society. Even children are encouraged to believe that the male is superior to the female. Oshia, for example, refuses to help the girls fetch water because, as he puts it, \"I am a boy\". Rather than scold him, all the people around merely laugh. This shows the aquiescence of even the women, pointing to the general acceptance of gender discrimination.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nwokocha Abgadi behaviour to his wives is a good example of the way the female gender is treated. In total disregard for the feelings of his wives, he makes love to Ona in his compound, surrounded by his family. His impatience at Agunwa's jealous reaction which apparently leads to her sickness and eventual death, is an indication of the discrimination which the female gender faces.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Discuss the view that Aku is a tragic character", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aku's position in The last Duty is pathetic. Reduced to penury by Oshevire's detention, she finds herself confronted with the proposals of Chief Toje, Oshevire's rival and accuser. Her tragedy in the novel is that in spite of her effort to preserve her dignity, she finds herself slipping down the abyss into sexual infidelity and disagrace.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aku's situation is indeed a difficult one. Her deprived condition clearly illustrates the disastrous consequences of the war on individuals. It is this deprivation which makes her easy prey for Toje's unscruplous exploitation. Right from the start she is aware of her disadvantaged condition and acknowledges it quite readily. Despite her expressed fears, she resigns herself to her fate. She admits that even though deprived of food and comfort, she has in fact realized what Toje is after. Whenever she goes on her tryst with him, she is full of guilt.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Paradoxically, it is her sexual, not economic, deprivation which leads to her loss of integrity. After Toje's impotent attempt to make love to her, she is sexually aroused and craves satisfaction. She thus turns her attention to Odibo whose vibrant sexuality she has only just become aware of. Aku's attempt to justify her behaviour carries with it a certain element of pathos. Tortured, tormented, driven almost to the limits of human endurance, she finds herself wishing that Toje could make love to her, repugnant though the thought is. The reality of sin would at least be better than the fantasy which Toje is dragging her through. This prepares the way for Odibo's subsequent love-making with her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Aku we see the result of a war which unjustly deprives a family of its breadwinner and a woman the right to love and enjoy sex with her husband. Her predicament also demonstrates the insecurity, both physical and emotional, consequent upon a civil war. Her relationship with her husband cannot remain in the same state after the scandal. Oshevire is released from prison in time to face the disgrace after the fight between Toje and Odibo over his wife.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The tragic end of Oshevire's life results directly from his attempt to leave the scene of his disgrace occasioned by the infidelity of his wife. This serves to further deepen Aku's tragedy.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE                                 ISIDORE OKPEWHO: The Last Duty    Discuss the horrors of war in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The horrors of war in the novel are presented through the experiences of different characters in the story.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The most obvious consequences of war is the general state of insecurity which it create. This is seen for example in the persistent air raids reported in the novel. Many civilians lose their lives and property and those who survive ate emtionally traumatized. They are uneasy because aircraft guns boom everywhere. Major Ali is welcomed as a commander who is around to ensure the safety of the people. His men use anti aircraft guns to bring down rebel planes that are causing destruction and suffering on the people. Members of the Red Cross have to cope with the injured and displaced in the community.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another example of the horrible consequences of war is the conscription of young men into the army. Young men who could have lived peacefully now find themselves being forced into fighting in the war.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Civilians find themselves at the mercy of soliders who believe that they are all powerful and can do whatever they like. An illustration of this is seen in Private Sule who kills his girlfriend and rival in a fit of jealousy.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is executed in public for his crime. It is the war which has created the situation in which Private Sule could have the guts to commit such a crime. It is the same war that permits a public execution for such a crime. This summary execution without due process shows that the war situation permits summary executions.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The atmosphere of insecurity in a war situation is accentuated by the detention of civilians on spurious charges. Oshevire's predicament offers a good example. He is detained unlawfully for three years during which period instances of brutality suffered by prisoners are highlighted.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Oshevire's wife and son are reduced to penury and consequentlyy exposed to the whims and caprices of their supposed benefactor, Toje.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Discuss the character and role of Eppie in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eppe is the product of a secret marriage between Godrey Cass and Molly Farren. The infant survives death miraculously when her mother dies in the snow while on her way to the Red House to get Godfrey to take up responsibilty of the child.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By chance, the young child crawls into an open cottage that belongs to Silas Marner a weaver in Raveloe who lives the life of a recluse. Silas considers this child as a replacement for his gold which has recently been stolen. He adopts the child and gives her the name Eppie on the day she is christened that Silas goes to church for the first time to Raveloe. He continues to attend church because Eppie has to go and he will not let her go without him. In time, he goes to church not only because of Eppie but because he himself wants to go.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eppie grows to be a great and wonderful companion to SIlas Marner. She is a life-giving force and she adds meaning to Silas' unhappy life. She has genuine love for her adopted father who in turn, sacrifies everything to make her unhappy. When she requests a garden to plant flowers, Silas readily grants her wish. Through Eppie, Silas gains acceptance in the Raveloe community and even the children who formerly ran away in fear are drawn closer to him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After 16years, Eppie love for Silas is tested, when her biological father Godfrey Cass comes to claim her. Eppie rejects Godfrey's offer to make lady of her. Her love for Silas is thus threatened but she is strong-willed and knows what she wants in life. In the response to Godfrey and his wife, she displays maturity and wisdom.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eppie is content with Silas' status in life. Her affection for Silas surpasses everything for she stresses that nobody shall ever come between Silas and herself. Eppie's words console Silas who is hurt by Godfrey's visit.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her presence in the novel advances the plot and makes it interesting. Through her, the reader notices the transformation of Silas' life. Silas' parental qualities are also seen with the arrival of Eppie. With the help of a neighbour Dolly Winthrop, Silas cares for Eppie from childhood to adulthood, when she happily marries Aaron, Dolly Winthrop's son.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After Eppie's marriage, the couple lives with Silas ad this ensures that Silas does not relapse into his former state.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner  NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner    Examine the relationship between Silas and William Dane.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The relationship between Silas and William is narrated through flashback. In Lantern Yard, Silas Marner and William Dane are very close friends. The are both members of the church assembling in Lantern yard. Their relationship is seen by the other members of the church as resembling the friendship of David and Jonathan.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite the seeming enviable relationship, the two friends regard their friendship with opposing interests. Silas is genuinely devoted to his friend  and reposes absolute trust in him. William, on the other hand, does not believe in the friendship and envies his friend. He also seeks to surpass him by bringing him down.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silas contributes to William's desire to hurt his interests. He tells William the truth about everything he knows. In his blind trust of William, Silas discloses his full intention concerning Sarah and even permits William to be present at even the most intimate of his meetings with Sarah.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; William plays on Silas' trust. Scheming as he is, William keeps a knife that Silas lends to him for use later, against Silas. He sees in Silas Maner's occasional spells of fit an opportunity to destroy his friend. He grabs his opportunity as soon as it presents itself.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While the two friends take turns to look after an ailing elder of the church with whom church money is kept, Silas apparently falls into one of his fits. William takes advantage of the situation and steals the church money. To nail Silas, he leaves Silas, he leaves Silas' knife on the scene to implicate his unsuspecting friend.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the crime is discovered, William aids the condemnation of his friend by his silence. Silas, in his naivety appeals to him. But William pointedly denies his friend asserting that he cannot vouch for his friend's secret thoughts and acts.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SIlas succumbs to the costing of lots that proves his guilt. The church grants approval for William to marry Sarah, who has broken her engagement to Silas.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; These events affect Silas drastically and he sees no profit in trusting any man or even believing in God. He therefore leaves Lantern Yard suspended from the church, to settle in Raveloe.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner  NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Discuss the relationship between Richard and the members of his Family", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The relationship between Richard and members of his family - his mother, father. grandparents, uncles and aunts - plays a significant role in his life.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard's relationship with his mother is vey close. She does beat him mericlessly when he misbehaves but Richard realizes that she does not do it out of spite. He really loves her and takes up a job to fend for her when she suffers a stroke even though he is merely a boy. The incident in which Richard encounters the boys on his way to the grocery is an example.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She prepares him for life in the violent society in which they live. Richard's father is the exact opposite of the mother. There is mutual hatred between them as is manifested in the kitten incident. His father also treats him brutally as illustrated in the incident in which Richard sets their house on fire. The father ends up abandoning his family with total disregard for the hunger and deprivation which this will cause.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard's grandmother in her obsession with religion regards him as a wayward child and treats him as such. She is stifles his physical and emotional growth. She prevents him from working on Saturday and whenever he steps out of his line, she punishes him severely.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aunt Addie sees him as a constant threat to all authority and takes every opportunity to subjugate him through punishment . This awakens the rebellious streak in Richard and he resorts to using knife to threaten her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The effect which Aunt Addie has on Richard is not much different from that which Uncle Tom has on him. Uncle Tom's persistent caning of Richard forces the boy to engage in violence. Apart from Richard's mother, the only members of his family who treat him like a human being are Aunt Maggie and Uncle Hoskins. They cater for both his physical and emotional needs. Unfortunately, his relationship is cut short by the murder of Uncle Hoskins.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2010>PAPER 3>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 GEORGE ELIOT: Silas Marner  NON-AFRICAN PROSE                                 RICHARD WRIGHT: Black Boy    Comment on the theme of racism in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Racism is predominate in Black Boy. The treatment of the blacks by the whites is primarily determined by the colour of their skin. This defines all relationship between whites and blacks in the novel. Blacks are regarded as no better than second class citizens in the society.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are many instances of racism in the novel. Richard's grandfather serves in the army during the civil war but is denied his pension till he dies. It is clear from the novel that had he been white he would not have been treated that way.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard himself suffers because of the practice of racism. One day when he is at work he is bitten by a dog. Instead of taking him to a doctor for treatment, his white boss dismisses his complaint with the statement that a dog's bite does not hurt a 'nigger'. Richard's treatment when he is working at the optician's and his fight with Harrison on the instigation of the whites, for their own pleasure, are examples of racism as it affects Richard.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Blacks are deprived of equal educational opportunities. They are denied the pleasure if reading books and access to health facilities and good jobs. Even where they achieve success through sheer andd hard work and make laudable achievements, they are not allowed to reap the benefits of their labour. Thus Uncle Hoksins is brutality murdered merely because he is prosperous. His family is even denied the opportunity to bury his corpse honourably.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When a black woman inadvertently trepasses on white property she is mercilessly beaten up. Whites do not hesitate to brutalize blacks for not addressing them 'sir' when talking with them.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other instances of racism abound in the novel, such as the different queues for blacks and whites in the train station and the killing of Ned's brother, Bob.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The dominant impression in the novel is that blacks are dehumanized because of the racist attitude of whites.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KOBINA SEKYI : THE BLINKARDS    Analyse the character of Mr. Onyimdze.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. Onyinmdze is a young unmarried barrister. He is educated in England. Depspite his education Mr. Onyinmdze has a basis for the African way of life. By his training he is a lawyer, a typical western profession. In his colonial environment Mr Onyinmdze must strike a balance between the Whiteman's way of life and that of his own people.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a lawyer, Mr. Onyimdze cannot but dress in his legal robes when he goes to court. Yet his inclination towards the traditional way of life makes him eager to be out ot European clothing when he is out of court. His favourite wear at home is the native cloth with native sandals to match.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr Onyimdze's favourite games are also traditional. For example he prefers ampe to tennis croquet and antsally, all of which he is familiar with because of his English training. At the garden party he guesses that the people will be playing tennis and other non-African games and wonders whether Mrs. Borofosem will let the young ladies play \"ampe\".     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His love for his native language-Fante - makes him believe that Mr. Okadu should speak Fante at the party. He also loves traitional foods.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the girls harass him and put pressure on him to wear English clothes, he resists them and tries to dissuade them from following Mrs. Borofosem blindly. And when the girls ridicule him for wearing native cloth that exposes his nakedness, he eduactes them on the difference between \"nakedness\" and \"bareness\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. Onyimdze's dislike of English manners as proteaed by Mrs. Borofosem is clear. During Mr. Okadu's romance with Miss Tsiba, he insists that Mr. Okadu should do the right thing and threatens to sack him if he does not express his intentions towards Miss Tsiba in the customary way. Mr. Onyimdze's respect for tradition and the elders is total. That enable him to intervene in the matter between Nana Katawerwa and the parson. The meeting in Mr. Onyimdze's office ends in the disgrace of the Parson who misquote the Bible.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thus, Mr. Onyimdze comes off as one who is abe to accomodate western values without sacrificing his own traditional way of life.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYI : THE BLINKARDS    To what extent is Mrs. Borofesem a blind imitator of the English way of life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mrs. Borofosem is a major character in the play. She is the wife of Mr. Borofosem who belongs to the merchant class. She is a 'been-to', that is one who has been to England, albeit for only thrree months. She claims to be a leader of fashion and insist on speaking English, although, her own English is, at best, sub-standard.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mrs. Borofosem is a blind initator of English ways of life. For her, everything African is barbaric, and that includes African dress, food, languages, customs and religion. For instance, she insists on kissing her husband openly (even though he is reluctant to do so) and demands that he call her \"Dukie\" as her neighbour, Mr. Gosh in England calls his wife. She even goes to the ridiculous length of encouraging her husband to smoke and spill the cigar ashes on the carpet in the belief that it perserves the carpert against moth.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is no fitness in Mrs. Borofosem's affectation of English ways. She seems more to be putting on appearances. She insists on having \"European sweets\" with dinner. But in her unguarded moments she is nostalgic about the African dishes she condemns openly.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her fixation of English manners is complete: her husband must sing as the english do even if he insists on singing in his own natural voice. \"I'm not an ass\" he says. Mrs. Borofosem's attitude to her servants apes what she sees as the attitude of the English people to their servants. For her, \"Nobody thinks of servants thinking in England\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Perhaps the most ridiculous thing about Mrs. Borofosem is her taking pride in using English, a language she speaks poorly. For a character like her who dotes on English, her grammatical slips are as ridiculous as her other affectations.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All these create a picture of her as a pretentious, ridiculous and ludrious character. Yet it is to Mrs. Borofosem's credit that towards the end of the play, she makes an about-turn towards embracing her own native language and customs", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMI OSOFISAN : WOMEN OF OWU    Justify the assertion that the people of Owu are the architects of their own destruction.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It can be argued that the people of Owu are the architects of their own doom. Their history lends some proof. The plight of Owu has both remote and immediate causes Prominent among these are the prophesy of the birth of the Prince, the attack on Ife, Owu's engagement in slavery, the sack of Apomu and the desecration of the Anlugbua shrine by the allied forces.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By prophesy, Prince Dejumo will bring destruction to his own people. The natural thing to do, according to tradition, is to destroy the child at birth. However, Erelu, his mother, he is permits him to live and he does fulfill his destiny.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Regarding the attack on Ife, Owu, full of pride, complacency and greed commits sacrilege. In sacking Ife, Owu sells into slavery her kith and kin and incurs the warth of the gods.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Similarly, the sacking of Apomu market by Owu warriors who take away their women as booty, including the abduction of Iyunloye, is Owu's own doing and undoing, for it gets punished. Again when the Allied forces avenge their dead, they too overreact by pursuing the fugitives to Anlugbua's shrine, killing the priest and desecrating the shrine. For this they pay a heavy price by being decimated on their way back home. They too are directly responsible for what happens to them.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Owu's rise and fall can therefore be blamed not on the gods but on the people themselves who do not heed the gods' instruction and individually and collectively pursue their own interests.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISAN: WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss the plight of women in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp A distinction has to be made between two sets of women in the play. On the one hand there are the women of Owu and those of the allied forces who are devastated by the wars, and on the other, the goddess Lawunmi who, by losing her shrine, loses her status. Iyunloye, also suffers disgrace and ridicule.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The play emphasizes the plight of Owu women during and after the destruction of the Owu kingdom. They are subjected to disgrace, humiliation, grief and sorrow. They lose their husbands, sons and properties to the war. Their various prestigious positions as wives and mothers change to those of slaves andd concubines sent to unknown destinations.    Erelu, the queen of Owu, in particular witnesses the death of her husband, sons, daughter, and eventually buries her grandson. She suffers degradation and disgrace torture and displacement by the invasion of the allied forces. She is to be sent to Balogun Derin to serve as maid to his wife. While leading the rite which leading the rite which is performed the transition of the spirits of the dead, Erelu is possessed by the god. Anlugbua pronounces the doom of Owu kingdom and dies.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now the women of Owu must be marched off into exile and slavery. It is this terrible fate which befalls them as they suffer in agony the consequences of their collective misdeeds. \"Our woman were seized/And shared out to the blood-splattered/troops/To spend the night\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As for the goddess Lawunmi, the allied forces plunder and desecrate her shrine, while Iyunloye looks to an uncertain future as the price she pays for her infidelity.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    Assess the character of Raina Petkoff.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina, the only daughter of Paul and Catherine Petkoff, is a very beautiful lady of about twenty-three years old. She appears in the play as a lovely and articulate lady, but one who is also given to fantasizing about love and war. For example, she is attracted to Sergius precisely because she believes war is a theatre for heroic exploits. Similarly, she is drawn to Bluntschll for about the same reason, he being a soldier.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina is also very intelligent and brave, she allows Bluntschll, a total stranger into her room and shields him, at great personal risk, from being discovered by the search party. Her taking to Bluntschll partly reflects her intelligence and her capacity to argue, as well as accomodate opposing views.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Apart from being intelligent and brave, there is spontaneity in her nature that enables her to adapt more readily to changing situations. In that, she is in sharp contrast with the more calculating Louka.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina is also an attention-seeker. She knows how to make use of opportunities that project her in a positive light. When, for instance, Sergius returns from the war, she times her appearance to coincide with his asking after her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is to Raina's credit that her character develops in the play. She is increasingly seen as one who is honest enough to recognize her mistaken ideals about war and love. She is able to come to terms with the mutual attraction between Sergius and Louka and this allows him to follow his heart's desire. In equal measure, she accepts the fact that her relationship with Sergius is based on social class, which excludes her own feelings. Thus she is able to welcome Bluntschll's proposal of marriage.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN  Comment on the relationship between the petkoffs and their servants.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Petkoffs are Major Paul, Catherine, his wife, and Raina, their daughter. Louka and Nicola are their servants, one being a maid and the other, a man-servant. The two groups constitute a relationship best described as that of master and servant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Petkoffs are of high a social standing, educated and wealthy. Their relationship with their servants must be seen in this light. Their behaviour and comportment portrays the presumptuousness of their class. They talk down to their servants whom they assume are unintelligent and have no ambition. The servants on the other hand have more intelligence than the Petkoffs credit them with.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For example, Nicola is a very wily character. He is perceptive enough to recognize Louka's potential and the possibility of propelling herself into the higher class. Thus, while the Petkoffs think he is engaged to Louka, Nicola is in fact counting on Louka's future patronage.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is also an air of frivolity about the Petkoff's manners and language. They pretend they know so much about the arts - libraries, exhibitions, war, etc while their conversations ramable on meaninglessly on these issues. Compared with the Petkoffs the servants are more purposeful. Louka for example would stand up to Raina in addressing her on first name basis. Indicating her scorn, if not outright disrespect of the high-handedness of the Petkoffs in their relationship with their servants. It needs to be emphasized that Louka refuses to accept the position which the Petkoffs believe she must occupy. She is ambitious and is intent on rising to the upper class. she is Raina's rival for Sergius's love without Raina knowing it. Thus, Raina, in her complacency, this opprotunity to her advantage. She reveals Raina's apparent infidelity to Sergius and is therefore able to scheme her way into Sergius's arms.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Analyse the deceptive nature of Algernon", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Algernon Moncrieff is one of the major characters in the play, He is an aristocrat, born into a wealthy and noble family. His late mother was a sister to the fashionable Lady Bracknell.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Algernon is an easy-going young man who takes delight in deception fun and pleasure. He confides in Jack his love for levity. He invents \"Bunbury\" in order that he may be able to go down to the countryside whenever he chooses. Algernon shrinks his responsibilty at home when he pretends to be going to see his imaginary friend called Mr. Bunbury.    Algernon deceives his aunt, Lady Bracknell, and lures her away to enable Jack have access to Gwendolen Fairfax. He also displays his deception when he goes to Jack's country home and claims to be the wayward Ernest, Jack's imaginary elder brother, just to woo Cecily, Jack's ward.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He deceives his friend Jack by telling him that that cucumber sandwiches are all reserved for Lady Bracknell. But rather eating all the sandwiches, he lies to his aunt that they have been unable to find any cucumber to buy in the market. He also falsely accuses the servants of negligence for not serving the cucumber.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Algemon also falsely informs Miss Prism that the Priest is waiting for her in the garden. He does this to send her away so that he can talk to Cecily in private. He leads the way in deception and instructs Cecily in how to deceive people in order to get what she wants.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All in all, we can say that Algernon is a character who is adept at deception. The good thing, however, is he does it all without malice, but for frivolous fun and pleasure.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    How important is Miss Prism in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miss Prism is a minor character who nevertheless plays a crucial role. She is governess to Cecily. She was also in a previous employment, a maid to General and Mrs. Moncrieff.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In spite of her lowly position and status, Miss Prism holds the key to the mystery about Jack's mistaken identity in the play, after twenty-nine years of anonymity. According to her account, she, as Jack's nanny much earlier, in a moment of mental distraction, mistakenly deposits the manuscript of a novel she is writing in the bassinette and places Jack then a baby, in the handbag instead. Then, she deposits the handbag in the cloakroom in a railway station in London. Jack is later found and nutured by the late Mr. Thomas Cardew.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Before Miss Prism's confession, no one knows that Jack is actually an adopted child except that he is a child who has come into Mr. Cardew's home through a mistake. Jack is himself unaware of his real identity and grows up not knowing that he is Algemon's brother. This leads to much of the confusion in the play.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miss Prism is also unaware of the implications of what she has done. The suspense in the play is heightened as the recogniton of the significance of her mistake dawns on her. She confesses. The mystery is thus resolved and Jack is able to claim his inheritance. All minds are put at rest. Miss Prism, as it were, brings light to the darkness which has engulfed the play.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miss Prism also serves to expose the absurdity of class distinction in the play. Lady Bracknell does not include Jack in her \"List of eligible\" suitors because he does not, supposedly, have a fortune and is of low social class. Miss Prism's confession shows how wrong Lady Bracknell has been and also, how ridiculous society's attitude to social class is.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miss Prism further exposes the hypocrisy of the society. Her relationship with dr. Chasuble exposes both as hypocritical and deceitful.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally, Miss Prism's name is symbolic. Like a prism which splits a ray of light into the different colours of the rainbow, through Miss Prism, the complex web of relationships which lie at the core of the mistaken identities in the play is unravelled.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN POETRY    How do the 'patriots' and the 'elite' contribute to poverty in \"Ambassadors of Poverty\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The question isolates two groups for special comment. These are the so-called patriots and the so-called elites of society. The poem states how these two groups contribute to the povetry of the masses.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the poem these two groups are separated as a matter of convenience. However, as the first stanza demnostrates they are one and the same. The metaphor of the \"head\" and the \"anus\" demonstrates how lopsided their interests are. Instead of using their heads to serve their country, it is rather the \"left overs\" of their corrupt activites which their country men are made beneficiaries of. Using damning language the poet describes these two groups as not worthy of the name \"saviour\". As merchant they \"loot\" to \"boost\" the economies of their colonial masters. As office holders they are \"loafers\", incompetent and avaricious with their \"kleptomaniac fingers\" and \"suckling filaments\" which turn them into predatory insects.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They are not worthy of the name \"patriots\" who withhold fom the people what is due to them until famished and hungry they abandon conscience and power and are themselves corrupted by the affluent in the society. As the political elite, they flaunt  their ill-gotten wealth in front of the people in the form of \"air-conditioned chambers\" and exotic cars while their constitencies are deprived of any form of modern life - their roads are \"death traps\", they have mud for water \"candle for light\" and the children go to school under trees and lack food and nutrition.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem successfully demonstrates how the so called patriots and elites of society have become parasites, turning their countrymen into destitute in the name of governing them.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss the poet's direction in \"The Fence\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet raises the serious issues of his dilemma and confusion especially to the threshold of decision-making. Accordingly he deploys appropriate diction to make his points. To this end he uses epithets that connote the uncertainty of things and a network of opposites that underscore his indecision.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For instance he finds himself helpless where 'the past and the future' are both 'dim' and 'the hopes and inspirations\" they raise are equally 'nebulous'. He is also confounded at that point where time ceaselessly moves 'forwards and backwards'. There he lies unable to choose between casting away the old and embracing the new.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With a skiful use of an effective network of contrasting words, he shows how he finds himself unable to take sides as he watches 'truth and untruth' locked in an 'endless and bloody combat'.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By means of the same language technique he portrays his dilemma, confusion and indecision at the crossroads of the \"need for good\" and the need for 'doing good'. There again he lies unable to take any decision.   It is also with the use of the right diction that the poet reveals how his dilemma, confusion and indecision seemingly peak, hallucinating as he feels the 'buoyant waves'.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the theme of loneliness in \"Daffodils\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ' I wandered lonely as a cloud' (line 1) of the poem indicates the first instance of loneliness in the poem 'Daffodils'.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet envies the union of the mass daffodils dancing beside the lake in comparison to his own loneliness.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The first stanza of the poem is where the beautiful union of the daffodils kept questioning the poets lonely mood. The daffodils are many, in contrast to the poet who is alone.  ' They streched in never - ending line'(line 9), 'Ten thousand saw I at a glance' (line 11).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Being alone, like the poet usually brings loneliness, depression and sadness but the view of the daffodils, the poet becomes happy and thrilled, forgetting his deep thought of sadness. ' I gazed - and - gazed -but little thought/ what wealth show me had bought ' ( lines 17 - 18).  The poet is later alone on a couch not once but many times (for often ... (line 19) ), in a dull mood but whenever he remembers the image of the daffodils, he becomes happy and calm ( which is the bliss of solitude/ And then my heart with pleasure fills) (lines 22-23).", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NON - AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on the poet's message to 'the court', 'Church' and 'Potentates' in \"The Soul's Errand\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'The Souls Erand' is a poem which is used to send messages to different aspects of human life and society. The poet sends the soul which is believed to reincarnate as the concsience, the message to  the church, potentages, the brave , etc. This message is to serve as a check to the opinion of men in high and low places as well as virtues and opinions.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet sends the soul to question the court of being arrogant and yet wholly rotten (line 8). Instead of giving fair judgement, it ends up bringing the poor to justice and leaving the affluent and the powerful off the the hook. The court also represents the palace in the olden days which amass wealth through taxes and use it to enrich itself at the detriment of the masses.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The church is being chastized for preaching what it does not practice (line 10). The church teaches essence of giving, but ends up amassing wealth without taking care of the poor and needy in their midst.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet further accuses the potentates (those in government) of favouritism and greed, respecting only those in large numbers (line 16). This poem is a satire which aims to proclaim the ills of the society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    Assess Eugene's relationship with his immediate family.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Eugene Achike is a prominent man in the Achike's village of Enugu, who runs several successful factories and publishes an English language newspaper infamous of its criticisms of Nigeria's corrupt government.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Eugene is a fanatically religious catholic who expects notjing less than perfectio n from his famil; Kambili(his daughter) , Jaja (his son) and Beatrice (his wife). Eugene is a strict and violent man who inflicts physical on Kambili and Jaga. Whenever any of Eugene's family member does anything that wouldn't even be considered wrong by anyone else, he makes sure that they have physical scars to show for it. He makes use of instruments and objects of turture to discipline his children when they do anything he feels is wrong. When he finds out that Kambili has a painting of his father, Papa Nnukwu, whom he loathes, he beats her until she was unconscious and has to be taken to the hospital. Jaja also has a deformed finger due to Eugene's severe punnishment.  Beatrice Eugene wife is also at the recieving end of Eugene's numerous beatings. He consider his family property and objects that must be treated as such. He hits his wife so many times and didn't ven stop when she was pregnant. All the sufferings and pain makes Beatrice poison Eugene's tea, which led to his death.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This inhuman character of Eugene also extends extends to his father, Pa Nnukwu and Ifeoma, his sister. His father lives in penury but Eugene, a rich man, refuses to alleviate his suffering all because Pa Nnukwu refuses to become a christian. Ifeoma also bears the burnt of Eugene's neglect because she didn't join the knights of Saint John, Eugene's order in the catholic church.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    Comment on the character of Jaja.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jaja is the son of Eugene and Beatrice. He is an older brother to Kambili. He is seventeen years old.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At the beginning of the book, Jaja is presented as a child. This is shown through the control his father has over him and how he blindly follows his father's orders. For example, Papa regularly forces Jaja, along with the rest of the family to go to communion. Inccidentially , this is what sparks the change that we see in Jaja throughout the story.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jaja becomes more confident and grows more both as a character and as a person. For example, he stands up to his father by refusing to go to communion. He knows he will get punnished but decides that his morals are more important.Jaja is a troubled young man as expected of a child from a family full of violence. He knows he ought to be supporting his mother and sisters but is not mentally strong enough . An example of this is when he could do nothing when his mother had a miscarraige.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As Jaja becomes mentally stronger, he begins to take more responsibility of himself and increasingly makes his own decisions for himself and his family. He later takes the blame for Mama (Beatrice) after she poison Papa ( Eugene), despite knowing the consequences.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    Narrate Pokuwaa's experience with her first two husbands.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pokuwaa marries three times in the novel, 'A Woman in Her Prime'. Her first husband is Kofi Daafo. She meets Kofi Daafo as a teeneger and they got married. However, she cant bear a child, so she leaves Kofi's house and marries Kwaku Fosu. With no child still, Pokuwaa is faced with so much unhappiness and scorn.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pokuwaa's mother nags her all the time, reminding her that a barren woman is not of use, so she pesters her to go through ancestral worships and ritual sacrifices. When all the efforts to have a child prove abortive she divorces Kwaku on her own terms. She later marries Kwadwo Fordwo.  Pokuwaa's Plight as a barren woman shows that the African woman frowns upon women who can't bear children. She is usually believed not to have done something right, and most times accused of being responsible for her misfortune. Pokuwaa later becomes pregnant in Kwadwo's house.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ASARE KONADU:  A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    How would you describe the relationship between Kwadwo and Pokuwaa?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kwadwo Fordwo is Pokuwaa's third husband. He is a successfulm farmer and hunter who is always ready to help his wife in her farm works and provide her games. Though he has other wives who had children before he married Pokuwaa, he is scared of loosing Pokuwaa because he loves her so much. He deliberately understands her situation and feels with her. 'There may be a time for a sitution. Nevertheless no situation is permanent' he contemplates. Sometimes, he even stays with her for a whole week, instead of the usual three days.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pokuwaa also loves Kwadwo and feels lonely whenever he is not around. She decides that Kwadwo will be her last husband and not even her inability to bear a child will make her leave him. The relationship between Pokuwaa and Kwadwo is cordial. Kwadwo acompanies Pokuwaa to Tano's shrine to make sacrifices concerning her barreness. When Pokuwaa also decides to stop bearing sacrifices, Kwadwo supports her and doesn't bother much about the sudden change of her mind and they lived happier than before.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At the end, Kwadwo's love and patience was rewarded when Pokuwaa conceives. This further strengthens their relationship.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ERNEST HEMINGWAY:  THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    Examine the character of Manolin", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Manolin, the boy is the symbol of the old man's lost youth. The old man treats Manolin as a father, so he teaches him fishing since his early childhood. After fourty days of fruitles fish hunting, Manolin's parents ordered him not to have anything to do with the man and he has no choice than to obey.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Though Manolin now works for a more successful fisherman, he continues to spend time with Santiago, bringing him fresh bart and food. Santiago humbly accepts these gifts and enjoys talking with the boy, Manolin admires Santiago so much that he declares the latter the greated fisherman.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Manolin is Santiago's last and deepest human relationship, his replacement in the generational circle of human existence, whom he wishes to entrust his skill as a fisherman and his memory. In accepting the Marlin's spear, Manolin demonstrates that he clearly understands and accepts all that Santiago wishes to bequeath him and all that comes with that inheritance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ERNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    Discuss the theme of Perseverence.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The book 'The Old Man And The Sea' portrays an Old  man Santiago, who suffers through life hardship to remain a live. Though he has skills as a fisherman, he comes home all the time from fishing trips, empty-handed. This made people refer to his as a failure but didnt give up fishing. He keeps trying to fish everyday and never sees himself as a failure. He perseveres all through the book, even when he makes a big catch that wasn't an easy feet for him.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The old man's battle with the fish is  not only a battle of strenght but a battle of wills. The old man makes up  for his old age with incredible endurance, willing to withstand hunger, physical pain and isolation from the world as he battles the fish.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Endurance becomes the way to connect the old man as he fights for the fish for over thirty hours though he was unsuccessful as the sharks ended up eating most part of his big catch.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    Give an account of the novel as a story of adventure.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Lord Of The Flies is an adventure novel which depicts the different facets of the human spirit. The novel took place on an Island where a group of British boys crashes. The boys are unruly and unorganized but finally the Ralph decides to take charge and calls a meeting. The boys declares him chief and follows his lead, assisted by piggy. The boys are getting along well until Jack Matthews decides to go on his own way.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The book is an adventure, as  we see how the nkids had to survive on their own. With Jack refusing to obey Ralph's orders, rivalry brews up between the two of them and Jack is chosen as the new leader, splitting the society into two communities. One comprises of those who hunt and subsequently become savages, and those who believe in rational conduct. With the passage of time, Ralph becomes an outcast. Most of the boys desert him and joins Jack's camp. This last move is informed by the fact that the boys drift more and more towards primitive existence since they now recognize the Island as their permanent place of abode. They see Jack as promising to fulfil this desire and Ralph as unduly rational.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this adventure , Simon and piggy loses their lives and towards the end of the novel, Ralph is tracked down by an army of hunters on Jacks orders. At the same instance that the savages are about to kill Ralph, a naval officer arrives with a rescue party.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2011>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    How does Ralph's exercise of authority differ form Jack's?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ralph represents a democratic and responsible leadership. He organizes assemblies, create rules and quickly matures into a 12 years old boy with a conscience. Unfortunately most of the boys are not looking for a  responsible leader. The boys want to be told what to do; they want to have fun and are easily manipulated. Ralph tries establish a working order. He is truly respectful of most of the boys and spends most of the time trying to prevent Jack from turning their Island into a living hell. Ralph is not forceful by nature and can not manipulate like Jack.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack on then other hand represents a dictatorship. He is naturally aggressive and learns to channel his aggression through clever manipulation. He learns to with hold when it benefits him and learns that ruling by fear is more effective than leading through consensus.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;While Ralph consistently tries to maintain order and civilized behaviour, Jack is consumed by hunting and meat. While Ralph successfully works on shelter for all, Jack hunts on his own because he is obsessed with killing a pig. When thing things begin to fall apart, Ralph grows wiser but Jack grows stronger. Ralph wants to talk and be reasonable but Jack only wants to use violence and force to maintain his power as chief over a tribe of 'savages'.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYI: THE BLINKARDS    Consider Barrister Onyimdze as a defender of African culture.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In spite of his sound knowledge of the English legal system, Barrister Onyimdze's love for, and practice of African ways of life, remain untainted and enviable. These qualities in him are shown on many occasions.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  One such occasion is when he bluntly refuses to marry a European lady when advised to do so by Mrs. Borofosem. This, according to him is most undesirable for Africans.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The lawyer also employs Okadu as his clerk and manages to teach him to appreciate African values.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His preference for African cloths, especially when he is not at work is remarkable; so is his love for African food and drinks such as 'ahe' a popular drink even among the fisherman's wives. In all these, he readily identifies with the common people, including their dance and music.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His love and defence of African values are eloquently expressed in his brilliant argument in favour of African traditional marriage when he takes the ill-fated Okadu-Tsiba marriage up. He acts as a foil to Mrs. Borofosem. It is his steadfast defense of African values which finally turns characters like Mrs. Borofosem around.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYI: THE BLINKARDS  Comment on the comportment of the cosmopolitan club members.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Members of this \"elite\" group are a bunch of Africans struggling between two cultures neither of which they are appreciably integrated into. The club is a motley assemblage of semi-literatures and university graduates who choose to adopt hook, line and sinker, a number of English ways of life at the expense of  their own authetic cultural values.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The speech delivered by their secretary during the ill-conceived Okadu-Tsiba wedding ceremony sums up all that is ludicrous in their comportment. The speech urges those aspiring to be gentlemen to abhor all that is African food, drinks and the use of the mother tongue to mention a few. To them, the ostenations use of high falum words and heavily loaded expressions shows a mastery of the English language. Thus Mr. Nku's speech is ludicrously laced with such jaw-breaking words as \"lachrimosity\" instead of \"tears\", \"celibacy\" instead of 'bachelor' and \"hymeneal altar\" instead of \"weddiing\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In their blind adoption of alien ideas, the club members completely lose touch with the essential aspects of marriage ceremonies in the two cultures. This abysmal ignorance is portrayed in their proposing three different toasts instead of one during the Okadu-Tsiba wedding ceremony, as is typical of English society wedding.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The expression \"black  skin white masks\" fittingly captures the component of the cosmopolitan club members. The sharp contradictions in their blindly adopted ways of life expose their ludicrous position between the two cultures.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISAN: WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss Gesinde's contribution to the development of the plot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gesinde plays an important role in the play. He provides information about important events in the play \"Women of Owu\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As herald of the Allied Forces, he is a symbol of loyalty and remains faithful to his master from the beginning to the end. According to Erelu, Gesinde is a messenger of Odom; anytime he appears among the women, they expect the worst. It is he who carries out the killing of Adumaadan's son and announces the fate of the captive women, including the queen, Erelu and her daughterss.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite the fact that Gesinde engages in terrible actions in obedience to the orders of his master, he is quite emotional and defensive. Gesinde claims that he is only a messenger and therefore not responsible for whatever action is taken on the women: \"I am only a messenger, just a borrowed mouth\". He sheds tears at the sight of Adumaadan's paying her last respects to her slain son. He is movef with pity and volunteers to dig a grave and bury the baby Aderogun - Adumaadan's son.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gesinde is also a gossip in the play. When he discovers that Maye is willing to take Iyunloye his unfaithful wife back home, he comments, \"beauty has conquered again, as before\". He callously announces the victory of Iyunloye to the women in their agony.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISAN: WOMEN OF OWU    Comment on the agreement between Anlugbua and Lawumi to punish the Allied Forces.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Allied Forces have sacked the city of Owu, and the ancestral deity, Anlugbua , looks upon the destruction, dejected. He is met by his mother - Lawunmi. From their conversation it seems that the war is the result of the intervention of the gods in the affairs of men even though the contribution of mortals cannot be ignored. It is Lawunmi's decree that Owu should be punished through its sacking by the Allied Forces desecrate the holy places and set fire to the shrine of Lawunmi. For this they must be made to pay.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lawunmi is particularly angry because the Allied Forces have not only killed her worshippers but also chased Owu people running to her shrine for refuge and massacred them there. They have even captured the princess Orisaye, who is the vestal votary of Obatala. Lawunmi's anger finds satisfaction in the help she expects from other deities who will confound the return journey of the Allied Forces. She avers that the gods are not the plaything of mortals. It seems certain that, being angry because his shrine has not been spared , Ogun, the god of war, will enter the fray. Anlugbua agrees to join.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The agreement that mother and son makes suggests that mortals are mere pawns in the game of chess that the gods play. At every stage of the conflict, it seems that the gods are the initiators of the animosity that leads to renewed aggression in the fight between mortal and his fellow mortal.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The gods seem interested in the daily conduct of mortals; they will cause mortals to fight other mortals to fight other mortals to punish their erring colleagues. However, these gods do not control the temper of the warriors or the tempo of the war. In the end, the favourite side in the reprisal game exceeds the mandate to punish and the extent of punishment. Then it must pay for its excesses. The gods are whimsical and capricious.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    Examine the differences between Louka and Raina", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The differences between Raina and Louka are both social and behavioural. On the one hand, Raina belongs to the upper class as a daughter of aristocrats. On the other hand Louka belongs to the lower class and works for the aristocrats Petkoffs as housemaid.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina as an aristocrat, tends to look down on Louka as she believes she is superior to her by reason of birth. For instancee, she will not want Louka to tell the family what to do when the latter warns them to take cover against the smoking guns. On her part, Louka does not accept an inferiority stains and sees Raina as her equal irrespective of her aristocratic status. And so she does not hesistate to call her by name.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina begins as an idealist and seems to be enamoured of Major Sergius owing to his actually wants in him. Therefore she continues to waste time, day-dream and date both Serguis and Bluntschli at different times.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the contrary, Louka is a realist and a schemer. She knows what she wants in marriage from the outset. Her grand design is to use marriage to climb up the social ladder and join the likes of the Petkoffs at the top. And she deploys everything, including boldness, eaves-dropping, gossip, blackmail, wit and seduction to turn Sergius and Raina against each other and then wins Sergius as would-be-husband.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina is complacent and believes that her social status is a sufficient credential to make anybody fall in love with her. Louka on her own part, knows her limitations as an underdog. She never takes things for granted and she always keeps her ears to the ground. That explains why she boldly restorts:    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"My love is at stake/ I am not ashamed\"  when Raina accuses her of jealousy and eavesdropping.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    How is Catherine revealed as an accomplished liar in the garden scene?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is a lot of lying and insincerity in the play as a whole. On various occasions, the characters evade the truth and put on dubious appearances. Catherine leads the way in this evasion of the truth.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Having enjoyed the hospitality of Catherine and her daughter, captain Bluntchli returns to restore the coat he has borrowed and to thank the women for coming to his rescue.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He arrives at a bad time because Petkoff and Sergius are in the house. Catherine is unable and unwilling to let the others in on her secret. She covers up through telling obvious lies.    She insists on taking Sergius's place in solving the problem of sending the three regiments to Philoppopolis so that Sergius and Raina may be alone. She is particularly afraid for the relationship between Serguis and Raina should the truth become known. Already Catherine has managed to tell a lie regarding the whereabouts of her husband's coat.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Louka announces a Swiss officer, Catherine knows who it is at once. She is determined that her husband should not know about the presence of the newcomer. When it becomes clear that Petkoff has actually seen the man already, Catherine declares that she has been trying to persuade the Captain to stay for lunch but he'd rather leave. This is a lie. It is a hint to the man to leave the family alone. When Raina enters and blurts out her familiarity with the man, the game is nearly given away. She recovers quickly and tells a tale to cover up her recognition of Captain Bluntschli.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Catherine backs her daughter's lie for obvious reasons: their acquaintance with the Swiss officer must not be known.  Then Nicola arrives with the man's bag as Catherine has instructed. She denies knowledge of what Nicola is talkig about. Nicola takes a chiding from Petkoff and is threatened with dismissal. Catherine dare not own up the truth. Having told one lie, she must back it up with others.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Examine the use of satire in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Satire occurs in a variety of situations in the play. Gwendolen is extraordinary obsessed with the name \"Ernest\", rather than with earnestness itself. This attitude of hers shows how members of the society set so much store by appearances and affectations. Wilde uses Brcknell's interrogation of Jack to satirize the values of a society who puts premium on social connections and downplays good character. Marriage in this society is based on wealth rather than on good behaviour. Lady Bracknells' list of eligible suitors does not include Jack who, presumably, has no name and no fortune.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Same is also at woork in the revelation scene. The inadvertent swapping of the baby with the manuscript of a mere novel is evidence of society's misplaced priority.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The scene in which Jack woos Gwendolen shows the reverse of the assumptions about gender roles. Decorum requires that young women be weak and passive while men are supposed to be active, competent and authoritative. Yet, Jack stammers ineffectually and Gwendolen actively controls the whole  business of the proposal. The rigid nature of Victorian conventions is exposed as Gwendolen insists that Jack start the whole marriage proposal over again in the conventional way. The same essentially applies to the Cecily Algernon relationship.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Comment on the role of Gwendolen Fairfax.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gwendolen is Algernon's cousin. She is also Lady Bracknell's daughter. She is not only elegant, fashionable and sophisticated, but also artificial and pretentious. She is in love with Jack because she finds him irresistible solely because of her belief that Jack's name is Ernest. She swears that she cannot marry any man who is not called Ernest.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This obsession of Gwendolen's sustains the plot as it stands in sharp contrast to Lady Bracknell's adherence to social convention. By what society approves, an eligible suitor cannot but be on her list, even if he is not Ernest. In contrast, Gwendolen's man need only be Ernest whether he is a man of enough substance to earn a place on her mother's list. Gwendolen exposes the misplced notion of the society about the nature of men. A man is seen as all strength, manliness and capabilty. Contrary to this, at the crucial moment, Jack stammers while Gwendolen takes over and steers the process of the marriage proposal herself.  As part of the hypocritical system, she pretends, on her meetings Cecily that she does not mind being in the company of a girl of the countryside. The argument between her and Cecily when the two become entangled in the confusion of which Ernest each is in love with reveals their infatuation with symbols appearances rather than reality.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thus, it is Gwendolen's resolve to marry only a man named Ernest that moves the plot forward. Her position leads Jack to his desire to be christened. This in turn leads to revelations that Jack, after all, is Ernest. He actually has been christened as such.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss the suffering of the masses in  \"Myopia\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poems depicts two categories of people, the rulers and the ruled. The rulers are the politicians and the ruled are the masses. By implication, the rulers/politicians have everything and are indifferent to the plight of the masses.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The suffering of the masses is graphically presented in the poem: They are unprotected from the elements, being described as  \" shivering in their emaciated bones''. And they lack substance as rice fields are ''putrid mashlands'' and are mere shadows of their glorious past.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The anger of the poet is both self-directed and other directed. His helplessness at ameliorating the suffering of the masses is felt in the line \"let me be the hangman hanging myself\". But the greater rage is reserved for the politicians who are responsible for the plight of the masses. The poem ends on a call to action against these politicians. Nothing but a revolution would do.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on \"Boy on a swing\" as a search for self identity.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The boy is obviously having a nice time on the swing apparently guided by his mother. As the swing moves slowly, to and fro, the boy seems to be in a joyful and playful mood, apparently undisturbed by the social events around him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the swing moves faster and faster and as matters become confused and uncontrollable in his head \"East becomes west...\" joy and happiness give way to serious concerns. The need arises for explanation from somebody, particularly his mother. That is the point where the identity crisis becomes prominent. This manifests in the rhetorical questions he asks:  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Where did I come from?  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When will I wear long trousers?  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Why was my father jailed?  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is increasingly worried about his identity. \"Where did I come from?\" the misery around him- \"When I wear long trousers?\" - and the injustice of society that has incarcerated his father - \"Why was my father jailed?\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem ends, not resolving the boy's crisis.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NON AFRICAN POETRY    Comment on the imagery in \"The Sun Rising.\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"The Sunne Rising\" is ostensibly a confrontation between a lover and the rising sun. In the encounter the poet employs various images. The opening lines conjure a powerful image of intrusion. The sun is presented as an intruder who 'through windows and through curtains call on us'. The visitor is clearly unwelcome. The sun's intrusion actually makes poet angry and he resorts to harsh words: \"Busie old foole, unruly sunne\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The sun is presented in the image of a busy-body who should take his meddlesome familiarity elsewhere - to rebuke 'late schools boyes' sowre prentices' or provide service to 'court-huntsmen'.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The image of the sun's powerful beam and his wink which can \"eclipse\" the sun is an interesting conceit. The poet patronizingly declines to pursue his challenge with the excuse that, he cannot afford to lose his mistress's sight.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet another image is that which involves the sun's age - \"thine age askes ease\" - as it performs its duty to shine on the whole world. By another metaphysical conceit, the whole world is shrunk into the poet's bedroom - \"these walls\" with the poet and his mistress at the centre. Thus by shining upon them, the sun reduces its labour of shining on the whole world which has now become the poet's bedroom.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reference can also be made to the image of the poet and his mistress as embodying all the riches of the world. This is seen in the lines -\"she's all States, and all Princes, I, / Nothing else is\" - Thus, honor, prestige, wealth are possessed by them and the sum does well by providing services to them alone.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss the theme of fate in \"Upon An Honest Man's Fortune.\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet confidently asserts that man is the author of his own life. The poet's views that man is his own star\" is consistent with the general belief that man is in control of his own destiny. This view is stressed throughout the poem as the poet pours scorn on the so-called astrologers and star-gazers.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As man is created in the image of God who endows him with talents, the poet rightly contends that the sky is the limit for man who is in search of perfection. As such, man should be able to find his own bearing in life and shape the course of his own affairs, as \"nothing to him falls early or too  late\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem reveals that, in spite of the influence of the stars and other forces of nature, man's fate in life depends on his honesty \"The soul that can/ render an honest and perfect man, commands all light...\". For it is man's action or inaction that makes or breaks him as is expresses in the line, \"our acts our angels are, or good or ill.\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet therefore condemns those who rely on outside forces to shape their destiny because God has empowered man to be the master of his own fate and should rely on him for direction.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ASARE kONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    How does Pokuwaa cope with tradition in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The novel provides a graphic picture of a society that is rooted in custom and tradition and Pokuwaa is no exception. Her devotion to carrying out the sacrifies and purification rites marks her out as a devotee of tradition.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, there is loss of confidence and disenchantment when she discovers that in spite of this religious devotion through sacrifices to the gods, her ambition is far from being realized. When thunder strikes the baobab tree outside the village, the people of Brenhoma feel it is a bad omen and that the gods are angry and must be pacified. Pokuwaa seriously takes part in the purification rites praying that the gods will make her fertile. She has performed several purification rites to the god Tano and has consulted several herbalists without success.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To add to her disappointment, she realizes that there is little difference between the herbal medicines given to her by the Tano priest and the ones she has received from other herbalists -- medicines which have failed to work. This accentuates her doubts about the efficacy of traditional medicine. Her doubts even extend to the belief in ancestral influences.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her journey to the Ananse stream, though made in ignorance, reveals an attitude of mind that has given up the idea of strictly following the tradition of the society. When Pokuwaa is urged to return the hornbill which she has caught from an eagle, she goes just a few yards into the bush and throws the hornbill away.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The resolve by Pokuwaa to discontinue making sacrifices to the gods is an expression of dissatisfaction with the state of affairs. She destroys the pot she has hitherto used to prepare the herbal drugs and burns the tailsman she has worn round her waist. After she has done all these, she experiences peace. Thus her coming pregnant only after she has discontinued the sacrifice, is a vindication of her refusal to adhere slavishly to tradition and spells victory for her.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    Comment on the significance of the search for Yaw Boakye.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yaw Boakye is an important member of the Brenhoma community. He leaves on a Monday to go hunting and does not return home. In keeping with the practice of the community, a search party is organized.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The search for Yaw Boakye highlights the gregarious nature of the society. It shows that people are concerned about the welfare of others. The young men of the village do not need any prompting: they turn up in their numbers to take part in the search as soon as Boakye's disappearance is announced.  Their commitment to seeking each other's welfare is not in doubt. They drop all that they are engaged in and concentrate on finding their kinsman - dead or alive. Pokuwaa's concern for the welfare of her husband, Kwadwo comes out during the search for Boakye. She does not want him to be first to come upon the hideous sight of Boakye's corpse. She has seen it, and does not want to subject her husband to the horror which it holds, if she can prevent it. She therefore directs him to conduct his search far away from where she knows the corpse is.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The search also demonstrate the highly orgainzed structure of Brenhonan society. The men are divided into several groups, each group led by a captain whose authority is undisputed.  Further, the search heightens suspense in the  novel. As the men move slowlyin groups toward the corpse of Boakye, the narrator captures their every movement. The suddenness of the end of the search surprises even the reader. As vultures whirl overhead, the reader suspects that the men are approaching Boakye's corpse. But, the end comes suddenly, encoded in traditional register: \"Wasps! Wasps! Take care!\" Soon the drums are relaying the message \"We mourn Yaw Boakye. Condolences\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally in the search highlights the belief in superstition which plays an important role in the lives of the people. Even though there is as yet no evidence that Yaw Boakye is dead, the searchers have come to the conclusion that what Pokuwaa has reportedly seen a couple of days earlier has been Boakye's ghost. Thus as they proceed in their search for him, the fear of encountering his ghost lingers in their minds.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    Compare Aunt Ifeoma and her brother's relationship with their children", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene and Aunt Ifeoma love their children dearly but hey will not permit their children to step out of line. When it comes to punishsment, Eugene and Aunt Ifeoma punish firmly and promptly any  infraction of their children. Whereas Ifeoma is humane and restrained Eugene is harsh and unreasonable.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Throughout the novel, Aunt Ifeoma is not seen punishing her children much. According to Amaka's account of punishment to Kambili, each time Aunt Ifeoma punishes them she explains the reason for the punishment. Amaka confesses in her usual, frank manner that she prefers her punishment not be linked with any attempt of justification. Aunt Ifeoma is seen constantly guiding her erring children with physical punishment.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On one occasion, however, she does what she must do. Her eldest son, present during a conversation with her friend rudely shows his disagreement with her by cutting into their conversation. His mother promptly orders him to shut up and go upstairs immediately. She apologises to her friend and after her friend has left, she follows the youth upstairs, slaps and gives him a thrashing. She tells him that she will not tolerate insolence. She is not opposed to her son disagreeing with her friend, it is his manner of approach that she punishes.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene, on the other hand, goes to the extreme and does not weigh his punishment with the gravity of the offence. Scalding the children's feet deliberatley for living with their heathen grandfather without informing him is no way to punish a child.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Again, when Kambili attempts to collect the pieces of her grandfather's torn painting she is beaten mercilessly and ends up in hospital. He explains to the children that the punishment is for their own good. It seems Eugene like Aunt Ifeoma does not hate his children.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Their behaviour to their children is very different. In other respects Eugene's home is opluent; he provides his children with all the comfort which he can give. Aunt ifeoma's children live ordinary lives. However, the atmosphere of Eugene's home is stifling and life-denying while Aunt Ifeoma's howe is warm and accomodating. Eugene's children have a strict schedule on how to conduct themselves. There is a strict limit to their liberty. In Aunt Ifeoma's home, however, the children are allowed to grow up as children and play without restriction to their freedom.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI : PURPLE HIBISCUS    Examine the role of Papa Nnukwu in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp Papa-Nnukwu is the father of Eugene and Ifeoma. He is a symbol of tradition in the novel since it is through him that we see the real tradition religion and how it is practised. He pours libation and offers food to the gods when he eats.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is essentially a traditionalist. He regrets the day his son went away with the missionaries. He is marvelled by the big mansion his son has which could accomodate all the people in Abba, while he lives from hand to mouth.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is not the type that can easily be lured by flashly giftss to change his principles. He refuses an offer of a bigger house and a car by his son if he abandons his faith - traditional religion. Although all the members of his clan side with Eugene, he maintains that he will want to see his grandchildren, a request which is granted, although grudgingly, by Eugene.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is prophetic. He announces to his grandchildren that his seeing them frequently presages that he would soon join his ancestors. It is not long after this that he dies in his sleep while with them at Nsukka.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Papa-Nnukwu is a humorist as opposed to his grave and unsmiling son Eugene. Whenever he is with his grandchildren he is either telling them traditional folktales or making jokes with them. He is a good entertainer. Thus Amaka, Obiara, and Chima can hardly stay away from him for long.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His role in the novel helps to lighten the tense atmosphere of tragedy that pervades it. While going out sightseeing with the grandchildren in Aunt Ifeoma's car, he creates laughter when he says. \"What are those children saying gbo Ifeoma?... Are they conspiring to share my gold and many lands?'\" Here we see the old man trying to put aside the commuincation barrier between him and his grandchildren. Again, he exaggrates his height, by saying that in his \"youthful days he could pluck \"icheku\" from the trees by just reaching out high'. This also exudes humor.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He respects his own religion just as Eugene respects his but Papa-Nnukwu is not fanatical about his. He prays for Eugene just as he prays for his daughter and grandchildren. He even prays for his enemies - an embodiment of a perfect traditionalist, and not a heathen.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    Comment on Jack's leadership style.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jack competes with Ralph for leadership of the group the very day the boys arrive and find themselves on the island. He is over-ambitious. He despises Piggy because of his ability to reason and Ralph because of his charisma. Jack does not want to follow protocol as they have all agreed. Rather, he is more inclined by nature to rule with force and give orders as he wishes without being questioned or seeking the others' views.  Jack is violent and, blood-thirsty by nature and makes a reckless display of these in public. Jack, together with Roger, masterminds a reign of a terror on the Island. He trains the boys to become savages. Jack's love for power crowds out his thought of rescue. He concludes that they may not be rescued and the best course is to enjoy the game of survival. Thus he breaks away from the boys, and sets up his own community where he can be the leader and dictate to his boys.  Jack wins the boys' support by creating avenues for them to have fun as he involves them in games and killing of Simon who is mistaken for the dreaded beast. Eventually the couch and assembly become ineffectual and the island becomes a place for the survival of the fittest. Piggy's pair of spectacles is stolen; and in the course of attempting to retrieve it , Piggy gets killed by Roger. Ralph is marked for death, as he is smoked out of his hiding, before being rescued by the naval officer.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    Discuss fear as a dominant theme in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fear runs all through the novel, and dictates the behaviour of the boys. Right from the day they appear on the island the boys are seized with various types of fear. These manifest in some of the boys and in their general comportment.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The fear of being marooned forever is Piggy's immediate preoccupation. He pesters Ralph with his sentiments. Not even Ralph's assurance that his own father, a pilot, will come for them in due course will allay Piggy's fears. Throughout his existence on the island, Piggy draws attention to actions that are likely to get them rescued, such as running to swim and keeping the fire going.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All the boys, except perhaps Simon, are afraid of the beast. The beast is not known and so the fear of it is not tangible. Perhaps this is what makes the boys' situation as dangerous as it is. This type of fear leads them to tackle their uneasiness by trial and error- hunting dancing and fighting in order to sweep the fear under the carpet.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ralph is particularly afraid that the unity of the group may disintegrate and the group may become debashed. What begins as a mere reminder to the boys to use the toilet and drinking and washing places as designated, turns real when the boys break into two antagonistic groups.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite Jack's outward show of toughness and capacity to lead, he struggles to hide his own fear of the beast. He tries hard to look natural, but intimidates others to feel on top of events. He easily keeps a boy tied up awaiting his pleasure; he dictates who may have meat, and offers Ralph and the others meat because he decides to.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack's fear intensifies with the murder of Simon and harden into a strong desire to eliminate Ralph. In this development, Ralph looks like a prophet. His premonitions and real dislike of Jack's behaviour are significant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through fear seems to be collectively felt by the boys, Simon appears to be the only one not affected like the others. Naturally, without fear, he demystifies the fear in the novel. Insightfully, he comments that the beast might just be themselves. This observation, which might have saved these boys, is ignored. Simon's ultimate discovery is never revealed as he is killed by others, who remain afraid of the beast, which he has discovered to be a harmless, undignified, dead man.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It may be said that several actions of the children are driven by fear of one kind or the other.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Ernest Hemmingway: The Old Man and the Sea    Examine the use of flashback and monoloogue in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The use of flashback provides the reader with ample information about Santiago's past-family life and failures. Through this means, the reader learns that Santiago teaches Manolin to fish and that they have both gone on several fishing expeditions before. Through the flashback device, the readder also discovers that, as a young man, the old man, known as Santiago El Campeon, is a bundle of energy. It is this vigorous energy that he unleashes to defeat the great negro of Cienfuegos in a nerve -racking hand game.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is also through the use of flashback that the reader learns of Santiago's love for baseball, and his liking for beer and coffee. All these serve to bring out the humanity of Santiago and make it easier for the reader to empathize with him in his travails at sea. The use of monologue also runs through the novel. By this means, the old fisherman talks to himself on several occasions. So also does he addresses the aquatics and aerial creatures, including the great fishes and the sharks he has to contend with as through they could hear him and respond.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In particular monologue, Santiago does not fail to recognize the strong affinity between man and the elemental forces, in spite of the relentless struggle between them and man. He believes that like us the elements have feelings and that they deserve not only understanding but also love and respect. For instance, he sees  the sea as feminine - la mar- and something that can give or withhold favours and that if she does wild or wicked things at times it is because she cannot help it. He equally believes that the marlin he traps and wants to kill also has the right to live, struggle for dear life and kill him in self-defence.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The use of monologue therefore enables the reader to have an insight into the old man's subconscious and inner self, especially his deep feelings about the marlin, Manolin, human nature and the quintessential stuff he himself is made of.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2012>PAPER 3>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Ernest Hemmingway: The Old Man and the Sea    Discuss Santiago's struggle with the Marlin.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The marlin is an extraordinarily big fish that Santiago uses much of his time struggling to catch. Going without catching a fish for eighty-four days, Santiaago has almost been certain that the fish he will catch eventually will be a large fish.  When the old man sets out on the day of his catch, he is businesslike. From his experience, he knows the exact measurement of the lengths of line, and the various depths at which different fish may be caught. He waits patiently, telling himself to fish the day well.  Santiago is ready when the marlin bites. He allows the fish to settle for the struggle, as he lets the line to run through his fingers. This strategy makes it certain that the fish does not panic, for it must not feel any tension in the line at this point.  Santiago idolizes the marlin and sees it as his own brother. He urges himself to match the fish's nobility. He tells himself that he has to prove worthy of the fish, when he catches it.  As the fish takes the bait and appears to take his time, Santiago fantasizes about what the fish is actually doing and the actual manner of the fish's eating of the sardines. He urges the marlin to be decorous and not spoil the event. Soon  the fish begins to move seaward, at first turning slowly. The old man tries to haul it in, but the fish stays down, moving further and further to sea. As they move seaward, Santiago resolves, not to hurry the struggle but hold on steadily, as the fish draws him away to sea, and give it line as is appropriate.  For a long time, the marline drags the old man about. He talks to the fish even though he does not see it. He misses the boy and talks to himself regarding his not having salt. He is afraid that his hand might become cramped at the crucial time.  Eventually, the fish rises to the surface and is caught, killed and strapped to the skit. But for sharks, this would have been the end of the struggle. Sharks, however, extend the man's struggle. Now he must save the fish from being stolen by sharks. In this he fails, and brings to shore only the skeleton of the marlin.  Yet Santiago, as far as his friend, the boy, is concerned, does not lose the fight against the fish. He has given a good account of himself, and from now onwards he will go to sea with the boy. At any rate, that this boy;s decision. Though he loses the fish, he emerges triumphant, and in high spirit.  Santiago's catch draws admiration from his colleague fisherman and tourists alike. They are full of respect for him in the end.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYI : THE BLINKARDS    How is African life presented in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Blinkards is about how people perceive the way of life of the African and that of the European. One view point is that the European way is suerior to the African.    In presenting African life as not only adequate but also appropriate  for the African environment, Sekyi uses satire which makes Mrs. Borofosem and her condemnation of African life look ludicrous. The position of Mrs. Borofesem members of the Cosmopolitan Club and others like them is that African life is crude. Mainly through the influence of Mrs. Borofosem, characters like Okadu and Miss Tsiba adopt this stance towards African culture.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mrs. Borofosem and her ilk assume that the things that European do are what should be done and that the way they do them is the way things should be done. For this reason, she does and sees things through an obviously faulty perception of the European life she so highly extols. She naturally begins her attack on African culture at home. To her husband's chagrin, he must not sing Fanti songs! He must drop cigar ash on the carpet and not wear cloth. He is under obligation to kiss his wife at random and call her 'duckie' because \"Mrs. Gush my friend at Seaborne on the East Coast is always addressed by her husband as 'duckie' \".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through Mrs. Borofosem's influence over Miss Tsiba and the ahyentarfo Mrs. Borofosem decrees that European dress be preferred to African cloth and African food and drink be regarded as unwholesome for civilized persons. It is ironical that Mrs. Borofosem herself does an about-turn to embrace African life, acknowledging that her earlier attitude has been a mistake.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr Onyimdze, Nana Katawerwa and Na Sompa and the atanfurafo hold a contrary view. For them, an African must look like and be African.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. Onyimdze is attached to his culture. However, he accomodates the European way. He does not reject European dressing; he wears his lawyer's robe and regards it as appropriate for his calling. However, after work, he takes it off, preferring African clothes. His diet comprises both European and African foods, hence when Miss Tsiba and Mrs. Borofosem visit Mr Onyindze in his home, Miss Tsiba may choose between a cake and borezentotoe.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Mrs. Borofosem and Onyimdze factions clash continually until the advocates of African culture prevail through Onyimdze's winning of the court case for Nana Katawerwa. All in all, African life is presented as adequate and suitable for the Africans. It is now left to Mr. Borofosem, who has not defended African culture that strongly to admit that \"Really, Onyimdze was right all long..\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KOBINA SEKYI : THE BLINKARDS    Comment on the role of Mr. Okadu in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr Okadu is a clerk in Clutney's store. He is one who follows western beliefs and practices blindly and treats African customs contemptuously. He cuts a ludicurous figure in his attempt to mimic the white man with his bad English and his ridculous mannerism. In presenting the character of Mr Okadu, the playwright satirizes Africans who copy western beliefs and practices indiscriminately. For example, when Mr. Onyimdze suggests at the garden-party that they should speak Fanti, Mr Okadu objects: \"Why, stir, this is a garden-party, sir- English idea. We must talk English, sir.\" This characterizes his behaviour throughout the play.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr Okadu serves as a destablizing force in the Tsiba household. His relationship with Miss Tsiba tears the home apart. First, it is a source of conflict between Mr. Tsiba and his wife, Na Sompa. Mr Tsiba supports the union because he sees in it a route to enhancing the status of his family. Na Sompa is incensed and does not conceal her hatred of Okadu. Na Sompa quits her home because of her opposition to the union and threatens never to speak to her husband again. Furthermore, the relationship between Mr. Okaddu and Miss Tsiba results in Na Sompa's heart failure and eventual death. This accentuates the negative influence of Mr. Okadu on those around him.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Okadu epitomizes the alienated African who attempts to defend the beliefs and values he has uncritically adopted when they come under threat. For example, when Okadu's marriage to Miss Tsiba to court on a charge of bigamy. He is stubborn and refuses to let go even though it a clear that he has little support. Interestingly, this action leads to the climax of the play. The triumph of lawyer Onyimdze over Mr. Okadu in court symbolizes a triumph of traditional values over imported western beliefs and practices. This hastens Mrs. Borofose's rehabilitation at the end of the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISAN: WOMEN OF OWU    Examine the role of the supernatural in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The supernatural looms large over the people of Owu and keeps the entire Kingdom under its influence. It is the combined acts of the gods and the blessing of Edumare, the Supreme God of the Yorubas that culminate in building and making Owu the safest of all Yoruba cities. But, it is also the action or inaction of the same gods that leaves the same city in ruins. This is attested to by no less a goddess than Lawunmi, the ancestral Queen mother and goddess of the Owus during her conversation with Anlugbua after the fall of the Kingdom. The fall of Owu does not come as a surprise to the gods, especially, Lawunmi. The fall is even supernaturally contrived, aided and abetted. It is in fact the logical and deserved consequence of Owu's condemnable acts of omission or commission.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One of such act is the Owu people's blatant show of arrogance not only to Lawunmi but also to the Ile Ife, the cradle of the Yorubas. \"Drunk with prosperity\" the Owus throw caution to the wind and sack Apomu, Ife's commercial satelite town, and send people away into slavery. By so doing they break the sacred law of Sango, the Yoruba god of thunder, that no Yoruba man shall sell his compatriot into slavery. For this, Owu must be punished by the gods and it is with the consuming fire power of the Allied Forces.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The pervasive influence of the supernatural is also seen in the unfallingly gloomy prediction of the Oracle. Through the priest, the Oracle warns that prince Dejumo must be killed in his cradle or else he will ultimately bring gloom ad doom to the Kingdom. However, Erelu, the mother, ignores the warning and spares the life of the son. The ill-fated prince grows up and abducts Iyunloye after the sack of Apomu. The aggrieved husband, an artist-turned-soldier. leads the Allied Forces to invade Owu and destroy it even beyond Lawunmi's widest imagination.  But the Supernatural influence is not over yet because the destruction of Owu does not leave Lawunmi and even Ogun - the god of metallic ore' unbruised. The gods agree to collaborate with Lawunmi to avenge the apparent excesses of the Allied Forces in flattening and desecrating their shrines even as women and children throng there to seek refuge. And as Orunnmila - god of divination, predicts, the return of the Allied Forces will be filled with grief; Esu will create problems for them at every cross-road; Orisa Oko will turn forests against them while Anlugbua, the ancestral father and deity, will unleash storm on them on their homeward journey. With their lives largely ruled and controlled by the supernatural, the Owu people seem to have no doubt in their minds that all this will come to pass.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMI OSOFISAN : WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss Maye Okunade's reasons for attacking Owu Kingdom.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To the causal observer,Maye, a successful artist, suddenly turned soldier, leads the Owu campaign for selfless and patriotic reasons. One reason is the need to punish Owu for attacking Apomu, the commercial satelite town of Ife. The other is to stop the slave trade.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, a close examination of Maye's real motive reveals other reasons. Maye is essentially an artist, not known to be a warmonger. Rather, he is a lover and defender of all that makes life worth living. And so he will rather go to war for reasons of romance than those of heroism. As events later show, the motive behind the man's war exploits is the burning desire to reclaim Iyunloye, his abducted bautiful wife.    Against all expectations that Maye will summarily execute Iyunloye for her promiscuity, he allows her to defend herself - an opportunit that Iyunloye seizes to seduce and bewitch him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp Maye -- against very stiff opposition, especially from Erelu -- rules that Iyunloye will no longer be killed in Owu but in Ife. To the dimay of soldiers and civilians alike, Maye and Iyunloye go back to Ife in the same caravan in a most erotic mood. This is how Maye actualizes his hidden agenda.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BERNARD SHAW : ARMS AND THE MAN    What are your impressions on Sergius as a soldier?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Major Sergius Saranoff is a Bulgarian army commander who leads his regiment to win a battle against the Serbs at Silvinitza. However, both his critics and admirers consider him to be a failure and he admits he is.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To Catherine, who sees him as a future son-in-law and to Raina his fiancee, he is no doubt the gallant and the perfect soldier. But he is an inexperienced soldier who leads \"a charge on his own responsiblity\" and blindly \"sweeps through the guns with ordinary swords\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bluntschll's assessment of his performance at the warfront is even more damning. Bluntshll describes him as a foolish, tactless and quixotic soldier who, without initiative, fights at close range with swords against enemies with fire arms. He is \"like a drum major\" and he and his men are like \"fools let loose on a field of battle\" where he leads them to commit suicide.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Because Sergius is an inexperienced soldier, he does not know how to save the lives of his troops. As he foolishly owns up himself, he conserves his own life but loses all his men while the Russian mercenaries lose only two generals but preserve all their  men.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a tactless and inexperienced soldier who wantonly wastes the lives of his men on the battle field, Sergius's conquest of the Serbs at Silvintza is therefore seen as a pyrrhic victory. For this reason Major Petkoff refuses to promote him after the war. This is why he resigns prematurely from the army.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BERNARD SHAW : ARMS AND THE MEN    How significant is Major Petkoff's coat in the development of the plot?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Major Petkoff's coat makes a significant contribution to the development of the plot. Much of the action of the play hinges on Bluntschll's 'borrowing' of Major Petkoff's coat and its return which builds the play's suspense.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bluntschll, a Swiss mercenary fighting on the side of the Serbs, in a bid to escape from his pursuers, strays into the bedroom of Raina, Major Petkoff's daughter. He needs to escape and Raina, already attracted to him, lends him her father's coat to facilitate his escape. The coat is therefore used to advance the plot as it serves as vehicle for Bluntschll's escape from Bulgaria.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raina places her portrait in the pocket of the coat. This raises further complications in th plot of the play. When Bluntschll returns the  coat, he gives it to Catherine with Raina's portrait still in the pocket.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Major Petkoff has noticed that the coat is missing although his wife has tried to convince him to believe the contrary. When he finds the coat, he sees Raina's portrait in it. He, however, keeps quiet, waiting for a satisfactory explaination. As he is preparing to go with Major Sergius and Captain Bluntschll for the rehabilitation of the Bullgarian soldiers, he calls for the coat. Cleverly, taking the coat from Nicola, Raina stealthily removes the portrait before putting the coat on the father. To her father's surprise the portrait is no longer in the pocket. This development provokes an anxious moment of accusation about who may have removed it. To everybody's surprise but relief also, Bluntschll speaks up and the whole story surrounding the escape is told at no cost to the major players. The matter is, therefore, resolved to the satisfaction of all.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Discuss the use of humour in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The play abounds with humour. The most serious matters are dealt with humourously and the mannerism of some of the characters exude humour.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First we see Algernon eating up the cucumber sandwiches he has prepared for his aunt; his denial creates humour. It might have been a serious situation, perhaps, had it been a matter between aunt and nephew alone. But, Lady Bracknell's qurestion elicits a lie from the master of thehouse, and this untruth is humorously supported by the servant, such that the audience wonders whether it has not been rehearsed. There is also the lineage of Jack which is anothe source of humour. Lady Bracknell's interview is, in itself, humorous.  But the purpose and method are even more so.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Among many other things she suggests to Jack in her interview, she asks Jack to \"acquire some relations as soon as possible\". How he is to do this and \"produce at any rate one parent... before the season is quite over\" is ridiculously funny.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The quarrel between Gwendolen and Cecily is funny, especially when we remember Algemon's comment that two women meeting for the first time must quarrel to get on. As we watch Cecily carefully ask what Gwendolen will have, and offer her her dislikes, we find the country girl the city girl boot for boot.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lady Bracknell's surprise when Dr. Chausuble asks Jack and Algemon whether they are ready for the christening is an occasion for humour. Apparently her ladyship is under the impression that the unborn child of her daughter and Jack is the object of the christening.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack's anger with Algemon leads to revelations that are complicated and funny. With Lady Bracknell determined to defend her nephew's honour, Jack is raging that Algemon has \"obtained admission\" to the house by pretending to be his brother. But Algemon is Jack's mother, anyway.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OSCAR WILDE : THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST.    How important is marriage in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Marraige is important theme in the play. All the major characters are deeply concerned with the issue of marriage and at one time or the other express strong views on this issue. It serves as a force which motivates most of the important actions in a play. Further, it forms the subject of many arguments and very lively, if not heated, debates.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The issue of marriage is brought into every conversation, however trivial it may be. Right at the start of the  play Algemon broaches the subject in a conversation with his butler, Lane. He asks the question: \"why is it that at a bachelor's establishment the servats invariably drink the champagne?\" Lane's response hits straight home at the point: \"I attribute it to the superior quality of the wine... I have often observed that in married households the champagne is rarely of a first-rate brand.\" They then launch into a short conversation on the nature of marriage in which Lane remarks that he does not find the subject of marriage an interesting topic for discussion. This leads to Algemon's comments, when \"Lane's views on marriage seems somewhat lax\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The conservation between the friends, Jack and Algemon, inevitably touches on the issues of marriage. Jack's sincere belief in the romanticism of marriage is countered by Algemon's cynical vies. While Jack expresses the wish to always enjoy the company of his wife when he does marry, Algemon insists that the married man should always created an alter ego which will give him an opportunity to run away from his wife from time to time. Algemon's views, of course, change when he falls in love with Cecily.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The question of marriage occupies the top spot in Lady Bracknell's list of priorities. Her perspective on marriage is expressed solely from a materialistic viewpoint. Her \"list of eligible young men\" does not, therefore, include Jack who wants to marry her nieece, Gwendolyn.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lady Bracknell puts status first: \" a man should always have an occupation of some kind\". Her \"list of eliglibe young men\" is based on social status and wealth. Therefore, Jack with his \"nondescript origin\" - having been found abandoned in a handbag at Victoria Station- will never make her list.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lady Bracknell's interview of Jack accentuates the ludicrousness of her criteria for eligibility. For her, \"a man who desires to get married should know either everything or nothing. To Jack's response that he knows nothing she says: \"I am pleased to hear it\". Wilde is certainly poking fun at Victoria ideals of marriage here. The important issues, such as a person's character takes the back seat: \"I am not in favour of long engagements. They give people the opportunity of finding out each other's character before marriage, which I think is not good thing\" (Lady Bracknell). As it turns out, Jack is actually Lady Bracknell's nephew - and Algemon's brother! This accentuates the foolishness of prohibiting marriage on the grounds that the proposed suitor's background is undistinguished. After all, she admits herself that when she married Lord Bracknell she had no fortune of her own but that she \"never dreamed for one moment of allowing that to stand in my way\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the chages in the persona's life in \"Expelled\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Expelled is a poem which addresses problems associated with change in the persona's life. The change is externally induced and it can be inferred from the poem that it is brought about by colonialism. The first two lines are suggestive: \"We had traded in this market place comptitively perfect/Till you came in the boat ...\", What is suggested here is an erstwhile communal life in which everyone understands the rules of the game, but not so any longer. The colonialists (you) virtually destroyed everything, material and spiritual. This fact is expressed in the lines: \"cut our ribs, dried our cows\" etc.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The allusion of Sodom and Gomorrah completes the picture of the perversion and destruction that colonialism brings abut gennerally.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the personal level, it is suggested that the persona never overcomes the suffering colonialism inflicts upon his compatriots. He refers to his personal loss, as living in both poverty and penury, unable to pay his debtors who \"tapped my rusty door\". Now he has become a pariah, as everyone avoid him while he himself plays hide and seek with death. Nature itself offers no consolation, as the \"broken lines run across my face\", indicating his ageing too quickly.   The last two lines with their image of the auctioneer hammering away the goods left behind are pathetic in their confirmation of the total deprivation that has become his lot.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;AFRICAN POETRY    In what ways are the fortunes of the rich and the poor linked in \"Homeless not Hopeless\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poor in the poem do not have homes. They live \"under bridges\". But they come to terms with their situation with equanimity. They see themselves as significant and playing a particularly active and useful role in society. By their situation, the poor rely on the rich for survival. But they work for their upkeep. They rise at daybreak and ply their trade and \"beg for alms\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The curious thing about the occupation of the poor beggars is that it sustains the system. They are clear-eyed and fully aware that they form a \"necessary part of your society\". It is ironical, even paradoxical, that the rich should imagine that they are removed from the world of the poor.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the persona puts it, the poor people are the \"translators of your dreams\". This refers to the rich of the society, who have everything while the poor have nothing. The poor say that they carry the burdens of the rich.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is significant because it hits at the very root of offering alms. Anyone who gives alms wants to be blessed. In requesting and accepting alms, therefore, the poor are \"angels\" who \"open gates of blessing\" for the rich.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The link between poverty and wealth is put succinctly in the paradox of the couplet: \"We are the lack/that take your lack\". The rich lack blessings as much as the poor lack wealth. When the wealthy give the poor a little of their possession, the acceptance of the offer of alms opens the gates of blessings for the givers. In this way, the fortunes of the poor and those of the wealthy are intertwined.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NON - AFRICAN POETRY    What is the poet's attitude towards the sun in \"The Sun Rising\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet's attitudes towards the sun is more complex than it first appears. There are two discemible attitudes which the poet adopts towards the sun.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Initially, the poet is irritated by the sun. He starts the moologue on a querulous note. The questions he asks indicate the irritation which the sun is causing him. The sun is personified as a \"Busy old fool\" who persists in waking him and his lover up even though no one has invited him to do so. The sun is, here, a busybody and might do well to mind his own business. The poet's later diction reinforces his contempt for the sun whom he sees as a \"pedantic wretch\". This suggests the sun's unimaginative and ostentatious following of rules. The poet's  distaste is obvious here. The implication is that the sun, if it wants to follow the rule of waking people up early daily, should look for others who are less earnestly engaged, such as \"late school boys and sour prentices\". These others are engaged in mundanre activities and should therefore be the target of the sun's rays. He and his lover are enjoying a relationship which is on a much higher level than the activities of \"court-huntsmen\" and \"country ants\", so the sun, which really determines time, can have no effect on them.  The poet's irritation is mitigated later. The sun is no longer a busybody. He focuses on the sun's pretentiousness; \"Thy beams so reverend and strong/Why shouldst thou think?  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet's conceit is a pointer to the fact that he believes that in the realm of things, the sun is really like a bleep on a screen. The poet could shut his eyes and the sun will cease to exist. A further shift in the poet's attitude is discernible. He still feels that the sun is insignificant though the focus has now shifted to himself and his mistress - the two are the most important beings in the whole world: \"she is all states, and all princes I/Nothing else is\". At this point he patronizes the sun by referring to its age and suggesting that it needs some rest. By shinning on them the sun will be doing its duty to the world.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NON AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the case against astrologers in \"Upon an Honest Man's Fortune\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The primary purpose of the poet is to debunk the astrologers' wild claim that they can read the positions and movements of the stars and use their observations to tell people's fortunes. The poet reminds the astrologers that it is fate and not the so-called starry influences that unalterably determine events in people's lives. He argues that fate is God-ordained and is therefore above human knowledge. For this reason, nobody including the astrologers, can pretend to know the destiny of any other person. \"Anf no man knows his treasures, no, not you!'\" He thus considers them as imposters for fraudulently using the so-called starry influences to fool and dupe such gullible people as are worried by issues of danger, position, love and the like.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Poet further argues that God, who made the stars which the astrologers daily read and fraudulently exploit to eke a living, does not reveal to anybody, not least the astrologers, His secret purpose of creating them. He reminds them of the helplessness of their Egyptian precedecessors to save Pharoah and his cohorts from the warth of God in theri futile confrontation with Moses. He sees them engaged in dubious calculations and permutations about the sacred purpose of the work of the creator which is beond their limited comprehension. Accordingly, he dismisses them as charlatans who are as \"blind\" as their calculations and as \"druken'\" as their conjectures.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet accuses the astrologers of being presumptuous and holds out that man does not need their service, being favourably equipped by the Divine to achieve his set objectives. Accordingly, he condemns the fortune-tellers with their spurious claims as lairs since it is only man and what he does that makes or mar him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ASARE KONADU    Comment on the suerstitious beliefs and practices in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The novel abounds with religious beliefs and practices. The people of Brenhoma believe in and worship deities, the most popular one being Tano whom they consider a great god. Fofie is the day set aside for the worship of this god. Fofie is a festive Friday which is observed every six weeks. The people go to the shrine, Tanofie, to worship and consult the ancestors for solution to their problems. On Fofie, it is held that the \"gods andd goddesses move among men to feast and grant people's requests\". Consequently, the plot begins when Pokuwaa is prepared frantically to go to Tanofie to present the items that she has been asked to bring as a sacrifice to the gods so that her ancestors and the gods would bless her efforts to get a child. Koramoa, Pokuwaa's playmate and childhood friend, is also there to thank the gods for blessing her with a child.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The people of Brenhoma also consult the deities and ask them to intervene on behalf of anyone who may have wronged others or, where the sins of the parents or ancestors are being avenged on an individual. Pokuwaa has been told by the priest at Tanofie to get a black hen so that the deities could be sought to spare her the pain of not having a child of her own in case \"she herself had wronged anyone or if the sins of her parents or ancestors were being avenged on her\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The people also believe in the power of evil spirits who inhabit tree tops and wreak all sorts of havoc on them. There are stories, first, of an evil spirit turning a child into a chicken and slaughtering her, and another of a man turning himself into a crocodile and devouring a girl who jilted him. Pokuwaa holds on to these superstitions. When Pokuwaa's jet black hen meant for sacrifice gets missing, she concludes that this is peharps the work of evil spirits \"who, knowing Tano's greatness, had spirited the hen away, to stop her from making her sacrifice\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The lighting that strikes the wawa tree is considered a bad omen. It is a sign that the gods are angry. To pacify them, the women are expected to cook, and prayers offered to appease the seventy-seven (77) gods. Brenhoma women are also prayed for to bear children, so that when the gods pay a visit, \"you will always find someone here to give you something to eat\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The people also believe that another world called asamando exists where their ancestors reside, a place where there is no pain or suffering. All manner of food is prepared for them. This is demonstrated during the burial of Yaw Boakye when different kinds of food are prepared and placed on his bed. His widows also give him cowries to pay for his passage on his way to the world beyond.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another practice of the Brenhoma community also manifests during the burial when on his way to the cemetery his corpse seems to have been held by unseen forces. Libation has to be poured in order to facilitate easy passage and the bearers resume their movement.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Again at the cemetry, each of the three widows runs ahead and throws a pot. This is to severe their martial relationship with the dead.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The hornbil episode is another incidence of the superstitious belief of the people. While Pokuwaa was at the river to fetch water, an eagle nearly slaps her. She kills the hornbill, wraps it with leaves and takes it home, as the women of the community stare at her. On showing the mother the dead hornbill she becomes troubled because, in the first instance, nobody has the right to go the Ananse stream on Akwasidde to fetch water. Secondly, a hornbill is said to be the food of the gods and as a result it must be returned if the family does not want to incur the wrath of the gods. A purification rite has to be carried out.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The observance of the Odwira festival meant to mourn the dead is central to the peoples' belief in the continuity of their existence. It is done with loud heating of drums, and vigils are kept for the celebration. It also serves as an occasion for lovers to meet as well as settle family disputes.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    What aspect of Kambili's character are revealed during the children's visits of Aunty Ifeoma?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Kambili and her brother, Jaja pay occasional visits to the home of Aunty Ifeoma at Nsukka. The contrast between Eugene's household and Aunty Ifeoma's home is striken and this reveals aspects of Kambili's character which have never before been seen.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene's regimental behaviour has left Kambili a withdrawn, tacviturn, it not forlorn child. The emotional aridity of Eugene's home contrasts sharphly with the warn vivacious and liberal atmosphere of Aunty Ifeoma's home. The children's visit to Aunty Ifeoma to spend time with her and her chidren after Eugene hhas beaten kambi unconscious marks a watershed in the action of the novel. The short time they spend with Aunty Ifeoma exposes Kambili and Jaja to freedom and cordiality they have never been exposed to before. Kambili, the quiet, withdrawn girl now starts to ask questions to probe her surroundings. An instance could be seen when Kambili overhears a discussion between Aunty Ifeoma and a colleague of hers about turmoil in the university. Kambili asks Amaka to explain what is happening in the university. In the past, this would have been unthinkable. Now, she is bold enough to question what is happening around her. While Eugene had conditioned her to an unquestionable acceptance to whatever he to her, Aunty Ifeoma's home has opened up a whole new vista of experience in which the child could demand to have to have to say in her own future. The chains of enslavement, as were, are now falling off.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the domestic scene we notice a transformation and seelf discovery of Kambili which hitherto has found it difficult to handle household chores, now becoming a good cook and a warm converstionalist.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another aspect of Kambili's character revealed in Aunty Ifeoma's house is her opinion of relationship to members of the opposite sex. Up to now, the dominant man in her life his been her father towering over her like a colossus, willing her to do his bidding and not ask questions. Now, in Aunty Ifeoma's house, she meets another man, a different kind of man altogether, Father Amadi. Whereas in the past, the clergy have been synonymous with oppressive long church services made worse by her being compelled to fast for the first time, she meets a clergyman who has a human face. She therefore finds herself falling in love. The shy girl who in the past will not even consider having a relationship with the opposite sex now opens up to a man and starts looking forward to spending time with him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    Examine the relationship between Kambili and father Amadi.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The relationship between Kambili and Rev. Father Amadi shows that real love does not only engender happiness and peace of mind, but it can also be a durable bridge between social and spiritual values.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Father Amadi is a Roman Catholic priest at Nsukka and a friend of the Ifedioras while Kambili is the daughter of Eugene Achike in Enugu. The relationship between the two begins whhen Kambili is on a holiday with the Ifedioras in Nsukka. When she sees the priest during a visit to the Ifedioras, she quickly recognises him as the one that conducts an Igbo worship on Palm Sunday in Enugu - a thing described by her father as a sin. From that moment, she begins to develop a secret love for him for one major reason; he unlike her father, is not a reliious bigot.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kambili's love for Father Amadi rapidly develops. She wears Amaka's shorts and tries to use the lipstick to please him while he also eagerly takes her to the stadium and accompanies her to her hairdresser's place. Kambili sees Father Amadi as someone rightly filling the vacuum created by her high-handed father, whose love for her only leads to fear and submission. On the contrary, she sees Father Amadi's love for her giving her hope and happiness and an opportunity to break from her father's rigid moral code.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kambili sees in Father Amadi a friend and an equal in whom she can confide. She does not hide her admiration of his handsomeness and wonders why he should remain a priest. She is alos unhappy that Father Amadi may leave her behind on his mission to Germany.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Father Amadi's love for Kambili is in a manner ambivalent. He grows fond of her. But, Father Amadi has enough self-control to hold back his passion and lift is relationship up onto a finer plane befitting his status as a priest. He leaving for Germany serves as a relief to him, which leaves Kambili distressed.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    Comment on the significance of Simon's death.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Simon is an important character in the novel. He appears to be a little retarded, while others think hom \"batty\". But his fits do not prevent him from being keenly insightful.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The circumstances of Simon's death are tragic and regrettable. He dies because of the timing of his re-emergence from the forest. Savagery has engulfed the boys and they are absolutely unable to discern the beast; they do not care about their fellow man.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is significant that by this death, the confirmation of Simon's earlier observation that the beast may be in the boys themselves will never be known. This death obliterates the light of civilization and insightful analysis. It can be seen that when Simon dies, hurting another severely no longer means anything to the tribe, if it had done so at all earlier.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the argument at the assembly becomes a discussion of ghosts, Simon says that the beast may as well be the human being. This does not go  down well with the rest. This is a point that might have been cleared had Simon not died.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Simon does see what the others have seen earlier. He does not run. He sees the strange sight for what it is and even without fear, reasons about dignity that the wind deprives the dead man of.So he relates the parachutist from his indignity in death. What is left is the revelation of what Simon has come to know. This knowledge would or might have restored sanity or prompted the savagery unleashed after Simon's murder. It appears as if his death opens the floodgates for further savagery and attack on decency. The boyss have no qualms about further killing. The crushing of Piggy and the conch is closely linked with Simon's death in the sense that the questioning that Simon does is taken to a higher level of Piggy. At any rate the bespectacled \"fatty\" is the source of light and insight. Naturally, after the brave investigator of mysteries has been done in, the bringer of light follows as a matter of course.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With the death of Simon and Piggy, the silent antagonism between Jack and Ralph breaks into open confrontation and war as Jack and his tribe hunt Ralph.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It can be seen that the death of Simon is significant in several ways. By his death, the avenue to obtaining the key to the mystery of the beast is closed. In its place, the sluice gates for the unleashing of brutal attacks on civility are opened.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING : LORD OF THE FLIES    Consider the view that the struggle for power is a major issue in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From the moment Jack Merridew appears on the stage with an air of \"superiority and off-hand authority\" with his chorus boys, even as Ralph is already presiding over a meeting of a group of others rescued on the island, it is obvious that power is going to be a major issue in the novel.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Power is sweet and Jack and Ralph love it. Like all those who love it, they both equally lay claim to it but by different means and for different reasons. While Ralph relies on the priviledge of holding the conch, jack in turn exploits self-assertion as he says with brazen arrogance: \"I ought to be chief ... because I'm chapter chorister and head boy\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through a popular vote the other boys elect Ralph their leader simply because of his size, his attractive appearance and, most importantly, because he has the conch although Jack seems to be the most obvious leader. This democratic process shows that power belongs to the people who take it away from or choose to give it to whoever they want. This is also demonstrated when Ralph again overwhemingly defeats Jack in the second leadership contest unnecessarily forced on the boys by the rebellious Jack.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Power in the novel manifests itself in two distinct forms - inclusive and integrative. The inclusive form allows for power sharing arrangement. This is why Ralph insists on the use of meetings and dialogues to get issues resolved. It also explains why he wants to bring Jack on board by conceding to him the leadership of the choir boys after defending him in the struggle for power but power is also used to foster social cohesion and advance the cause of the people. For this reason, Ralph is earnestly concerned with the welfare of the boys and their immediate rescue.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the other hand, power can be used autocratically as an end in itself. In this case it is primarily wielded to advance the myopic interest of the ruler. Jack after seizing power builds a cut of personality around himself and unleashes a reign of terror on the Island. The development is regretted and bemoaned even by Roger, his second-in-command. In the process, Jack leads his hunter boys from Rock Castle to the Beach Platform to destroy the shelter under construction, molest Piggy the voice of reason, and steal his glasses. It is also the same reign of terror that prematurely terminates Piggy's life in their wild and maddening chase to kill Ralph. Power corrupts as shown by Jack but when it is seen as an effective means to a useful end as demonstrated by Ralph, it is desirable.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;EARNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    Examine Santiago's attitude to nature.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Santiago, an old and experienced fisherman, spends the most part of his days at sea. His fishing expeditions which often take him far away from the shore enable him to know and understand the ways of the sea and its creatures. They also give him a vantage ground from which he can have a clear view of birds and such other phenomena as the stars, the moon and the sun. As a result of his experiences at sea and his intimate observation of birds, Santiago develops perculiar views about them.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For instance, the old man recognizes, respects and empathizes as well as talks to them as if they can hear him and respond like human beings. He does this at great length through his monologues. For example, he says \"If the others hear me talking out loud they would think I am not crazy, I do not care\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As opposed to the views of others, Santiago always thinks of the sea as a woman who gives or withholds great favours. This may explain why he bemoans his bad luck rather than bear the sea any grudge for losing the marlin he catches.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The old man recognizes the ability of birds to give a fisherman an insight into where he can find fish to catch. Such is the warbler that circles over him and leads him to locate the marlin he kills. During his ordeal with the big fish, he feels sorry for turtles but is also inspired by them as he compares his heart to theirs which live long after they have been killed. Hence, he eats their white eggs all through May to be strong in September and October.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In his fantasies, Santiago regards fish including the sharks which he knows species by species and which also deprive him of his big catch not only as friends but also as nobler, more beautiful and more able although less intelligent brothers. He sees the sinister sharks not as mere scavengers but as creatures with friends, mothers and relatives in their own right. He kills them in self-defence and to protect his catch.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His unusual view about other creatures is most noticeable in his encounter with the marlin. He pities the fish in its moment of anger and anguish even as his own life is on the line.  He catches and kills the fish since no one is worthy of eating it from its behaviour and great dignify. He acknowledges its equal right to live and kill him if in self-defence. He argues that he kills the marlin neither for money nor for food but simply for pride. He wishes that the big fish were like the moon, the stars and the sun that no man can kill.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;EARNEST HEMINGWAY : THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    What role does Manolin play in Santiago's domestic life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Santiago lives in a shack by himself. He has lost his wife, whom he occaionally remembers by the few relics of her past existence. Though Santiago does have a home to return to at the close of a fishing day, that home is truly empty- no wife, no child and little property.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At home, Santiago is to be found with his friend, Manolin discussing football, or meals, or Africa and lions. Without Manolin, Santiago seems to have no reinforcement in life. His life is kept alive, hopeful and humane by his firm friendship with Manolin. He maintains Santiago.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Santiago's home life is reflected in his friend, Manolin. He is always concerned about the old man's diet. The two play the 'rice game' when they both know that the old man is going to have no supper. The least the boy can do is to humour the old man. The old man's daily baits are provided by Manolin, apparently from his own resources. The boy packs the old man's things for him and sees him off to sea. He also welcomes the old man when he returns from seea. he leads him home and tells him the latest gossip.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the day of the big catch, on his return, only Manolin visits him. None of the other fisherman comes by. This seems to be the normal way things go, as Santiago appears never to visit anyone.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Manolin not only mitigates Santiago's circumstances by easing the old man's plight but also enters the pains of the old man's condition at home. Having resolved to buy Santiago the winter things he has neglected to provide him with, Manolin does not spare himself the trouble to secure rest and recovery for the old man. He is significantly overwhelmed by emotion as he goes about doing his duty. Manolin asks that no one disturbs the old man's sleep. Then he breaks down weeping because of the state he finds the old man and blames himself for having neglected to take better care of him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The old man's home life is tangled in the boy's who as young he is, discerns Santiago's needs. He goes at these ardently like a mother as well as a wife to Santiago.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Manolin watches over Santiago as a mother does her ailing child. He never permits him to worry and always gives the old man reason to live on", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2013>PAPER 3>I", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "I", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    Compare Pokuwaa's and Koramoa's Marital experiences.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pokuwaa and Koramoa are very close friends. As girls, they spend a lot of time in each other's company and share a lot of things and play Ampe and Asogoro. Fortunately, the girls meet and fall in love with two friends, Kofi Daafo and Kofi Dede respectively. The two couples get married at about the same time.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfortunately, the two women are not blessed with children early in their marriages. Their attitudes to their predicament are however different. Despite the stigma surrounding a woman who is presumed barren, Korama sticks to her guns andd endures her deprivation with her husband. She does not leave him and search for a solution elsewhere, even though the temptation to do so is very strong. Pokuwaa, on the other hand is very impatient. She soon starts to fret and eventually succumbs to her mother's pressure for her to move on, against the advice of Koramoa, marrying two other husbands after her first marriage.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pokuwaa's change of husbands does not lead to immediate results. She still remains childless. In the meantime, Koramoa's persistence pays off. She conceives aand gives birth to a child. This upsets Pokuwaa all the more as at that time she is with her second husband, Kwaku Fosu and still childless. In her frustration, Pokuwaa confdes in Koramoa her intention to discontinue her sacirfies in a bid to get the gods to bless her with a child. Koramoa is rational in her approach and reveals this in her pleas with Pokuwaa not to give up hope.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Koramoa has had a child, but she catches her husband with another woman. This almost leads to a break-up in their marriage. However, it must be noted that Kwadwo Fordwuo,in spite of his first wife, is more committed to their relationship. He continually encourages Pokuwaa, raising her hopes when in a state of despair. He admonishes her: \"to give up sacrifices is to give uo life itself\".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In time, Pokuwaa conceives with her third husband though she still irks at having to share him with his other wife.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KOBINA SEKYI : THE BLINKARDS    Compare the characters of Mr. Onyimdze and Mr. Borofosem.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are so may similarities and differences between Mr. Onyimdze and Mr. Borofesem. Both characters once lived in England and belonged to the educated class.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Onyimdze is a young barister who dispenses his judgement with truth and fair play while Mrs. Borofesem is a merchant who lacks the sense of decision and right judgement, which is reflected on his unstable attitude as he is being tossed about by his wife's outrageous behaviour.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Onyimdze is presented in the play as a custodian of African culture, who, not minding his british education, still has value for the traditional code of conduct. Mr. Borofesem is a henpecked husband who allows his wife to direct what he does in their matrimonial home.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. Onyimdze later wins a case of bigamy in favour of Miss Tsiba who is bewitched by foreign system of marriage. He not only protects traditional values against western encroachment, he also brings back all the anglicised characters including Mr. Borofesem to appreciate their culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYE: THE BLINKARDS    Assess the negative impact of colonialism in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Blinkards is a comic satire which is based on a kind of social epidemic which occurs in Africa with the introduction of Colonialism. Colonialism imposes a foreign culture, tradition and way of life on Africans and as portrayed in the play, some citizens of Gold Coast blindly abandon their lifestyle and follow foreign culture.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the play, one of the effects of colonialism is the blind invitation of western culture by some characters in the play, such as Mrs. Borofusem, Miss Tsiba, Mr. Okadu among others. They all disregard African culture so much that they portray different kinds of characters which is against traditional culture.  Mrs . Borofusem employs the wrong use of English language and regards African food, drinks and games as archaic and irrelevant. Mr Okadu and Miss Tsiba also disregard African marital engagement and this leads to series of unfortunate events. All these are the negative impact of colonialism in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISA : THE WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss the significance of the meeting between Lawunmi and Anlugbua.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lawunmi and Anlugbua are ancestral dieties. Lawunmi is Anlugbua's grandmother while the latter is the son of Oba Asunkungbade, the ancestral founder of Owu. The two dieties meet to discuss the tragedy that has befallen Owu.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From the meeting, the cause of the destruction of Owu is revealed. Lawunmi reveals how she makes the Owus suffer for their greed and wickedness in the attack of Ife and Ijebu traders. This shows the role of the gods in the lives of men and the human nature of the gods. They are vindictive, unreliable and susceptible to human frailties. They react with their might when they are wrong or feel humans have done something wrong.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The meeting also signifies the helplessness and vulnerability of men in the hands of the gods. The gods feel the Owus are not good people and should be punished and this makes the whole town to be wiped off. The Allied Forces of the Ife, Ijebu and Oyo Empire are also destroyed by the gods after their victory.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FEMI OSOFISAN : WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss the role of chorus in advancing the plot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The chorus in traditional Greek theatre is a group of actors on stage who comments on the actions of the play. In the play, Women of Owu, the chorus comprises a group of Owu women who survive the destruction of the city and are partakers of the suffering. They provide information on current and past events in the play, warn people about the consequences of certain actions, encourage other women to accept their challenge and serve as custodians of the people's culture and tradition.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This women plead with Anlugbua to intervene on behalf of Owu, plead for those who are dead and ask for forgiveness for those who live. They sympathize with Erelu on calamities that have befallen her and remind her of her duties to perform the rites of passage. They warn her not to speak evil of the gods, but rather encourage the people to have hope and curse the Allied Forces.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BERNARD SHAW : ARMS AND THE MAN    Discuss the theme of heroism in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Heroism is portrayed through Bluntschli who is forthright, practrical minded, pragmatic and possesses military skill. These qualities earn him the love of Raina who later breaks her previous engagement to get married to him. Sergius on the other hand, represents an unprofessional style of military campaign as a soldier. He is tactless, unprofessional and inexperienced as displayed at Slivinta on the battlefield. This denies him his promotion and it results in him quiting the army in frustration.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another act of heroism is illustrated by Louka as she changes her lower class status through courage and determination when she marries Sergius who has an aristocratic background.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    Comment on the significance of the battle at Silvnitza", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The battle of Slivinta is between the Bugarian and the Serbian forces in the ongoing war. The battle takes place in a ''little town near the Dragoman pass'' on the border between Bulgaria and Serbia. The Bulgarian side wins as a result of the '' able'' leadership of Major Sergius Saranoff. The victory makes Catherine proud of Sergius. The war dominates the action of the play and most characters are introduced as the war is being discussed.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bluntschili's attempt to escape capture by the enemy soldiers drives him to taking cover in Raina's bedroom. The encounter results in romance and later ends in marriage. Also, Sergius's character as a foolhardy general who cares little about the safety of the soldiers under his command is brought to light.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This exposes the myth of heroism relating to war exploits. A good commander saves lives whenever possible, as in the case of Bluntschili but a ruthless one only cares about winning the battle.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OSCAR WILDE : THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Discuss the significance of the revelation of Jack's true identity.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cecily and Gwendolen, who stay at the drawing room of the manor house, confront Algernon and Jack as they enter from the garden. This marks the begining of the revelation and the revelation process continues until it climaxes.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The revelation emphasizes the theme of appearance and reality. This is closely allied to the double identity or double life which is what many people's life portray. Cecily and Gwendolen are fooled by their emotional attachment to the name Ernest.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The farcial moment when Jack calls Miss Prism ''mother'' leads way to the exposition that he (Jack) is really Algernon's brother and that he is the son of lady Bracknell's sister. Jack knows his father's name is Ernest, and that he is named Ernest after his father.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    What impressions of the upper class life do you form from your study of the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The upper-class, as portrayed in the play, holds itself out  as superior to the lower class. The upper class is pretentious in nature as they appear glamorous outside but on a close examination is not that special but morality and ordinary expectation.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The upper-class is high-handed in their treatment of the lower class and they are hypocritical as regards their frivolous and materialistic view of marriage. The upper-class is also obsessed with name and family.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the use of imagery in \"Ambassadors of Poverty\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet was predominating visual images to express his disgust with the corruption which is prevalent in African societies. The negative activities of the so-called ''Ambassadors'' expose the depth of the corruption in the societies. They are all ''Ambassadors of Poverty'' giving the word ''ambassador'' an ironical twist.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The visual image involving ''the head abroad and the anus at home'' (line 3-4) emphasizes the stench of the endemic corruption in the society. There is also the image of government workers who are described as ''office loafers'' (line 11) and ''barons on incompetence\" (line 12).  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are other images involving ''the landlords'' who charge exhorbitant rents, thus contributing to the theme of corruption. The political elite, and the elusive importers who pursue their own comfort and personal wealth at the expense of the poor.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN POETRY    Consider the presentations of the theme of poverty in \"Myopia\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem consists of three uneven stanzas with each developing the theme of poverty. The poet's opening statement borders on the plight of the peasants; how miserable, vunerable and rain-battered they are. The last and longest stanza presents the poet's attitude towards whom the society has inpoverished and his determination to punish the culprits .  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem also shows contrast between the rich and the poor as well as the neglected rice pads of the country which deepen the misery of peasants. In the last stanza, the poet is determined to get rid of the corrupt politicians and eventually sanitize the society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Examine the poet's attitude to man in \"Upon an Honest Man's Fortune\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the poem, the poet blames man for his misplaced belief in astrologers and his failure to appreciate God's love for him. He also castigates man for putting his trust on worthless astrologers, instead of in God.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The poet is surprised at man's forgetfulness that he can walk himself to glory through hardwork and chides him for his short-sightedness and lack of belief in the power of God over his life. In the end, the poet worries about man fear of the facts of life like affliction, sickness and death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NON-AFRICAN POETRY    Discuss the major regrets of the slain soldier in \"Strange Meeting\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the poem '' Strange Meeting'' , the soldier regrets his undone years i.e his lost years. ''Save the ondone years/ was my life also'' (lines 16-17) He also regrets the lost oppurtunity of experiencing love and making people laugh.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He laments his failure to fulfil his life's aspirations of changing the world through honest labour and humane deeds. He also regrets that men will continue to agonize and fight one other continually and that he has no option now, but to rest. In all, the poem presents war as futile, and admonishes people to make the most of life.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AFRICAN PROSE  ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME      Comment on the fate of childless women in Brenhoma society", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Brenhoma, childlessness or barrenness is considered a grave misfortune bacause a barren woman will be doomed to loneliness in her old age. She will have no child to care for her; no grandchild to enliven the compound, as well as no issue of her blood to mourn at her death. Although she will definitely be buried by her relatives, nothing is better than a woman having her own children at her funeral. This is the fate Pokuwaa is desperate not to suffer as being barren in Brenhoma is \"the worst thing that would happen to a woman\".   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Again, in Brenhoma the people treat barren women with lots of scor. Pokuwaa is barren in her prime so the people treat her with contempt. Even though she is fond of children and welcomes them heartily to her house, some mothers are not happy with this. For example, when Afua Fofie's daughter visits Pokuwaa, Afua storms into the house and without greeting Pokuwaa, takes her little girl away. When Pokuwaa questions her, Afua Fofie cheekily responds by saying she is the mother and so has every right to take her daughter away without greeting Pokuwaa. Pokuwaa is deeply hurt and so resolves to stick to Kwadwo, her lover, and religiously performs her sacrifice as prescribed by the priest of Tano so that the gods and her ancestors will take pity on her and grant her request to have her own children.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  When Kwadwo, Pokuwaa's lover, tells his wife that he will be spending seven days with his mistress, Pokuwaa, she protests vehemently against it arguing that she will \"not sell her rights to any barren woman\".     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  In Brenhoma, it is held that \"there is no difference between a barren woman and a man\" because women are supposed to give birth to children who will pertuate the existence of the state of Brenhoma, as well as defend the land. Thus, Pokuwaa's mother is not happy with her decisions to discontinue the sacrifice she is making to the gods to grant her request to have children. She believes strongly that in Brenhoma, \"a woman gets well past fifty before her blood stops flowing\". To this end, she goes to see the head of the Asoma clan, Opanin Kofi Owusu and declares \"a woman who says, \" I will not give birth is useless, useless!'     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Besides, in Brenhoma, moters also suffer the ripple effects of their daughtee's fate when they are barren because Brenhoma is a matrilineal society. Pokuwaa's mother will bear the burnt of Pokuwaa's fate because Pokuwaa is her only daughter; Pokuwaa's mother tells her consistently that the children of five brothers are not her grandchildren. They belong to their mothers' families. She adds that Pokuwaa should bear her own grandchildren. Therefore, unless Pokuwaa has a child, \"their lives will end miserably\". This is the reason Pokuwaa's mother is angry and frustrated when Pokuwaa discontinues the sacrifices seeking Tano's favour for a child. Cosequently, she gets very excited when Pokuwaa becomes pregnant.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;AFRICAN PROSE  ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME      What does the death of Yaw Boakye reveal about the Brenhoma society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yaw Boakye appears to be a gallant member of the Brenhoma society. One day, he goes to the bush but fails to return. His decomposing body is first seen by Pokuwaa but she is prevented by her mother from reporting to the chiefs for fear of being implicated. Later, when the search party of youths and warriors finds the body and brings it home for burial, the whole town is astir.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Yaw Boakye's death causes so much excitement. It triggers various activities that reveal the essential make-up of the Brenhoma community: their beliefs; unity as a people; historical experiences, traditional way of handling cases of murder; and their decorum.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Yaw's death galvanizes the youth into action that shows the spirit of unity not only of the young people but also of the entire community. The chief sends out a command to all young people in the town to join in the search on pain of punishment by the greatt oath.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The bravery of the town appears to be legendary. It is not uncommon to have two individuals settling issues between them through combat in the bush. Such a fight could \"be carried out brutally until death\". It could also be an attack by enemy groups, and the victim left to die in the bush. Soon enough the final lap of search ends in the discovery of the body of Yaw Boakye.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The very discovery of the dead body reveals the attitude of the people towards the dead reverence. The group that finds the . body observes the decorum that the moment demands. It announces the find with the cry of \"Wasps! Wasps! Take care!!\". The message of the result of the search is relayed by the drummer and messengers are sent (into town) for the town to prepare to receive the outcome of the search that  has been ordered.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  That the people of Brenhoma are superstitious and highly spiritual is not in doubt. During the funeral of Yaw Boakye, the priests take centre stage. They conduct peaceful separation between the dead man and his wives. If this is not done, the dead man's ghost may hover about, pestering his living wives.         &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The priest's role again is seen when the coffin refuses to move. The procession come to a halt and it takes the priest's intervention, the pouring of drinks of libation - for the procession to continue to the burial ground. Here the closing ceremony is performed in utter silence - no weeping is heard.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Yaw Boakye's death, then, is a mirror in which the nature of the people of Brenhoma and their way of life is reflected.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI : PURPLE HIBISCUS    Discuss the relationship between Aunty Ifeoma and her father.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One can hardly talk about Aunty Ifeoma and Papa-Nnukwu without mentioning Eugene. Despite being brother and sister, the two have very different outlooks on life. Eugene, because of his nature, has given up on is father, whom he considers to be hell-bound. Because of this conviction, Eugene will have as little as possible to do with his father.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aunty Ifeoma, on the other hand, is fanatically devoted to their father, never once missing an opportunity to come to his defence. Several times she has told Eugene that labeling the old man as heathen is erroneous: if Papa-Nnukwu is not Catholic, he is a traditionalist not a heathen.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aunty Ifeoma adores her father, whom she is careful to include in their Christmas sightseeing. She listens to his stories no matter how many times he has told them. There is a special intimac between the old man and his daughter. Papa-Nnukwu on his part loves his daughter deeply. He respects her tenacity as a single mother in their kind of society. She is premanently in prayers. Papa-Nnukwu prays for his daughter that her circumstances may turn around.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Petrol is in short supply when Papa-Nnukwu's health fails. Thanks to Father Amadi, Aunty Ifeoma brings her father to Nsukka where he dies. But while he lives with her, Papa-Nnukwu's burden is borne by Aunty Ifeoma gallantly.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Determined to break Eugene's indoctrination of Kambili about Papa-Nnukwu, Aunty Ifeoma directs her to watch her grandfather at worship. Having heard and seen Papa-Nnukwu pray for everyone including Eugene, Kambili is left wondering whether there is not a mistake somewhere. He has prayed and wished everyone well. He even smiles after praying, which rarely happens in their Catholic home.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  When Papa-Nnukwu dies, Aunty Ifeoma needs help to bury him. Eugene offers her conditional assistance for which she flares at him. There is no way Aunty Ifeoma is going to approve a Catholic funeral for her father.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  It is quite clear that Aunty Ifeoma holds her father in the highest esteem. Papa-Nnukwu returns this sentiment unconditionally.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI : PURPLE HIBISCUS    Consider Amaka's view of Eugene.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene's character is baffling. Some of the people who have come into contact wih him are hard put to affirm whether he is a good person or \"a bad man\". Amaka, Eugene's niece, from what she has come to know about her uncle, is unwilling to say he is a bad man, but must justify to herself that he truly is not a bad person, in the face of evidence of her uncle's cruetly to his immediate family, such as Jaja's finger. Aunty Ifeoma makes only a passing reference to it, but it is not discussed. Yet its effect on Amaka andd the other children is strong and exposes Eugene to his niece and nephew as neither loving nor caring.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Amaka is scandalized by Eugene's hold over her cousins. She expresses her anger through a brutal game of teasing Kambili about her deficiencies in domestic chores in which her mother intervenes, urging Amaka to accomodate Kambili's very little exposure to the very ordinary things that she (Amaka) has grown used to and taken for granted: wearing shorts or lipstick, romance, music etc.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Amaka can stretch her imagination to envision not only the boredom imposed on her cousins but also the true nature of the harsh punishments they bear, They have no choice in anything they do and Amaka is very angry for her cousins.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aware of Eugene's attitude towards his own father, whom she adores, Amaka cannot regard her uncle in a positive light. She simply cannot approve Eugene's relationship with Papa-Nnukwu.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet Eugene, in his own way,, expresses love to all, On his visits home, he gives many people gifts, not to mention his endowment to the church. In a sense, too, he is protective of his family and provides for his home. He cannot be a bad man, really? Amaka wonders how such a generous and loving person can at the same time be cruel.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Papa-Nnukwu dies, there arises a grave moment for the family at Nsukka. Taking the situation of the shortage of almost everything and Aunt Ifeoma's financial state together, times are hard. Then comes Eugene, who says he has sent the necessary things for his father's funeral to his sister, even though he himself will not attend nor have anything further to do with the burial of the old man.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For Amaka, the question of how to label her uncle in these circumstances becomes important and urgently needs an answer. She is impressed by the man's latest generosity. Despite her inclination to condemn the man who treats his family harshly,, she relents in her condemnation. She sees Eugene's recent behaviour as positively mitigating, and so Eugene, she confesses, is not a bad man, really.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; WILLIAM GOLDING: LORD OF THE FLIES    To what extent is Jack a better leader than Ralph?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the leader of the whole group, Ralph has been elected democractically. He assigns roles as best as he can. Civic responsibility is shared among the boys. Not knowing what to do with Jack, he assigns him the leadership of his choir.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Things go bad when the litte ones and even older boys set hygiene aside and attend to the call of nature anywhere and anyhow. The rescue fire is neglected. All of Ralph's arrangements for a decent orderly living go haywire pretty fast. Ralph is unable to see the shelther building project through. This is because he is unable to make anyone work. Practically, only he and Piggy shoulder the building of the shelters. This is poor leadership. When the fire is neglected and he notices a passing ship, Ralphh is pesonally agonized. However, he is unable to articulate what it is that has gone wrong and cannot proffer any remedy.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Several times, at meetings, Ralph goes blank and it takes Piggy to fill him in and keep his thoughts on thoughts on track. His reliance on the couch for authority is legitimate. But the conch does not speak for Ralph at the critical moments; Ralph has to. Thus Ralph fails to take the bull by the horns.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack on the other hand, continues in his role as leader of the choir boys who are now hunters. He takes his job seriously, probably to absurd limits. But he certainly gets results: leadding others and having them do his bidding.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This may sound authoritarian. However, in a sense, keeping the boys in check is that missing adult presence that Piggy bemoans. Jack's leadership is adult-like and focused.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the hunt, the feasting and the game, everyone is a participant. In this way; there is a sense of commitment and belonging to the tribe among Jack's boys.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The assignment of roles by Jack is methodical and specific and one dare not leave one's post; one carries out instructions to the letter.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack's leadership is unifying and attractive. Even Ralph and Piggy are gleeful participants in the fun hunt in which Simon perishes. They have been under no overt complusion to join the hunt.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ralph's insistence on having been active in a pig-hunt is ridiculous. As Jack is in charge of the hunters, if Ralph hunts he does so under Jack. The overall leader may instruct or direct or superintend the hunting, but need he participate? Doing so detracts from Ralph's leadership, wobbly as it is. All in all, it can be said that Ralph's leadership is a weak one compared to Jack's firm manner of controlling others and managing affairs.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING: THE LORD OF THE FLIES    Discuss the conflict of order and chaos in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The central is the conflict between two strong drives in human society: order and chaos. These translate as the quest to live by law and order, to value the good of others versus the drive to satisfy one's personal interest and use of  force to establish ones supremacy over others, on the other hand.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Throughout the novel, Golding associates the drive for order with civilization or good, and the drive for chaos with savegery. The conflict between the two is explored in the narrative about the degeneration of English boys from civilized, moral, and disciplined behaviour to a wild, brutal, excessively harsh, and murderous existence in the jungle.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The novelist conveys most of his central ideas through symbols which transcend characters and objects. The conflict between order and chaos is represented in the conflict between two major characters: Ralph the protagonist who represents order, and Jack, his antagonist, who represents savagery with his morbid thirst for power.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the novel progresses, Golding shows how the drive for order and chaos impacts on people differently. Piggy, for example, is not influenced negatively. He stands for the intellectuals and scientific principle of arguing to arrive at the truth or order.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jack on the other hand, seems bereft of the principle of order. He represents brutality, savagery and blood-lust at its most deplorable state.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; William Golding tends to pass on a message: the human psyche is more prone to chaos than to order. He portrays moral conduct many times in a lot of instances as superimposed by civilization rather than natural human mind which evinces evil, cruelty ans savagery. The idea of innate human evil is notably evident through recurring symbols like the head of the sow on a stake and \"the beast\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The influence of order and chaos reigns throughout the novel. Indeed, there are places where chaos seems to overpower order, where Ralph's boys are brutally murdered. In the end however, order dominates all the action as the boys are rescued.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ERNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    What do you learn from the life of Santiago as a fisherman?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Much is learnt from Santiago's life as a fisherman. In the first place, his humble background  and simple needs are informative. Although he has gone out to sea for 84 days without a catch and neighbours in the community consider him luckless, 'salao', in spite of earlier successes, he is not one to give up. This demonstrates his great tenacity that never-say-die spirit which lets him go out to sea again.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We learn that perserverance and tenacity help a lot, and that one must not give up easily when the odds go against us.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The boy, Manolin's relationship with Santiago is also a useful lesson to learn. He is an old man and he needs the boy just as much as the boy loves him. Manolin's is able to read the old man's mind and determine his needs. He provides him food, keeps him company ad helps him carry his fishing gear to and from the skiff. Thus, the boy is sorely missed on that ill-fated expedition to catch the big fish. The old man cannot have felt lonelier and keeps on regretting the boy's absence. Here he provides another lesson which is the fisherman needs from others. This is clearly a cooperative enterprise and the old man learns this lesson at great cost.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is clear that no man is an island. We must help one another. The old can be friends with the young and the young friends with the old. This relationship is mutually beneficial. good lessons for young people. He is tolerant, resilient, dedicated and persevering. He always goes back to the sea despite his travails on it. His good human relation makes him able to be friends with Manolin despite the age difference.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Apart from the cooperation required, there are also the uncertainties at sea. The old man is unable to predict how long it'll take him to catch a fish, nor where exactly to find it, in spite of some telltale signs. He does not also know how big his catch will be and therefore cannot adequately prepare for all eventualities. This lack of adequate preparation and equipment is badly exposed when he is unable, finally, to ward off the attacking sharks which eats up his big catch.   We also learn from the old man's respect for the marlin, that we should show respect to our rivals.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally, the old man's attitude to the sea, which he calls 'la mar' when others call it 'el mar', indicates a certain love relationship. Thus, no matter how badly he has been treated by the sea, he is prepared to go back again and again.  In conclusion, so much is learnt about Santiago's life as a fisherman.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2014>PAPER 2>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ERNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    Comment on the narrative techniques used in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The story of Santiago who goes out to sea and returns with the skeleton of the largest fish he has ever caught is captivating because of Hemingway's choice of narrative technique.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The story begins to be told from the third person or authorial point of view. \"He was an old man who fished alone in a skiff in the Gulf Stream and he had gone eighty-four days now taking a fish\". Santiago's physical build-up, his humble, virtually lonely life and sea fishing activities are told in the voice of this third person who seems to know so much about fishing and describes in detail all the kinds of equipment Santiago possesses and all the activities he goes through at sea, including weather-watching and fighting the sharks that attack his fish. This third person also seems to like Santiago very much, and approves of his attitude and empathizes with his disappointment and suffering.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But much of the story is also told in dialogue between Santiago and Manolin, the little boy who is always there for him, even when his parents order him to join another boat, since the old man is luckless, \"salao\". The bond between the old man and the boy is strongly felt throughout their interactions and even when the old man is at sea and alone, he never ceasses to miss the company of Manolin. There is also the use of the interior monologue, much of which is evident in Santiago's engagement with the marlin and the sharks. He is often seen talking to himself and giving himself in a contest of will and endurance with it. He respects its nobility and fights the sharks to preserve it until they unrelentingly eat it up. Much of Santiago's thoughts and responses are presented in this manner with great pathos.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The use of flashback is also a narrative technique, which Santiago relies on to recall past incidents. Thus, Hemingway's use of the four modes of narration enables Santiago's story to be told from different perspectives, so that the reader's interest is sustained throughout.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ASARE KONADU : A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    What role does tradition play in the relationship between Pokuwaa and her mother?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tradition plays a very significant role in the relationship between Pokuwaa and her mother. Being the only daughter among the five sons of her mother, the old woman tends to be closer to her than her sons. By tradition of matrilineal inheritance, the offspring of sons belong to the families of the sons' wives. So although Pokuwaa has brothers, who have children, it is to Pokuwaa that her mother looks for her grandchildren, properly so called. Because of this, the old woman takes keen interest in Pokuwaa's affairs, especially her search for a child.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Being old and a custodian of their traditional beliefs, she supervises the offering to the river god, Tano.This is what the priest says will open the way for Pokuwaa to get a child. Pokuwaa goes along well enough and her mother takes care of her interest and is watchful that she does not come to harm through ignorance. When Pokuwaa deprives the eagle of its meal at the Ananse stream on a taboo day and brings the hornbill home, her mother sees disaster looming for Pokuwaa. Quickly she arranges the necessary purification for Pokuwaa. If Pokuwaa dies now, how will her mother get a grandchild? This is a serious matter for the old woman.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is evident that Pokuwaa's mother's involvment in the affairs of her daughter is deep. She closely directs Pokuwaa's observance of the rites concerning Pokuwaa's search for a child. She keeps her daughter alert to her responsiblities to Tano.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All along, however, Pokuwaa seems to have ideas of her own. She is obedient to the directives of her mother and the priest. Somehow, she looks higher up the ladder to Almighty Onyankopon. When things seems to be taking too long to happen, she feels frustrated. She simply repudiates Tano and devotes herself direct to Onyankopon in her own manner.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The relationship of Pokuwaa's decision to reject Tano has a shattering effect on her mother. For the older woman, it is unthinkable to do what Pokuwaa does. She reports the matter to the head of the clan, Opanin Kofi Owusu, whose assurances that things will work out do not convince her. She sobs for a doomed state whose women refuse to bear children. It can be seen also that more seriously, she laments because she will not get a grandchild if Pokuwaa does not bear a child.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is much natural motherly love borne towards Pokuwaa by the mother. During this love appears to be the expectation of an old woman who wants to count her grandchildren in her final days on earth, and be assured of their tears when she dies. Pokuwaa's mother does not hide her ardent desire and this urges her into getting very deeply involved in her daughter's affairs", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  ASARE KONADU: A WOMAN IN HER PRIME    Discuss the significance of Tano Kofi in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tano Kofi seems to occupy a central position in the small village of Brenhoma. Although it is not the highest God - Nyankopon Twedeampong - its activites as a god are observed throughout the story. This is so because the people are traditionalists and highly superstitious.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  There are seventy-seven other lesser gods, but the great Tano's name is mentioned with awe. He seems to be the founding god of Brenhoma as the Asafo captain calls his people in his song during the search for Yaw Boakye. Tano is a uniting force and a custodian of the welfare of the people.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is evident in the way the people throng to his shrine for consultation and sacrifice. The haste and excitement displayed by Pokuwaa at the beginning of the novel show that the shrine is no doubt a melting point where people go to either put their requests forward to the great Tano or to offer thanks. This is why we meet Pokuwaa making frantic efforts to look for the lost jet-black hen which she has been asked to present at Tanofie on the day of sacrifice.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pokuwaa's friend Koramoa, has had a baby boy through the intervention of great god Tano and that is why every Fofie, she goes there and dances to the beat of the drumming. In their routine prayer during the Odwira festival the name of Tano and the seventy-seven gods are invoked to bring healing, blessing, and happiness to the people. This is the activity we see Pokuwaa engaged in through a good part of the novel until she gets fed up with the practice and stops.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Because of the respect accorded to this god by the people, Pokuwaa's decision to discontinue following the directives recommeded by the Tano priest is not taken lightly by her mother. Pokuwaa's decision angers her and prompts the Old Lady to report Pokuwaa to the head of the Asona Clan, Opanyin Kofi Owusu. When Pokuwaa discontinues making sacrifices to the god Tano, her mother continues to make the sacrifices.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Pokuwaa eventually becomes pregnant, Kwadwo and her mother attribute the pregnancy to the great god Tano. It is therefore obvious that for the people of Brenhoma, no good thing happens without being attributed to god Tano.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI : PURPLE HIBISCUS    Examine the relationship between Eugene and his wife in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene seems brutally oppresive and aggresive in his relationship with his wife, Beatrice, who is loving and submissive. He does not seems to consider her condition or feeling when he decides what to order her to do. Sometimes, he even appears to punish Beatrice for nothing at all. This treatment of her detracts from Eugene's show of love in the things he provides her and the children.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whereas Eugene explains carefully to the children that the excessive punishment he metes out to them is for their sins and necessary for their recovery and redemption, Eugene does not care to tell his wife, or anyone else, why treats her as he does. His beatiing her, from Kambili's brief comment, is routine. And he seems to relish hitting her only on the belly and particularly when she is pregnant.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Once, when the pregnant Beatrice, unsure of what may happen in the priest's house if she goes there, asks to be excused, Eugene bullies her into going. He is livid and implacably condemns the woman at dinner. At night, Kambili keeps count of the thudding of brutal punches. The Eugene carries Beatrice off to hospital. She has been bleedin. She comes back home without the pregnancy.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Besides, Eugene expects his wife to concur in all he does and keep her place in line. When her figurines are broken, she meekly clears the debris. Eugene's wife is so totally unnder his thumb that she dares not offer reasonable objection to anything. She looks on as Kambili is beaten to unconsciousness. Yet she has her silent resentment.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The last straw is the beating she gets while the children are away in Nsukka. This makes her miscarry yet another pregnancy. From her own account to her sister-in-law, this time, Eugene does not know that she is pregnant. All the same, he breaks a table on her belly. This mild attempt to excuse Eugene's brutality rather brings his cruelty to Beatrice into focus: even when he knows that his wife is pregnant, he will hit her bulging belly.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beatrice's docile resignation to Eugene's treatment of her is unacceptable. She cannot risk leaing him for another woman to take her place. If she cannot change him, no other woman must have Eugene. So she poisons him slowly.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene's wife does not deserve the harshness he metes out to her. Quitely, she takes extreme steps to deal with the situation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADICHIE CHIMAMANDA NGOZI: PURPLE HIBISCUS    Examine the importance of the military in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The military play a peculiar role in the novel. They show what human beings are essentially like: greedy, passionate, biased and corrupt, besides other attitudes.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The military highlights the inclination of man towards treating his fellow man harshly for whatever reason. Human beings pursue their principles passionately, however their actions affect others. Whether a soldier or a civilian, man is greedy.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Life under civilian administration is therefore, not different from that under the military. Eugene's prosperity is not affected by the conduct of the civilian administration that is overthrown by soldiers who claim that the civilian are corrupt. Certainly, it is not soldiers who order university professors to victimize university workers or treat other lectures shabbily. The favouritism in University of Nsukka is an exxhibition of human nature. Besides, military administrations are deployed to the University and they paralyse the school system by short funding and embezzling the funds. There is students' unrest and the university is closed unnecessarily. Aunty Ifeoma takes all that with equanimity and is pragmatic. She takes her chance when thiings become intolerable and leaves for America.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eugene's treatment of his own father and other \"heathens\" and of his wife and children is based on his rather strong religiosity. However, much the others may be distressed by his zealous pursuit of his principles and love for God, he simply must do his duty - by them and by himself. He tells his children that he punishes them severely for their own good.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the soldiers arrive by a cou-d'etat, they allege corruption against the civilian regime they overthrow. However, in the pursuit of their principles of assumed legitimacy, they run rough shod over everyone to the extent of eliminating whoever is in the way. Nwankiti Ogechi disappears and nobody is expected to talk. After his arrest and release, Ade Coker should have learnt that the military will stop at nothing. As he will not relent, he receives a letter bomb. It is clear that the military have suppressed opposition and freedom of speech is minimal. Their hold on the people is significant in that it shows their intention to have things their way.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet there is the normal side of life that the corruption and whims of neither the military nor civilians can curtail. Eugene pursues his sternly ordered control of his household, and, according to Kambili, there is laughter in Aunty Ifeoma's home. Business goes on all over the place, and as Father Benedict notes, there is prosperity that only Eugene among businessmen, is using to promote God's work. The market women experience military brutality and the soldiers enjoy humiliating the woman. If the brutality is in the name of justice and fair dealing and uprightness, it should be commended. But military conduct is uncommendable. Jaja's imprisonment and the unfulfilled promises made towards his release show the rate of degeneration in the society. Justice is delayed to allow for corruption from the people in government to thrive. Ade Coker dies because he will not stop criticizing military corruption. If civilians are shot for drug offences how come the soldiers are linked to heroin? The answer is that no one must talk as Ade Coker does to his detriment. Eugene condemns the lack of democracy unnder civilian rule, and decries the coup. What the country needs he says is \"renewed democracy\", not military rule.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All in all, it can be seen that the greed and corruption of politicians that is condemned by all is even more entrenched in soldiers who overthrow the corrupt regimes for being corrupt.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;WILLIAM GOLDING : LORD OF THE FLIES    Comment on the significance of Piggy's glasses.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ralph and Piggy are the first two boys to appear on the island after a plane conveying them to safety has been attcaked. Piggy reveals to Ralph in his first encounter that he has been wearing spectacles since he was there. In many respects Piggy is both physically and health-wise a weak boy. He has asthma so he has been warned by his guardian not to run, and he wears spectacles because he has sight challenges.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Piggy's glasses are one of the symbols in the novel which are significant to the meaning of the novel. Apart from the conch, the glasses appear to be the next most significant symbol which bear directly on the survival strategies of the boys. After the boys have settled on the issue of the need to have a Chief and the use of the conch as a symbol of authority, the next challenge confronting them is the issue of rescue. This challenge is projected to be addressed by setting up a fire on top of the mountain. Piggy's glasses becomes the useful tool to light the pile of wood for this purpose. Jack instantly points to the glasses and there is a general agreement by the boys. Both ack and Ralph jointly use the glasses to light the fire.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The general enthusiasm which greets the setting up of the fire is shortlive as Jack and his group fail to watch over it. He leads his hunters on hunting adventures and the fire dies down, which makes the dream of rescue to fail when a slip passes by on the sea. However, Ralph leads Piggy and Samneric to re-light the fire. Again Piggy's glasses are used to re-enliven the boys' rescue attempts. Even though Jack is not so much concerned about the fire at this point, the significance of the fire is underscored by the equally important glasses.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfortunately, the glasses are stolen by Jack's group in a raid they carry out on the shelter where Ralph. Piggy and Samneric are now camping. Here the glasses are significant in two respects. First is their importance to the tribe. The hunters realize once again that much of their survival depends on having a fire with which they can roast meat and light their part of the island. Second is its significance to the plot. The event of stealing the glasses signifies te beginning of the events that culminate in the final peace and order on the island. Piggy's glasses are partily broken at this point. The attempt to recover the glasses leads to the climax of the story. Jack captures Samneric and engages Ralph in a physical fight. Finally a rock falls and kills Piggy, destroying the conch and breaking the glasses. Thus, the glasses are not only a symbol of Piggy's weakness as a character but also significant to the development of the plot of the novel", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; WILLIAM GOLDING : LORD OF THE FLIES    Consider Ralph as the hero in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ralph plays a dominant role that is inenvitably crucial to the development of the plot.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is the first among the boys to emerge from the creepers. When he finds the conch and is taught how to use it by Piggy, he blows it and its sound attracts and draws the other boys to where he and Piggy are. There and then he begins to exercise some form of authority over the boys by asserting that is only he who has the conch that has permission to speak.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Next he initates the democratic process of electing the leader and is thus elected when he squarely beats Jack in the leadership contest. As a practical expression of his leadership, he leads the delegation that explores the island and reveals that they are probably the only inhabitants on the island.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a leader who takes action, he begins to work out the strategy for their survival on the island and their eventual rescue in earnest. This he does by wisely relying on Piggy's exceptional intelligence. And so he assures the other boys that his father, a naval officer, will come to the rescue as soon as possible,...\"he's commander of the navy. When he gets leave, he'll come and rescue us\", he says. In this regard, he suggests that they make a fire that will raise smoke to attract rescuers.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In spite of Jack's antagonism to this leadership, Ralph remains cool-headed and does all he can to run an inclusive administration by conceding the choir boys' leadership to Jack so that he can come on board. Rather than use brute force like Jack, he pursues the peaceful option and places the unity of all the boys over and above all other considerations.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a caring leader, he courageously defends Piggy as much as he can against the unwarranted brutality of Jack. He grieves deeply when Simon's life is abruptly cut short and painfully mourns when Piggy's life is untimely terminated. As a good leader, he never wavers even when he is virtually deserted by all the boys. And when he is constrained to fight for dear life, he does so bravely and tenaciously thwarts the sinister attempts put together by Jack to kill him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the hero in the novel, Ralph's fighting spirit eventually pays off. As the author's embodiment of civilization and acceptable leadership, he lives on while Jack, the antagonist, is consumed by the uncontrollable inferno he wickedly raises. He is thus able to respond proudly and loudly, \"I am\" to the rescuing naval officer's question: \"Who's the boss here?\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ERNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    To what extent is the old man successful on his last fishing trip?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The old man Santiago has fished in the Gulf Stream for eighty-four days without catching a single fish. In the firist forty-days, the boy Manolin has been with him. But after forty days of fruitless search for fish, the boy's parents decide that the old man is unlucky. They, therfore ask the boy to withdraw from the enterprise. On the orders of his parents, Manolin joins another boat on a fishing trip which catches three great fish in the first week.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The old man labours days after day with the same ill luck. But he loves the sea and fishing and so persists in spite of repeated faillure. One morning Santiago determines to break this cycle of failure and turn defeat into victory. He therefore sails far out to a sea, equipped with sardines and two baits wrapped in a newspaper. The old man works hard and long. Eventually he catches a big fish. In his loneliness Santiago has a bird for company.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Santiago knows it is a big fish beccause of its weight. The old man moves with the fish for a number of days. He loses sight of the coastal landscape but he feels at home in his boat on the wide expanxe of the ocean. The old man experiences intense pain of endurance with a cramped hand before the fish is caught. The old man feels exhausted. He has little food, feeds on raw fish, and has quite scant sleep at night.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The old man is surprised at the enormous size of the fish. Killing the fish is very tasking and strenuous work, but fastening the huge fish to his boat presents a very challenging task. The old man is happy at the turn of events. He makes calculation of the monetary worth of the fish. 'He is my fortune', he thinks. He cannot believe the size of his fish. His mental calculation pegs the weight of the fish at fifteen tundred pounds, may be more. It would bring the highest prices on the market, which is enough to compensate for all the toil and ill-luck of former times and trips.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fortunately, the trade winds rise and begin to drive the boat towards the coast . He is homeward bound with a successful catch. But the old man has not recokened with the sharks which begin to eat the fish. He kills several of them but came in a pack. He fights hard and bravely, but the sharks are one too many. Besides, he has no weapon to fight with \"Nothing\", he says aloud, \"I went too far\". By the time he reaches the shore, there is nothing left of the huge fish which measures 'eighteen feet from the nose to tail'. The old man is completely exhaustd physically. The big fish which is to have brought in a large amount of money is now a mere skeleton to be taken away by the tide.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In spite of his apparent failure to retain his catch, it is worth noting his indomitable courage hugely displayed in his fight against the sharks. The sea defeats him. He is physically broken, but there is much virtue in him having fought hard against tremendous odds.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 2>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ERNEST HEMINGWAY: THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA    Comment on the significance of Santiago's dream about the lions.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The lions on the beach of African appear as a significant symbol in The Old Man and the Sea. Santiago, the protagonist of the story, dreams about them three times in the novel. Each of the times the lions appear in Santiago's dreams, they are portrayed as key to the life ot the old man and the plot of the story especially this sojourn in Ccassblanca and his heroic hand wrestling victory over the negro of Cienfuegos.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First, Santiago dreams about the lions as he departs on his three-day fishing expedition. They appear as ordinary cubs and play like young cats in the dusk. Santiago here sees aa similarity between the cubs and his boy, Manolin. He loves them as he loves Manolin because they are youthful like Manolin who seems to him a sign of great things to come. The image of the lions is also significant in Santiago's dream about them because they always make him, like Manolin, happy; they are also good company to him because he sees them in the image of his apprentice.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Secondly, the lions appear in Santiago's dream as he sleeps on the boat for a few hours during his battle with the ferocious fish, the marlin.This time the lions appear as adults. In their majesty, the lions suggest ggreat strength and honour, providing Santiago with inspiration, a nobility of purpose, and a sense of vitality that keeps him on toward his ambition. They are therefore significant in Santiago's dream because they provide him with inspiration and belief in himself and urge him to be hopeful in his adventure.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In additon, the lions are significant to the story because often, the old man almost simultaneously drreams about them as he dreams about Manolin. Whenever, the boy appears in Santiago's thoughts, he is depicted as exerting himself and proving his worth. Whenever Santiago thinks about the lions, he relaxes because they appear in his imagination to be in control and thus inspire to have confidence in himself.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally, the lions appear in Santiago's dream at the very end of the story. Their significance at a time that the old man appears to have been finally defeated is that there are still promises of regeneration and renewal, particularly because Manolin also comes into the picture to rescue his master. The sombre atmosphere at the end of the novel is reinforced by the final image of the lions to suggest the interplay of destruction and renewal in the story of the protagonist.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KOBINA SEKYE: THE BLINKARDS    Examine the importance of setting in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The play is set in Cape Coast which used to be the capital of the then Gold Coast in the 1930s. References are made to two categories of Cape Coast society. One is built around The Cosmopolitan Club whose membership qualification is that English, however haltingly spoken, is the norm and some forms of English manners of dressing and behaviour are observed. The dominant figures in this society include Mrs. Borofosem, her ladies and admirers. The other is traditional society, still birth vibrant with its demands that the Fanti language and culture should not be set aside. There is a third setting, alluded to, which is England where Mr. and Mrs. Borofosem have lived (and in the case of the latter, for only 3months). The latter's poor manners and badd English appear to have been acquired there. And that is where Mr. Onyimdze trained as a lawyer. Setting, in respect of place, is thus important in contextualizing all the actions of the characters.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Combined with place setting is time setting. The action of the play takes place during a period of colonial rule when colonial Cape Coast is no longer at ease with traditional ways of life. There is conflict between \"been-tos\" like Mrs. Borofosem, who ridicuously imitate English manners and traditionalists like Na Sompa and Nana Katawerwa. Both sides seem to have their moderates and extremists. For example, Mrs. Borofosem would have nothing to do with traditional culture and believes that  everything English is good. She is severely ridiculed and satirised in the play, alongside the Parson and others. Yet, this society has its moderates like Lawyer Onyimdze who follows the bibilical rule of giving unto Casear the things that are Caesar's. He would therefore wear the traditional cloth, eat traditional food, but go to court in his lawyer's outfit where he speaks his impeccable English. And while Na Sompa and Nana Katawerwa represent traditional ways of life, pure and simple, people like Mr. Tsiba and Mr. Okadu are fascinated by English manners for various reasons. It is the extremists on both side who bring about conflict in the play. In the end, with the conflicts resolved and accomodations made, characters like Mr. and Mrs. Borofosem can freely speak Fanti and unashamedly participate in their culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;KOBINA SEKYE: THE BLINKARDS    Examine the humour of the wedding reception at Hamilton House", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Several instances of humour abound in the play, The Blinkards, notable among which is Mr. Okadu and Miss Tsiba's wedding reception at Hamilton House. It is a reception characterized by pandemonium, bombastic and hilarious incidences through the actions and the speeches of the characters.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Playing a prominent role at the reception are members of the Cosmopolitan Cluub who have been invited by Aldiborontiphoscophornio Chrononhontonthologos Tsiba to the wedding ceremony of his daughter, Barbara Ermyntrude and Mr. Alexander Archibald Octavius Okadu.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For a start, all the members of the Cosmopolitan Club are dressed in frock coats, carrying their silk hats. The President, having volunteered to be the  master of ceremony is busy running around with a bottle of whisky, glasses and soda.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the bride and the groom get set to cut the cake, Mrs. Borofosem jumps up, walks to Mr. Okadu and asks him to \"take the knife and stick the cake\" while the bride, Miss Tsiba is asked to \"hold the knife and cut it to the plate\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another instance of humour is the proposition to the health of the bride and the groom by one Mr. Kyerewfo who declares: \"I have great pleasure for proposing the health of the bride and bridegroom today. The manifestations of incredible merrimentations has displayed in this capacious hall due to wedding matrimonial jollification\" whatever that means. Wiping his face, he asks his neighbour, \"What did I say? Did I speak well?\" to which the latter replies, \"Very nice, almost like a European\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While responding to the toast, the groom, highly excited and bent on impressing the august gathering replies: \"On behalf affectionate consort and self, I thank you all for coming to see my wedding ... our matrimonial and connubial amiability assuring our nuptial knot is inextricably woven with the minister of God Almighty\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With cheers following this response, Mr. Nkuntu proposes the health of the bride and the groom saying, \"My eyes are effusive of their joyful lachrimosity to preceive coram us this reception, and its bride and bridesmaids of amazing pulchritudity. I harbour expectation that they too will be espoused, and not recommend celibacy to young men, and will be led to the hymeneal altar\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The best man, not wanting to be left out of the show appreciates Mr. Nkuntu for proposing the toast to the bridesmaids and that \"people will not be wanting to chant their epithalamium with becoming vociferosity\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Proposing the toast to the health of the parents, Mr. Odziekyir declares \"at these magnificient celebration of happiness consequent on insoculation of viniculum matrimonii affords me utmost satisfaction...\" While responding, Mr. Tsiba in great trepidation says, \"I am glad. Praise touch God for the kindness he has taken to show me. Amen! I am glad that my daughter has marriage English fashion.\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Against the background of the decision of the members of the Cosmopolitan Club that to be a gentleman, they must imitate the Europeans, and that weddings would afford them the opportunity \"to speechify in public\", the wedding reception thus provides them the opportunity to display their knowledge and use of the English language and display the mannerism they have learnt, even if not appropriately. Thus, the wedding reception, with its hilarious jokes, laced with bombast, provides a lot of humour in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMI OSOFISAN : THE WOMEN OF OWU    Comment on Orisaye's madness in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Princess Orisaye is behaving strangely and it is thought that she is not of sound mind. The war may have affected her badly and she appears to have lost control of her senses. Her utterances are incoherent. Yet amidst the incoherence one finds shards of profound truth and prophecy. She speaks truths and prophesies. If these were presented in the clear language of a same person, they might have benefited the Allied Forces who could well have adjusted their plans to suit Orisaye's predictions.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Orisaye accepts her painful lot and is determined to do something about it herself. Having decided to kill her ravisher, she is impatient for the eventual moment. Her celebrating the occasion with a death dance is quite real. She is fully aware of the consequence of her killing Baloguun Kusa. She is prepared for her sacrifice.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The explanation that Orisaye gives for lighting the torch is deep.That she has been given to a moral to use as he pleases is terrible news. Hearing it kills \"all the light inside us\". The metaphor of light is used to elucidate her predicament, as well as her intended killing of the \"handsome butcher\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Orisaye's fear of failure is not a slight matter. She must be able to arrive in Balogun's arms, being carried on his horse, and laid on his bed before she can carry out her revenge. She is satisfied with the consequence for the General's people of her sweet revenge. But what happens to her does not matter. She knows her object. \"put a blade to his lovely throat...\".    This is prophecy.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Gesinde rudely orders Erelu to wait to be transported to General Balogun Derin, Orisaye prophesies that her mother will die in her land. This comes to pass quite quickly.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Orisaye reiterates that her revenge and death are the hardiwork of the gods. She knows what she is talking about. Perhaps madness is the only state of escape from which Orisaye, in the circumstances, can declare these profound truths and prophecies.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMI OSOFISAN : THE WOMEN OF OWU    Discuss Iyunloye's defence as a victim in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Erelu does not hide her antagonism towards Iyunloye. To her, Iyunloye has profited from the sack of Apomu and brought destruction to Owu, refusing to make amends while she could.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Maye Okunade has Iyunloye brought out for questioning, his mind is made up as to what to do with her. Her has support from Erelu, who warns him of treachery.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Iyunloye starts to placate her husband. Urged on by Erelu, the Maye rebuffs her entreaties as best he can. He accuses his wife of infidelity and desertion. He must punish her to set an example for others. Her overtures of love for the Maye having failed to move the warrior, Iyunloye begs to be heard. She defends herself by blaming Erelu who has refused to kill her son who grows up to take her away from her husband, bringing about the war.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is Iyunloye's defence that she has been taken captive and put in the harem of the youngest son of the King of Owu. But, she has never forgotten her husband. She swears that everyone has given up her husband for dead, she has endeavoured to immortalize her husband's art through her position in the palace.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Iyunloye swears that she has tried several times, during the seven years of siege, to escape to her husband, but each time the guards have stopped her. She has thus had no means of escape.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; These averments are rebutted by Erelu, who paints a picture of Iyunloye as a mercenary bent on enjoying the good things of Owu Kingodm that she would never have had in her backward country. Iyunloye seizes upon this to cry against being ridiculed because of her minority status. She disgresses and makes elaborate argument for the worth of the minority. Of course, this is neither here nor there. Iyunloye has been uncaring about her husband since her domicile in Owu. She refuses the personal offer of Erelu to lead her out to her husband so that the war might end.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Erelu's presence does not help matters. The Maye pronounces his decision: Iyunloye shall die by stoning. As the chorus and Erelu hightlight the guilt and just punishing for Iyunloye, Okunade appears more and more resolute.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But, against Erelu's advice not to do so, he looks into the eyes of Iyunloye and the effect is disastrous for Erelu. Iyunloye's looks rather than her plea of being of being victimized, decides the Maye's allowing her to join his caravan. She is not to be killed immediately. Rather, she will be dealt with in Ife where women will lynch her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  From Gesinde's account, however, husband and wife are reunited and \"Iyunloye is riding back with us in triumph\". Iyunloye has her way and Erelu's gleeful expectations come to nought.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    How is romantic love treated in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Romantic love is a predominant theme in the play. But this is welded into a compact whole with the theme of war. In the play, the experiences of the characters how that the romance of war is closely connected to the romance of love.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the play opens, the audience is introduced to Raina's romantic perceptions of love. She is a pretty, young lady whose reading of two poets, Byron and Pushkin, has impacted her idea of love. Standing on the balcony of her bedroom, she admires the beauty of the night, dreams of her finace, Sergius, who is currently fighting in the war between Bulgaria and Serbia. Raina, in ectasy, receives the news of her finace's bravery on the war front from her mother and in her bedroom, adores her lover's photograph affectionately. She feels that she has been, before now, a \"prosaic little coward\" in her doubts about Sergius' heroism. Thus, her lover's supposed heroic performance feeds into her romantic perceptions of love. Raina glorifies Sergius as a hero. On returning from the war, a \"higher love\" develops between them. Sergius calls her \"My queen\" and \"goddess\" and she calls him her \"king\" and \"hero\". They glorify each other because they are blind to their own failings. Later, both of them have to face the realities of love and submit to their own common human imperfections.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This idealized world of romantic love is contrasted with Bluntshli's blunt but realistic perception of both love and war. The fugitive is used to voice the playwright's position on the issue of love. He shocks Raina by presenting a realistic view of Sergius' foolhardness on the war front.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The fault in Raina and Sergius' perception of love is further brought to the fore as we see them cheating on each other, Raina flirting with Bluntschli behind Sergius back and Sergius flirting with Louka behind Raina's back. Their romantic love is therefore treated as something that cannot last.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through Bluntschli and Louka, the playwright is able to focus the searchlight of truth and reason on the idea of love. Bluntschli and Louka are intectually superior to Sergius and Raina in this play. The futility of romantic love is stressed when Nicola is forced to give up on Louka for business and profit, and Louka for social status.  In the final analysis, love is treated as a matter of strict realism. Romantic love is more of an illusion..", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BERNARD SHAW: ARMS AND THE MAN    How is the conflict between Bluntschli and Sergius resolved.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sergius and Bluntschli are soliders fighting on either side of two waring countries, Bulgaria and Serbia respectively. Bluntschli is, however, a Swiss a mercenary on the side of the Serbs. Running away from the battlefield after an unprofessional chivary charge led by Sergius which destabilizes the Serbian army, Bluntshli takes refuge in Raina's chamber. Even though Sergius acknowledges Bluntschli's proffesssional qualities while recalling the last battle before the end of the war, he never realizes until later, that his lover Raina, Major Petkoff's, daughter is the one who shelters him and helps him to escape. The grounds for a conflict between the two soldiers are being established through Raina's amorous feeling for Bluntschli, in spite of her romantic idealization of Sergius.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, Raina, in the early part of the play, expresses her scepticism about Sergius' heroism. She tells Catherine, her mother, \"Our ideas of what Sergius would do - our patriotism our heroic ideals. I sometimes used to doubt whether they were anything but dreams\". Thus, it seems this scepticism is proved right wheen she meets Bluntschli. Bluntschli demonstrates the reality about war and warring to her as she sheilds the 'chocolate-cream soldier\". She later rebukes Sergius ' \"coarse\" retelling of Bluntschli's escape story in her presence. Bluntschli has apparently related his escape to the Bulgarian army during the exchange of soldiers after the ceasefire.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Louka's revelations about Raina's secret love escapades to Sergius provides the necessary reasons for this later challenge to Bluntschli. In the third Act, the stage direction portrays Sergius as admirably envious of Bluntschli as the latter works to map out the disengagement of three cavalry regiments to Phillippopolis. Sergius contemplates \"Bluntschli's quick, sure, business-like progress with a mixture of envious imitation at his own incapacity\". The impression given in this regard is that in spite of the initial lack of knowledge about the identity of his rival, Sergius is already nursing a grudge against Bluntchli. The revelation of Bluntchli as the man who has won over Raina's love, which Sergius uses as excuses for challenging him is only being underscored by the growing envy which Sergius has already nursed against Bluntschli. The conflict between these two is not, therefore, rooted in Raina's switch over to Bluntschli but on the personality crisis Sergius has.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The path to the resolution of the conflict begins to emerge as Bluntschli reappears to return Major Petkoff's coat given to him by Raina to prevent himself from being identified as the enemy by Bulgarian soldiers. Louka recognizes him and in one of Major Sergius secret love advances to her confronts him to challenge Bluntschli. Almost immediately, the tensions and apprehensions that the audience has been put to begin to reach the climax. This also shows how the story of the two men forms a sub plot in the play and the conflict between them a sub conflict of the overall conflict in the play. Bluntschli appears on the scene only to be challenged to a duel by Sergius even though he (Sergius) does not state the grounds for the challenge. Yet, Bluntschli accepts the challenge to fight him without any demand for his offence. As Raina comes in, the truth about Bluntshli's identity as the escaped solider and the secret romantic advances of Sergius to Louka are all revealed. The whole business of fighting to resolve the conflict is no longer necessary as both men have now discovered where their true love belongs and so they become happy people.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Comment on the use of irony in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is much use of irony in the play. In examining the characters and events, there is much more than meets the eye.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During Algernon's arguments with Jack's cigarette case. Algernon reveals much about himself. One such revelation is the depth of his insight into human nature. He asserts that two women cannot become friends before they have quarreled. Ironically this is how the relationship between Gwendolen and Cecily develops. The apparently agreeable women quickly grid themselves for serious confrontation over the personally \"Ernest\" that either claims for her lover.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The doubel identity of Jack is replicated in Algernon's \"Bunburyism\". It is ironical that this is used effectively against Jack. As Jack gives his country address to Gwendolen Algernon eavesdrops. He takes down the address and promptly asks Lane to prepare him for \"Bunburying\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By her own confession, Lady Bracknell has gone into marriage with hardly an y wealth. She should not be rating people for their wealth, as she does Jack, before being eligible to marry into her class. For this reason her interview of Jack concerning Jack's worth is ironical.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Advising Jack regarding his percentage, Lady Bracknell finds Jack's being found in a bag at the railway station unsatisfactory, so she asks him to acquire at least one parent. This appears rather impossible. Soon enough, however, Miss Prism comes to the rescue. Upon Lady Bracknell's own insistence, the whole story of Jack's genealogy is made bare and he does acquire adequate percentage in dramatic fashion.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Being called Ernest, as it turns out, is really serious business. The flippant naming of an imaginary wayward brother as Ernest by Jack is ironical. In due time he will need to have to acquire that name to solve a critical problem. This is ironical.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OSCAR WILDE: THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING EARNEST    Examine Miss Prism's importance in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When casually observed, Mrs Prism is simply a minor character. On close examination, however, she is seen as playing a most revealing role, particularly at certain defining moments.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her actions initiate the various mistaken identities that dominate and largely shape the course of events in the play. But it is also through her that the raging confusion is finally and happily resolved.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her actions and their ripple effects begin to manifest when she is Jack's nanny. Jack is then christened 'Ernest John'. At one time this nanny absent-mindedly drops the toddler in her bag instead of in a pram, at Victoria Railway Station luggage room in London. The bag is mistakenly given to one Mr. Thomas Cardew on his way to Worthing. Mr. Cardew arrives home, adopts the \"abandoned\" baby and names him Jack Worthing. The baby grows up to be known as Uncle Jack for about 29 years. And for that long, Miss Prism inadvertently obscures his true identity.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is Jack's obscured identity that makes him had Algernon, his younger biological brother, to think that they are ordinary friends. The same mistaken identity makes his aunt - Lady Bracknell; believe that he is a poor commoner; unworthy of her daughter's love. It is a fall-out of Miss Prism's absent-mindedness that leads Jack to pledge to convert his name to Ernest to please Gwendolen when in fact he is named Ernest at birth. These situations that give rise to instances of mistaken identities and dramatic irony that are directly or indirectly set in motion by Miss Prism's apparent slip of memory.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, there is nothiing of a slip of memory in her relationship with Chasuable. She will not be out done by the other characters in the choice of a partner and in her deliberate, calculating secretive manner, the succeeds in getting married to the Parson.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But it is also Miss Prism that comes to cut the Gordian knot (unravel the mysteries) in a most dramatic way. This comes at a time when the proposed marriage between Jack and Gwendolen is facing the mother's stiffest opposition. As the mother sights Miss Prism and casts her mind back on an earlier event, she calls for explanation. Miss Prism readily obliges and, true to what her name seems to symbolize. She sheds the necessary light on Jack's true identity. There and then all other issues of mistaken identity are resolved in what turns out to be a comedy of errors.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; POETRY    Examine the Identity crisis in \"Boy on a Swing\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem depicts a boy swinging to and fro on a swing. The emphasis is on the activity and it seems he is enjoying himself immensely as the swing moves \"faster and faster\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More gets known about the boy as the poem progresses. Reference is made up to his \"blue shirt\" billowing \"in the breeze\"; and its comparison with \"a tattered kite\". What is here revealed is his background and his poverty which the words - \"blue\" and \"tattered\" - suggest.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the boy's movement on the swing intensifies, more is suggested about the happenings on the swing. Now its rapid motion becomes disorienting as the boy loses bearing in the metaphor of \"east becomes west\", \"north turns to south\" and \"the four cardinal points/meet in his head\". At this point, it is suggested, confusion sets in and the boy is no longer at ease in his former state where he seems to be at home in familiar poverty and class.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The crisis of identity is then reached in the final stanza in the cry of \"Mother!\", in the one and only first line, to be followed by the the series of rhetorical questions in the succeeding lines. These questions allude to the boy's origin and aspiration ending in the profundity of the line - \"Why was my father jailed?\" It seems that at this point the veil has been removed from the boy's face and, like a clairvoyant, he can see the unacceptable situation in which he and his race find themselves. The poignancy of the revelation is felt, rather than said, as a world of innocence crashes before the boy's eyes.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; POETRY    How does the poet present his experience as a blackman in \"Expelled\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet presents an image of a world before colonialism which brought great devastation. The dominant image is that of commerce. The statement -- \"We had traded in this market competitively perfect\" - suggests peace.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The picture changes dramatically, however, when colonisation sets in to disrupt the erstwhile peaceful co-existence. The metaphor of \"cut our ribs, dried our cows\" and \"burst the cowshed\" presents a picture of devastation affecting agriculture and the economy which have been the bulwark of the people's properity. The very natural environment is not spared by the reference to words like \"drought\" and \"famine\". The blackmaid's confidence is thus eroded as he is cut off from his means of livehood.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After presenting such a grim picture of life after colonialism the poet enters into a state of personal lamentation. This is captured by the hyperbole in \"my tears flowed to flooded streams\", while the allusion to Sodom and Gomorrah presages the complete penury into which the poet has sunk. The image of the debtors and creditors at \"my rusty door\" is poignant. He has become the laughing stock of others as what is left of his miserable possessions is auctioned. The devastation brought in by colonialism is total and the poet's own life becomes a veritable testament.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; POETRY    Discuss the changing mood of the poet in \"The Sun Rising\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"The Sun Rising\" is a dramatisation of an imagined confrontation between a lover and the sun. Initially, the poet feigns a foul and angry mood, as the sun shines into the room where he and his mistress are still lying in bed. He not only describes the sun as \"busy\" and \"unruly\" but also calls the sun a \"fool\". The poet directs the sun to its routine rounds \"goe chide late schoole boyes, and sowre prentices...\" etc. admonishing it to do its job and not annoy him. All this occurs in the first stanza.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the second stanza, the poet's stance appears to soften as he acknowledges the power of the sun's rays. He trivalises it and boasts that he could \"eclipse\" it \"with a wrinkle\". In this, there is both arrogance and sarcasm.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The boast continues in the third stanza where he presents his lover as protection itself. For both of them are an embodiment of royalty and all the riches of the world. The mood here is triumphant. Suddenly (still in the third stanza) the poet's mood becomes concillatory and amiable. He sees the sun as ageing and requiring rest, yet having his work to do. The poet's anger seems to have cooled off considerably. He asks the sun to shine on him and his lover. He is obviously proud that, after all, the best place for the sun to do his job, if he is to do it well, is the closet/room where the lovers are, for that  epitomises that vast world round which the sun must travel daily. This, the poet contend, will ease the sun's burden though he will have fully accomplished his task by staying with the lovers. The mood at this point, besides conciliatory, is also patronizing.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It can be said that the initially angry mood of poet changed to become persuasive, then conciliatory and patronizing.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2015>PAPER 3>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  POETRY    Comment on the errand of the soul in \"The Soul's Errand\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet, in acknowledging human frailty vis-a-vis the inviolability and immortality of the soul, sends it on an errand to defend the truth against human lies and machinations in all places, high and low. Everywhere, doing the wrong thing holds sway and prentention is rife. Thus the errand involves speaking against the previous of intellectual, moral, emotional and other forms of human behaviour.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poet is mainly worried that institutions uphold the reverse of the fundamental values of their existence. Religious and secular institutions as well as ethical values come up for censure. These include Courts, the Potentates, the Church, Honour, Love and Beauty. On his deathbed, he asks the soul to pay visits to each and every one of these perverters. While out at it he must \"give the world the lie\" as nothing is done right anywhere in the world. The repetition of the line \"give the world the lie\" acts as a refrain and highlights the poet's preoccupation.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That his concept of mortality and living right is not easy to uphold is not lost on the poet. He is aware that facing the truth can be a bitter experiment; telling it, even more so. The bearer of the message of truth may be threatened with death \"to give the lie/Deserves no less than stabbing\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, it is comforting that the soul has the advantage of immortality and will definitely come out unhurt: \"No stab the soul can kill\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Faceless by Amma Darko  Discuss the relationship between Nii Kpakpo and Mea Tsuru in the Novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nii Kpakpo is Maa Tsuru's second 'husband'. As is the case with Kwei who fathers her four eldest children, Nii Kpakpo and Maa Tsuru are not really married; they are merely cohabiting. She meets him after Kwei has abandoned her and her children.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is no evidence in the novel that Nii Kpakpo loves Maa Tsuru. His main goal in the relationship appears to be sponge on her and make himself as comfortable as he can. Nii Kpakpo has a temendous influence on Maa Tsuru's household as later events are to show the way in which he worms himself into Maa Tsuru's affections exposes him as a scheming and heartless fraud. He is able to endear himself to her through an elaborately conceived and executed plan of deception. When he meets her for the first time, he explains his being out of job as a consequence of renovation being carried out on an aluminium factory in Tema. He is testing the ground. He soon realizes how gullible Maa Tsuru is. Though she has not heard of the factory before, she believes Nii Kpakpo's story. This first victory boosts Nii Kpakpo's confidence.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Next he makes it a habit to visit Maa Tsuru's home at lunch time so that his afternoon meal is assured. he puts off her requests to visit his home under the pretext that his \"people\" will not welcome her because of the curse on Maa Tsuru's head. Then growing in confidence, he suggests after heavy drinking and a hefty meal, that he moves in with her because as he claims, \"I miss sharing the same bed with you at night\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Totally enamoured of this man who appears to her to be restoring her self-esteem, dented by her disastrous relationship with Kwesi, she gratefully invites him into her one-bedroom home. Nii Kpakpo's very first night in Maa Tsuru's home presages the destabilizing effect which he will have on the household. On the morning after a night-long bout of love-making in full view of the children, the two eldest children of Maa Tsuru's, the boys, leave home, never to return. WIth them disappears Maa Tsuru's main source of income for the sustenance of her family. This causes untold suffering to Maa Tsuru and her two remaining children added to his burden is that she has one more mouth to feed- an adult mouth at that! she begins to worry and cannot even sleep at night.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Maa Tsuru is 'blind' to Nii Kpakpo's misdemeanours. Even after she learns the truth about the non-existent job in Tema and the fraud which he perpetrates on prospective tenants for his one room in his family house, she does not take any action. Everyone expects she will, but quite naively she keeps allowing him to exploit her. Soon Maa Tsuru is carrying Kpakpo's child.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nii Kpakpo's exploitation of Maa Tsuru further manifests itself in his sexual abuse of her daughter, Baby T. Even then, Maa Tsuru does not react. His exploitation culminates in his facilitation of Baby T's sale to Maame Broni. He deceives Maa Tsuru into believing that Baby T is going away to serve as househelp to some rich person. His influence over Maa Tsuru is such that whatever he suggests is readily acceptable to her and makes sense. Eventually Baby T is brutally murdered. Nii Kpakpo is thus, to some extent, responsible for Baby T's awful end. Fofo, the younger sister, soon leaves home, realizing that there is no possibility of a meaningful relationship with her mother as long as Nii Kpakpo is around. He thus serves as the knife which serves family relationships.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In conclusion, the relationship between Nii Kpakpo and Maa Tsuru  is one between the exploiter, Nii Kpakpo, and the exploited, Maa Tsuru. In the end, he abandons Maa Tsuru, having fathered two boys with her, thus renewing her fate as single parent.    Points to note    (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They are not husband and wife in the traditional sense.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Nii Kpakpo exploits Maa Tsuru's desire to have 'a husband'  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Maa Tsuru's gullibility makes the man more confident to move in to live with her.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His presence in the house causes the departure of Maa Tsuru's four children to live in the streets.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nii Kpakpo finally leaves Maa Tsuru worse off.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Examine the significance of Vickine and Kabria's visit to the police station.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vickie and Kabria of MUTE visit the local police station to request information on the status of the police investigation into the murder of Baby T. This episode, more than any other in the novel, illustrates the moral bankruptcy of the society and paints a bleak picture of the future.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The physical state of the police station is a metaphor for the decadence which has engulfed the institution. Vickie and Kabria are greeted with the sight of \"broken windows, leaking drains, cracked walls and peeling paint\". Given the importance of the police in good governance, the appalling lack of basic facilities stands as a testimony to the neglect which state institutions have suffered over the years. The telephone which should be an important aid in police work is dead. The Inspector's table, like the state of the society, is dilapidated. The cabinet in which supposedly confidental files are kept has no lock and is wrenched. We learn from the Inspector that it has been in this condition for at least a decade. In addition to the non-funtional telephone, there is no vehicle in the station so the police will find themselves incapable of responding in cases of emergency. The expression which the narrator uses, \"sorry sight\", succinctly sums up the situation.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The attitude of the officers manning the station comes under the spotlight. The front desk officer has an air of boredom, only nods in response to the visitors' greetings and points to the Inspector's door. One would except a more friendly welcome to members of the public, who after all, are the sole clients of the police.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Inspector, in command at the station, is, if nothing else, worse in his demeanour. When Vickie and Kabria enter his office, he is engrossed in a game of lotto. Clearly, the visitors are a distraction. This is a public officer who should be on duty. Throughout the visitor discussion with him, he is nonchalant and sometimes downright hostile. Only when he learns of the interest of the press in the matter does he adopt a near conciliatory tone. He typifies the public officer whose belief is that his continued occupation of his current position depends on creating a good image in the press, rather than performing his duties diligently. Even this veneer of civility is dropped as soon as the visitors' enquiries become too much for him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The author intends this episode to serve as a backdrop to the major incident in the novel the murder of Baby T. It shows that the people whom the police should serve can hope for no protection from them, especially if they are poor complainants. Baby T's case has been 'filed' put away and forgotten. The police have made no attempt at investigating her murder. They cannot be bothered with the brutal murder of an unidentified street girl.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Granted, the police are ill-equipped, but the author does not provide any justification for their incompetence and hostility to their clients. However, an organization like MUTE, and their visit to the police station, helps to raise hope for the voiceless.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The visit clearly shows MUTE's interest in Baby T's case.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It brings out the decadence of the facilities at the police station.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It reflects the dysfunction in the society.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It brings out the lo morale (and unreliability) of the police.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It promises hope (i.e. MUTe's visit) for the hopeless and voiceless people in the society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Lonely Days by Bayo Adebowale  Discusss the theme of homeless in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loneliness is a major theme in the novel. It is the outcome of a tradition of Kufi which isolates widows for a period. Three widows, Dedewe, Radeke and Fayoyin, suffer this fate, but only for as long as they end their widowhood by the cap-picking ceremony.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, one character who is most afflicted by loneliness is Yaremi, whose marriage to her husband, Ajumobi, comes to an abrupt end through his untimely death. Thereafter she is consigned to a life of loneliness.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a motif, 'loneliness' and its associations such as 'left her alone', 'lonely' and 'solitude' permeate the novel. Yaremi is rendered lonely after the death of her husband, Ajumobi. Her two daughters Segi and Wura, after being given away into marriage, no longer keep her company. Her only son, Alani, now lives in Ibadan, and to him, Kufi has become a lonely settlement at the very end of the earth.  Yaremi's only companion is Woye, her little grandchild.  On very cold nights, when other lucky women of Kufi enjoy the company and warmth of their husbands, Yaremi sprawls dejectedly on her bamboo bed, missing Ajumobi and can only launch into a spate of rapturous reminiscences. It becomes her habit to visit her husband's grave at least two times a day. There she sits alone and monologues her earthly problems, hoping for Ajumobi's response.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For fear of losing her only companion, Woye, she does everything she knows of medication, cajolling, coaxing and prayer - to get him healed of his high fever, No wonder, at the boy's sudden decision to leave with his mother for Olode to enroll in school, Yaremi perceives 'a steadying positive factor in her loneliness going away'.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the end, Alami's strange pronouncement that he is going back to Ibadan after his short visit to Kufi, throws her into a swoon. Later when the village elders announce the punitive measure of sendiing her into exile for refusing all the caps, she is galvanised into resolving that it is her dead body that they will carry out of Kufi. She draws her strength and will power from Almighty God and braces herself for the paniful continuation of her lonely days.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Major cause of loneliness in the novel is widowhood  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yaremi, Dedewe, Radeke, Fayoyin are victims.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The effects of loneliness on characters.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yaremi's rejection of the tradition of cap-picking.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Comment on the writer's narrative style in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The writer tells his story from the well-known third person viewpoint. With this omniscient perspective, he demonstrates his skill in observing people and events very closely and passing appropriate comments on them.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One remarkable feature of this style is his drawing very deeply from the African oral tradition in his narrative. This is evidenced in Yaremi's folk tales about such animals as the tortoise that often over-reaches itself in its own wiles and cunning, the antelope that often falls on its own pride and the gluttonous baboon that dies from its rapacious greed. There is also the use of incantation as shown by both Ajumobi and Yaremi to neutralize the evil machinations of their perceived enemies.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The writer employs flashback as Yaremi, on a good number of occasions recalls the past days with her late husband and eulogises his sterling qualities as a husband and his prowess as a hunter.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dialogue is also empowered in the narration. Instances are the exchanges between Yaremi and Woye, Yaremi and Ajumobi, Yaremi and her suitors, the widows on their way from the river, etc.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The author also gives some characters the chance to air their convictions, thus making them use the first person narration as seen in the toasting by Anyanwale, Olonade and Lanwa. The number game (which takes more than one page) also contributes a child's perspective to the narration, coming from Woye. Also significant is the use of local influence, which comes from tradition, folklore and setting.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The writer adopts the omniscient perpective.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He draws largely from oral tradition.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He uses the flashback technique.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He uses local terms to add colour to the setting.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Native Son by Richard Wright  Consider the view that it is the society that makes Bigger a murderer in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The situation in which Bigger finds himself is the general predicament of the coloured person in the world of the novel. Living amidst opportunities and with aspirations for doing well. Bigger feels hemmed in by the society's attitude towards his race. Whites and blacks are segregated. Each must know his or her place. Even in prison, as Bigger experiences, whites and blacks are segregated.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is stereotyping that gives the black man very little chance to stand or speak for himself. According to the Jackson Daily Star, the Thomas family is \"of a shiftless and immoral variety\". But for \"his extreme youth\", Bigger would have been the spotlight on the black youth without their being able to escape. In Dixie, the blacks are \"depraved types of Negroes\" on whom punishment has no effect.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Outlandish suppositions and presumptions made about non-whites place them in the class of scum and criminality. Bigger is said to be of \"jet-black complexion\", but may have a minor portion of white blood in his veins\". Such a mixture, it is supposed, makes a potential criminal of an individual. Though it is claimed that \"here in Dixie we keep Negroes firmly in their place\", that is the approved attitude of whites towards blacks in America. Male blacks must not make white female friends. In having Bigger make Mary Dalton's fatal acquintance, Jan is breaching a fundmental code of segregation.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The likes of Bigger do not have a normal progression in life. He is unable to become anything he has wished to be. For example, he cannot become a pilot because society will not allow him to do so. This thwarting of his ambiton is in contrast with the general belief that hard work leads to success. For Bigger that is most bewildering.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bigger's whole race is considered inferior to the whites. He dares not aspire. Yet he assists corrupt white political aspirants by selling his vote to them for five dollars. This is the general situation of the black youth and they resent it. Resentment has led to mutual hatred, distrust and fear.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This mutuality shows in the arena of crime. Upon suspicion of being responsible for a crime, the cry for the blood of the suspect is louder and more insistent when the suspect is black than when it is a white man. The \"shouts of Lynch 'im!' Kill 'im!' that greet Bigger at the inquest are typical.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Given this situation of white intolerance of blacks, a growing black child learns to be and does become aggressive, bitter and self-defensive. This nuturing of mutual hatred has fatal consequences as results in the case of Bigger Thomas.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All this promotes in Bigger bitterness and fear, which explains why he rebelliously wishes to drop a bomb on white people if he has the means. It is also the fear that society instils in Bigger that makes him shove Mary's corpse into the furnace to avoid detection and brutally murder Bessie to escape justice.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Segregation/social discrimination  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Deprivation  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fear  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bigger's inherent tendencies.    Max considers the conventional treatment of the black man as inconsistent with a good man's conscience, and he cannot support those who uphold the system.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 2>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Native Son by Richard Wright  What is Max's attitude towards racial relations in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Max is a legal practitioner of repute. He is clearly dissatisfied with American society. He does not favour the subjugation of minority groups in the Union. This attitude may explain his joining the communist Party and the Labour Defenders.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Whether Max's joining the Communist Party is a means of personal escape or an avenue for political achivements, Max takes exception to the exception to the existing racial relations.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Max knows all about the black situation. As he points out to Bigger in prison, the whole black race, including other minorities, and its structures are kept together and alive only by faith. Losing that adhesive causes the collapse of any ideas that sustain the blacks. This is why Max urges Bigger, even at the point when Bigger is headed for the electric chair to be staunch in his belief in himself.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  For Max, it is unacceptable to regard any human being as second rate or deny him opportunities. Seggregation is wrong; condesecension is not constructive.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Max's pointed interrogation of Mr. Dalton is very revealing. The millionaire philanthropist toes the line of the system. In his gandd offers to and patronage of blacks, Mr. Dalton appears to be eager to be seen as doing good through not doing desirable good. Max does not accept that Mr. Dalton should be allowed to perpetrate the wrongs of the system simply because, in what Bigger has done, a \"grave harm has been done to two people who've helped Negroes\" more than anyone else. He insists that it is critical to go to the root of the matter of the black-white dichotomy. In sending a \"dozen pingpong tables to the South Side Boys' Club\", Mr. Dalton is only scratching the surface of the problem. Max asserts that pingpong will not \"keep men from murdering\".     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Max also rejects Mr. Dalton's attitude towards his own philanthropy. When he emplous the likes of Bigger, he sends them to school. But he does not employ the educated blacks he creates. Mr. Dalton is not shifting from the path beaten by the system. The system does not permit him and he cannot make his Negro tenants pay a fair rent.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Seeing the Bigger saga as one throb of the heartbeat of the minority groups, Max insists that \"killing this boy isn't going to help us any\". Nobody is asking Mr. Dalton to \"atone for suffering\" that is not his creation. But from Max's point of view, what Mr. Dalton is \"doing doesn't help\".        Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Max's stance on racial relations.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Max's defence of Bigger.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Max's indicment of the whites.   (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Max's final submission on Bigger.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "DELE CHARLEY:  The Blood of a Stranger     Consider the view that the play exposes the colonialist exploitation of Africa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Colonialist exploitation is an important theme in the play. At the centre of this exploitation is a white stranger, appropriately named Whitehead.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitehead works out an elaborate scheme of deception and treachery. Before he comes to Mando, he enlists, through bribery, the support of Maligu, Chief Advisor to the King. His strategy is deliberate. He comes to Mando Land ostensibly to cultivate tobacco. This, however, is a cover for his plan to steal the people's diamonds. Maligu in turn bribes and blackmails Soko, the Chief Priest, to support the plot. So, even before Whitehead arrives in the Kingdom, the ground has already been prepared.      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitehead epitomises the colonialist who ruthlessly and selfishly exploits the resources of Africa. Even his closest accomplice, Maligu, does not know Whitehead's real intentions. His arrogance and lack of respect for the custom and tradition of the people is exposed on his arrival in Mando Land. He arrives in the kingdom and he fails to pay his respects to the King because he claims he is too tired to do so. This behaviour flies in the face of the mores of the people. The impression is given that his action is not a result of his ignorance of the custom. He does this because he does not respect the society.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contrary to what he tells Maligu, Whitehead's real intention is to exploit diamonds. Part of his scheme involves intoxicating the people with alcohol and hard drugs and exploiting their labour. He succeeds up to a point in deceiving everyone excpet Kindo, who is to be his nemesis. In his exploitation, Whitehead ignores the custom and tradition of Mando Land which he does not find convenient and uses to his advantage those which he thinks will be benefits to him. He is aware that his supply of alcohol and hard drugs to the people is causing debauchery and laziness but he coludn't care less. When, however, he wants the people to hand over all the diamonds to him, his strategy is to play on their superstition.     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitehead is treacherous and will treat as expendable anyone who can no longer be of use to him, no matter how close the person has been to him. He does not value the life of even those he calls his friends. He plans to rape Wara, Kindo's woman, and then sends Parker to kill Soko who has been part of his deception all along. When Maligu remarks that Kindo will kill Parker, he replies, \"That is what I want to happen Parker is of no use to me any longer\". This is a chilling reminder of the heartlessness and exploitative nature of colonialists.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The focus of the play is colonialist exploitation. The playwright, however, also exposes the complicity of the blacks in their own exploitation. Maligu and Soko, consumed with greed, lend their full support to Whitehead in his exploitation of their own resources. Both are self-seeking and greedy, Maligu more so than Soko. Without their conivance, Whitehead's plan would not even have been put into action, much less succeeded. It is only Kindo who stands between disaster and salvation.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The final impression in the play is that contact between Africa and the West, though disastrous, can be salvaged by people like Kindo.     Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitehead as a colonialist representative, not an agent.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His enlisting through bribery, the support of Maligu who in turn bribes Soko, the priest.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His concealing his real intention to steal diamonds by announcing that he is interested in cultivating tobacco.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The blackmailing of Soko, the Chief priest, by Maligu to support Whitehead.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His arrogance and lack of respect for the custom and tradition of Mandoland as manifested in his failure to respect the King and his attempt to rape Kindo's woman.  (f) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His introduction of alcohol and hard drugs in his design to exploit the people's labour and introduce them to immoral activites.  (g) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His treacherous nature as seen in his intent to kill Parker whom he has no use for any longer.  (h) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The role of Kindo in opposing colonalist exploitation and restoring dignity to Mando Land.  (i) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The complicity nature of some natives in colonial exploitation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Examiine the role of Kindo as a warlord in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the Chief of the warriors of Mando Land, Kindo's life is ruled by one great passion; it is the steadfast commitment to guarantee and safeguard the security and cultural integrity of the Mandos.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kindo, who is heir apparent to the throne of Mando Kingdom, is under no illusion about his sacred duty and sterling responsibilities as a warlord. These are well-known to the people of Mando Land, including Soko, the priest, and Maligu, the King's Chief Advisor both of whom are Kindo's sworn enemies. For instance, he tells Wara, his fiancee, that as a warrior, he does not beat women, he does not venture into the bush without his \"jonga\" or hunting knife and that \"the enemy warrior who would kill Kindo as not been born yet\". Maligu who like Soko, views Kindo's guts and grit with awe, warns the latter not to touch Wara for \"Kindo is fire and he will burn you if you touch Wara\". On another occasion Maligu also warns Soko: \"Kindo will refuse to let us admit the stranger\" who is coming as a wolf in sheep's clothing to deprive the unsuspecting Mandos of their rich diamond deposits.    Kindo's consciousness about his duty to the people of Mando Land drives his conduct. He passionately cares about their Welfare and places their security and safety over and above his deep-seated love for Wara. Accordingly, he tells her without mincing words \"My destiny seems not to care about Kindo-who-is Wara's man, but Kindo-the-Chief-of-the Warriors\". Thus, Maligu reminds Soko that Kindo does not allow his love for Wara to interfere with the security of the people. And this is why Kindo, against all odds, is implacably opposed to the coming of Whitehead into their land which he perceives as an ill omen.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Although Kindo as a clear-headed general prefers peace to war, being fully aware of its dire consequences, he remains an iconic warlord by boldly defending their cultural values when Whitehead and Parker come to dishonour them. He drills the two and compels them to pay due respect to the King and their tradition when they appear before him.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kindo's warlord role is not only crucial in safeguarding the present, it also secures the future of Mando Kingodm. Unlike his gullible and rather complacent father, Kindo is highly intelligent. He is able to detect and frustrate the shady deal of Maligu, Soko and Whitehead to mortgage the future of Mando Land by heartlessly coverting the people's precious diamond deposits under the guise of cultivating a tobacco plantation.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kindo as heir apparent to the throne of Mando Land.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kindo as Chief of the Warriors with a passion to safeguard and to defend the cultural integrity of Mando Land.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His opposition to Whitehead and his accomplices.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kindo as foil to Maligu and Soko.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His regarding his role as chief warrior above his love relationship, demonstrating his commitment to the state, which in the end sustains the state.  (f) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Even in exile Kindo's influence felt as defender of his people's culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Comment on Aloho as a victim of circumstance in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aloho is the protagonist of the play. She is a young graduate who has migrated from her village to the city in search of a job and ends up being victimized. She eventually losses her life through child birth.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aloho is a victim. She finds herself unable to secure a job several years after graduating from the university with a decent degree in Mass Communication - Second Class Upper. it is her desperation to secure a job to take care of herself, her mother and her siblings that drives her to the city and into the hands of her exploiters.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Significantly, she is ushered into a life of vice by her university friend, Ochuole. The main predator is Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka, Minister of External Relations. His offer of a job to Aloho as a protocol officer is merely a front. He exploits her both as a drug trafficker, and, as a sexual partner, he lures the unsuspecting girl into a false sense of security. She is thus not fully aware of what she is getting into when she is getting into when she is instructed to take a package to America. She does have some misgivings but she is intimidated into acquiescence  by the Chief: \"Remember, I don't tolerate failures, but I have a way I reward hard work and success, so be careful,\" he tells her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On both fronts, she suffers. Aloho is caught while trafficking drugs and spends some time in detention. This leaves her emaciated and traumatised. When she is released she is a different person altogether, having lost faith in both man and God. As she says, \"I have gone beyond understanding Christian doctrine\"     &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the meantime, Chief has been sexually exploiting her. This resulted in pregnancy which ultimately claims her life. Throughout her life, therefore, Aloho appears to have been a victim.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aloho, however, does bear some responsibilty for her predicament. She does not listen to the sensible advice of her friend, Ogeyi, who warns her not to associate with the morally lax Ochuole, in the first place. When she is offered a job in the Ministry of External Relations, Ogeyi tries, without success, to dissuade her friend from taking up the offer. Ogeyi is also persistent in her warning to Aloho not to travel to America on an errand for the Chief, but she will not listen. Aloho also turns a deaf ear to Ogeyi's protestations when she makes up her mind to terminate the pregnancy. In the end, she loses her life.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In spite of Aloho's stubbornness, part of the responsibility for her predicament should rest on the exploiters: Chief Ade-Amaka, Ochuole and Madam Hola.    Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aloho's undergraduate's years of relationship with her friends Ogeyi and Ochuole.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aloho's desperation for a job after graduation to take care of herself andd family.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aloho's entanglement by Ochuole, who introduces her to Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka, her boss.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka's exploitation of Aloho for sex and illicit business.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aloho's arrest and imprisonment, release and pregnancy.  (f) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Aloho's attempt to abort and death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Discuss the role of Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka epitomizes the corrupt and depraved politicians who siphon the state's resources into their private overseas accounts. He symbolizes all that is evil in the society. He is heartless and corrupt. He demonstrates the penchant of African leaders for corruption. His visit to the Chief Justice after Aloho's arrest is significant in this respect. The first words of the Chief Justice, Odili, to him are, \"Chief, you seem to take too many things for granted\". This statement is an indictment on the politician's attitude towards the law, with collaboration from the likes of Chief Justice Odili. But Chief Ade-Amaka is shocked when the law will not spare him and he suddenly needs \"to see a doctor\" while in court.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Minister has thought that money opens all doors. His influence and connections do get Aloho acquitted and discharged for lack of evidence, even though she has been caught red-handed with the cocaine at the airport. However, he himself is eventually arrested and is sentenced to a jail term.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Besides his corruption, Chief Ade-Amaka is lecherous. He represents depraved \"big\" men who prey on young women and abuse them sexually in return for small favours and financial reward. He lures the vulnerable Aloho into his web and methodically inflicts physical, emotional and psychological pain on her. This treatment leaves Aloho devasted and leads to her early death.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Chief Ade-Amaka's end encapsulates the theme of corruption in the play. Corruption is evil, and those who indulge in it should not end well. The likes of Judge, Yakubu and Inspector Inaku show that it is possible not to be corrupt.    Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Chief Ade-Amaka as Minister of External Affairs.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His being an example of corruption and depravity in politicians and leaders.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His exploitation of vulnerable women for sex and illicit business.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His responsibility for Aloho's trauma and early death.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His arrest and deserved punishment, thus restoring some faith in state institutions.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "A Raising in the Sun by Lorraine Hansberry    What impression do you form of Mama's character in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mrs. Lena Younger, otherwise known as Mama, is a lion-hearted woman, a doubtful housewife and a loving and listening mother all rolled into one. To that extent she is truly a remarkable character.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama is a strong-willed widow who proves herself to be an effective matriarch of the Younger family after the death of her husband. In this regard she exercise a firm grip on her household. Like her late husband, she teaches her family to never to be subservient. She cautions Bennie when she is becoming too atheistic in her views and prevails upon Walter to recognize  the worth of Ruth, his wife. Significantly, she prevents the family from falling apart by buying a decent house for their comfort with a substantial portion of her husband's pension. She also prepares the family to brace itself for Ruth's second child rather than entertain such a morbid thought as abortion because of their economic difficulties.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As an understanding woman and dutiful housewife, Mama recalls with nostalgia, the wonderful time she spent with her late husband, its hardship notwithstanding. She ownplays his waywardness, especially with women, but extols his virtue as a loving father, teaching his children to learn to live and be on their own, \"working and working and working like somebody's old horse\" and grieving himself almost to death when she lost Claude, her little baby.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mama symbolizes the indomitable dream, the will amd the consciousness of the average coloured person to work himself/herself into the middle class and get integrated into the larger. American society by fighting racism in all its facets. This explains why she spends 35% of her husband's pension to acquire a befitting house for her family in the so-called non-coloured area of Clybourne Park in spite of the risks.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a caring, loving and listening mother, Mrs Lena Younger epitomises the universal image of motherhood. In this regard, she is very close to and profoundly shows affection to her children, her daughter-in-law and her grandson. She shares Bennie's aspirations to become a medical doctor. She relates with Ruth caringly and offers to help her with her domestic chores. Rather than give the pension money away to charity, she decides to utilise it for the welfare of the family and provide a decent place for Travis and the baby Ruth is expecting. In order to keep the peace in her home, she transfers the headship of the family to Walter - her eldest child - and entrusts to him the safe-keeping of a larger percentage of the pension money.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; surely Mama's goodness and sense of judgement are fittingly rewarded with surprise presents from her appreciative family. Her emphasis on freedom rather than money as the defining attribute of real happiness is reflected in her belief that people should \"sit down and talk to each other ... to understand the other fellow's problem\".    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Bennie's choice of Asagai to acheive the object of her quest -the return to her African roots - and Walter's living up to expectation as the family head as he derisively rejects Lindner's consdescendingly racist offers, all stand to Mama's credit as a remarkable character.    Point to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lena Younger, popularly referred to as Mama, is Walter's and Beneatha's mother and head of the family.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama is the building force in her family.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama sacrifically provides for her family and willingly gives Walter the insurance money to manage.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama loves her grandson, Travais, symbolising her love for all the family.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama has the family's comfort at heart.  (f) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama epitomises the determination of blacks to move out of the poverty-stricken and racially-segregated life to which black Americans have been consigned.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "A Raising in the Sun by Lorraine Hansberry  Consider the importance of check in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The Younger family lives in a cramped two-bedroom apartment, where they share the bathroom with neighbours over a long period of time, in a black neighbourhood.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The family is expecting a check of $10,000 from the insurance office. This check is the entitlement of their deceased father's (Mr. M. Younger) life insurance policy.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The check comes in after a very long wait and everyone in the family is happy. However, they see the check as the vessel  that will take them to higher heights.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mama, the matriarch wants to use the money to buy a house in fulfilment of the dream she shared with her late husband. She longs for a bigger accomodation that will have a little garden where her children can breathe out. Above all, she wants her family together with her son taking responsibility as the head of the family. Walter, Mama's son wants to use the check money to invest in a liquor store business with his friends in hope of great proceeds that will improve their lives. At the thought of this project, Walter suddenly becomes more confident and energised as he talks to Travis, his son, of his plans to do a transaction that will make them rich. His excitement grows as he describes his dreams of their potential house, a car, as well as Travis's future education plan.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ruth, Walter's wife, shares Mama's dream of a new accomodation with proper trimmings like abig kitchen and a bathroom where she can luxuriate in a proper bathrub without any disturbance. In addition, she wants her husband to venture into business and provide a good education for their son, Travis.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beneatha, Walter's sister and Mama's daughter, wants some of the money for her medical school tuition. She wants to be a medical doctor and to be independent and take decisions about her life.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Each member realizes that the check will bring about great changes in their lives. They long for a better life in their various dreams and only the check, well utilized, can give them that. However, the check raises a lot of conflict as a result of the diverse interests of the individual family members. It takes the firm decision of Mama to resolve the issues in their lives, but, later, they realize that it is only the check, well utilized, that can give them the unity and progress they need as a family.    Points to note:    (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The check creates suspense in the play as every character is full of individual expectation.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama's fundamental resolve is to get a new home for the family from the check.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Everyone is convinced that the check will change things for the better.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama's decision causes a rift in the family. She tactfully settles matters by giving Walter the remainder of the check to manage.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The usefulness of the check can only be seen if it is used judiciously.  (f) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mama epitomises the determination of blacks to move out of the poverty-stricken and racially-segregated life to which the black Americans have been consigned.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Examine the use of dramatic irony in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The major device that sustains the tempo of the play is dramatic irony. Dramatic irony occurs when characters in the play are unaware of the consequences/significance of their actions in the scheme of things, though the audience is.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Young Marlow and Hastlings, men of the world, are easily led by the joke of Tony into believing that they are in an inn when, in fact, they are in the house of the Hardcastles. Under this ironical impression, they consider Mr. Hardcastle as an inn keeper, his daughter a barmaid.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The two are deceived about Kate. Thinking that they are, indeed, in an inn, the object of their visit, Kate, falls to the level of a mere maid at the inn and she is made to tolerate abuse, to the amusement of the audience. Hastings and Miss Nevile's elopement plan hinges on her jewels. Tony steals these jewels for Hastings who hands them over to Marlow for safekeeping. Seeing that he has no safe place, he, in turn, hands the jewels over to Mrs. Hardcastle who has been looking for the lost gems. This is ironical, as,unknown to Marlow, he has just foiled Hastings' plans and rescued Mrs. Hardcastle from the trouble of losing Miss Neville's jewels.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tony is at his pranks again when he rides Mrs. Hardcastle round about the vicinity, pretending to be heading for Aunt Pedigree's place. He dumps his mother in a bog and frightens her that robbers are in the area. The fact, however, as the audience is aware, is that they are not far from the Hardcastle home and there is no gang of thieves.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Such use of dramatic irony creates amusing moments in the play.    Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dramatic irony occurs where characters in the play are unaware of the consequences/significance of their actions in the scheme of things, but the audience is.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The expectation on the part of Marlow and Hardcastings that they are in an inn when, in fact, they are in the Hardcastle home.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The deception on Marlow that Kate is a barmaid when, in fact, she is daughter to Mr. Hardcastle and his (Marlow's) future fiancee.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The entrusting of the jewels in care of Marlow who presents it to Mrs. Hardcastle.  (e) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Mrs. Hardcastle's believing that she is among a gang of thieves when in fact she has not moved far from home.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Assess the Character of Mrs Hardcastle", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Mrs. Hardcastle is the wife of Mr. Hardcastle and mother of Kate and Tony - the latter a previous marriage. She is a woman overwhelmed by pride, and love for fashion.    She is over protective of Tony, whom she cares about but fails to tell his true age for reasons personal to her. It is her poor upbringing of Tony that contributes to his sense of mischief. Mr Hardcastle refers to them both as \"a pair that only spoil each other\".    Mrs. Hardcastle stands in contrast with her husband (Mr. Hardcastle). She often disagrees with her husband over issues. For instance, they cannot agree on the cirtues and vices of city life. She complains that Mr. Hardcastle does not take the family to the city now and then \"to rub off the rust a little\". They also differ in their attitude towards Tony's behaviour.    Mrs. Hardcastle is corrupt and selfish. Her plan to match Tony and Miss Constance Neville is motivated by a selfish desire to keep Constance's jewels in the family. To ensure that she achieves her goal, she does everything possible to frustrate Hastings and Constance's relationship. When she gets the hint of the elopement plan, she quickly arranges to take Miss Neville off to Aunt Pedigree, some forty miles away.    Mrs. Hardcastle appears simple-minded in the way she falls victims to Tony's tricks quite often. Tony, for instance rides her round and round the house and she ends up in a horse-pond. She foolishly believes that she is forty miles away from home when she is just forty yards away from her door. She also mistakes her husband for a highway man on this same occasion.    She symbolizes greed and materialism and ends up as the only character who remains unhappy at the end of the play.    Points to note:  (a) Mrs. Hardcastle as wife and mother of Kate Hardcastle and Tony Lumpkin the latter by a previous marriage.  (b) Her relationship with Tony whom she dotes on and allows to go wayward.  (c) Her love of Toppery and her determination to live like Mrs. Grigsby and others.  (d) Her incessant quarrels with Mr. Hardcastle who would rather tell tales about his past military exploits than pay attention to her nagging about city life and material wealth.  (e) Her greed which drives her to keep Constance's jewels for Tony whom she would have Constance married to.  (f) Her being easily fooled and made a laughing-stock of by Tony as she falls to his pranks.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the clash of cultures in Okara's \"Piano and Drums\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Considering their essentially perculiar features,  the two cultures referred to in the poem seem to be strange bedfellows.    On the one hand, there is the authentic, indigenous African culture characterized by a certain simplicity in its rural setting. This is the culture with which the poet is familiar and thus captures with nostalgia. It is the culture identified with simple unsophisticated music as portrayed by its \"jungle drums\". Its rustic and idyllic setting is also vividly captured by the images of the riverside and the animal kingdom such as the \"panther ready to pounce\" and \"the leopard snarling about to leap\". The images extend to those of the pastoral world, such as the hunters that \"crouch with spears poised\" and the \"green leaves and wild flowers\" along simple paths made by \"hurrying feet and grouping hearts\".    On the other hand, there is the new and alien culture. This is identified with an entirely strange musical expression - \"a wailing piano\" with complex and complicated tunes, speaking of a new dispensation with its strange and mechanically sophisticated musical register of \"tear-furrowed concerto coaxing diminuendo\" and \"crescendo\" etcetera.    Trapped between these two diametrically opposed cultures, the poet is confused and in a state of dilemma. This is because the two cultures are patently incompatible.    There is no doubt, however, that given the contrast between the warmth, vigour and dynamism of the traditional culture, and the coldness, 'heartlessness' and distance of the new culture, he will gravitate towards the former.    Points to note:  (a) The diametrically opposed cultures symbolised by the piano and the drum.  (b) The distinct elements of the two cultures - African and Western as described by their music.  (c) The distinct effects produced by the music of these two cultures, i.e. the evocation of the Vigour and pastoral simplicity of African culture vis-a-vis the cold, heartless and mentalistic culture of the west.  (d) The confused state of the personaa and his inclination to go for the warmth of African music and culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the persona's view of ageing in a \"The Panic of Growing Older\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  \"The Panic of Growing Older\" highlights the different stages in man's life. The persona refers to the ageing process as inevitable and bound by time.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The fear of ageing dominates man's psyche through all the stages of life. Our ageing is manifested in our progressive loss of physical strength and our suceptibility to illness, some of which defty diagnoses.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  After age thirty, there seems to be nothing left to hope. References to \"legs cribbed\", \"no swiden leaps\", \"copyback bisected\" suggest this interpretation. Only \"failure\" stares us in the face as we realize that the things we used to do, we can no longer do, in spite of science offering hope of longer life. Disillusionment now sets in:    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"Inner satisfaction  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; dwindles in sharp  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; blades of expectation\"    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the end, we resign ourselves to a passive rather than an active life.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  This family is captured in the line, \"From now on the world has you\".    Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The inevitablity of ageing  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The ageing process, beginning with childhood \"fluttering wings\" and ending in death.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Our initial hopes and expectations as we grow up and the panic of aborted dreams, followed by terminal illness.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our succumbing to fate/death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the poet's attitude in Frost's \"Birches\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The poet's attitude to nature in \"Birches\" is fascinating. There is nature in the form of snow and ice - the elements, and there are the birches which in winter, are bent, covered by the ice-storms. They click and crack, but as soon as winter is over, the ice melts and the bent birches steady themselves once more, even though as never before.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The poet sees nature at work here, for though the ice-storms completely crush the birches, they rise again, which celebrates their resilience. On a light-hearted note then, nature in the form of the birches is a source of play. The poet recalls his childhood when he swung birches because of their resilience which enabled them to toss him up and down in great but frantic delight.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  But there is another attitude to nature which is more serious, for it is life sustaining. The poet refers to times that he is buffeted by all sorts of troubles and \"life is too much like a pathless wood and when your face burns and tickles with cobwebs\", which reminds him of the experience of the birches in nature. It is their ability to bend under the ice and come up again which he fondly recalls as he swung them as a school boy. That's the attitude to life he wishes to have - the never giving up attitude as he points out in the last line \"That could be good both going and coming back\".    Points to note:  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The categorisation of nature in the form of the elements - ice-snow storms and the birches.  (b) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The beauty and the havoc wrecked by the elements on the birches and their ability to bounce back.  (c) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The poet's attitude to nature/birches as a source of childhood play.  (d) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His more serious attitude to the birches as life sustaining in times of trouble.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2016>PAPER 3>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the theme of beauty in the poem \"Shall I compare thee to a Summer Day?\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This sonnet celebrates the inestimable beauty of a lover.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  To depict this rare beauty, the poet evokes images of summer in all its splendour in the first three quartains.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  First, although the poet views and admires summer for being lovely and temperate, he strongly believes that summer's beauty can in no way be compared to his lover's beauty. This is because while summer's \"lease\" is short-lived, the persona's lover's beauty is not time bound.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Then, although summer's weather can be both unstable and unpredictable since it is sometimes too hot and sometimes overcast, his lover's beauty will ever remain untainted and serene.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  And then, to the poet, the lover's beauty is not only unparalled; it is also eternal. Death itself can never boast of obliterating her beauty, for her beauty lives in the very poetry that celebrates her.    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The persona's celebration of his lover's beauty is given the strongest expression in the concluding couplet which underlines his unwavering conviction that as generations of  people read this poem, her immortality is assured.    Points to note  (a) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Knowledge of the sonnet form and how and it expresses aspects of his lover's beauty.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (i) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The contrast with summer's temperature but shortlived nature.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  (ii) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The comparison with summer's unsteady heat which sometimes keeps its gold complexion dimmed.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  (iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The supremacy of his lover's beauty, being immortal i.e. immortalised by the poem.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  (iv) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  The generations of humanity who read the poem and keep her beauty alive.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN DRAMA  DELE CHARLEY: The Blood of a Stranger    What do you learn about the culture of Mando land in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The land of Mando is depicted as a community which regards and supports peace. The people of Mando believe so much in their culture. However, their culture undergoes a change and an external challenge. The arrival of the white man, whitehead, poses no little threat to the serenity and culture of the people. The threat to the people of Mando surrounding the entry of Mando into their land cost them; as has earlier been stated by Kindo.    The priesthood is as sacred by Wara, she not giving into Kindo's idea of desecrating the shine because she does not want the spirits to be displeased. Though Maligu also desires the idea of offending the spirits, he is not driven by sincere desire to speak the truth, he is only capitalizing on the people's culture to make robust his pocket. He also advises Kindo not to challenge the virgin sacrifice. Kindo advises king Santigi Mando V, who does not listen to him as a result of the influence of gin and strange tobacco.     Before the coming of Whitehead, the white man the people of Mando used to be diligent, they used to follow the principle of decency but after his entry, they become lazy and morally loose. This is what infuriates Kindo when he says the men are \"singing, dancing and drinking\" he also says the women are giving themselves to men everywhere\" and \"running about naked like children.\" This shows how much the white man cuses havoc to the people 's moral, religious and ethical values. It signifies how Africans neglecting their culture and embracing that of the whites can do much harm to themselves and even their children generations.     The culture of the inhabitant of Mando land also places much worth on human life. The punishment for murder during a period of peace is banishment. Another interference of Whitehead with the people's culture is his suggestion of a goat being killed in the stead of a virgin, this however, as Soko admits to Wara, is strange to Soko the chief priest.    Male Chauvinism is also prevalent in the land of Mando. Women have privilege of priesthood. They are not given major rulership posts. This is the reason for Soko, the chief priest's anxiety about who is taking over from him because he has no son.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN DRAMA  DELE CHARLEY: The Blood of a Stranger  Examine Wara's role in the development of the plot", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Wara is the central female character in the play when Kindo makes an attempt to drag her into the sacred cave to have sex with her but she resists the attempt. This act of resistance is what saved her and Kindo from being caught together in the sacred cave. Soko the chief priests will charge them with sacrilege.     Wara gains the interest of men because she is attractive. Though Wara is Kindo's girlfriend, he is vulnerable to the evil intentions of Maligu and also Soko in their intention to at Kindo. She is abducted by Maligus, Parker and Soko and Whitehead attempts raping her after lusting after her. She resists the temptation and escapes, later aided by Soko. This act of resistance prevents an indisputable confrontation between Kindo and Whitehead.     Wara is targeted by Maligu and Soko to be sacrifice being supposed to be a strong, and a virgin. These claims are later rendered wrong by both Wara and Kindo. Wara in the end, discloses to Kindo that she is a stranger in Mando land. Kindo also states that Wara  is no virgin and that it was Parker's body on the sacrificial stone, not Wara's.     Thus, Wara serves as a source of conflict, both religiously; between Maligu, Parker, and Soko and Kindo being abducted and intended to be used as a sacrifice and socially between Whitehead who attempts raping her and frustrating her relationship with Kindo and Windo. This drives Kindo to kill Whitehead.    Wara being a bone of contention in the play whose character helps in driving the plot forward.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE:  Harvest of Corruption    Justify the title of the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The title, \"Harvest of Corruption\", perfectly suits the play because it puts forth some corrupt personalities and their end punishment. The theme of corruption is central to chief Halada Ade-Amaka. He collaborates with some other characters to carry out corrupt acts. He involves in financial figure falsification, exploitation of girls and approval of bills for unpurchased capital items. He carries out these acts of corruption in support of character such as the commissioner of police, Justice Odili, Madam Hoha, Ochuole and some agents. This means chief Haladu Ade-Amaka has the support of law agents; the commissioner of police and Justice Odili. This means corruption can even catch hold on those who should be haters of it.     Chief Ade-Amaka goes to the extent of taking advantage of naive girls by having sex with them and luring them into cocaine business. Aloho is a victim of these as she is lured into the chief's sexual desires and cocaine business. The commissioner of police ensures that Chief Halahu Ade-Amaka's evils are not found out, he also compels officer below his rank to remain silent about the chief's evils. He employs boys to technical areas to ascertain the chiefs safety. Justice Odili too makes sure criminals who are linked to the chief are exonerted and liberated, this is seen when Aloho is vindicated and set free despite being caught with the cocaine. These law agents are greased in the palm with dividends from the chief.     The proprietress of Akpata Hotel, Madam Hoha is no exception in the group of the corrupt. She aids the recruit of girls to chief's corrupt business. Through her, chief Haladu Ade-Amaka gets to defile and recruit Aloho. She says she will get on well with chief's business provided he provides her with money.     In the end, corruption proves to be a seed which when planted, grows up gradually until mature, and then bears bitter fruits of punishment. All the corrupt personalities are duely punished. Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka who seems to be invisible and safe is later found out, alongside his co-workers. He is sentenced to twenty-five years imprisonment with hard labour. His defenders, the commissioner of police and justice Odili are both to serve twenty years imprisonment. Madam Hoha the \"supplier\" is sentenced to ten years imprisonment. Ochuole, the agent of Chief both in and outside the office is also sentenced to ten years imprisonment. Ayo the boy who releases official documents for a sum is sentenced to five years imprisonment while Aloho pays with her life.     The play, therefore is rightly titled the \"Harvest of Corruption\" as those who plant the seed of corruption in the play harvest the fruit of punishment.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE:  Harvest of Corruption  Assess the character of Ogeyi in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ogeji is portrayed as a modest and good-mannered girl. She is fair-complexioned and of average height. She has three permanent tribl mark on each side of her face. As a graduate of University of Azuka where she studied Business Administration, she works as a receptionist in ABC Company. Ogeyi is religious, she belong to the christian faith. She is fond of reading Christian books and the Holy Bible. She also sings moral-teaching songs.     Ogeyi displays her generousity by accomodating Aloho, her friend. While Aloho applies for a job, she needs an abode, Ogeyi welcomes her to home, feeds her and even occassionally shares her dress with her. Ogeyi also tries to help Aloho's spiritual life, she preaches to her frequently and admonishes her not to accept the ungodly offer from Ochuole and chief.     Tolerance is also a quality in the character of Ogeyi. This is revealed by her temperance with Aloho who accuses her of being envious of her \"good fortuning\" of being employed as a protocol officer with a satisfactory pay, after (Ogeyi) advising her against the offer from Ochuole, Ogeyi does not get upset by Aloho's deed but continues to accommodate her.     Ogeyi also serves as a source of encouragement and admonition to Aloho when She gets pregnant. She advises Aloho to give birth to the baby and not to abort it. She is also helpful by siving Aloho support during her travails, and helps her to return to her family and deliver her baby.     Boldness and justice are also qualities of Ogeyi. She displays these by voluntarily taking on a task of righting societal wrongs. She exposes chief Haladu Ade-Amaka's acts of corruption. She provides the police with cogent information about Chief's encounter with loho which results in her death. She seeks redress in the court of law as a prosecution withness against Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka. Through her, corruption is arrested and it key agent punished.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE:  Harvest of Corruption  Examine the Youngers as a close-knit family.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Unity is the blinding force which keeps the Youngers close-knit. Mama plays an essentail role in making sure the family is united by playing the dual role of wife and mother in the family. Love is an integral feature of the shared among member memebers of the family. Someone lends the other a helping hand in one way or the other. Ruth for example, ensures that the family wakes up early to bath in the bathroom before others in the neighbourhood overcome it.     Walter shows love and concern to Travis, gladdening his heart by giving him fifty cents for school. Ruth is implored by Walter, her husband to convince Mama that his demand for a portion of the insurance money to set up a liquor store is essentail in keeping the family united. Mama shows motherly love to Ruth which makes Ruth feel like Mama also cares for travels making sure he has hot cats rather than cold cereal for breakfast. Mama also shows love to Beneatha, insisting that she put on a rope in the cold morning.     Mama allocates the ten thousand dollar insurance to members of the family. The joy of the articipated cheque is first shared with Ruth. The cheque also aids Beneatha's medical school attendance and Walter's yearning to establish a bigger house at Clybourne Park which is bought with the cheque. Though the residence ownership of the Youngers threatened by Mr. Karl Linder's offer to buy their house, they unitedly fight back against his plots.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE:  Harvest of Corruption  How are Mama, Ruth and Beneatha portrayed in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Mrs Younger Mama is a character who is loving and caring. She has a belief that men should be in control, she frequently tells of her husband and her submissiveness to him. The mantle of power in the family is passed to her after her husband dies, thus she becomes the family matriach. Walter Jr is lax with his responsibility as the next family need after his father's death, to the disappointment of Mama. When the arrives, mama takes the decision on what to do with it first: She buys a house at Clybourne Park, though to the disapproval of Walter. Mama uses the cheque to enhance the dreams of her children, and being selfless, she also uses the cheque to take care of Ruth and Travis. Mama shows that she is caring and selfless by offering to help Ruth iron. Mama trusts Walter with the remaining money and encourages him to awake to his responsibility.     Ruth, the wife of Walter believes in the existence of God. She is displeased with Beneatha's heresy about God. She does her best to keep the family united. She corrects Beneatha for her childishness after Mama has corrected her (Beneatha) about her heretical statement about God. She then goes to meet mama and tells her \"she said she was sorry\". Ruth does challenge her husband's will. But for mama's intervention, Ruth is resolved to aborting her pregnancy in disobedience to her husband. She also disobeys her husband by scrambling the eggs which he prefers as \"not scrambled\".     Beneatha does not follow the belief that the African American woman who is not expected to have aspirations to professions reserved for men. She dreams of being educated and becoming a doctor. She rejects being intimidated by men, for example when George tells her to drop the Garbo routine because he does not want to listen to her thoughts. She then says a then why read books, why go to school \"she is shocked by his reply; \"you need books... to get grades ... to pass the course .... to get a degree. That's all ... it has nothing to do with thought.\" This does not get down well with Beneatha who concludes that George is a fool and will not waste her time with  fool-Beneatha does not not respect Waalter when he stakes the rest of the insurance money on a deal that does wrong. She rather calls him a \"toothless rat\" and that in him, she sees \"the final triump of stupidity in the world. However, when Walter wakes up to his responsibility Linder's offer to buy the house, Beneatha calls him a \"man\". She no longer address him as \"not a man\" or a \"toothless rat, but a \"man\". Thus, Beneatha is a character who does not respect people when they are wrong but speaks against their wrong, but she also supports and praises them when they change for the better.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLDSMITH:  The Stroops to Conquer    Compare the relationship between Tony and Constance with that between Young Marlow and Kate", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony Lumpkin is Mrs. Hardcastle's son for her former husband. Constance Neville stays with her aunt and, Mrs. hardcastle and she is a cousine to Tony. Constance and Tony are courted by Mrs. Hardcastle who is driven by selfishness and greed to retain Constance's jewels in the family. This matching is to be a mis-match as Tony and Constance have a affection for each other. Tony prefers marrying \"Big Betty Bouncer\" while Contance Neville chooses Hastings. Constance confirms her love for Hastings and not for Tony when she says Mrs. Hardcastle \"suppose that I am in love with her son (Tony) and she never once dreams that my affections are fixed on another man (Hastings). She also says Tony \"I'm sure would wish to see me married to anybody but himself.\" It is thus obvious that there is no love lost between Tony and Constance.     Kate (also called Miss Hardcastle) is the daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Hardcastle. She is attracted to young Marlow. Her father, Mr. Hardcastle is decisive in her attraction to him, he calls Marlow \"... the gentleman I have chosen to be your husband.\" This he does preparing kate for the arrival of Young Marlow from town. Young Marlow also has affections for kate but he is too timid and cowardly to reveal this to her, regarding her as a high-classlady. kate realises Marlow's timidity and promises to \"cure him of his timidity\" This is what makes her to feign the root of a maid, she brings herself down to Marlaw's convenience. By this, Marlows gets free with kate and their relationship gets on well. Thus \"she sloops to conquer.\"    The relationship between Tony and Constance is unfounded and lacking the basic principle of love. It is rather built on the foundation of greed, machination and materialism, thus it collapses. On the other hand, the relationship between Young Marlow and kate is built on solid foundation of love, pure affection and attraction thus it stands.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER GOLDSMITH:  The Stroops to Conquer  How does Mr. Hardcastle feel towards his stepson?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony is Mr. Hardcastle's spoilt, over-pampered stepson. He is Mrs. Hardcastle's son from her former husband. He is not properly trained but spoilt by Mrs. Hardcastle. Due to his mild nature, Mr. Hardcastle does not find it difficult to cope with Tony Lumpkin's cunning and trickish character. He (Mr. Hardcatle) blames his (Tony's) mother for his (Tony's bad character, he says she is the cause of it.     Mr. Hardcastle bears no grudge against Tony, though he detests his bad character, he says Tony's learning is 'a mere composition of trick and mischief. He is not infuriated by the way Mrs. Hardcastle, his wife defends Tony's trick as 'humous'. Mr. Hardcastle, thus, has a clear mind towards Tony and bears no ill against him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "SECTION C  AFRICAN POETRY     Relate the title of the poem \"Ambush\" to the theme of frustrated dreams", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ambush is the act of hiding and secretly awaiting somebody and then attacking them suddenly. The room presents a group of people who are trapped in the valley of hopelessness and helplessness, having their dreams frustrated.     The fishermen whose dream is to catch a good number of fish and sell to have a living have their hook, line bait and sinker all swallowed up by the giant whale; living them hopeless and helpless. The fishermen are left with nothing with which to fish;\" All Peter with petered out desires' their hopes of profiting are frustrated. This symbolises people who are deprived of their means of living, this may come as lack of employment opportunities. They have big dreams but the necessities for achieving them are taken away.     These people are not only trapped in the sea, they are also trapped on the land by the \"Sabre-toothed tiger.\" They are deprived of their freedom of movement because of the danger of the 'tiger's teeth. They wish to go about on a daily basis, in pursuit of their dreams but are restricted by a danger, thus 'the grizzled one snatche their guts.\"    In the air is the 'giant-hawk', courting unceasing disaster/as it hoots and hovers in space.' Like the hawk, a predator, flies around in the sky, looking for a prey such as chicks, lizards, worms etc. making the chicks who have dreams to go about in search of food restricted to a place of safety, so does the land keep the people in a restricted confinement.     The three habitats are traps bluring the people's dreams of pursuing and realizing their goals. The air is the 'giant hawk', in the water is the 'giant whale', and on the land is the 'sabre-toothed tiger.' The people are in danger but there is no safe route of escape to a place where they can achieve their dreams.     The people are ambushed and their dreams frustrated.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "SECTION C  AFRICAN POETRY   Discuss the use of symbolism in Okara's \"Piano and Drums\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The peom presents a conflict between the African culture and the Western culture symbolically. The 'jungle drums' and 'the panther ready to pounce syms to darkness of African culture. The 'jungle drumsy the rustic and idyllic setting of Africa, with it unsophisticated music. The darkness of the 'panther's complexion relates to darkness of Africa's skin. The hunters that \"crunch with spears poised\" and the simple paths made by \"hurrying feet and groping hearts\" both symbolize the pastoral world, bringing to memory the typical rustic village life in Africa.     The Western culture is represented with a 'wailing piano', symbolizing the complexity, strangeness and sophistication of the new culture. This 'wailing piano' is said to create \"tear-furrowed concerts, counter-point, coaxing diminuendo and Crescendo.\" This piano is said to constitute a mundane and cacophonous sound. This symbolizes the difficulty of the African to imbibe the culture of the whites.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "SECTION D  NON-AFRICAN POETRY     Comment on the use of pun in Herbert's \"The Pulley\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The poem employs the use of pun (i.e play upon words) between God and His creature. The use of pun is seen in the process of the creature being blessed and God restricting a blessing from Him. The word 'rest' which is repeated in the peom is played upon.     In the second stanza, we see 'rest' used in the clause \"rest in the bottom lay.\"    This may mean that 'rest' is at the bottom of the glass of blessings, it could also mean the rest of the blessing (i.e 'rest) remains at the bottom. The word 'rest' is also where it is a noun, it is used as a verb to mean 'rely' in Nature.    In the fourth stanza, we observe the word 'rest' used in the line \"let him keep the rest.\" This does not mean 'comfort' or 'convenience,' the creature is not given 'rest' rather it means 'the remaining.' It means man sould retain the remaining blessings which are strength, 'beauty', 'wisdon,' 'honour' and 'pleasure but without the blessing of rest' (i.e comfort). In the next line is 'But keep them with repinning restlessness.' This ma should keep the rest (remaining) of the blessing without rest (comfort/peace).     The word 'rest' is played upon throughout the poem. It is both as a noun and as a verb to mean things. As a verb, it is used to mean \"rely\" - 'rest in Nature\". As a noun, it is used to mean 'comfort/peace' and in the second stanza \"Rest in the bottom lay\", hower, the 'restlessness' in the fourth stanza - \"But keep them with repining restlessness' without rest'. As a noun, it is also used to mean 'remaining blessing lay at the bottom of the glass. It is also used in the fourth stanza in - \"Let him keep the rest\" i.e Let him keep the remaining (blessings)' fourth stanza in - \"let him keep the rest\" i.e \"let him keep the remaining (blessings)'     As a matter of fact, the reader of the poem's ability to understand the various usage of the word 'rest' has great importance on his ability to comprehend the poem.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>DRAMA AND POETRY>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "SECTION D  NON-AFRICAN POETRY   Examine the theme of endurance in \"Birches\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The resilence of birches is used to illustrate endurance in the peom. Birches are trees that survive in temperate regions. In the peom, the tree is described as being bent, both by nature and by man. The tree are bent naturally by snow and ice-storms and by a boy swinging on them. The birches endure the inconvinience and famages of then snow until the sun comes out in summer and its heat mealts away the snow, enabling their growth again.     The birhes are bent into archs by the boy swinging on them, they 'endure' and do not break. Even after the damage nature (through snow and ice-storms) and man do to them, they endeavour to rise again and grow, though 'years afterwrds.'     Endurance is learnt from the birches' resilience, in temperate regions, being bent into arcs by swinging of a boy, suffering damages from snow and ice-storms awaiting the sun to melt them away, and growing-up again after being damaged. The peom teaches humans to endure all their inconvenience situations until there solutions to them appear and also learn to rise from their past failures into a prominence just like the birches endure the damages done to them by both man and nature until the sun comes, melts the ice and snow away and then they grow again.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN PROSE  AMMA DARKO: Faceless    Examine the significance of Fofo's visit to Odarley in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The significance of Fofo visit to Odarley   Fofo is a friend to Odarley and with both are street sisters. They are neglected children who live in slums and earn a living through fair and foul means around the Agbobloshe market. Prison had earlier tried to rape Fofo before she escaped to Odarley's Shack.   The mysery of street children is described during Fofo's visit. The children have no one to care for them, no precise source of income, safe abode, or even food. It is observed that the children live hopelessly and helplessly with little assurance of a better future. They were constantly vulnerable to rape and indiscriminate sex by perverse men, not excluding poison.    Odarley's shack is described as being in a very unpleasant condition, thus, providing only a little more protection. The room is described as lacking proper ventilation and jam-packed with children of both genders, nude and fast asleep.    This illustrates the poorly and destitution which children who are compelled to fend for themselves face. The children are used to sexual perversion as they watch constantly practice pornography, Odarley, for example has had several sexual encounters with the shoeshine boy. The children also live highly unhygienic life.    Fofo's visit to Odarley also reveals the street children's vulnerability to being robbed. This is seen when the duo are easing themselves at a waste dump in the vicinity. In the process of easing themselves, a street bully named Macho attacks them and lays hands on Fofo's plastic bag containing all the money she made the previous week. This area is seen as an area where government is not by political power but by physical power; a place where only the fit survive", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN PROSE  AMMA DARKO: Faceless  Consider Baby 'T' as a victim of social injustice", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Baby 'T' is the sister of the protagonist in the play and is an evidence of the theme of the play, 'Faceless'. She is Maa Tsuru and Kwei's first daughter and third child.     Baby 'T's character reveals the degree of social injustice which neglected children may undergo and their alarming need for good societal responsibility.   As a child yet Baby 'T' suffers social stigmatization in allegations that she was accused. She grows up without even discovering herself, nor developing a standard of relationship with her environment, she is indeed faceless without an identity and her name testifies to that.     Baby 'T' suffers sexual abuse by several men of lawlessness. First, her irresponsible father, Kwei deserts her, her mother and her simblings, paving the way for another perverse man, Nii Kpakpo. Nii Kpakpo severally abuses Baby 'T' sexually, disabilizing her psycologically, mentally and physically. A Mr - do - good uncle who lives in the neighbourhood also abusing her sexually. Poison, the street attempted to rape her.   baby 'T' did not only suffer parental neglection and sexual abuse, she also suffers harrassment and bullying from Macho a street bully and a petty criminal who harasses her and forcibly get away with her bag of money. All these happen and the community watches on, not sanction Kwei the run-away husband nor even bothered on discovery of her badly mutilated carcass when discovered behind the Kiosk in Agbobloshie market. Baby 'T' suffers social injustice from cradle to the grave.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN PROSE  AMMA DARKO: Faceless  How is Ajumobi portrayed in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ajumbi is Yaremi deceased husband. He is portrayed as a successful hunter, an adorable husband, an ambitious farmer and a sociable man. Ajumobi show that he is capable of being a husband by neglecting and disappointing claims that as a hunter, he will have a child that looks like an animal, aimed at discouraging their wedding.     Ajumobi is a capable husband and father who is capable of ruling his house. Yaremi described him as \"the mighty baobab, king of the Savannah, towering above ten husband lesser trees around\" She also says he takes care of his children.     Though deceased, Ajumobi still lives in Yaremi's heart, as Yaremi is outspoken of her love for him, she also claims he appears to her in the dream. As a hunter, Ajumobi brings home different games for Yaremi his wife including impala, antelope and buffalo, making Yaremi able to distinguish the taste of games, relating them to different tasks of \"Sagarcane, coconut, ripe banana and honey.\"     Since Ajumobi is sociable, he does not find it difficult to relate with his friends. They give to the beat of Sakara music, sporadically release fickle slogans and drink palm wine together.     Being versatile, Ajumobi also involves in part-time farming, he had plantations of cocoa, banana, kolanut, palm and cassava, he also has a garden in his backyard. During his youth, he is said to have completed with Deyo his brother who was strong enough to make eight hundred heaps in a day.     During the cap-picking ceremoney, Yaremi refuses to pick a cap which would mean that she would remarry if she does. This is due to her mindset dwelling in the innermost part of her heart, sweeping her off her feet.\"", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A  AFRICAN PROSE  AMMA DARKO: Faceless  Comment on the attitude of the people of Kufi towards superstition", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The people of Kufi believe in superstitions. Though many of their believes are unfounded and lacking cogent evidences, the people of Kufi believe their beliefs are traditional and hence, should be strictly practised. One of these superstitions is that death seldom comes naturally and so, if any married man dies, his wife will be made to undergo certain strict, strenous  and humilating practices to prove her innocence of his death. For example, the corpse of her deseased husband in a dark room and to confess sins she is innocent of. Yaremi and Radeke also undergo social stigmatization and wrong accusations about the reasons behind their husbands' deaths.     The people of Kufi also hold that natural objects and creatures can pass massages to humans. For example, Yaremi claims the shooting star seen zooming across the empty sky and the bird which sings a mournful song proofs that Ajumobi has been accepted by His Creator.     Another superstitions belief strongly held by the people of Kufi is the concept of reincarnation. Yaremi believes she will meet her husband again someday, the news of Ajumobi's appearance at Oyedeji strengthened this belief. Another belief held by the people of Kufi is that the refusal of a mature woman to marry and of a widow to re-marry is an indication of rebellion to authority of the men. This is seen when the men in Kufi keep pressurizing Yaremi to remarry with a suggested sanction of abanishment if she refuses.    It is also commonly held in Kufi that specific animal can be used to do evil. For instance, the hawk seen perching on Ajumobi's roof shortly before his death is linked with his death.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B  NON-AFRICAN PROSE  RICHARD WRIGHT:  Native Son    Examine Mrs. Dalton's blindness as a metaphor for race relationship in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The blindness of Mary Dalton's mother is what Bigger capitalizes on to cover Mary Dalton's mouth and in the process, suffocates her to death.     Mary Dalton's mother symbolizes the whites, their way of life and beliefs while Bigger symbolizes the blacks, their way of life and belief.    The whites are racist; they have a sense of superiority over the blacks, they treat them as slaves and generally make life difficult for them thus, blind to their needs, desires and reality. Just as Mary Dalton's mother's blindness makes Bigger kill Mary, so the racism of the whites leads the blacks into different attrocities and social vices just to survive.    Bigger, the murderer represents the blacks who fall victim of the inhuman treatment by the whites. The whites make life so difficult for them by giving them little employment opportunities, mean social importance and no access to self discovery. They are rather interested in making them subjects and workers for mean wages. These helpless blacks who have had their destinies architectured by the whites resort to criminal acts. Examples are Bigger, Gus, Jack and G.H who resort to robbery.    The blacks also have a low esteam of themselves. They see themselves as less important and inferior to the whites.    Mary Dalton's mother's blindness, thus, metaphorically represents the master - servant relationship between the whites and the blacks. The blacks therefore are left in a three-fold plight of fears, flight and fate.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B  NON-AFRICAN PROSE  RICHARD WRIGHT:  Native Son  Comment on the use of irony in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Irony can be seen on several occations in the play. An instance is Bigger's feigning boldness about the idea of robbing the white man.   He pretends to be bold enough to carry out the task and even makes mockery of Gus' cowardness, though he later finds his way of the plan, his daughter.  The apparent calmness Mr. Dalton during the ignorance of Mary Dalton whereabouts in contrast toMr. Britten's shows nervousness is also ironical. Another instance of irony is when Mr. Dalton apologizes to Bigger for being rough-handled by Mr. Britten, unknown to him that Bigger himself is the murder.     Irony is also used when Mr. Dalton protects Bigger from being interrogated by the press, unknown to him that he is defending a criminal.    Also, that Mrs. Dalton is the one who finds out that Mary has never gone out without a note bearing the information of her whereabouts. This observation is what arouses the need for investigation.    That Bigger is accused of, charged with and punished for an offence (murder) which he accidentally committed and not for the offence of killing his girlfriend, Bessie, which he intentionally commits is ironical.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "HORACE WALPOLE:  The Castle of Otranto     Justify the view that the novel presents a struggle between good and evil", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There is a struggle between the forces of good and evil in the novel. Majorly, the plot of the novel centres on the fulfilment of a prophecy of old which states that Ortranto \"should pass from the present family, wherever the real owner should be grown to large to inhabit it\" and the bid of Manfred to hinder it.     For fears of losing the kingdom, Manfred prepares a marriage between his only son, Conrad and Isabella, who is in the lineage of the true heirs. This is a bid to unite the lineage of the true heirs in order to strengthen his feet on the stage of power. Providence, however, intervenes in this affair and a large rock descends from heaven and crushes Conrad to death, aborting Manfred's evil plan.     Manfred, the figure of evil in the novel makes a series of attempts to secure the throne illegitimately, not being legitimate heir to the throne. However, divine providence always hinders his evil plots.     After the death of Conrad, Manfred's only son, Manfred makes a move to marry Isabella himself. This evil plan is also aborted by supernatural intervention as the Mantred's grandfather's portrait hanging in the room makes a \"deep sign\" and leaves its frame. This occurence symbolized Manfred's evil plot and creates a mode of escape for Isabella. Isabella escapes and she is helped by Theodore and Friar Jerome.     Fredrick, the rightful heir to the throne and father of Isabella who is believed to be dead eventually shows up, making the struggle between good and evil heighten. This appearance surely poses a threat to Manfred's rulership, prompting him (Manfred) to cunningly devise another method of uniting with the rightful heir. He demands an agreement with Fredrick to exchange the hands of their daughter in marriage.     The supernatural again intervenes, as a mysterious figure appears commanding Fredrick to forget Matilda, manfred's daughter. This makes Fredrick readiness to marry Matilda diminish. Driven by jealousy, Manfred ironically kills Matilda his daughter, thinking it is Isabella and he is left to repent.    Though the struggle between good and evil last a while, yet, expectedly, good overcomes.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2017>PROSE>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "HORACE WALPOLE:  The Castle of Otranto   To what extent can we say that Manfred's downfall is caused by his lust for power?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Manfred's lust for power is the major theme in the novel. He attempts to hinder the fulfilment of the ancient prophecy that \"the castle and lordship of Otranto should pass from the present family whenever the real owner should be grown too large to inhabit it.\"     Lust for power is demonstrated by Manfred in that he does not want the rightful heir of Otranto to take of the power, rather he wants to keep ruling, despite the illegitimacy of his rulership. To maintain his rulership, Manfred devises several tactics to satisfy his lust.    Manfred intends to unite with the lineage of rightful heirs and so makes arrangement for marriage between his son, Comrad and Isabella who was in the lineage of the rightful heirs. His lust for power also made him attempt divorcing Hippolita, his wife on grounds of she not being able to provide him a \"proper heir\" to the throne.    Manfred's lust for power is so high and this is what makes power more important to him than human life. This is justified by his asking Friar Jerome to choose between killing his son and releasing Isabella (so that he can marry her and have a person who is from the lineage of rightful heirs in is a close relation). It is also revealed by his attempt by his attempt to kill Theodore who he considers to be a threat to his rulership.     Manfred's lust for power thus, in the long run, does not only leave him heirless, but also scatters his home and He is childless, no divine providence in the end.   Manfred's downfall is thus, caused by his inordinate desire for power.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A - FACELESS - AMMA DARKO    Explain Kabria's presence in the hairdressing salon at Agbogboshie.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Agbogbloshire Market is where Kabira shops for her vegetables. On the Monday following the discovery of Baby T's body behind a hairdressing salon, she and Fofo get acquinted under curious circumstance. Disguised as a boy, Fofo attempts to steal Kabira's purse.    Kabria is moved to rescue the 'boy' as a matter of conscience when 'he' is about to lynched by the crowd that apprehend 'him'.   Later at the office of MUTE, the foursome officials- Dina,Vickle, Aggie and Kabira, discuss Fofo and Baby T and reach a concensus that Kabria ought to honour her appointment with Fofo at the Agbogbloshire Market in order to get to the bottom of the death of Baby T and Fofo's predicaments.    All of the above scenarios trigger Kabira's visit to the hairdressing Salon. Kabria therefore goes to the salon at Agbogbloshire not to have her hair done, but to primarily conduct investigation to unravel the mystry surrounding the death of Baby T. Therefore, Kabria's presence in the hairdresser salon is purely in her private capacity as an investigative reporter'.        Unfortunately for Kabira, her visit to the salon is initially a disappointment. She is unable to obtain information of any substance from the hairdresser. She is tense: **\"To tell you the truth, my sister, what at all am I suppossed to know?, and she shrugs. Actually i didnt come to meet the body\". Instead of information about the dead girl behind her salon, the hairdresser pours out fustration about her broken marriage, which has saddled her with responsibility to cater for the children of a runaway husband, Kabira wins her Sympathy after telling her worse situation in her own marriage. She then directs her (Kabira) to see her own senior apprentice for some details about the dead girl.    Kabira approaches the hairdresser's senior appretice who makes the interesting revelations. It appears Baby T is killed somewhere else and the Kayoyoos say Baby T is not one of them. Three days after the corpse is dumped near the Kiosk, pacification rites are performed at the spot by unknown persons. These, among others, leave more questions unanswered on Kabra's mind.    This, however, gingers Kabria and her colleagues into more actions. Eventually, Kabria's presence at the hairdressing salon leads to a host of investigative activities that trace the murder of Baby T to the door step of Poison and Onko.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A - FACELESS - AMMA DARKO Comment on the significance of Sodom and Gomorrah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Sodom and Gomorrah is the seat of the various foms of evil of the various forms of evil in the world of Faceless. It is that part of the citu where people can be said to be faceless and without an identity. It is home for hardened thieves, prostitutes and children driven from home or ones without a home. It is an area that is covered in filth and sqealor. A the same implies, the place that breeds all sort of evil in the children who live there. Fofo, ordarley and the other do not leave home already depraved. it is the life at Sodom and Gomorrah that makes them so.    The going-ons in Sodom and Gomorrah are debashing. The best word to describe the morality of Sodom and Gomorrah is \"depraved\".The habits of the juveuile inhabitants who engage in acts of debauchery by \"drinking bottle of akpeteshire and watching adults films\" are deplorable. Youngsters steal and engage in prostitution fora living in the evil enviroment. Bullies like poison and Macho terrorize the children, deprive them of their money and even attempt to, and do rape the young helpless girls. There is no way of ptotecting these vulnerable young people. The early mention of Sodom and Gomorrah in the novel establishes its significance. It is a phenomenon that has   \"catapulted from the pages of old testament to super impose itself at Agbogbloshire\"    Sodom and Gomorrah is significant in a number of ways. When Kabira goes \"to visit Agbogbloshire market for some garden eggs and tomatoes\", she meets a petty thief from sodom and Gomorrah, who picks her purse. She saves the life of the pick-pocket who would have been subjected to instant mob justuce (lynching).    Anotther aspect of Soldom and Gomorrah which is significant is its sustenance by those who profit from it. The coming of children into the streets and their living in Sodom and Gomorrah appear unstoppable. This is because of the activities of the likes of Maami Broni and Poison. Sodom and Gomorrah depicts the helplessness of the situation of children who are driven into the streets and have no prospects for the future. As the children are driven into the street, there are ready recievers who ensure that they stay, and they supervise their abuse. Sodom and Gomorrah is also significant in as far as no steps seem to be taken by the powers of that be to intervene. Sodomand Gomorrah cries for cleansing but the state machinery does not hear or seem to care. The police are sileint about,and invisible in, the affairs of the street children. No actions is taken when crimes ar reported to the police .    But for Kabira's encounter with Fofo, the NGO MUTE, would not have come to the rescue of the girl. The support of Harvest FM gives impetus to the MUTE effort. The question, as to whether this single intervention of the non-governmnetal organisation is all there and can be and whether it suffices, require critical answers. The enquires about the murdered girl found in the gutter recieve lukeworm attention from the police.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A - LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE    \"No woman's life is ever complete without a man.\" How is this applicable to Yaremi in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Yaremi, a beautiful widow in her early fifties in Kufi, has recently lost her husband, Ajumobi. Their children, all grown up including Alani the only son, have left home.  Women In Kufi, by tradition, are only considered complete when they ar part of a couple,even if they are the second or third wife. In the unfortunate event of the death of a husband, a woman is expected to remarry.  Yaremi, being the strong-willed woman she is, decides against re-marriage to any of the available suitors. Nine months after ther death of her husband, Yaremi is still without another husband, to thr changrin of the men in Kufi, who she tells she is \"neither a napkin or a rag to clean up mess with\". Hence, she rejects all the caps of the three suitors who wants to mary her.  With that firlmy established, she then directs her energy towards filling the void left by Ajumobi's death. She decides to work hard, doing manual jobs to fill in the long hours of her lonely days under the hot sun. She does the farm work , cleans the family compound, dries the maize, grains, uproots cassava tubers for the goats, cocks, fetches water and firewood and does other household chores alongside her main jobs for which she requests assistance from the villiage men like uncle Dayo. She still needs her husband to eat the food she prepare. She also needs, she realises, a husband to eliminate the termites,red ants, and rats around the home,  Yaremi also longs for husband's touch and his deep manly voice. In her loneliness, she dreams about him often, and imagines he has come to visit her. She misses their quarrels and prays for him to return as it is impossible for to forget certain events.  She tells Segi: \" Your father was to me like the mighty Baobab, king of savannah, towering above ten thousand lesser trees around, protecting me under its cool shade.... But death was so cruel. It came like harmattan blaze to strip my only dress, my Baobab, leaving me to stand alone in mournful nakedness  Thus, despite Yaremi's determination tostand aganist tradition in her refusal to remarry, she realises that desirability of being part of a couple,as long as her husband is Ajumobi.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION A - LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE Examine the author's narrative technique in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The author tells his story from the third person point of view. With this omniscient perspective, he demonstrates his skill in observing people and events very closing and passing comments on them.  One remarkable feature of the author's technique is his drawing very deeply from the African oral tradition in his narative. This is often overreaches itself in his own wiles and cunning, the antelope that often falls on its own pride and gluttonous baboon that dies from its rapacious greed. There is also the use of incantation as shown by both Ajumobi and Yaremi to neutralise the evil machinations of their percieved enemies.  The author employs flashbacks as Yaremi,on a good number of occassions, recalls the halcyons days with her late husband and eulogises his sterling qualities as a husband and his prowess as a hunter.  Another feature employed in the narration is dialogue. Instances are the exchanges between Yaremi and woye, Yaremi and Ajumobi, Yaremi and her suitors, the widows on their way to the river, etc.  Indeed, the use of figurative language permeates the entire work. Refernces can be made to the cap-picking ceremony where the suitors' personalities, etc., are delineated.  Also significant is the use of words or expression drawn from the local language. often, these put emphasis on tradition and folklore, thereby adding colour to the setting. There is also the use of traditional songs.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B - NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT    Discuss the role of the black clergy in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Rev Hammond is a black dergyman of Bigger's Mother's church.    He visits Bigger in his cell. As soon as Bigger recognises him, he is on guard against him. Bigger fears pastors make him feel remorseful and wants to tell him to go out but cannot speak.    Reverend Hommond kneels on the concrete floors to pray for the salvation of bigger's soul. He repeatedly refers to bigger as a \"poor boy\", seeing Bigger as a sinner who needs salvation. As the words of the pastor's prayer register themselves in Bigger's conciousness, they make him remember his mother's voice telling of suffering, hope and love beyond the world. this makes bigger feel condemned and guilty.    Bigger hates the Clergyman's creed and wishes he will stop praying. He cannot repeat any of the preacher words, but they make him (Bigger) feel like leaping up strike him. Before he leaves , Reverend Hammond gives Bigger a wooden cross, trying to make him believe that life is all suffering. This, Bigger rejects in his heart.    The visit and prayer of the black clergyman expose the hyprocritical attitude of the black church and its attitude of Capitulating to the situation of its members. It is ironical that the church cannot even engage the services of lawyer for Bigger, which is what he needs at this time. This Reverend Hammond knows as he tells Jan that if any body needs help, then Bigger does.    The clergy contrast, Jan, not only in race and Occupation, but in his beliefe in what man needs in life. Jan forgives Bigger and engages a lawyer to defend him now. But Reverend Hammond thinks of the hereafter. Bigger's case needs prompt and immediate attention, but the clergyman offers freedom of the soul, whilst Jan offers immediate and prompt attention.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B - NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT What have you learned about black life from the conversation between Bigger and Gus at the entrance to the pool room?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bigger leaves home that fateful morning to avoid his mother's incessant nagging about the family's poor living condition and he is not able to be of any help. She warns him against his continued involvement with the gang and prophesises doom for him if he disregards his warning. He heads for the pool room where he feels more at ease. He meets Gus, a member of the gang at the entrance and they drift into a conversation.     Their conversation reveals much about the living conditions of the black people. It exposes their forced segregated lives, their exclusion from participation in the political, militatry and commercial life of white America, as well as their bottled up fudtration which stir up anger in some of them    We learn, for instance, that blacks live under very poor conditions. Bigger and Gus observe and appreciate natures i.e, the warm day, both reflect on the poor heating system in their homes. Though their landlords 'dont give much heat, they always demand rent'.    They reflect also on the segregated lives, which bother a lot, Bigger observe that whites live \"over across the line, over there on, cottage grove avenue\". Explaining the source of their bitterness, he intone:\" we live here, and they live there, we black and they are white. They get things and we aint. They do things and we cant . Account for his feelings, he says, \" I feel like I'm not outside of the World peeping in through a knot-hole in the fence.    Bigger and cavs refers also to the power structure in American Society, from the presidency to the military, business and commerce.  Their simulations of a telephone conversation between the president of the United states and his secretary of the state on the one hand, and J.P Morgan, a business mogul and someone else is also revealing. It is revealed that the president's secretary of State is more ready  to attend a Cabinet meeting about \" the niggers rising send all over the country\" than one Involving Germans. And J.P Morgan is prepared to sell twenty thousand shares of U.S steel, a mind-boggling figure. That kind of business transaction is way beyond blacks to do. These shows the extent to which whites suppress to put blacks in their places.    Blacks are also prevented from aspiring to do anything worthwhile, \"They get the chance to do anything\", but \" They dont let us do anything.\" Whereas the whites, like the pigeons, can go wherever they want, the blacks are restricted in their movements.    The conversation reveals two contrasting attitude of the blacks towards their situation in the novel. Some blacks, like Gus, are resigned to their fate. Others, like Bigger, breed anger in themselves against the system.    Thus, the conversation gives a microscopic view of black life in the novel.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B - THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACE WALPOLE    Comment on the significance of Conrad's death in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Conrad's death is significant both in its contribution to plot development and also to character delineation.    Conrad, son and heir of Manfred, dies when he is mysteriously crushed by a gigantic stone helmet. He does not really appear as a character in the novel but is very important and his death has a direct influence on the major actions in the novel.    Conrad is supposed to many Isabella, daughter of Federic. Fedrick is in actual fact, the real heir to the castle of Otranto. Manfred arranges the marriage between Conrad and Isabella in other to unite the two factions claiming rights to Otranto. Conrad's death put's paid to Manifred's attempt to consolidate his own position through his son. Thus he turns his attention to other means to attain his goal. This sets into motion a chain of events which culminate in his downfall and the restoration of the castle of Otranto to Theodore who is decleared as the true heir of the castle. The prophecy that the castle will be restored to its rightful heir \" Whenever the owner should be grown two large to inhabit it\" it thus fulfilled.    Isabella's repugnance at the Idea of her marrying Manfred, after his proposed divorce of his wife, Hippolita, leads her to run away from the castle to the church of St. Nicholas, to seek the protection of Friar Jerome. This action is in itself significant since it brings the holy father into direct conflict with Manfred to sin futher by challenging the spiritual powers.    Conrad's death also introduces Theodore into the actions of the novel. Theodore's explanation on discovery of the dead Conrad generates a conflict between him and Manfred. Theodore's alliance with Isabella complicates the novel's plot further. Manfred mistakenly believes that the two are in love much to his annoyance as he regards it as an affront to his authority. This stage is therefore set for the final confrotation in the novel which results in Manfred's downfall and the return of the return of the castle of Otranto to its rightful heir.    Conrad's death also contributes to the delineation of Manfred's character. It exposes Manfred's depravity and his capacity for evil machinations. Conrad's death leaves him with only one option as he sees it to consolodate his hold on the castle. When his attempt to obtain Isabella's consent to marry him by lechery and subterfuge fails, he resorts to violence. His lechery and unscrupulousness are accentuated by Conrad's removal from the scene and he is esposed for what he really is. With the Introduction of Theodore immediately after Conrad's death, a formidable opponent to Manfred's evil plans emerges.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "SECTION B - THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACE WALPOLE Examine the relationship between Manfred and Hippolita.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Manfred, the prince of Otranto, is married to Hippolita, a body he later points out to be a distant relation of his.    They have two children, Matilda, Their eightteen-year-old daughter and Conrad, their fifteen-year-old son.    Hippolita is described as \"an amiable lady\" and is presented in the novel as a subservient wife who treats her husband with outmost respect. Her love for her husband is not reciprocated. This is so because Manfred's attitude towards her is one of utter disdain, though he himself says of her, \"true, I honour Hippolita's virtue, I think her a saint.......\"    In the first place, he does not take her suggestions into consideration. When Manfred's hatches plot  the marriage between conrad and Isabella, Hippolita calls his attention to the fact that Conrad, their ailing son, is too young to marry.Manfred responds  by blaming her Inability to give him more than one heir. The marriage plan ends disastrously with the mysterious death of Conrad on the wedding day.     Manfred's Inhuman treatment of his wife only intensifies after Conrad's death. Hippolita, on recovering from the initial shock at the news demands regular updates on her 'Lord' the way she refers to Manfred, on the other hand, doesnot even mention his wife or daughters, as the first words he utters to the ladies in the chapel after the incident are;\" Take care of the Lady Isabella\" Hippolita sends matilda,their daughter to see how Malfred  is coping with his loss. When Maltilda attempts to do so, she cannot find words to explain to her mother ' reception she has recieved from her father, on her return to Hippolita.    Hippolita, on her part, registers her disappointment that manfred has not reguested to see her when she says mournful; \"But will he permit  me to blend my tears with his, and shed a mother's sorrow in the bossom of her Lord\".    She is also worried that Conrad's tragic death must have affected manfred very badly and demands that she be taken to see him, when says to her maids;\" Raise me , my maidens; i will see my Lord. Bear me to him instantly; He is clearer to me than my children.    It is heart-rending that manfred does not cave or ask to see his wife but sends to summon Isabella instead. Hippolita, in innocence, thinks that manfred is apprehensive of meeting herself  and maltilda and that is why he chooses to send for Isabella instead. She tells Isabella, \"console him, dear Isabella and tell him i will smother my own anguish rather than add to his\"    This is contrary to an ideal marriage relationship situation where, at least, both the husband and wife show concern each  other. little does Hippolite knows that Manfred is desirous to propose to Isabella. She trust her husband very much.    When Isabella, on hearing the proposal fleas the castle, Manfreds Footsteps on the stairs, Hippolita hastly goes out auxious to meet him for the first time after son's death. He pushes her \" rudely off\" demanding to know Isabella's whereabouts and even mentions Hippolita is jealous of Isabella. Hippolita, through surprised at this uterances being the obedient wife she is, carries out manfred's order to send her chaplain to him. Hippolita later tells Manfred that the 'gigantic leg' is just a figment of the imagination. Manfred is relieved but his attitude towards his wife does not improve; infact, it get worse.    Relaying on Hippolita's submissiveness, manfred plots to divorce her and marry isabella. When friar Jerome comes with the information on Isabella. Manfred sees the opportunity to get into dissolve his marriage to Hippolita so he could marry Isabella his once proposed daughter in law. When he insists that Hippolita should not part of the discussion, she quickly obeys.    Manfred, as villaince as he is, pleads with Friar to dissolve their marriage on the grounds that its was ill-contacted as Hippolita is his relative, but the Friar refuses to do. Hippolita comes up with a proposal to end the dead lock that fails to materialize. When Isabella protests about such proposal, she says to her:  \" Hold, you must not in my presence, young lady, mention Manfred with disrespect, he is my Lord and my husband\".    Hippolita is there till the very end to support Manfred when he is expelled from Otranto.    It is evident that the relationship between Manfred and his wife is strange and appears to be an unhappy on for Hippolita.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "The Blood of a Stranger by Dele Charley  How does the love for wealth and power influence the actions of the characters in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Some of the character demonstrate love for money i.e greed and ambition throughout  the play whitehead, the whiteman and stranger, Maligu, the king's adviser, and Soko, the village shrine priest, are three of the characters that demonstrate the vice. Their sole objective is to get rich. whitehead  to  Mando  land intending to plunder the wealth of the people  and carry away their diamonds, under the pretext of Tobacco farming.       Greed sets in when Maligu and soko begin to lose trust in one another and plan to get rid of each other for the greater advantage of the diamond and wealth. The three want Kindo, the son of the king of Mando land and head of the Warriors, out of the way for them to succeed in their plan. Kindo recognizes it when he tells Maligu to \"pray for greed and ambition not to destroy\" him. Whitehead also wants Parker, an African who acts as his secretary and as assitant interpreter, and Soko did as they do not exactly fit into his plan beyond using them to acheive his aim. When Maligu stands the chance to save whitehead from death on his hands, he betrays him and simply thanks him for the diamond wealth that now apparently belongs to him alone.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "The Blood of a Stranger by Dele Charley  Assess Santigi's reign as king of Mando land", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Santigi  reigns in a  time of peace, the people of Mando land having come out of previous wars  with neighbouring tribes. Assisted  by Maligu his \"Wise counselor\" Soko, the priest, and his son who is chief of the Warriors, he appears  to be heading towards a quiet  and peaceful death in his dotage (old age).  However, santigi's kingdom is suddenly ruffled by the news of Soko's  contrived divination of a white stranger appearing  in the land. Aided and abetted by Maligu and Soko. the whiteman,symbolically, called Mr. whitehead, who has sent his messenger/secretary (interpreter...), Mr. Parker for (short) before him, appears, much against the custom of the people and does not  pay his respects to the king upom arrival, which is also against the custom. Kindo, the king's son, point this out, but his appeal is ignored  by the king who rigidly insists on things being done according to custom.    whitehead's arrival in  Mando land bodes no good for the people of Mando land under Santigi's reign. In complicity with Maligu and Soko, he deceive the king (urged on by Soko and Maligu)  that he brings  prosperity to Mando land through the introduction of tobacco farming, when his real diamond resources of the land, is never listened to by his father, the king.Thus, Santigi's reign is characterized by the violation of custom; for instance, the custom which forbid the people to smoke tobacco, alchohol and hard drugs, and as reported by Kindo, the men and women engage in sexual orgies, as societal norms and restrictions are abandoned \"in the name of happiness under the very eyes of Santigi\". A normally self-sustaining farming lose the will to work hard and embrace Laziness, rather.    Things do not improve, even at this stage, as whitehead and his accomplices, Maligu and Soko, single  out Kindo, the king's son, as the main obstacle of pursuing their greed for money and wealth. They hatch a plot which receives the king's support. To atone for the revival of  stranger  within, there should be a sacrfice involving  \"the blood of a stranger born in another place\". Soko interpretes this as being the blood of a virgin. Wara, Kindo's woman, is chosen. However, such is the distrust between the accomplices  that Soko spares Wara's life and on the day of the sacrifice, Kindo kills Parker, whitehead's secretary, who then become the sacrificial lamb.Santigi sit on his throne unaware of the demand of his custom and acquiesces to Wara being sacrificed instead. It takes Kindo to expose the grandf deception  and the killing of the whitehead to stop the descent into depravity that has engulfed the people.Ironically, Kindo's banishment is sanctioned by his own father, king Santigi, according to custom.    Here, therefore, is a king who, though old and insistent on tradition,has no high moral intergrity to show in his  violation for custom for money. Instead of protecting his people from outside negative influence, he superintends a corrupt and effete society whch is unlikely to improve under an equally  corrupt Maligu, if he should die and Kindo is unanle to return from banishment.    When it emerges that it is parker who has been sacrificed instead, whitehead calls for the enforcement of the tradition  which prescibes death for anybody who kills in peace time.whitehead in turn dies on Kindo's sword, accidentally.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Comment on the proceedings at the Wasa High Court of Justice", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Investigations into the activities of Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka are already in progress when Ogeyi goes to the police station on  account of her friend Aloho. Her story help the police to wrap up their investigation and prefer charges against Chief and five others, includind, Ochuole,at Wasa High Court of Justice presided over by the judge.    It appears that  only a fraction of the minister's sins against the state and some people is known. According to judge, \"for all the atrocities you must have perpetrated in this country under the cover of Minister, which have not been detected, i say nothing\" chief then faces  four counts of embezzlement, involving 1.2 billion naira and 5.8 million naira (two counts); dealing in cocaine and corrupting a public officer.    prosecution counsel clearly outlines the role of the police in their investigation and what makes each accused person culpable. Inspector Inaku evidence is claer and concise. What triggers police investigation is set down as \"Miss Ogeyi and the 'Jacassan Flash' of  21st june 1997\". Following the newspaper report, the inspector goes to the Ministry and bribes Mr Ayo to get acces to official documents. By the inspector's own    admission, Mr Ayo does not ask for a bribe; rather the clerical officer \"promised to cooperate after  i enticed him with the sum of two thousand naira\". This show of Zeal is wrong. The law seems to be that both the giver and the receiver of a bribe  are criminal, One would expect, then, that the court reprimand or even sentence Inspectore Inaku once Ayo goes in for five years.    In her evidence, Ogeyi  clearly  tells Aloho's story and firmly incriminates chief. Her reason for going to the police is conssistent with her love  for her later friend; failing to persuade Aloho not to abort the pregnancy, she \"was moved to go to the police to relate the story\". However, chief lies on oath, alleging that  the \"cocaine had been put there to incriminate\" him. In the end, the court does not believe him and his bfreaking down avails  him nothing. of the two, ogeyi is found credible by the court.    Both counsels do their work to the best of their abilities. Prosecution counsel notes  and draws attention  to Defence counsel's  \"clearly weaving  the evidence of the prosecution to confuse this honourable court \". He draws the court's attention to the relevant flaws in the case of the defence and leaves the rest to the judge and jury. The judge sums up succinctly and his guiding of the jury is balanced.    On the whole, the proceeding go well and the verdict arising from the evidence appears to be satisfactory.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Consider Aloho as a foil to Ogeyi", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Aloho and Ogeyi are friends from their universities days. They are both pretty, slim,and of average height. While Aloho is dark-shined, Ogeyi is fair. They are both born again christians.    Years after their graduation, Ogeyi secures a job with the ABC company as a recptionist,while Aloho is still searching for employment.Ogeyi, thou not that well off, is very benevolent.She does not accommodate and feed Aloho alone,she also encourages her to be patient and not lose faith in God.    When Aloho comes home with the promise of a \"bogus\" job by a notorious friend, Ogeyi counsels caution, but in Aloho's frustration and desperation,she flouts Ogeyi's advice and accepts the job of a protocol officer in the Ministry of External Relations.    Ogeyi does not give up in her preachings: she tries to dissuade Aloho, but her word fall on deaf ear as the glitter of the good life eggs Aloho on, Aloho soon find herself  in police custody for drugs traffkicking.    As soon as she is cleverly acquinted and discharge through the corrupt string-pulling of chief Ade- Amaka,Aloho discovers that she is pregnant. she attempt to abort the pregnancy but fails due to her nightmaish dream,Dr Chukwuma the gynaecologist's evasive delays tactics and Ogeyi fervent dissuasion.    In her cornered and remorseful situation, she finally returns to her family,but later dies in childbirth, through the baby survives.    Ogeyi launches into action to seek justice for her friend's death. she testifies boldly in court against  Chief Ade-Amaka, helping to bring him to his deserved \"harvest\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "A Raising in the Sun by Lorraibe Hansberry  What is the significance of karl Lindener's visits to the Youngers?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Karl Lindner is a whiteman. He visits the Youngers home twice  on the  same day, The purpose of his visit is to persuade the youngers not  to move into the house Mama has bought in clybourne park for the family.These visit are significant for understanding some aspects of the wolrl of the play.    The day Lindner goes to see the youngers they are preparing to move.\"The man\" meets Beneatha, Ruth and walter.Marna is out. Lindner's misson is simple:The cybourne Park improvement Association has sent him to let \"you people\" know that they do not want the younger family in the neighbourhood, for the whitemen there came from \" a common background \" in which  the youngers are unwanted aliens. He asasures Walter that \"overewhelming majority of our people out there  feel that people get along better, take more of a common interest in the life of the community when they share a common background\". For that reason, the whiteman wants \"to buy  the house from you at a financial gain of your family.\" The mission fails as Walter orders Lindner out of the house. As her goes out perflexed, Lindner leaves his card.    Lindner's second visit is at the invitation of Walter. Ostensibly, Walter wants to seal the deal of the sale of the house. But yhis does not happen. Walter has been inspired by his mother's fighting spirit to reject the offer of Lindner with finality.Lindner, of course, does not understand fully as he departs.    This visit are significant for understanding the Negro experience and the black-white relationship in America. Bobo's intervening report of the loss pof the family money that  Walter has handed over to Willy Harris for the Liquor business gives the family a philosophical outlook. Walter learns from hereand take the bold decision.it will be incompetent with the family's pride to agree sell house since \"ain't nobody in my family never let nobody pay 'em no money that was a way of telling us we wasn't fit to walk the earth\".This is how succintly Mama explains what Lindner seeks to do. Because \"we ain't never that poor\", the family must stict to its purpose and move into the new house. Mama is larger than life, as they say,and her stand establishes her as such.    The speed with which Walter picks the import of the philosophy is astonishing. This is a proud family and must hang on hope with tenacity. It is this that makes Walter decline Lindner's offers with finality  and for which Mama commeds Walter as having 'finallhy come into his manhood.'    Though Lindner protests that his visit  and Clybourne parkresidents' resistance to the yojungers family's  occupation of the poverty has no racial implications or racist undertones,that is not what the visit shows. The whiteman wishes to have little to do with the Negro as a neighbour.It is Lindner's  conviction and that of the white community in Clybourne part that  \"Our Negro familesare happierwhen they live in their own communities\".    Lindner's visits, therefore, reveal the reality of white rejection of Negroes as neighbours and the determination of the Negroes to improve the circumstances of their life at all cost.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "A Raising in the Sun by Lorraibe Hansberry  Trace the transformation of Walter \"into his manhood\" in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Wallter, as a man should  have been head of the younger family. Yet, it is Mama who has been at the helm of affairs from the outset.Not satisfied with his situation in life, Walter is preoccupied with his dream of making it big,through the investment of money that is not his own. He dreams constantly of becoming a self-made man with the backing of his wife,while complainingh that no one understand him. Several he has proved a disappointment to Mama.    Uncaring about what goes on around him,Walter gets a good opportunity of showing himself as the worthy man his mother expects him to be when his wife decides to have an abortion. Typically, he is not even aware of his wife condition until Mama tells him.Mama urges him to take the bull by the horn and speak to his wife and talk her out of her decision. He falters in this and, bitterly disappointed, Mama calls him a \"disgrace to your father's memory\".    When George Murchison calls to take Beneatha out, Walter is inexplicably rude to the young man. He will not leave them alone despite Ruth's attempt to have him behave civily. George aptly describes him as \"all whacked up with bitterness\". On his part, Walter goes on about his vision and his being littlre understood.    Unable to see the wisdom in Mama's  buying the house with the insurance money,walter becomes bitter. He is rude at home and even absents himself at work. Hurt because his mother will not approve his liquor business intentions, he gets another chance to prove as the head of family \"like you supposed to be\", when Mama entrusts the remainder of the insurance money to him with specific instructions. Walker speedily goes and hands all of it over to Willy Harris who takes off  with the money.    The final opportunity to become the man he  should be comes when he rejects Lindner's offer to buy Mama's new  home. Bobo's report that Willy  has bolted with the money shows that the family has no more of the precious insurance money left. This makes the prospects of moving into 406 Clybourne street in the white neighbourhood of Clybourne park particularly bleak and precarious.    The man in Walter emerges, however and he invests Lindner over. Under a show of accepting the whiteman's offer to buy out the family, and contrary to the family's fears, he rejects the offer. He tells Lindner, \"we have decided to move into our house....don't want your money\". All this while, Mama has been showing her approval, as though she were in church with her head nodding the amen yes\"    Thus from a spineless dreamer and loafer, Walter transforms into a responsible head of the sixth generation younger family. Henceforth, things look secure in his hands.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Examine the importance of the jewels in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Jewels in the play refer to the box of jewels that is in Constance Neville's inheritance left in the care of Mrs. Hardcastle her aunt.    Mrs. Hardcastle does not wants to release the Jewels to the rightful owner, Constance. she intends to keep such inheritance in her family. Therefore, she cover up the intention by forcing Constance to marry Tony, mischievous son.    Constance is wise enough to play along with Mrs Hardcastle by letting her \"suppose that i am in love with her son and she never dreams that my affections are fixed upon another\".Hasting is the one Constance love and not Tony. Tony on his part, prefers Bet Bouncer to Constsnce. Because he is aware of his mother's plan to rob Constance of her inheritance,he agrees to be inlove with his cousin, Constance, in the presence of his materialistic mother.    Constance Neville is in no way ready to part with her inheritance as she confides in Hasting, her lover. So she pleads withj Hasting to bear with her until the moment the jewels are put into her hands; then their marriage can take place. The more Constance persuades her aunt to allow her access to the jewels, even if for a day, the more Mrs. Hardcastle insists on her marrying Tony.Meanwhile, Hasting discovers that truly Tony prefers Bet Bouncer to Constance. He therefore, persuades Tony to help steal the jewels from his mother.    Mrs. Hardcastle tells Tony to bear false witness before Constance, that the Jewels are missing. Ironically, the jewels are indeed missing because Tony has given then to Hasting to  help him elope with Constance. Hastings immediately gives the jewels to Young Marlow for safe keeping who, in turn gives them to Mrs. Hardcastle for safe-keeping too.    Tony informs his mother that the jewels are stolen, the mother then goes to check and discovers that the jewels are really missing, She raises an alarm that she's been robbed but Marlow tells her that the jewels are with him and gives her the jewels.    The jewels help to accentuate the irony, comedy,and indeed  the mistakes of the night in advancing the plot. Through the jewels, Hasting and Constance's plan of elopement is exposed. The jewels bring out the selfish and ,materialistic character of Mrs. Hardcastle.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Assess the role of Tony Lumpkin in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony Lumpkin is  the older child in the Hardcastle family. He is Mrs. Hardcastle's child by her first marriage. He is a spoilt child, thanks  to his mother's permissive ways towards him. Obiviously Mr. Hardcastle would have been of help in bringing up Tony Lumpkin properly,but his wife will not allow it. He enjoys making practical jokes.    In the first place, Tony loves to spend his time among commoners in the village tavern. He is there when Young Marlow and Hasting come looking for there way to the Hardcastles. Tony takes this opportunity to take his stepfather back for calling him names all the time. He misdirects the visitors, describing the Hardcastle home as inn. This deception brings about exciting incidents in the plot. Young Marlow and Hastings go to the Hardcastle's house thinking it is an inn and the many mistakes of that night unfold, including the first meeting between Kate and Young Marlow.    Secondly, when Tony learns  that Hasting means to elope with his cousin,Miss Neville, whom his mother has been courting for him, he is more than stealing her jewels for her to enable her elope with Hastings.Tony succeed in doing this, and givers the jewels to Hasting who in turn give them to Marlow for safe keeping. Mistakenly, Marlow hands over the jewels to Mrs. Hardcastle. As a result  of this, Mrs Hardcastle decides Miss Neville must go live with aunt Pedigree at crackskul common.    Again it is Tony Lumpkin who comes to the rescue of the lover.He drives the carriage carrying his mother round and round pretending they are on the  way to Aunt Pedigree. They end up close to where they set out from and later Hastings has to make a formal proposal to Miss Neville to settle matters.    To conclude, Tony Lumpkin seems to be the pivot around which the plot of the comdey  develops. Anytime he appears, a new event begins or a situation is saved.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the use of contrast in Okara's \"Piano and Drum\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Contrast is a device of juxtapose opposing idea or structures for effect. The poem makes use of extensive use of contrast to elucidate the theme of cultural difference between the Africa and the Western Culture.    The very title of the poem presents two contrasting musical instrument, a piano and drums. The former represents European culture whiles the latter, the African culture. The poet uses these contrasting musical instruments to comment on their effect on him. The drums are simple and easy to play. On the other hand, the  piano requires more effort to master. Auditory, the drum are \"pulsing\" while the  Piano \"wails\". The drum invoke memories of a past gone by- a past of \"hunters crouched with spears\" , a simple life filled with dances. The piano, on the other hand, speak of \"complex ways\", \"faraway lands\" and the poet  being \" lost in the labyrinth of its complexities\".    At the symbolic level, contrast is used as a device to shapen the differences between the cultures and to convey  the poet's  attitude towards both. Interestingly, the poet devotes the first two stanzas to drums while only one stanza is assigned to the piano. This contrast in  structure suggests his bias. It shows his sincere interest in the ways of his people. In each  stanza the poet examine the sound of the instrument and its effects on him,The piano is \"wailing\" and speaks of faraway lands\" and complex ways, none of which the poet deciphers, leaving him confused.    The last stanza portrays the poet as one caught between the influence of the two cultures. However, the force of the drums seems overwhelming and tilts him towards the African culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the mood of the poet in \"Ambush\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"Ambush\" portrays a society under siege. The Isolation of the people pre-empts or prosperity. The powers-that-be appear to hold their subject in a vice like grip.    By the use of powerful imagery and symbols the poet unveils his mood of despondency in his deprived and gloomy circumstances.  This is also the mood of the citizens of the land, who, individually and collectively, are denied any means or opportunities of improving their lot.  By whatever means imaginable( by sea,land,or air) various agents, allices of \"the land\" (the autocracy) reinforce  the deprivation of the people. The people's  means of livelihood is obliterated;they are  frightened and intimidated; their very existence is threatened. Above all, they dare not seek relief outside the land.    Through the metaphor of the \"giant whale\", the poets conveys the miserable picture of the people's chances of earning any livelihood being put paid to. The image of angling conveys this vividly, for the land swallows the angler's hook, line and sinker thus \"aborting dreams of a  good catch\".    Thus the people are bereft of hope and expectation as their desires dwindle. The metaphor of the sea serves to convey the harsh restriction imposed  on the people. The people are also held in terror unleashe by another agent of the \"land\" by land. The frightful tiger keeps the whole population in  fear. None is exempted: both the old and the    young dare not exhibit any bravo, nor venture out at night. \"This is how the \"land\" denies the people any escape by land.     The function of the agents that hovers overhead is to heighten the people's and invite chaos on  them. The hawk continuosly \"courts\" ruin of the land with its \"hoots in space\". The impossibility of attempting to escape without being picked up is made certain by the hawk's  presence.    Matters are sealed for the poor masses as local forces are harnessed and the \"land lies patiently ahead/awaiting in ambush\" for its own kith and kin. The purpose of the ambush is not to pritects the people from invaders.Rather, it is to frustrate any attempt to escape for relief elsewhere. In the homeland, \"where nothing happens\", the signs of want are apparent and the people need to migrate \"toward the shore of possibilities\", But they dare not.    The hopeless and frustrating circumstances of the poet make him utterly exasperated and depressed. Thus the mood of hopelessness and frustration permates the poem.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the poet present death as a voyage in \"Crossing the Bar\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the poem, death is presented as the end of life on earth and the start of man's return to his maker. The metaphor of a voyage appropriately  describes this transition.    The symbol marking the end of life are \"sunset and evening star\". These constitutes \"one clear call for me\". Thus the persona knows when his life has come to an end and he  needs  only to embark gladly on the voyage home. Death, therefore, is not to be feared .    The barrier between the mortal world and the world of eternity is human body. This is represented by the sand bar. At death, one's spirit leaves the mortal body and is free to go \"home\". Without death the spirit is not freed to set off. This makes death inevitable.    Death is described as the final extinguishing of the light of life. It is when the light s gone that one sets out to board the eternity-bound vessel. This is captured succinctly as:                             \"Twilight and evening bell                           And after that the dar\".  The symbols appropriately echo the earlier symbols marking the end of life:                                       \"sunset and evening star                          And after that the dark\"    The certainty of death and the obvious final signposts  are clearly  put down in the poem. After death, the spirit is transported  across the waves  as it \"turns again home\". On crossing the bar, the spirit passenger boards the ship and must be introduced  to the captain , that is, \"see my pilot face to face\".    The prospect of death and actually dying are not frightful, sorrowful or regrettable. They are all in the scheme of our mortality. As for the persona, he can take these in hs stride. However, his  experience has been that survivors do mourn for the dead. This is not necessary. He urges  survivors of the dead  thus:                             \"And may there be no sadness of farewell                             When i embark\".    His hope, which is almost a certainty, is that, when he has \"crost the bar\" (died), he will be quite safe meeting his \"pilot\" who will take him to his destination, however far it s  and however long the voyage lasts.    Through effective metaphors and imaginary, death is presented as the inevitable close of the chapter of living on earth and the opening of the way...\"again home\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine Blake's use of diction in the \"School Boy\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Regardng theme, the poem deals with the restrictons imposed by adults on children's natural freedom, as these stifle their natural growth  and development. Blake  uses te natural ryhthm of speech to convey this theme, particularly as he allows the boy to express himself in his own languagge,as much as possible. Apart from the rhymed stanzas, most of the lines read like colloquial speech. The following examples illustrates the point. In stanza one, the boy express his love for summer in the word: \"i loveto rise on a summer mourn\". Then, In stanza two, he expresses his unhappines about going to   school in the line, \"Oh it drives all joy away\". Many more lines are couched in such monosyllabic words.    In additon to the above expressions , it can be said that the very words used in the poem are simple. Indeed the longest word used the entire poem is \"mellowing\" which is made up of three syllables. Words associated with spring and summer are used to describes the season positively.    They include \"sing\",\"joy\", \"sweet company\", \"blossom\" and so on.The focus of the poem being summer, such words expresses the boy's delight in being associated with his activities. Similarly in referring to spring time, he refers to \"buds\" and \"blossom\". However,words associated with school do not have positive association. In school the boys tasks about \"singing\"and \"dismay\", and \"drooping\". The teachers are \"cruel eye outworn\" and school, which should be a \"learning's bower\" has become a \"dreary shower\" . The boy associates his misery with that of a \"bird caged\" and unable to \"sing\" or with  that of a tender plant that has been \"stripped\" of its leaves, or with that of \"buds\" that have been nipped before they blossom.    Indeed there are many more negative words and expressions in the poem. These illustrates the boy's melancholic mood as he laments his inability to enjoy summer  because of the insensitivity of his parents to his feelings and natural inclinations by sending him to school. However, beyond this meaning is one larger, which is the need to give children opportunity to be self  expressive, so they can psychologically withstand the crisis of adulthood. it is to the poet's credit  that such profound wisdom is conveyed in the simplicity of the vocabulary or diction.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "DELE CHARLEY: The Blood of a Stranger    Examine the role of the shrine in the culture of the people of Mando land", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Most of the scenes in Dele Charley's Blood of the Stranger takes place at the shrine. Infact the play begins and ends at the shrine. Therefore, the play has a unity of time. This simply signifies the importance placed on the Shrine as a sacred place that the people of Mando are gullible to any directory that comes out from there,even the King too.  The play begins with plotting between Maligu; the king's Chief Adviser and Soko; the Village Priest,whom he has just included in his plan to bring in a stranger into Mando land and he needs the Chief priest to be on same page so as to lie to the people that the gods had instructed him to allow the stranger in their land. However, the success of this plot unfolds all other actions in the play.  The shrine also serves as a place where the villagers get atonement for their sins. They believe the priest  must sleep on the cold hard floor in the shrine to atone for their sins. However, the shrine is antithetical to the interest of the people of Mando. It thrives on falsehood,greed and superstition. Activities from the shrine also blurs the king' sense of reasoning that he banished his son who serves as the voice of reason and enlightenment in the village.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "DELE CHARLEY: The Blood of a Stranger How does the relationship between Kindo and Santigi affect the future of Mando land?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "How does the Relationship between Kindo and Santigi affect the future of Mando land    The relationship of the father and not just a Son, but the heir to the throne of Mando land between Santigi and kindo comes to an obstruct end  when Maligu deceitfully makes the king to send his own son on exile on the accusations that he reeks of blood and is unclean.  Kindo is the chief of the warrior and the son of the king, he opposed to accepting the stranger in the village. He is irrevocably committed to the welfare of his people that he crushes every opposition to the welfare of his people. He killed Parker to save his people from Maligu's greed and selfish ambition. The reason he is disowned by his father. Santigi on the other hand is the king and the father of Kindo. He is deceived by the priest and Maligu to accept the stranger as an order from the gods. He banished his son for killing a man in peacetime, he follows the custom to the latter that he says his son is not above the law.  However, the out of  their relationship at the end of the play could only means that when the king dies the ruling of the land will be in care of Maligu; a selfish and a greedy leader because Kindo is the only heir to the throne. And this may swindle the people of Mando land the true and passionate leader as kindo who serves as the voice of reason and enlightenment in the village.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE: Harvest of Corruption    Consider any three dramatic elements used to develop the plot of the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The play, Harvest of Corruption is doubtlessly a satire which castigates the corrupt lives of public officials, saddled with the state's trust, responsibilities and resources. Some dramatic elements used in developing this play include the following:  Dramatic Irony: This is a dramatic element in which the audience are more privilege to some information than a character. This device heightens the sustenance of suspense in a play. In the play, the job offer which Aloho gets is nothing but a Greek's gift. Gullibly, she walks into a trap which Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka, Ochuole and Madam Hoha had laid for her by accepting the job offer. Aloho's host in Jabu, Ogeh warned her severally in dealing with Ochuole but she would not heed.  The job offer was simply a recruitment into their drug trafficking cartel but while the audience know this, Aloho is ignorant. Another dramatic element effectively used in the play is.  SOLILOQUY: The deployment of this device makes the intention of some characters known. Through the device, we see a character, showboy; the madman unravel the corrupt circumstance of the state and even profer solutions to the menace. ACP Yakubu is able to decode sense from the lunatic display of showboy and strategizes means of clamping down on chief Haludu Ade-Amaka and other corrupt elements in the play.  Another device in the play is: Situational Irony. It is through this dramatic element that the ironic Honourable Minister of External Relations who ought to represent the interest of his country positively in other nation is using his position to perpetrate crimes especially drug trafficking. Also, the commissioner of police who should stand against crimes and criminals provides cover for the same. He is heavily bribed and settles his \"boys\" who allow chief Amaka's cantel to suffer no harm.  Justice Odili, the custodian of law, symbol of equity, representation of Justice and punishment of offender does not live within his mandate. He collects bribes at will, perverts the course of justice and provides judicial coverage for criminals. It is note worthy that they all have a bountiful harvest of their corrupt deads.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "FRANK OGODO OGBECHE: Harvest of Corruption  How is ACP Yakubu presented in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "ACP Yakubu is one of the revolutionists who turn the course of events in the play. His strict stance against corruption is first seen in Act one. He is angry at the scandalous reports emanating from the Ministry of External Relations and vows to do something about it. He is also the only character who is able to unravel the message of showboy's lunatic display. Officer Yakubu is an anti-corruption crusader in the play. He refuses to join the bad wagon of his immediate boss, the Commissioner of Police whom Yakubu advises to \"Sanitize his cupboard if he has any skeleton therein\".  Yakubu is a good representative of the police force and he exudes courage and audacity in his disposition.  He is very industrious. The police is notorious for finding various excuses when confronted with evidence of their inefficiency but ACP Yakubu is a better breed. He acts swiftly when Ogeyi presents glaring evidence against the corrupt elements in the play following the death of Aloho. The character of ACP Yakubu helps to ensure that there is justice..", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "LORRAINE HANSBERRY: A Raising in the Sun     Comment on the character and role of Asagai in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The character of Joseph Asagai In Lorraine Hansberry' s A raising in the sun\" is portrayed as a zealous idealistic ,he accentuate an international perceptive throughout the play. He is proud of his African heritage and hopes to return to Nigeria to teach with the view to bring advancement to his country.  He is Beneatha' fellow student and one of her suitors. He serves as a great influence on Beneatha that he tries to teach her about African culture and heritage. In contrast to Beneatha' other suitor; George Murchison who is arrogant.  Asagai helps Beneatha to rediscover herself and realize that she can achieve her dream even in a turbulent time. Especially when she feels her  dream of attending a medical school is tied up to her father's insurance money that even when the money is lost to shoddy investment by Walter, her head was up the waters. Asagai is presented in the play to strengths the notion that Black-Americans can find their true identity. He proposed to Beneatha towards the end of the play which means she may move to Nigeria with him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "LORRAINE HANSBERRY: A Raising in the Sun Consider the relationship between Mama and Travis in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Lena Younger also referred to as Mama is the mother of Beneatha and Walter, she is the matriarch of the Younger family. She is a fantastic and  a caring family head. This is  fully presented through the way she nurtures her plant. Travis on the other hand is a ten year old son of Walter and Ruth. He is a grandson to Mama. He is greatly love by Mama, who tries to shield him from punishment. She helps him with his domestic chores,a practice Ruth does not approve of. Travis has no bedroom and sleeps in the living room. Out of love for him, Mama searches for house with a yard in which he can play and also own his own bedroom  which he may share with the baby his mother is expecting. Mama uses thirty-five hundred dollars as down payment on a house .", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER Goldsmith: She Stoops to Conquer    Discuss the view that Tony is to blame for failure of Hastings plan to elope with Constance", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "George Hastings and Constance Neville are both in love with each other but Neville has been paired with Tony Lumpkin by Mrs Hardcastle. The reason is not farfetched: Constance has been bequeathed with lot of jewels and she will only have them if she marries Tony. Fortunate enough for the pair they do not love each other despite persuasion and coercion from Mrs Hardcastle. When Tony Lumpkin discovers Hastings is in love with Constance, he rejoices greatly and pledges his support to ensure they (Hastings and Constance) elope successfully. Tony steals the jewels from his mother's closet, gives it to Hastings who turns it in to his innocent friend Marlow and the jewels find their way back to Mrs Hardcastle's custody.   This is the first set back in the elopement plan.  The major action that makes Tony Lumpkin complicit in the elopment failure is his illiteracy. Tony is an uneducated and spoilt brat \"tied to the apron string of his mother\".  Hasting's secret letter to Tony to intimate him on the elopement gets intercepted by Mrs Hardcastle. Tony can not read the letter, so Miss Neville pretends to, but Mrs Hardcastle takes the letter from her and reads the plan.  This knowledge infuriates Mrs Hardcastle who vows to take immediate action on her niece's \"betrayal\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "OLIVER Goldsmith: She Stoops to Conquer  Discuss the information provided in At 1, Scene 1 and how it advances the plot of the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The first scene in the play is simply an exposition of some basic knowledge to guide the audience on the play's plot. Mr Hardcastle are the first two characters introduced in the play. Their conflicting hobbies is the central discourse between the two because while the husband cherishes old books, friends wine, Jokes, fashion and all, the wife is simply a contemporary woman and she defests her husband's hobbies. She also complains about their mansion which looks like an inn (this is a significant one as marlow and Hastings are also made to believe same).  Another subject of the discourse is Mrs Hardcastle's son, Tony lumpkin while Mr Hardcastle's castigates the boy's naughtiness and folly, Mrs Hardcastle makes excuses on his behalf. She is portrayed to have spoilt the son in this light. Tony's silly pranks such as tying Mr Hardcastle hair to his chair and burning of shoes are obviously not funny here, but his mother tolerating his excesses. Another information provided in the play which aids the plot of the play is the recommendation of the two adults. While Mrs Hardcastle wants Tony to go to school to study latin, her husband says ale house is the suitable school for Tony. This offers background information on Tony's addiction to the three pigeon, a famous alehouse in the play. The argument drags on between the couple for a while until Tony himself shows up. His mother persuades him to stay around but he refuses. While she insists and blocks his way, she hauls her mother off stage in a disgraceful manner. All these action show the nature of the three characters: Mr Hardcastle, Mrs Hardcastle and Tony Lumpkin.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the poet's use of rhetorical questions in \"Vanity\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Birago Diop employs the use of rhetorical questions consistently from the first stanza to the very last two lines of the poem. This helps to accentuate  the issues that are significant the African sons and daughters.   In the poem; \"Vanity\", the poet persona' use of rhetorical question, typically portrays and deepens the root of how Africans castigate a child.  The poet effectively use rhetorical questions to probe Africans and to awaken them to reality of them neglecting their culture as it moves into extinction, while they do nothing but to talk, cry  and complain.  In addition, the poet explore some vital themes in the poem through his effective use of rhetorical question. Such as the theme of Ancestral presence, The futility of Embracing foreign culture, etc.  The poet use of rhetorical questions in a consistent manner instill wisdom on the Africans that the ancestors will turn a deaf ear to them because they have neglected their own culture and embrace the foreign.  In line 11- 14, the poet warms that as the torments increase, though they beg for help but the ancestors will not have pity on them. \" What hearts will listen to our clamoring?/What ear to our pitiful anger/Which grows in us like a tumor/In the black depth of our plaintive throats?   The use the rhetorical question in  line  28-30; restate the poet' position over his choice of subject matter of Africans rebellion against their own culture.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the persona's resolve to be a revolutionary in \"The Dining Table\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"The Dining Table\" is a satirical account of the eleven years civil war that was fought in post-colonial Sierra Leone. The persona relates occurrences in the so called \"Dining Table\" in the third person narrative style at the beginning of the poem until he opines :\"the table that gathers us is an island where crocodiles surf and guerrillas walk\". This explains the fearful atrocities of militia groups and dictatorial leaders who are complicit in the mass destruction of the citizens. Towards the ending of the poem, he states: \" I promise to be a revolutionary \". The reason for this decision is not farfetched. Like every peace loving citizens, he is obviously tired of the senseless killings ongoing for years. It is thus a commendable effort to become a revolutionary but the persona's resolve hit a brick wall when he says \" but my boot have suddenly become too heavy to carry me\". He also complains of his body that has been ravaged with \"catch of gun wounds\". This is a great impediment to his planned revolution as the gun wounds could kill him if not treated. Several African nations have had their share of civil wars. From Nigeria to Rwanda to Sierra Leone and other countries. It is unfortunate that the major underlying cause of these needless wars have been unhealthy ambition, corruption among leaders, leadership incapacity and so on. While the masses are the major set of people who bear the brunt and desire a change, like the persona of this poem, there is little the distressed, sick, hungry and tired member of the masses can achieve.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the deffects of a summer's day as high-lighted by the poet in \"Shall I Compare Thee to Summer's Day\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This Shakespearean classical poem discusses the beauty of the persona's lover which is beyond description. The persona poses a rhetorical question to the lover, \"Shall I Compare Thee to a Summer's Day?\" Simply because there is no apparent comparison that can be with the lover. However, this does not mean the summer's day is flawless as the persona concludes in the second: \"Thou  hath more lovely and more temperate\". This shows the first set of defects: it is not all that lovely neither temperate like the persona's lover. \" Rough wind \" stirs and clears all that is on its path at summer and \"summer lease hath all too short a day\" reveals the brevity of days in summer. The symbolic interpretation here is that if the lover is compared solely to a Summer's day, his life would end quickly just like the shortness of a summer day. The second stanza shows more defects. \"Sometimes too hot the eye of heaven shines\" depicts the scorching nature of the sun at summer. Unlike the chillness which winter days are known for, the hotness of the sun during summer is a big minus which he does not desire for his affectionate lover. On the effect of the summer day sun on the lover, the persona dislikes the \"dimness of complexion\" conspicuous on people who have borne the brunt of fierce sunlight. The persona appreciates the beauty of his lover and fears it might vanish get marred if exposed to much sun. Thus, an imperfect beauty,  ill temperament, disastrous rough wind, brevity of summer's days, the lover hotness of the sun which is metaphorically represented as the \"eye of heaven\" and few more are the defects of a summer's day itemised by the persona.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the poet's use of sight and sound images in Frost's \"Birches\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In \"Birches\", Robert Frost uses imagery of sight and sound as a way of conveying his message as well as to paint a vivid image of how the poet persona  imagines the birches. In line 1- 5 of the poem, he employs the image of sight to accentuates a mental vividness of the Birches.  \" _When I see a birches bend to the left and right/Across the lines of straight dark trees,/ I like to think some boy' s been swinging them.\".   In line 17-18 another images of the sight is employed. \" you may see their trunks arching in the woods...trailing their leaves on the ground \"  and also in line 55-56 : \" black branches up a snow-white trunk/ Toward heaven \"   The use of words in these lines are words  that are scenic in description thus strength  the image of sight in the poem. Importantly,the poet use of comparisons enables the reader to view the Birches in numerous perspective. They are appealing because they are pragmatic, and create a clear image for the reader. The poet deploys the images of sound through his artistic use of some lexical words. For instance: \"swinging\" in line 3 means to move from side to side while hanging from a fixed point. \" I like to think some boy's been swinging them\".  Also, \"Cracks and crazes\" in line 9 suggest violent shaking, \"dragged\" suggests an application of force before motion, \"swish\" in line 39 means a soft sound that is made as one moves swiftly through the air.   The poet picturesque description evoke pictures of beauty and serenity in the mind of the reader.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>13", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "13", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE FACELESS - AMMA DARKO    Discuss the significance of Agbogbloshie Market in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The market represents pain, misery, deprivations, hardship, survival and also hope for various characters in the novel. Agbogbloshie market is an highly dense popular market where low income earners like Kabria patronize and market men and women also sell their cheap wares. The market is also a 'haven' to several street children such as Odarley, Fofo, Baby T, Poison and Macho. Having been forced out of their various homes as a result of intense hunger, the market offers itself freely to these deprived characters who engage in anything just to survive. The first encounter with Fofo in the novel shows her passing the night at a closed shop near the market because she wants to meet up with her carrot washing job. This presents the market as a ray of hope, an opportunity for success and survival. Macho and Poison are street lords who extort money from other street children. The market is also a redemptive point for poor Fofo who ways almost lynched by angry mob but for the timely intervention of Kabria. Fofo would not have stolen but she has just been advised to flee from Poison and she has no money. It seems to many, this market is a means to every desired end and this prompts her to pick pocket. This encounter builds the novel's subject matter as Fofo gets adopted by MUTE and her life becomes better. The plight of the street children is also revealed in the market. Baby T's remains for example were recovered behind a kiosk in the market. Various people who patronize the market are also used to unravel happenings that pervade the novel.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>14", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "14", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE FACELESS - AMMA DARKO Examine the relationship between the street child and the title of the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "A street child in the novel is a child who lacks parental care, forced to fend for himself or herself and abandoned to the street. Some street children in the novel are: Fofo, Baby T, Poison, Macho, Odarley and others. The relationship between the novel's title and a street child is simply identity. The identity in question is in two forms: the personality of the corpse recovered behind the blue kiosk and its killer which  unfolded the events in the novel that shows that Baby T is the street girl. Circumstances surrounding her death is unknown and several characters make painstaking effort to unravel first, the identity of the dead girl and her killer. Sylv Po, the moderator of Good Morning Ghana, Dina, the Director of MUTE, Aggie and Vickie represent the solution finders while Poison and his gang members make concerted effort to frustrate the plan.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>15", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "15", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE    Comment on the significance of moonlight nights among the people of Kufi in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Comment on the significant of the moonlight nights among the people of kufi      Bayo Adebowale tells the myths that surround the moonlight nights in chapter seven. Kufi being a village where the villagers are still close to nature as they measure time by the length of the shadows, the movement of the sun, or the call of the cock.   Moonlight nights is depicted in Kufi as an astir moment, where lots of activities, such as: story telling, riotous drumming from drunkards, dogs barking, bats flying, etc.  The moonlight nights also wrapped up people of Kufi in mystical thoughts by their visual stimulation of the moon,for instance it could be an image of a washer man, old woman, musician etc. There are times the moon may appear like a human head with glittering teeth.  Most of all, the people of Kufi entertains the myth that the moon in the past pitched its abode in Kufi's sky, so low that one could jump and touch it and it illuminates the village such that farmers would go to farm to plant and harvest during moonlight nights.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>16", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "16", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE Examine the role of Uncle Deyo in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bayo Adebowale' Lonely Days tells the story of Yaremi, a woman thrown into widowhood by the death of her husband Ajumobi. Her humiliation, loneliness and struggle for survival in Kufi are prototype of the plights of widows in our larger society. The novel lent a voice to African widows. However, in all  of  Yaremi' plights, the character of Uncle Deyo is that one of a fantastic friend to the Ajumobi' family. Against all odds, Uncle Deyo stood by his Late friend wife.He is a perfect definition of a loyalist. He remain committed to up holding his friend's household.   Uncle Deyo is Ajumobi's bosom friend, He assisted Yaremi in mending the leaking roof and rebuilding the walls of her mud house. He stood as a fatherly figure in Ajumobi' family as he didn't mince his words of criticism towards Alani' negligence, he  scolded Alani for keeping away from his mother.   He took  the responsibility of showing Alani  some of his father's farmland  and encourages him to take over the control of his father's properties as well as him identifying with his mother in her time of need.  Uncle Deyo stood by Yeremi even when all the village elders castigate her for her refusal to pick another cap,which symbolises her picking another husband, during the cap- picking ceremony.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>17", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "17", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT    How is Henry Dalton portrayed in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Henry Dalton is the father of Mary Dalton in the novel. He is the ideal representation of capitalism in the novel and he acquires his wealth by investing in real estate. He does not tolerate Jan Erlone and his fellow Communists because Henry views them as a threat to his fortune. Henry is also presented as anti-racist who employs blacks and coloured as his domestic aids and workers. This kind gesture can be said to have been fuelled by guilty conscience as he is among the elites who had structurally impoverished the blacks. The interview he holds with Bigger shows he is the landlord of the former. Thus, granting of employment opportunity to the black boy is his way of \"giving back to the community\". He is also portrayed as loving husband who cares for his blind wife, Mrs Dalton and a responsible father to his daughter, Mary. The events following the death of Mary also reveals some aspects of Henry. He believes in Bigger and doubts the possibility of the young chauffeur being complicit in the disappearance of his only child. He cautions Mr Britten his private investigator to deal gently with Bigger. Henry also shows willingness to pay ransom of ten thousand dollars to secure the release of his child. After Bigger had been unveiled as the killer, he demands what every reasonable father would: that is, justice.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>18", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "18", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT Examine the significance of Bigger Thomas' trial in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bigger Thomas, the protagonist's trial in the novel is met with national uproar.  Following the discovery of Mary Dalton's remains in the furnace and Bigger's flight, hundreds of volunteers and police officers launch a man hunt for him. Not because these \"passionate\" volunteers are advocates of justice in the racial discriminatory society, they are only vengeful that a black man had raped and killed a white girl. Obviously, if Bigger had killed a black girl, nobody would have cared; after all,  Bigger killed Bessie his girlfriend after the accidental death of Mary but because Bessie was black, it was no big deal. After his capture, Bigger's trial arouses sentiment and rage. Some blacks are sacked from the jobs, a move that is both retaliatory and discriminatory. The mob that usually gather at the court on Bigger's trials days who are predominantly whites protest against the trial. Their wish is the release of the accused, Bigger to them for a jungle justice. They scream and carry placards that read \"kill him\", \" lynch him\" and many more. To this mob, the trial of a black boy complicit in the death of a white girl is needless: kill him right away! The trial also shows the great influence the media wields over the people. Bigger is subjected to media trial because the people who own these media organisations are white. Thus, they use the instrument at their disposal incite, manipulate and control the feeling of the public. Also, the battle of supremacy between the capitalists and the communist plays out in the trial. While the former such as Mr Henry Dalton, Mrs Dalton and Mr Britten want the execution of Bigger, the latter such as Jan Erlone and Max want justice to thoroughly take its place. The Capitalists see a black rapist and murderer who deserves death while the Communists see a black victim of racial discrimination  who accidentally commits a crimes out of fear of the whites.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>19", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "19", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACLE WALPOLE    Comment on the attitudes of women to their roles in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the principal female characters  are Hippolita, Matilda, and Isabella. They are are predominately presented as passive and emotionally fragile, particularly in contrast to their male counterparts such as  Manfred, Frederick, and Theodore. This equates to the fact that Walpole and his culture are patriarchal.   For example,  Manfred being a tyrannical husband of Hippolita  as well as an obsessive father of Matilda and Conrad. The tyranny he inflicts upon his family and those visiting his castle make him a prime example of a Gothic villain. That even when faced with Conrad's death Manfred reacts \"in a tempest of rage,\" while Hippolita appears \"anxious... [and] swooned away\" (14, 16). A constant reaffirmation of gender-based attitudes occurs throughout the novel: women are expected to remain quiet, to dote upon the men, and to attend to the sickly, while men robustly venture forth to discover the cause of danger and bravely confront it.  Also, isabella is threatened with kidnapping, rape, and an overall unwanted marriage, she tries to escape from the castle after the death of her intended husband, Conrad. She narrowly escapes Manfred's grasp, preventing a nearly incestuous and non consensual marriage from taking place. Matilda, a young woman of extreme sympathy and virtue falls in love with Theodore but the display of tyranny of her father she could not get approval to be with him, she is instead betrothed to Frederic, Isabella's lustful father. However, Manfred's ultimate display of tyranny occurs when he mistakenly stabs her to death.  Even Hippolita remains submissive, excessively religious, and depressed under the influence of her husband, catering to his whims despite her own longings for happiness. Women are portrayed to flee a fight while men stay. These gendered fictional representations reflect, influence, and perpetuate patriarchal attitudes toward women. Walpole's novel depicts women without the right to self-determination and submissively accepting their lower status.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2019>20", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "20", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACLE WALPOLE Examine the use of irony in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The use of irony  in Horacle Walpole's The Castle of Otranto at different level is pivotal to the success of the tragedy in the novel as it leaves  the characters completely blind to the truth which the reader or audience already knows. There are moments of dramatic irony, situational irony, and verbal irony in the novel. First of it is the opening of the novel with the assumption  that Conrad, Manfred's son and future heir, will have a big part in the narrative. Ironically Conrad dies He could not make it to the nuptials that Manfred has hastened upon but instead meets his doom. Another significant use of dramatic irony occurs when Manfred makes an ill-fated mistake when he learns that Theodore is meeting a lady in Alfonso's tomb. Manfred, convinced that Isabella is having an affair with Theodore, sneaks into the tomb and fatally stabs the lady. In horror, Manfred realizes that he has slain not Isabella but his own daughter, Matilda. Shortly after Matilda's death, the castle wall behind Manfred crumbles, revealing a gigantic vision of Alfonso. The image of Alfonso declares that his grandson, Theodore, is the true heir of Otranto. Manfred thereupon reveals that his grandfather poisoned Alfonso and usurped his throne.   In an attempt to atone for his wrongdoing, Manfred agrees to abdicate the throne.  Another use of dramatic irony is Matilda falling in love with the very person who signals the ruin of her family's claim to Otranto. Theodore will supplant her and her family, but she cannot help her feelings thus sets the events of the story on a crash course towards tragedy.  Another obvious use of irony occurs when Theodore vows to fight the great knight to defend Isabella, but ends up wounding her father instead.  Manfred's claim that he and Hippolita are related, which he proffers as a reason for divorce, is supremely ironic given the fact. Finally, it is ironical that Manfred, beginning with him as a Prince, then having to sign his abdication and working at a convent.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Dele Charley : The Blood of a stranger    Compare Kindo and his father in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Lorraine Hansberry's \"A Raising in the Sun\", the character of Mrs. Wilhemenia Othella Johnson is portrayed as a pretentious woman. She is a neighbor to the Youngers who takes advantage of Mama's hospitality, although concealed her displeasure over her visit to their home.  She visits the Youngers in the course of their planned movement to the whites' area. While she deceitfully rejoiced with them she also informed the Youngers about the catastrophic news of a colored family that was bombed for living in a white neighborhood. She even gives Ruth a copy of the paper that reported the incident. Although, she told the story in order to serve as a warming to the Youngers against their planned movement to the whites' neighborhood.   In addition, in contributing to the development of the plot, Mrs. Johnson's character upheld the view that the Younger's family could be bombed within a month as they move to the whites' area. She wonders how they are willing to face the reality of such risk.  Mrs. Johnson is a bundle of contradiction who seems to have preference for Walter because of his obvious low level in the society but criticizes Beneatha for what she perceive as arrogance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Dele Charley : The Blood of a stranger   Examine wara's encounter with soko in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Hansberry's 'A Raising in the Sun', Walter lee being Mama's(Lena Younger) only son, Ruth's defiant husband, Travis's caring father, and Beneatha's belligerent brother, serves as both protagonist and antagonist of the play, also known as antihero. The plot revolves around him and the actions that he takes, and his character evolves the most during the course of the play. Most of his actions and mistakes hurt the family greatly, but his later rise to manhood makes him a sort of hero in the last scene.  Throughout the play, Walter provides an everyman perspective of the mid-twentieth-century African-American male. He is the typical man of the family who struggles to support it and who tries to discover new, better schemes to secure its economic prosperity of his family. However, the difficulties and barriers that obstruct his and his family's progress to attain that prosperity constantly frustrate Walter. He believes that money will solve all of their problems, but he is rarely successful with money.  Walter Lee Younger Wants to use his father's life insurance money to open a liquor store. He believes that he should get the money and he tries to convince his family to see it his way.  Eventually, he realizes that he cannot raise the family up from poverty alone, and he seeks strength in uniting with his family. Once he begins to listen to Mama and Ruth express their dreams of owning a house, he realizes that buying the house is more important for the family's welfare than getting rich quickly. Walter finally becomes a man when he stands up to Mr. Lindner and refuses the money that Mr. Lindner offers the family not to move in to its dream house in a white neighborhood.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Frank Ogoo Ogbeche : Harvest of corruption    Examine Ogeyi as a deeply religious person in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ogeyi Ogah works as a receptionist at ABC Company in Jabu, although poorly paid but very contended. She is portrayed at a voice of reasoning in the play and especially to her friend; Aloho. Ogeyi being a born again Christian, she would not compromise her faith or act in line of compromising her believe in God or the moral ethics of the society. She seriously warms her friend Aloho against any association with Ochuole who is knew as an immoral person even during their undergraduate days at the university.  Ogeyi is portrayed as a kind and sympathetic due to her religion, she accommodate Aloho in her small room and do not hesitate to share all that she has with her some of which are food,clothes,etc. she is often seen the play to encourage Aloho in waiting upon God's time , so as not to run into musky waters.  In spite of Aloho's obstinacy, Ogeyi is sympathetic when she hears of her friend's unwanted pregnancy. As a religious person, she counsels her against abortion because she believe it is a sin.  Ogeyi is a virtuous woman and a voice of reason with a tinge of prophetic insight. She maintains her Christianity integrity all through her days and refuses to be lured into immorality thereafter even in the face of unemployment, poverty and stagnation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Frank Ogoo Ogbeche : Harvest of corruption  Account fo the downfall of chief inthe play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Frank Ogoro's \"Harvest of Corruption\", Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka's downfall is mainly because of his over confidence in the fact that there is absolutely nothing money cannot do. His involvement in all manners of atrocities with impunity, he refuses to heed to warnings from his protectors, the police commissioner and the chief judge.  He been the Minister of External Relations is expected to promote his country's image in the comity of nations, uphold the ethics of the society and even seen as a good role model, but surprisely, He is the epitome of corruption in the play. He leads all the criminal network of drug peddlers. He engages in bribery, large-scale embezzlement of public funds, sexual immorality and fraud. His character is ironical to his position in the play. Through his many vices, he portrayed his country in a bad light.  Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka, for his many vices is sentence to twenty -five years' imprisonment with hard labor, along with five others who are to serve various jail terms. His downfall in the play underscores the fact that no one, regardless of his or her political status or other status in the society is above the law.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Lorrane Hansberry : A Raisin  in the Sun    Consider the role of Mrs. Jonhson in the development of the plot", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Lorraine Hansberry's A Raising in the Sun, the character of Mrs. Wilhemenia Othella Johnson is portrayed as a pretentious woman. She is a neighbor to the Youngers who takes advantage of Mama's hospitality, although concealed her displeasure over her visit to their home.  She visits the Youngers in the course of their planned movement to the whites' area. While she deceitfully rejoiced with them she also informed the Youngers about the catastrophic news of a colored family that was bombed for living in a white neighborhood. She even gives Ruth a copy of the paper that reported the incident. Although, she told the story in order to serve as a warming to the Youngers against their planned movement to the whites' neighborhood.   In addition, in contributing to the development of the plot, Mrs. Johnson's character upheld the view that the Younger's family could be bombed within a month as they move to the whites' area. She wonders how they are willing to face the reality of such risk.  Mrs. Johnson is a bundle of contradiction who seems to have preference for Walter because of his obvious low level in the society but criticizes Beneatha for what she perceive as arrogance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Lorrane Hansberry : A Raisin  in the Sun  Account for the Walter's expectation in the play", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Hansberry's A Raising in the Sun, Walter Lee being Mama's(Lena Younger) only son, Ruth's defiant husband, Travis's caring father, and Beneatha's belligerent brother, serves as both protagonist and antagonist of the play, also known as antihero. The plot revolves around him and the actions that he takes, and his character evolves the most during the course of the play. Most of his actions and mistakes hurt the family greatly, but his later rise to manhood makes him a sort of hero in the last scene.  Throughout the play, Walter provides an everyman perspective of the mid-twentieth-century African-American male. He is the typical man of the family who struggles to support it and who tries to discover new, better schemes to secure its economic prosperity of his family. However, the difficulties and barriers that obstruct his and his family's progress to attain that prosperity constantly frustrate Walter. He believes that money will solve all of their problems, but he is rarely successful with money.  Walter Lee Younger wants to use his father's life insurance money to open a liquor store. He believes that he should get the money and he tries to convince his family to see it his way.  Eventually, he realizes that he cannot raise the family up from poverty alone, and he seeks strength in uniting with his family. Once he begins to listen to Mama and Ruth express their dreams of owning a house, he realizes that buying the house is more important for the family's welfare than getting rich quickly. Walter finally becomes a man when he stands up to Mr. Lindner and refuses the money that Mr. Lindner offers the family not to move in to its dream house in a white neighborhood.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Oliver Goldsmit : She Stoop to Conquer    Assess Marlow and Hasting's fist encounter with Hardcastle .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony Lumpkin, the mischievous son of Mrs. Hardcastle from her previous marriage, had tricked Young Marlow and his friend George Hastings to pass the night in an \"inn\" which is actually the destination of the two men. Tired, hungry and exhausted, Marlow and Hastings enter the so-called inn to get maximum comfort. Tony's deceit that the old \"inn-keeper\" (Mr. Hardcastle) would feign to treat them well amuses the duo who toss him and his servants about.  Prior the encounter, Mr. Hardcastle had known his age long friend, Sir Charles Marlow to raise a thoroughly bred, educated and well-mannered man. It is this expectation that makes him desire to give his daughter's hand in marriage to Marlow. Undoubtedly, Mr. Hardcastle looks forward to a cordial relationship with his future son-in-law. He makes adequate preparations for Marlow's arrival and drills his servants the appropriate conduct that should be given to the guests.  However, the first encounter between Mr. Hardcastle and his guests turned out to be a great disappointment. Firstly, Both Marlow and Hastings treat Mr. Hardcastle with disgust since they believe they are dealing with a \"hypocritical inn-keeper\". Mr. Hardcastle, although shocked by their impudence but acts calmly.  Also, Mr. Hardcastle prior to the guests' arrival had selected his choicest old jokes which he plans to tell to their amusement. The jokes fell blank as either the guest did not give him audience to tell the jokes due to frequent interjections or they simply refuse to laugh at the jokes. This makes Mr. Hardcastle embarrassed.  Another cause of dissatisfaction for Mr. Hardcastle is the meal. Marlow and Hastings out rightly reject the lavish meal Mr. Hardcastle had prepared for them. They instead ordered the servants to give them a different treat. The dramatic irony here is highly glaring as the guests feel they could order any food and pay for the service rendered. Whereas, the conduct of these two arrogant lads greatly unsettles Mr. Hardcastle.  Thus, the first encounter of trio leaves much to be desired because of the seed of confusion sowed by Tony Lumpkin.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Oliver Goldsmit : She Stoop to Conquer  Comment on Tony's attitude  to Mr. and Mrs. Hardcastle", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tony's attitude to his parents is not very different from how silly he behaves to others in the play. Tony is full of mischief, tricks and silly behaviors. In Act One/Scene One, his mother reveals her good intention of making Tony study Latin. Mr. Hardcastle counters the thought that the \"ale house would be his school\". Truly speaking, Tony is apathetic to formal education in the play. The mother tries to persuade her husband in getting his support for the plan but Mr. Hardcastle further counters the suggestion. He exposes Tony's mischievous acts, which include frightening the house cleaners and the kittens, burning visitors' shoes and how Tony once tied his hair to the armchair he sat.  While this discourse is ongoing, Tony enters and bids his mother farewell. She begs him to join in their conversation but Tony declines as the Three Pigeon, a pub house is beckoning him. Mrs. Hardcastle tries to block his path from leaving but Tony hauls his mother out of the way and leaves.  Tony does not regard Mr. Hardcastle as a father figure neither does he give him any sense of regard. Tony desires a lavish, carefree and extravagant life. He once boasts of his father's love for \"wine, women and horses\" and promises, \"not to be a bastard when he comes of age\". With this mindset, he jettisons every form of control by anyone including his parent.  As the play progresses, he plays a scary trick on his mother whom she carries in a carriage behind their mansion. Mrs. Hardcastle is sorely afraid and believes they have walked into ambush of highway bandits. She faints when she sees a man not knowing it is her husband.  The attitude of Tony is that of spite, dishonor, mischief, tricks and rebellion towards his parents.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section C>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the dicition convey the theme of Adeoti's \"Ambush\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Diction is a writer's or speaker's choice of words while theme is the central preoccupation/message of a literary work. 'Ambush' by Gbemisola Adeoti is a satirical poem which lampoons dictatorship, bad leadership, destruction of collective national wealth and the frustration of the masses in the \"land\". This \"land\" metaphorically represents Nigeria alongside other African nations whose leaders engage in nefarious acts that hamper national development of those countries.  The persona employs simple and straightforward diction by using highly notable predatory animals to highlight the affected disaster.  In the opening stanza, the persona adopts the world's largest water predator:  \"The land is a giant whale,   That swallows the hook, line and bait,  Aborting the dream of a good catch\"  In the stanza above, the persona shows anglers(fishermen) as the number one group of victims. Their aspirations of a \"good catch\" is dashed as their fishing tools are swallowed by the gigantic sea creature. These \"Blue peters on empty ships return home at dusk\" with nothing to show for their labor.  In the second stanza, the largest predators in the cat family is unleashed and it haunts the people:  \"The land is a sabre toothed tiger/ that halts venturous walk\". While the first predator, the whale lords itself over others in the sea, this ferocious looking tiger walks freely in the street and intimidates the people from going out, earning a living and fulfilling their dreams.  The third stanza introduces the third predator:  \"The land is a giant hawk  That courts unceasing disaster\". This large bird of prey with its sharp vision monitors every creature on the land or sea and at the slightest opportunity, snatches its victim for food.  Thus, the common denomination among all these predators is Destruction. Destruction awaiting in the water, destruction lurking on land and destruction hovering in the air. The fear of these predators leads to another theme, which is Intimidation. Every other creature in the water, on land and in the sky are afraid. Their lives, livelihood and being is shrouded with fear. With their life support cut off, these smaller creatures wallow in frustration and penury.  It is noteworthy that these predatory animals are leaders. Political, economic, social, religious leaders, who employ the instrument of influence of their position to intimidate, frustrate, cow, and destroy the will, resources and lives of the people they are supposed to protect. The social-political relevance of this poem is overwhelming particularly at a time in Nigeria and Africa where the masses languish in diseases, malnourishment, hunger, high maternal mortality, famine, drought, unemployment and a host of many other menaces while the leaders live in affluence.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section C>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the theme of accommodation in \"The Anvil and the Hammer\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Awoonor's \"The Anvil and the Hammer\" thrives in metaphor from its title alone. Using the vocational implements of a blacksmith, which is one of the most popular occupations of Africans before colonialism and civilization, the persona, impresses his message on readers' mind using imagery.  An anvil is a broad, thick and flat metallic piece where new-to-be-fabricated instruments are beaten into desirable shape. The hammer on the other hand is a striking tool with wooden or metal handle. It is the major forging instrument. Metaphorically, the \"Anvil\" in the poem represents Africa. Africa the beaten continent. Beaten by forced slavery for centuries, beaten by colonialism from diverse colonial masters for decades, beaten by imperialism and neo-colonialism and the rest. Like the Anvil, Africa is the beaten one, the voiceless, the victim and the conquered world. The \"hammer\" represents Britain, Germany, Portugal, France, Germany and other ex-colonial masters who, like the hammer, forcefully etched their will and influence upon the helpless anvil (Africa).  The theme of accommodation in the poem arises from the need to inculcate values from Africa's newest imposed culture at colonialism. For example, the Anglophone ex-colonies of Africa adopt English as their official language and Francophone ex-colonies like Togo and Benin Republic adopt French as their lingua Franca. Africa has been able to accommodate new ways of life in her politics; sports, marriages, religion, education, defense, economy, trade, currencies, and diplomacy are largely due to her colonial experience.  \"Sew the old days for us our Fathers/  That we may wear it under our new garment\"  This excerpt from the poem is a warm appeal to African ancestors to help her successors in their newest quest of nation building. As seen in the excerpt, total reliance or adoption of European cultures by Africa is not possible, as it would portend confusion. Thus, this necessitates the persona's appeal to invisible African \"founding fathers\" to \"sew\" the good old days for their children to \"wear under the new garment\" of Africa's newly acquired independence.  Unlike some other African poems, which castigate the cultural clash between Africa and Europe during colonialism, Awoonor explores the option of reaching a compromise between the two cultures for a fruitful African future.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section D>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine God's reasoning in \"The Pulley\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The major thematic preoccupation of \"The Pulley\" is God's creative prowess and His relationship with Man. The opening stanza remains eternally picturesque:  \"When God at first made man, having a glass of blessing standing by\"  Subsequent lines show how God summons other members of the Trinity-in-Council as \"pour on him all that we can\" and allow, \"The world riches contract into a span\". Thus, every desirable virtue find its way into Man, God's most fascinating masterpiece!  Strength, beauty, honor, riches and everything good fills man. However, when almost all was out from the \"glass of blessing standing by\", the persona shows how God \"made a stay\".  What could have restrained the most benevolent God to make a stay at this stage and refuse to bestow all He has upon His work? The persona reveals a profound reason. God intentionally refuses to bestow the blessing of \"Rest\" upon man because this could make man \"rest in nature and not the God of nature\". God in His infinite wisdom had thus perceived that man has the capacity to forget Him if he possesses rest alongside other blessings bestowed on him. \"Both will losers be\" in the ending part of the poem also shows the loss both God and Man would have if man possesses rest. How? Man would find his purpose in nature and not God while God would lose His devotion from man, which would be transferred to nature.  God allows man to have all other blessings but Him to enjoy them with \"repinining restlessness\" so that if blessings do not drive man to God, misery, pain, restlessness would \"toss him to my breast\".  Thus, this deep reasoning does not only reflect God's omnipotence but an omniscient being who understands the dynamics of His work.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Drama and Poetry>Section D>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the image of caged bird explain the boy's experience in \"The Schoolboy\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "William Blake's \"The School Boy\" is a romantic poem; it appreciates the aesthetics/beauty of nature. The poem persona in the poem, like every other romantist finds tranquility, grace and purpose in nature. He expresses his joy in the opening stanza:  \"I love to rise on a summer morn,  When the bird sings on every tree  The skylark sings with me  O! What a sweet company!\"  However, the persona's childhood joy is shorten in stanza two:  \"But to go to school in a summer morn/Oh it drives all joy away\".  These lines contrast the beautiful experience of nature he had enjoyed in the first stanza. The mere idea of going to school \"drives all joy away\" as the child is held in the tutelage of a \"cruel eye out worn\" where children spend \"many anxious hour sighing and in dismay\".  Stanzas three, four and five show hostile experience in which children are subjected to learn. This fuels this persona's subsequent outburst:  \"How can the bird that is born for joy, /Sit in a cage and sing?\"  Metaphorically, it is obvious that the schoolboy is the \"caged bird\" and there is no motivation that may be given to make it sing. This \"bird\" is born to spread his wings and explore vast opportunities, which it could only get by flying and not by sitting in a confined hostile environment called school.  The persona uses the image of the caged bird to drive attention of everyone to the irreparable damage poorly structured formal education could have in children's life. In addition, the rhetorical question, \"How shall the summer appear with joy when buds are destroyed\" further reveals the negative impact of the \"caged bird syndrome\" which is common in formal education.  The \"caged bird\" persona ends the poem with a clarion call to parents, teachers, administrators, government and all stakeholders to structure learning in a way that does not jeopardize childhood interests, experience, inquisitive spirit and beauty.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Amma darko :Faceless    comment on Fofo's visit to maa Tsutu.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Amma Darko's Faceless, Fofo is the fourteen-year-old daughter of Maa Tsuru whose ordeal in life and many unanswered questions leads into the street where she lives at in a notorious enclave known as Sodom and Gomorrah.    Fofo, who rarely visits home from her abode, comes visiting in a bid to find out why Poison attempts to rape her. In this light, she seeks explanations from her mother whom she sometimes feels for and most times incline to hate and blame her for the exits of her two older brothers over the arrival of their mother's live-in lover and the sexual abuse of her sister, Baby T by her supposed stepfather, then after, sold her into prostitution.   The significance of her visit to Maa Tsuru is that it sheds more light to how Fofo should feel about her mother and the revealing of many untold stories of how the body found behind a blue Rasta hairdressing salon at Agbogbloshie's market is that of her sister, Baby T.     In addition, this visit unravels the puzzle behind Poison's attempt to rape Fofo, just because he is angry that Maami Broni informed Maa'Tsuru of the death of her eldest daughter and of course, the obvious intention of probably replacing Baby T's with Fofo to continue exploiting them for his own benefits.    Finally, Fofo's visit to Maa'Tsuru awakened the sleeping anger in her since her mother's reasons seems not to be convincing enough for her go away from Accra or even beyond, latter incidence in novel suggests that she relentlessly seeks justice for her sister's death through the help Kabira who works with an NGO known as the MUTE organization.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Amma darko :Faceless  To what extent are men protrayed as oppressors of women in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Women oppression is a serious concern that still ravages our present-day society of its sanity. How does one explain such in a modern world where colossal technological advancement is the order of the day, yet has no change on the grim reality that women are discriminated against and suppressed because of some cultural beliefs, traditions and religions!  We live in a society where more attention is given to the men thereby ensuring the continuation of the domination and repression of women.  In Amma Darko's,  Faceless, male domination is portrayed to a large extent. In fact, it is not out of place for one to say that the social ills suffered in the novel are as a result of the obvious male oppression that raged the society.  First, is when Kwei beats Maa Tsuru in the bid to abort her pregnancy goes unchallenged because she has no one to defend her and later abandons her, after they have jointly made four children, under the pretense of a curse is nothing but a smack of oppression. In addition to that, her child, Baby T is refused the honor of Kwei's family name for the sins of her parents were bestowed on her but the narrative could have change if she were a male.   Even among the middle class in the novel, we have Kabira who dares not operate based on equality with her husband, Adade. Adade expects her to take his briefcase from him while he walks leisurely into the house. In her own case, family care does not permit Kabira any time for recreation; while her husband goes on to have all fun socializing with friends at a drink joint every day.  In furtherance is the instance when Onko brutally defiles Baby T and when Maa Tsuru tries to fight his cruelty. To shut up her complaints, he gives her a 'wad of cash' and she drops her concerns in defeat. By so doing, she partakes in turning Baby T, Fofo's elder sister, into a street girl in order to save her from incessant sexual assault by Onko; and this leads to her eventual death. The same smack of oppression enables Poison to silence Maa'Tsuru after he murdered Baby T and his attempt to rape Fofo.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Bayo Adebowale : Lonely Days    How does Alani reject ancentry in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Alani is the only son of Yaremi and the late Ajumobi. He is an expert in furniture making and resides in the city. Kufi as his ancestral village holds no attraction for him. In fact, he pays no attention to his mother or the property left behind by his father. Through his character in Lonely Days Bayo Adebowale buttresses the theme of contrast between the village and city life, where the city is portrayed as a place of empty hope and frustration as well as immorality and extravagance. The city is described in the novel to be a \"glittering mansion of chaos\" as opposed to the countryside where people live poverty -stricken but contented lives.  However, Alani rejects his ancestral as he exhibits a devil-may-care attitude to legacies of any kind. His superficial nature of life in the city is captured in the novel as he is been described to have bleached his skin, dyed his hair curly and tangled, wears a shining necklace as well as a pair of intimidating high-heel shoe.(p.135)  In addition, Alani rejects his ancestral as his uncaring attitude caught up so much with him that he shows no interest in making commitment to his family. He does not identify with his mother in her plight or take charge of the legacies his father laid down.  Even after his father's friend, Uncle Deyo took him round his father's farmland, all Alani could suggest is that the farmland should be sublet or leased out which further buttresses that he does not care if the farmlands are finally usurp by adventurists like Okanlawon.  Alani is irredeemably lost to the city that even words of admonition from Uncle Deyo fell on his deaf ears. He informed his mother of how he has impregnated a pretty girl in the city with the intention of not involving his family in his wedding preparations.  Finally, Alani's utterl rejects his ancestry when he hastily returns to the city, without much consideration for his mother. Thus, it becomes evident that he does not want to have anything whatsoever to do with his ancestral home or with his family.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Examine the advice of the three widows to Yaremi in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bayo Adebowale's Lonely Days is set in Kufi, a typical African society. Kufi is of course a male dominated community in which women are restricted. These women lose their status in the society upon the death of their husband and have no right to be heard. Yaremi is not the only widow in the village as the three other widows have picked new caps in other to enjoy a measure of dignity and respect again. Picking a cap is symbolic for getting married again.  The three other widows, Fayoyin, Radeke and Dedewe, recount their ordeals in the hands of their deceased husbands' families as they pay Yaremi a solidarity visit on the eve of the cap-picking ceremony, pledging their support and advising her to pick a cap for it was in her best interest. They admonish her to be humble and submissive as well as caution her on the consequences of making the wrong choice.   However, the visit of the three widows only portray the women to be weak. These women do not wish to do things differently just because they feel their comfort and stability lies in the hands of having a man in their lives.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Richard Wright : Native Son    Comment on bigger's last moments with max", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Richard Wright's Native Son, the character of Bigger Thomas is the protagonist. He is portrayed as the fusion of several men caged by racism as they unleash their frustrations on others by being antisocial, violent behavior, etc.   After Bigger is sentenced to death and while waiting for execution, he shuts himself off from every other person, and tells his family to forget about him and not visit him. However, he demands to see Max whom he feels knows how he felt in his situation.    Boris Max is a Jewish lawyer and a communist who takes up Bigger's case to defend him free of charge. He speaks so passionately to defend the crime he committed, stating that they were instigated by the racist American environment that had condemned him to a fearful, hostile and hopeless existence.   However, during Bigger's last moment with Max, the readers are able to deeply penetrate into his inner consciousness  to understand that Bigger is not a violent criminal and his propensity for crime has nothing to do with race; rather, he is a product of America's racism and violence in which he was raised.  Finally, it is through his last moment with Max that a prophetic admonition is raised. That is, if  fundamental changes are not introduced in America's social and economic realities to integrate the oppressed fully into the mainstream of the society, then the oppressed would sooner rise to revolt against their tormentors.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Richard Wright : Native Son  Examine Bigger's visits to Bessie in the Novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bessie Mears is Bigger' girlfriend. However, their relationship is such that is not based on romantic love but upon mutual conveniences. In the novel, Richard wright present the character Bessie to portray other escapist reactions to frustration of the blacks. She takes alcohol in order to forget her sorrow. Alcohol to her is equivalent to Mrs. Thomas religion.  When Bigger first visited Bessie, after he had accidentally killed Mary Dalton, her offhand comment inspired him to try to collect a ransom from the Daltons for the release of their daughter since they are yet to know that she is dead.  Bigger's second visit to Bessie was fueled with the aim to carry out some plan on the ransom letter and as well to bully Bessie to be part in the ransom scheme. He later forcefully fled with Bessie into an uncompleted where he raped her and later killed since her refusal might leak his secret of the murder of Mary Dalton.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Horace Walpole : The castle of otranto    Asses the relation between father and their children in the novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Walpole's: \"The Castle of Otranto\", the relationship that exist between Manfred and her daughter; Maltida is surly and irascible.  In the first chapter of the novel, Manfred reactions when Matilda is hesitating outside the door of his room that he flings it open and demands to know who is there. His reply when he realizes that it was his daughter and how he slams the door in her face indicate that Manfred has no feelings of love for his daughter. Except, for the fact that he later regarded his action as expedient to his schemes to marry her off to Frederic.  Manfred never regards her as anything more than a pawn, however, Matilda on the other hand, is a dutiful, obedient and devoted daughter to her parents, especially to her father despite his lack of love towards her.  She loves him still and would not have him insulted or denigrated by anyone, not even her admirer or lover.  Walpole's 'The castle of Otranto' portrayed Manfred, as an unapproachable father who does not even recognize his daughter in the twilight. He eventually kills his only surviving child because of his desperation to realize his desire of keeping the scepter of the Otranto in his lineage.  Although, Matilda shows dutiful filial affection for her father even when she is unloved but she is also terrified of him.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2020>Prose>Section B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Comment on the presence of ghost and spirits in the Novel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Walpole's The Castle of Otranto is an gothic literature and by definition, a gothic novel refer to a style of writing that is characterized by elements of fear, horror, death, and gloom, as well as romantic elements, such as nature, individuality, and very high emotion. However, these emotions can include fear and suspense.  In Walpole's 'The castle of Otranto', Supernatural elements like ghosts, visions, mysterious suits of armor, and prophecies run through the novel. Part of this is achieved merely by his presentation of Gothic and supernatural elements. For example, Conrad's death by giant helmet, as well as the tragedy that befall most of the story's characters, completely indicate the presence of ghosts and spirit in the novel.   In addition, the curse on the family of Manfred, the villain of the story indicate the presence of spirit in the novel. The appearance of a giant in the castle, in the great hall, and then vanishes indicates the presence of a ghost. Next, is a statue that develops a nosebleed, Two other supernatural omens are a second appearance of the giant and an animated skeleton.   Finally, the dead Prince Alfonso rises from the grave in human form and speaks. None of these events is rational or seen as an illusion but instead they are treated as actual occurrences in the novel, which of course connote the presence of spirit, and ghost in the novel.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN K. KARGBO: Let Me Die Alone    Comment on the character of Yoko in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Madam Yoko is the main character in the play. She is the queen and leader of the Senehun people and the Mende Chiefdom. She takes over the throne after the poisoning of Gbanya, her husband and leader of the people.    Yoko's character is resilient and formidable in the play. Despite knowing that her husband was poisoned by some unscrupulous elements who may want to do the same to her, Yoko seizes the mantle to the throne from Lamboi and his cohort, and proceeds to become the leader of the people. Even as she has secured the throne, she does not relent in being vigilant and strong for her people. One cannot also but see the formidability of Yoko when she alone confronts Lamboi and Musa as they plan to enthrone Lamboi after Gbanya's death.    Also, Madam Yoko is the tragic hero of the play. The play is seen as a tragedy because it has tragic elements. However, it varies a little from Classical tragedy. While the play does not follow the Classical tragic plot, Madam Yoko is still seen as a tragic hero whose circumstance pushes to commit suicide in order to stamp her integrity into the history of the Senehun people. She is tragic in the sense that she does not deserve what happens to her in the play: the accusation that she killed Jeneba for ritual purposes and Governor Rowe's division of the kingdoms without informing her. Of course, just as in a tragedy, the play ends on a sad note: in the death of Yoko.    Finally, Yoko stands as a symbol of resistant to the British colonial administration which swept through sub-Saharan African countries in the wake of colonialism. Yoko stands tall, not scared, as Gbanya is being beaten. After her husband's death, she welcomes the governor's representative but does not grovel at his feet. Her act of suicide is a symbol of resistance to the colonial administration of her era.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN K. KARGBO: Let Me Die Alone  What challenges is Mende chiefdom confronted with in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Madam Yoko is the leader of Mende chiefdom. She takes over the mantle after the death of her husband. From the beginning of the play to the end of the play, the people of Senehun encounter different challenges. These challenges are either as a result of internal issues or external issues.    One of these challenges is the overthrowing of Gbanya's regime. Lamboi and Musa connive at killing the king, and they succeed in doing so after Gbanya has been beaten by Governor Rowe's men. A further extension of this particular challenge is Yoko's having to be suspicious every time after ascending the throne. Generally, the ruler and the ruled are suspicious of each other.    Another challenge that the people had to face is the British colonial administration. The people are being ruled by proxy and they watch as Gbanya, their king, is being beaten by Governor Rowe's soldiers. Even after Gbanya's death, and Yoko has become the leader, Governor Rowe still divides her kingdom without consulting her. This is quite painful because she helps the governor contain those people who have refused to pay the tax imposed by the governor.    Again, the tax imposed by the governor is another instance of challenge faced by the people. The imposition of the compulsory housing levy is done after Yoko takes over the mantle of leadership. Yoko handles the situation by fishing out rebels and making them face the consequences of rebelling.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Why does Lakunle lose Sidi to Baroka?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the play, The Lion and the Jewel, Soyinka portrays Sidi as an archetype of an integral part of the Yoruba tradition - chastity. In the unfolding events addressing the clash of values, Sidi's characterisation undergirds the tenacity with which the culture of bride price is held important in the African marriage custom - in the Yoruba tradition. It is against this that Lakunle's civilisation is rejected as he fouls his chance of engagement to Sidi in the play.     Lakunle argues that Sidi's cultural belief is barbaric and retrogressive. He questions the essence of bride price when the world is so civilised. He plans taking her out of Ilujinle if she accepts his proposal. She fits in the modern lifestyle so well. The implication I their dialogue is that we see two contradictory beliefs arguing the superiority of their values. Also that, Lakunle does not regard the this requirement because he sees Sidi's beauty all in the light of the same westernisation Sidi deems unbecoming. Although Lakunle is progressive in exposure, Sidi's makes no sense of his disavowal of what her culture demands so long marriage is concerned. As such, she will not marry a man who is not ready to meet the demand of her honorable tradition.     Further, Lakunle loses Sidi to Baroka's position. Baroka becomes a formidable obstacle to Lakunle's chance, being an influential viceroyal chieftain (Baale) whose influence is revealed as an imperial control. The reader is made to understand how bleak the possibility of marrying Sidi is for Lakunle the moment Baroka declares his interest in her. Since Baroka always gets what he wants, even at all cost, Lakunle's hope shrinks. To further undermine Lakunle's aim, Sadiku, the head of Baroka's harem, is a persistent persuader. It is needless to say that her influence works on Sidi to make her agree to meet Baroka, against her erstwhile decision. Sadiku dispels Sidi's reservation for the Baale by revealing that he is impotent. Upon knowing this, Sidi wants to go to the palace with a view to mocking the chief. When Lakunle interrupts the discussion, he is not recognised. He quickly senses Baroka's 'game' more so. He finds his choice in competition with the Baale's, which frizzles his desire to an irretrievable loss.     To that end, in the resolution of the conflict, Sidi falls prey of the Lion (Baroka)'s cunningness in the reality of which she loses her virginity. When she comes out of Baroka's room and breaks the news to the duo of Sadiku and Lakunle who have been apprehensive, they are surprised at the chief's egregious act. On the minute still, Lakunle reaffirms his love for Sidi and promises to marry her regardless. Sidi refuses. She must marry her 'husband', the man to whom she has lost her virginity. She - and Sadiku - leaves to make the wedding preparation for the marriage between her and Baroka.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel  Examine the theme of love and marriage in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The play, in its treatment of the conflict/clash of values, explores prominently the theme of love and marriage as a spectacle of the author's treatment of reality. The play centring on the 'struggle' between Baroka and Lakunle for Sidi implicitly addresses the notion about marriage within the look of tradition. The idea of love and marriage, we see, thus facilitates the resolution of the (main) conflict in the plot.    On the hand, Lakunle's westernised belief is refuted by the high-handedness of cultural marriage values. He must abide by the dictate of the existing tradition if he wants to marry Sidi. But he debases this with his 'alien' values. Love means the payment of bride price and vice versa. In the argument that ensues between Lakunle and Sidi, the latter emphasises that if she marries without her bride price paid, then she marries cheap, and such is never befitting. She tries to convince Lakunle to her claims. Also, that he loves her does not - and will not - change the traditional belief. We begin to see the definition of love in the African marriage setting: that a woman is with more than the man's professing of love without action; that bride price is an inseparable part of marriage custom. A compulsory step at that. Since Lakunle disbelieves this, then his acclaimed love for Sidi is not genuine and marriage cannot happen. The author shows: African marriage custom demands, above all, that bride price be paid, which is the proof of love.     On the other hand, the author uses irony to show the condition for marriage in the African setting: Baroka who is ready to pay the bride price owns the bride. Although this happens in an obscene manner, love is portrayed as the readiness to marry a woman according to the standard of tradition. Sidi eventually unarguable belongs to Baroka who cunningly takes her virginity. This brings to the fore the ribaldry common in the African society, especially among the traditional elites, which precipitates marriage, as seen in how Baroka gets Sidi as wife. While Lakunle's love for Sidi is true and genuine, Baroka's is ribald and borne by his influence. Baroka proves his 'love' to Sidi by marrying her as custom demands; Lakunle fouls up his chance by countering that with his civilisation. Although Sidi could have accepted Lakunle's marriage proposal, she is obliged to marry Baroka who does the right thing.     To the trio of Lakunle, Sidi and Baroka in the love triangle, love and marriage are understood differently. To Lakunle, it is the outlook of civilisation; to Sidi, the payment of bride price; to Baroka, the possibility of influence. Soyinka bears on these differences to bring the play to resolution. He explores love and marriage as an instrumental force in highlighting his subject matter.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger    Compare Jimmy and Cliff as friends.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jimmy Porter was a twenty five years old who lived in Britain, in the industrial midlands. He is educated, well read and works in a factory and also tends a sweet shop. He is never tired of criticising the British society which denied him many opportunities because he belonged to the working class. He was an honest person and was proud of it. He was very cruel in his verbal attacks on his wife Alison and friend Cliff. He is ego centric and is oblivious to his own faults. He criticises his wife but has no worry about his affair with his wife's friend Helena. He cannot empathize with his wife when she grieves over the loss of her baby. He accepts Alison only after realising that she had suffered enough like him.    Cliff Lewis is a friend of Jimmy and belonged to the working class like Jimmy. Cliff is a gentle person and does not have the fire or wit of Jimmy. Cliff is fond of Alison and appreciates her housekeeping efforts. It is Cliff who bandages the burns on Alison's hands and not Jimmy. Cliff is the only character in the play who understands the feelings of other and he is the first to see Helena's intention behind breaking Alison's marriage. He dislikes Helena and moves out when she moves in.    Cliff acts as the foil of Jimmy. While Jimmy is an aggressive, go-getting kind of person who hates passiveness, Cliff is a passive character who loves the status quo.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger  Discuss Jimmy Porter's sense of alienation in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jimmy Porter feels alienated from both his wife and society in general.  He is a struggling middle class working man who is bored and confined by his monotonous life.  His wife Alison has come to accept life, silently bearing any and all burdens. Jimmy feels resentful of Alison's aloofness and indifferent demeanor and strikes out at her to get a reaction.    Jimmy is an angry man who feels that his opportunities in life were shaped by his middle class upbringing.  Alison's brother Nigel has a university degree and is a member of Parliament.  Jimmy hates him for his connection to the world.  A connection that he knows that he will never have.  Jimmy is a character who contemplates the world beyond the dimensions of his own existence.  He cannot find anyone to talk to about the injustices or curiosities he feels about life.    Part of Jimmy's alienation is from a general feeling in Great Britain in the 1950s when the ordinary British citizen felt passed over by a government who had promised prosperity for everyone.  Instead, following WWII, in which London was destroyed, the British people struggle with new threats and a country put back together with a socialist system in place that is designed to keep everyone equal, except the very rich who remain the upper class, high above the ordinary citizen.  Jimmy resents all of this and knows that it will never change.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AUGUST WILSON: Fences    Consider Raynell's contribution to the plot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Raynell is the child born by Alberta to Troy in the play. Although Alberta dies from childbirth, the child remains alive. The character of the child alone contributes a lot to the development of the plot and the issues discussed therein.    Consider, for instance, the issues of fidelity and truthfulness in the play. Troy Maxson is shown as a character who romances infidelity and is not truthful in his dealings. The birth of Raynell is used to reveal his infidelity, which will otherwise have been hidden from Sarah and the rest of his family. Of course, Cory is the one used to reveal that Troy is pocketing the money meant for Gabriel, his mentally-disturbed brother. So, Cory also serves as a development tool to the plot in his own right.    Raynell also serves as a token of separation between Troy Maxson and Sarah Maxson. Troy might have been a imperfect, mistake-prone husband and father, but that does not warrant the separation which occurs in the play. However, Sarah uses Raynell as a token of separation between her and her husband. She says Troy is now a \"womanless man\" because of Baby Raynell.    On the flip side of the coin, Raynell serves as a uniting factor between Sarah and her husband, and between Cory and the rest of the family, even though the uniting occurs after troy's death. It is because there is nobody to take care of Baby Raynell that Sarah agrees to take care of her and be a mother to her. She also does not leave Troy because of the baby.    Of course, Cory comes home after Troy dies, but it is with Raynell that he finds what connects him to their father: Raynell and Cory sing one of Troy's father's blues songs. And it was a moment of nostalgia, reminiscence and togetherness.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AUGUST WILSON: Fences  Comment on the appropriateness of the title, Fences.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "August Wilson's Fences is a play set in the 1950s America when blacks were migrating North in order to find greener pastures. The title is a symbol connoting division and separation: a fence separates two things; it alienates two things from each other; it divides a whole into two. In some cases, a fence can even divide into more than two. However, in this play, we have the plurality of the word: fences. This means that there is more than one fence in the play. When this claim is examined, it is discovered that it is not only true but also concluded from the various instances in the play.    One of such instances is the dichotomy between white players and black players in the baseball league. Even though black players outperformed white players, they still were not recognised in the major league, forcing black players to be confined to their own league. Troy Maxson himself mentioned different instances of his outperforming major white baseball players who, yet, were deified. The bitterness caused by this fence remained in Troy until his son, Cory, is about to be recruited by his college football team. Apparently, the prejudice spanned more than just the baseball league. Troy refuses to consent to Cory's joining the football team and this creates another fence in the play.    When Cory does not get his father to consent to his joining the football team, he leaves home and joins the US Marine Corps. For eight years, Cory and his father stay apart, either one not knowing the well-being of the other. It can be conclusively stated that it is the larger fence of racial prejudice in the baseball league which extends and creates this smaller fence between Cory and his father.    Another instance which corroborates the plurality of the title and affirms its rightfulness is the job disparity between white garbage workers and black garbage workers. For a number of years, Troy Maxson worked for the garbage company, yet, he still remained a garbage collector while whites were automatically given the job of drivers. This creates not only a disparity between the two races but also a deep-seated belittling for black garbage collectors. Fortunately, Troy is able to fight for his right and he becomes a driver.    From what these highlighted instances, one can see that there are more than one fence in the play. Of course, one should never think of the title as referring to the actual fence in the play; the fence has metaphorical meanings for 1950 America. The playwright has done well in representing the issues of that era using symbolism which can be understood by literary critics and the general readership.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section C>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the personification of rage in the poem, \"Raider of the Treasure Trove\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Lade Wosornu's \"Raider of Treasure Trove\" can be said to revolve around the reason for man's existence: to be happy or fulfilled. The persona opines that those who are happy are likely to achieve success than those who are not. He therefore presents life as a journey where one should seek happiness and eschew rage. That is, rage constitutes one of the impediments that can restrict a person's happiness and even cut short the person's life - \"rob you of your life\". This essay will therefore discuss how rage is personified in the text.    To personify means to give an inanimate or abstract object human qualities. Here, rage can be regarded as abstract because it is a quality that can neither be seen nor touched. In the text, rage is personified as it is given human qualities in a bid to show the effect it can have on an individual. Important to note is that none of these effects can be deemed as positive; rather, rage is presented as a killer, thief and other epithets.    Firstly, rage is regarded as chief of all the things that could rob a person of his life: that is, a killer. By this, the persona unequivocally places rage as a destroyer who must never be entertained by anyone. This pattern of branding rage a destroyer is further seen in the subsequent lines where rage is given the ability to drag a thing - \"rage drags rags\". Undoubtedly, the image created in this extract is one of destruction; that is, instead of bringing about positivity, rage brings negativity, dirt and destruction, all of which are metaphorically marked as \"rags\".    In addition, rage is regarded as \"a thief\". It is one that steals laughter, sweetness and light. Of course, the ability of rage to perform these tasks that are reserved for humans constitutes a personification of rage. Apart from being a thief, rage is also regarded an \"enemy of equanimity\". Equanimity suggests a calm state of mind that means that you do not become angry or upset, especially in difficult situations. Rage, therefore, erodes this calmness by causing trouble and spelling or bringing about calamity.     The persona, thus, admonishes against rage. He warns humans of the consequences of rage by personifying rage as a killer, thief and bringer of calamity. In conclusion, this essay has been able to comment on the personification of rage in Lade Wosornu's \"Raider of Treasure Trove\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section C>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Show how Africa suffered and survives still in Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\" is one that retells the suffering experienced by Africa and its inhabitants under the cruel oppression of her colonial masters. The poem graphically depicts events such as colonialism and slavery, and shows the inimical effects they have had on Africa. However, despite all these nefarious acts done, Africa and her inhabitants still survive. The reason for their survival is owing to the dogged spirit of every African. On this note, this essay will show how Africa suffered and how it has managed to survive the hardship meted by the colonialists.    Of course, it is no news that the coming of Western powers caused untold hardship to Africans. In this text, the suffering experienced by Africa is brought to the fore through the anaphora - \"The grieved lands...\" Another way this was done was through the Trans-Atlantic Slave Trade where many Africans were ferried across the Atlantic to serve as slaves in plantations. This act is well captured by the persona in the first stanza where he made reference to \"ancient and modern slave\" and \"...degrading sweat of impure dance of other seas\". The reference to \"sea\" can be seen as an allusion to the slave trade that occurred across the Atlantic. Thus, it can be justifiably said that Africa suffered as a result of slavery.    Apart from selling off many Africans into slavery, Africa was also subjected to colonial humiliation. This humiliation is evinced through the way the colonialists came to Africa and imposed their will on its inhabitants. Because these colonialists believed their ways to be superior to African cultures, they forcefully made Africans to abandon indigenous cultures for westernization. This is aptly portrayed in the text where the persona describes the \"flower\" to have been \"crushed in the forest by the wickedness of the iron and the fire.\" Flower, as used, literally means African ways while \"iron and fire\" represent the destructive tools of the colonial masters. The use of the image of \"iron and fire\" to symbolise the destruction of African values shares great semblance with Kofi Awoonor's \"The Anvil and the Hammer\" where he portrays the colonialists to be blacksmiths who are reshaping African values.    Furthermore, the issue of slavery and colonialism brought about unfair laws that arrested and jailed Africans indiscriminately. Agostinho Neto does not mince words as he describes how the dreams of many Africans are cut short by their incarceration: \"In the dream soon undone in jingling of gaolers keys.\" This imprisonment of Africans further piles up their misery.     Despite all these punishment meted out to Africans, they have still survived. This survivalist attitude of Africans is highlighted in the last four stanzas. Words like \"alive, live and life\" are used to show that the African spirit has not been killed by the hardship it has been subjected to. Also, the repetition of the lines, \"They live\", in the last two stanzas is testament of the fact that Africa still survives.    One way Africa has been able to survive the onslaught of her colonialists is through the doggedness of Africans. Despite all they have suffered, Africans remain steadfast. The African spirit is believed to remain alive in dreams. Dreams, here, symbolise hope. Thus, this hope or optimism about a better future helps African to overcome their tribulations. In fact, the hardship faced in the hands of the colonial masters have only made Africans more resilient; hence, this resilience has been able to aid their survival. The fact that Africans still survive explains why the poet described them as \"imperishable particles\".    In all, despite all the suffering and hardship meted out to Africans, Africa has still managed to survive, and the persona attributes this survivalist attitude of Africans to their doggedness. This essay has therefore been able to comment in how Africa suffered and survived as depicted in Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\".", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section D>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Consider the use of alliteration, assonance and repetition in the poem, \"Binsey Poplars\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Analysis of any critical work should involve the consideration of both the elements of form and those of contents. Form, of course, refers to elements such as sound, figurative expression and rhythm while content revolves around the thematic concerns. The elements of form and content are not exclusive because they depend on one another; that is, the formal elements are used to derive the thematic concerns. This essay will therefore comment on the use of sound elements such as alliteration, assonance and repetition in Hopkins' \"Binsey Poplars\". These sound devices will be analysed based on how they are able to project the themes.    \"Binsey Poplars\" can be considered as an ecocritical poem that mourns the felling of poplar trees in Binsey Village. This destruction according to the persona is one that alters the landscape by making it less beautiful and appealing for the generations to come. The persona affinity for these trees is captured through the way he uses endearing terms to describe the trees: \"My aspens dear\". It can therefore be said that this poem revolves around the despoliation of nature.    To perspicuously describe the destruction brought my man on nature, Gerard Hopkins infuses different artistic devices that help to paint vivid pictures of man's destructive acts on nature as well as the consequences. One device that is used to serve this purpose is repetition. For instance, the repetition of \"felled\" in \"All felled, felled, are all felled\" is used to emphasize man's destructive tendencies, thus painting a picture of destruction. The consequence of this felling of poplar trees is that the scenery is changed from something beautiful to something less appealing. The repetition of \"scene\" in the last three lines brings into focus the persona's sadness at the fact that the next generation will not witness the once beautiful scenery. Note that the repetition of various words in this helps to lay emphasis on key issues.    Another major device deployed by the poet is alliteration: the repetition of similar consonant sounds at word-initial position. Alliteration as used in this text helps to add musicality and makes the text pleasurable for reading. One instance of the deployment of alliteration is seen in the extract below when the sound /f/ alliterates:    \"All felled, felled, are all felled;  Of a fresh and following folded rank\"     However, more importantly, it helps to accentuate the thematic concerns. The alliteration above undoubtedly shows the theme of destruction. Other examples of the use of alliteration include: (i) Quelled or Quenched in leaves leaping sun ( Q Alliterates); (ii) shadow that swam or sank (S Allitterate); (iii) wind wandering wind winding bank ( W Alliterates)    Apart from using alliteration, the poet also employs assonance. Assonance refers to the repetition of similar vowel sounds, usually at word-medial position. The use of assonance creates a pleasurable sound pattern as in \"dear...airy\"; \"quelled, quelled... quenched\" ; and \"felled ...felled...felled\". The vowel sounds in these words are all similar.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section D>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the Poet's attitude to death in \"Do Not Go Gentle Into That Good Night\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Thomas Dylan's \"Do not Go Gentle into that Good Night\" is a villanelle. It has six stanzas, with the first five having three lines each and the ultimate stanza with four lines. It centres on death and how men should react to it. It can be said to have been written as a form of encouragement to the persona's sick father to strive to stay alive. Important to note is that the persona affirms that death is inevitable; however, he urges everyone not to be accepting towards death. To put simply, the persona is of the opinion that people should fight against death. On this note, this essay will comment on the poet's attitude to death.    As mentioned earlier, this poem in its entirety is pervaded by death and images of death. For instance, \"good night\" is used to mean the \"end of day\", but in this context, it paints a picture of the end of a person's life. Furthermore, expressions such as \"the dying of the light\" also paint vivid images about death. Therefore, the fact that the aforementioned expressions are constantly repeated in the various stanzas of the poem show that death constitutes the focal point of the poet's attention.    The poet's attitude towards death can be said to be one of defiance. He admits in several stanzas that death is an inevitable end to life, but this does not stop him from advising against the placid acceptance of death. The title itself, \"Do not Go Gentle into that Good Night\", strengthens the stance of the poet as he unequivocally instructs against dying peacefully. To the poet, death should not be accepted gently. Thus, it is no coincidence that these very lines are echoed in the last line of some of the stanzas as a form of refrain, thereby giving further credence to the stance taken by the poet persona.    In a bid to show his defiance towards death, the persona cites several sets of people who never accept death. These individuals are classified as \"wise men\", \"good men\", \"wild men\" and \"grave men\". He admits through the wise men that death is unavoidable - \"Though wise men at their end know dark is right\" - but this fact does not make the men any less accommodating to death or the thoughts of dying. By citing these men as examples of those with the right reaction towards death, the persona is able to intensely plead with his addressee, his father, to imitate these men by staying alive.    In conclusion, by urging people to try to stay alive even when death metaphorically calls, the poet is trying to defy nature because death is an unavoidable part of nature. Taking cognizance of the all that have been written, one can justifiably say that the persona's attitude towards death is one of defiance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "BUCHI EMECHETA: Second Class Citizen    How are women treated in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Second Class Citizen is a semi-autobiographical novel that focuses on the oppression of women and racial discrimination in the society. It exposes the significance of the title of the novel, Second Class Citizen, that is, how women are treated as second class citizens while men are considered first class citizens in the Nigeria society. The novel revolves around Adah, the protagonist of the novel, who grows up with the hurdles of life due to her gender and tries to escape by migrating to London. But unfortunately, her dreams are shortened as she faces another problem of second class citizen as well as catering for her children. Women, in this novel, are treated negatively not only by men but also by the society as a whole.     They are regarded as irrelevant creatures who are not meant to be heard in the society, especially in intellectual activities. Many parents, just like in Ibuza, expect a male child to please the people and to show the importance of their families to the society. This makes them feel disappointed when they deliver baby girl because the people do not value the female gender as the male, since they end up getting married no matter their level of education. As seen in the story of Adah, she was considered \"so insignificant\" and a disappointment to her parents because she arrived as a girl when everyone was expecting a boy which made the people unconcerned about recording her birth to the extent that she pitied her parents for giving birth to her.     Apart from that, women receive blame for any evil that befall their families - husbands and children. They are never credited for a job well done, rather their husbands draw all praises to themselves despite the efforts of their wives. For instance, Adah's mother was forced to drink garri at the police station as a punishment for Adah's loss. Francis, Adah's self-centered husband, blames his wife his examination failures. And, the pronoun \"her\" is used to replace \"their\" when the children exhibit bad characters as emulating the mother and grandmother.     The oppression of women heighten as women's education is seen as a means of survival through high cost of bride price. Every male child has the freedom of education for it was regarded as a \"bright future\", while a female child is only permitted to attend school to get bigger dowry from her future husband. The society, as seen in the novel, claims that girls should be taught how to be very useful at early stage in preparation for their suitors. This is because only old men could pay high bride price in which some women find themselves unfortunate rather than being fortunate to be educated as they end up becoming wives of baldies. However, Adah was lucky to escape this dejection because of her ugliness, but she later married a man leading her to poverty.    Moreover, women in this novel are treated to be subjugated to their husbands and in-laws. This occurs especially when such a woman is a literate and earns more money than her husband. Her in-laws make her a fool in the name of \"wife\" and use sugar-coated mouth to get her do their wishes. She, then, becomes a supporter who neglects her dreams to fulfil her husband's and to please her in-laws. To illustrate, Adah thought herself lucky to escape from an unpleasant marriage until she finds herself in another problem where she neglects her dream of travelling abroad to sponsor Francis' education and to please her parents-in-law who use her to get what they want, as seen in Big Pa's advice to Francis illustrated below:     \"Where will she take the money to? Her people?...   The money is for you, can't you see? Let her go and work for    a million Americans and bring their money here, into this house.   It is your luck. You made a good choice in marriage, son.\" (p. 20)  This evidently reveals negative treatment of women inflicted by men for selfish purposes.    Nevertheless, women are treated as sex objects that can be used when it is demanded. It is unfortunate that many women suffer from moral decadence in marriage due to the dissatisfaction of their husbands. Many husbands prefer having sexual intercourse with their girlfriends despite the capability of their wives in satisfying them. And, those wives are not to complain when they find their husbands in such heart-wrenching act, as seen in the character of Adah who knew about Francis' sexual relationship with Turdy but still pretends as if she knows nothing until her son, Vicky, becomes sick.     Asides this, some women are forced to sleep with their husbands any time and receive beatings when they refuse until they give in. Adah is a good example of such women. She suffers from her husband's sentiment about a woman, \"a second-class human\", to the extent that he beats her whenever she refuses to give in when he needs her in bed. Then, he sent her out of bed to wash his clothes and cook for him at the right time, after he is done with her (p. 175).    Lastly, men are free to do whatever they like with their women. They are not reprimanded by the society, rather women have no choice but to accept what is in store for them. For example, women are used as opportunities for African men to boast of their stay in abroad, they do not care about the origin of those women as long as their marriage with them is a consolation and to defend themselves from the shame of not accomplishing their dreams. Women have no right to involve themselves in intelligent conversation for the fear of women domination. In addition, the maltreatment is not only bestowed on women but also on young females, as seen in the characters of Francis and Titi. He only cautions and threatens Titi for speaking Yoruba, but Vicky is never reprimanded. And, this threat inflict fear in the poor girl that she hardly talks to anyone since she can not speak English.     In synopsis, this essay has evidently shown how women are treated in Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen using their symbol of irrelevance, subjugation, fear, and as sexual objects to men as illustrations.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "BUCHI EMECHETA: Second Class Citizen  Consider Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen, Adah is seen as an embodiment of confidence and determination. She is the main character of this novel who depicts an act of endurance to face the challenges of life since her childhood age. She is determined and confident to be different from other women that are maltreated by the society, through education, as her pursuit of dreams. This pursuit, however, leads her into three important phases of her life, that is, from childhood to adulthood, and from adulthood to motherhood.     It all begins when Adah was birthed to the Ofili family as a female child. She knows she is considered irrelevant to her parents and the society because of her gender which made her pity her parents. The preference of a male child going to school while the opposite gender is given little or no permission to be in school as long as she can read and write. This gender discrimination instigates Adah's confidence and determination to be educated to the extent that she becomes envious and frustrated for not having the same right as her brother, Boy, to be in school.     Surprisingly, Adah's confidence and determination to pursue her dreams grows stronger that she indulges herself in mischiefs. She takes law into her hands by sending herself to school without the consent of her parents. Her determination gives her the idea of attending Methodist School since it is cheaper than Ladilak where her brother attends, and she needed to be in school by all means. Even her self-confidence makes her courageous to meet Mr. Cole, a Sierra Leonean neighbor, in the school despite his students' mockery of her - \"I came to school - my parents would not send me\" (p. 6). This shows that Adah was ready to endure pains and insults for her to be educated. And, she finds it safe to share her problems with men than women because they \"were so solid\" like she aspires to be. Moreover, Adah was happy her mother was tortured because it made her go to school, and she wasn't bothered about the strokes her father gave her for Ma's benefit.    Also, Igbo's custom of marriage makes Adah grow in determination and confidence. Their women are to degrade themselves to their husbands, whether rich or poor of which she wasn't ready to do. She needed equal rights as men to have a say in her family; and she objects to the idea of getting married to an old man who could only afford her \"high bride price.\" She was unready to be subjugated like other Igbo women, even when it brought a very bad reputation to her. In fact, she refused to be impressed despite the enticement of all the suitors with their new Raleigh bikes with flashy lights. She even stole two shillings given to her for an errand to pay her entrance examination fee in spite knowing it was wrong and never cared about the punishment and hatred she got from Cousin Vincent. She endured the pain from the strokes her cousin also gave her as long as \"she had to go to the Methodist Girls' High School or die\" (p. 17). But she later decided to marry since it was the only way to achieve her dreams.    Nevertheless, the significance of the \"Presence\" boosts Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams. It becomes an image in her mind that assures her of a brighter future and her dreams coming to reality. It creates smile on her face because its assurance suits her dreams. For instance, Adah heard the Presence telling her that she will attend one of the best schools and be successful which came true. Adah did the entrance examination with a large number of students with the demand of a few students for scholarship. And fortunately, she was among the chosen five students that was awarded scholarships. Notwithstanding, she felt the Presence no more and realized that it was just an imagination that came out of her determination to live in London which has already left her when her dream came to reality.    Furthermore, Adah's realization of racial segregation in the Western culture and of her marital life contribute to her growth in confidence and determination. She noticed that life in England was different from that in Nigeria, that is, minor things are taken seriously which almost shorten her dreams and belief in education. Starting with her first meeting with Francis who enlightened her about the idea of second class citizen, her disappointment of his poverty life as a black man, their inability to get a foster mother for her children, the rejection of her family to get an apartment, and so on. Despite all of these differences, she never gives up on the society till she finds herself lucky to be employed as a librarian in the city. Aside this, she suffers several ill-treatments from her husband who never cared about her and the children except for himself. She was determined that her marital suffering will be of the past which made her endure pains until Francis burnt her manuscript.    Her pursuit of a writing career strengthens her confidence and determination that she faced her husband for killing it. She refuses to be vulnerable like other women who had lose hope in themselves. Her hope for a brighter future instigates her old dream which makes her attempt writing. Even when she knew she was not a professional writer, she believed in herself as she was able to write a manuscript called The Bride Price which she learnt from a copy of Teach Yourself to Write, \"Write; go on and do it, you can write\" (p. 174) was what she keeps hearing. She also vows to love and care for her children since Francis neglects them. And, she defends this at the magistrate court where she told the judge, \"Don't worry, sir. The children are mine, and that is enough. I shall never let them down as long as I am alive\" (p. 185). The use of \"will\" shows that Adah is fully grown in determination and confidence for a brighter future.    In conclusion, this essay has shown Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams through the societal rejection of her gender, her desire to be in school, Igbo's custom of marriage, the significance of the Presence, racial segregation, her marital life, her writing career and her vow to cater for children in absence of her husband, Francis.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ALEX AGYEI-AGYIRI: Unexpected Joy at Dawn    Discuss Nii's encounter with I-Put-it-to-me in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I-Put-it-to-me, rarely known as Tally O, is an illegal dealer in gold. He is a frustrated citizen whose fear of poverty turns into an excessively greedy human.  He lives in Ghana, too, where some of the main characters like Nii, Joe and Aaron also abide.  Of course, his encounter with Nii brings out the element of irony in the story. Tally O has once met Nii's sister, Mama Orojo, whom she sells fake gold to in the plane. Mama has been deceived by his faked kindness that she forgets to even question his credibility for once. He appears perfect. Mama buys the gold feeling so exhilarated because she thinks she has invested her money in something that will be of immense value to her when she gets back to Nigeria. Unfortunately, the gold turns out to be against her expectation; it's forgery. A taxi driver who takes her from the airport reveal this to her knowledge.    Also, Tally O is a good friend of Joe. They are both involved in the illicit activity of gold dealing. They operate at night after they have been properly hinted on the flexibility of the gold camp and the security that hover it. Even when Mama tells Joe of her experience with I-put-it-to-me in the plane, he does not know that it is Tally O, his friend, that dupes her. It is also quite surprising that throughout the course of the story, this mystery is unravelled.     The day that Nii sets to leave Ghana for Nigeria is the same day that Mama Orojo arrives in Ghana. Despite the fact that they have both encountered similar persons, none of them takes cognisance of their resemblance till they are finally apart again. Joe knows Nii from Expense Bank so he is able to tell Mama Orojo some things about Nii when she finally confides her main mission in Ghana in him. The few encounters between the duo have a huge impact on Joe who develops a strong feeling of love for Mama at instance. He confesses his love to her on one of their searches for Nii and she accepts wholeheartedly. When Joe tells Tally O of his desire to leave their dubious life and settle down with Mama Orojo, Tally O is displeased.  He feels there's more to life than marriage and that Joe may be constraining himself by getting married. On their final operation at the mining centre, Tally O's head is cut off with an axe because he's trapped and his screaming could get them exposed and caught.    From the aforementioned, it could be deduced that the encounter between these two characters is symbolic as well as suspenseful. It also helps to build the plot and subsequently connect other characters.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "ALEX AGYEI-AGYIRI: Unexpected Joy at Dawn  Consider Mama Orojo's relationship with her church members in Amen Kristi.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Mama Orojo's relationship with her church members is a good and enviable one. She is so passionate about her evangelical duty that she carries it out without nonchalance or fear. One of the members of the church is Ibuk. In most parts of the evangelical duties, Ibuk and Mama Orojo are together till when, on a very sad day, Ibuk loses her life in a fire attack spurred by a religious riot.     Apart from Ibuk, Mama Orojo is able to bring Tom Monday into Amen Kristi. Though Tom Monday admires her, the manner at which she presents her religious arguments makes him accept the ministry wholeheartedly. Also, when Mama returns from Ghana, she goes to meet some of these members in the hope of gladdening their hearts with the news of her marriage to Joe; however, the Chairman refuses to accept her marriage for he sees it as a disloyalty to one's country as well as God. Though Mama is sad on hearing this, she still tries to convince the Chairman the more, and, eventually, desires a reason for the blatant opposition. Her good relationship with the church keeps her from staying away from them even when she is old enough to decide for herself. She still goes ahead to get engaged in the voting system proposed. Though she loses to the opposition party in the votes cast on her marriage decision, she still goes her ahead to get her wish fulfilled many because she upholds the belief that religion should not be a barrier for marriage, and that if people are to be engaged based on only religion and tribe, then the religion institutions will wallow in the discrimination it actually sets out to curtail.    Mama's release of the chairman that is trapped in the religious riot fire incident depicts her as a good religious woman who innately understands people. She could have decided to have her revenge on him for bitterly going against her decision to marry Joe, who is from another tribe and religion. But she understands that even the Chairman has nothing against her personally; he is only scared that the image of the church may be badly painted by her act and he somewhat feels Tom Monday will make a good husband for her.     In all, it's apparent that the relationship between Mama Orojo and the members of her church is a good one. She's highly respected for her effort towards facilitating the growth and development of the church, and, in most cases, always given enviable position to hold.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "RALPH ELLISON: Invisible Man    Comment on the character and role of Mary in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the narrator's experience at the Liberty paint factory hospital, Mary comes into the narrator's life as a motherly figure. She showers him with kindness and generosity. She understands his need for help; thus, she takes him into her home and treats him back to good health. Mary serves as the figure that backs the narrator up. She believes in him to be an upholder of their race. From the authorial vision, it is no surprise that she bears the name, Mary.    From the first meeting, the narrator views Mary as a mother figure as well as his guide and anchor. He also appreciates her place in his life. However, upon meeting Brother Jack and his involvement in the brotherhood; his perspective of everything, Mary inclusive, begins to change. It is at this point that the narrator begins to note the flaws - one of which is Mary being loquacious. Initially, he enjoys her cooking; now the narrator complains of the cabbage diet. Her home that naturally served as comfort to him, now becomes discomfortable as he notices the noise, poverty and filth around.    The narrator finally leaves Mary without a goodbye as he believes she will do well alone because she is black. Overall, Mary symbolically represents the black heritage and race. She represents the courage and dignity of the black people and in the narrator's bid to discard this heritage, he leaves Mary behind.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "RALPH ELLISON: Invisible Man  Examine the narrator's experiences at the eviction.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The narrator had just met a street vendor selling baked yams and experiences a nostalgic home feeling (home =the South). He buys three to eat as he walks down the street as he feels no need to hide his identity as a southern; part of which has been denial of his love for this food. He imagines his classmates' shock at seeing him have this food that represent Southern culture. He scorns them for distancing themselves from the food all in the name of neglecting their own culture. It is at this point that the narrator encounters an eviction. He saw two white men bringing out the possession of an old black couple. Other blacks stood around as this is a common occurrence. The old woman calls the narrator's attention to her predicament and this propelled him to react.    The old woman tried to return into the apartment to pray but the white men stopped her. A scuffle ensued at this point and the old woman fell. This angered the bystanders. The narrator tries to stop an impending violence from erupting as he pleaded for calmness and explained the consequence of a possible violent action. The narrator gives an emotional speech against dispossession and this urged the bystanders to stop the eviction and return the possession of the old couple back into the apartment.    It did not take long after for the police to arrive and the narrator fled as he knew he was at the forefront of this breach of law and faces a possible arrest. It is after narrowly escaping the police that the narrator meets Brother Jack who introduces him to the brotherhood which the narrator initially rebuffs.    This part of the novel is significant as the narrator has gone from one extreme to the other. The narrator has come at the back of denying his black identity to embracing this identity; first through the food scenario and further reaffirmed by his stance at the eviction. The actions of the blacks at the eviction also illustrate the powerful, although largely unacknowledged, role of black people in the struggle for freedom and equality. At the core, the narrator's emotional speech solidifies his individuality in the context of the collective black American experience, one that he has just come to embrace.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "EMILY BRONTE: Wuthering Heights    Comment on the importance of setting in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "THE IMPORTANCE OF SETTING IN EMILY BRONTE'S WUTHERING HEIGHTS    The setting of a piece of literature is the time and place in which the story takes place. The definition of setting can also include social statuses, weather, historical period, and details about immediate surroundings. Settings can be real or fictional, or a combination of both real and fictional elements.     Wuthering Heights is comprised of two main settings, one obviously being Wuthering Heights. The other is Thrushcross Grange, and together they create a perfect atmosphere filled with conflicts that match up with the plot. Wuthering Heights is a setting filled with passion and strength, but it is also filled with doomed intensity. Thrushcross Grange is filled with civility and kindness, but is filled with snobbishness. The two are complete opposites of each other; they are foils for each other in the sense that the two heighten each other's characteristics. The inhabitants of Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange are perfect representatives of everything the two settings represent.    The story is realistic set in the harsh and isolated Yorkshire moors in Northern England, Wuthering Heights practically makes a character out of its geography. The \"present day\" action of the novel takes place from 1801-1802 with the retrospective plot events occurring over the previous thirty years. All of the action happens in a small, isolated, and wild area dominated by two grand estates owned by neighboring families. Because of the geographical isolation, many conventional social rules don't seem to apply at the Heights, which is part of why Lockwood is often shocked by what he learns about the local residents.    The setting is also dominated by stormy, unpleasant weather. Lockwood explains that the word \"Wuthering\" refers to \"the atmospheric tumult to which its station is exposed in stormy weather.\" However, the Yorkshire moors can be a beautiful place as well as a violent one. As Lockwood reflects when he returns to Yorkshire at a more pleasant time of year, \"In winter, nothing is drearier, in summer nothing more divine.\" Thus, the setting also serves as a parallel to the love of Cathy and Heathcliff, stormy and devastating yet divinely powerful. This choice of setting allows for an intense and focused plot that is concentrated on a small cast of characters.     The novel's setting also plays a huge role in the lives of the new generation which consists of Cathy, the late Catherine and Edgar's daughter; Linton, the late Isabelle and Heathcliff's son; and Hareton, Hindley's son. When speaking with Linton about a perfect day in the moors, Cathy and Linton have two very different ideas of perfect. Cathy wants a lively, exciting day at the moors while all Linton wants is peace and rest. This shows how incompatible and how contrasting their characters are. Cathy is headstrong and lively like her mother, while Linton is weak and whiny like his mother.     In all, the main importance of the setting in the story is that it marks it genre out. It is the setting that enables us to quickly tag it a Gothic novel. It also gives us some hints about the events that will likely take place.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "EMILY BRONTE: Wuthering Heights  Examine the relationship between Lockwood and Heathcliff in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN LOCKWOOD AND HEATHCLIFF IN WUTHERING HEIGHTS    The relationship that exists between Lockwood and Heathcliff is a complex and unfriendly one. Lockwood is the new tenant who pays Heathcliff a visit twice at the Wuthering Heights. Mr. Lockwood is described as a wealthy gentleman who has just come to spend a year in the country at Thrushcross Grange. Heathcliff, as the owner of Thrushcross Grange, is Lockwood's landlord. Lockwood meets Heathcliff at Wuthering Heights, Heathcliff's home atop the English moors. Lockwood is struck at once by the beauty and isolation of the area His two visits to the Wuthering Heights are met with hostility and contempt. Even the male servant, Joseph, whom Lockwood thinks will help in calming Heathcliff's unfriendly nature contributes more to the adverse effect Lockwood faces at the Heights.    Initially, Mr Lockwood has thought that Heathcliff is a philanthropist who has a kind heart. This thought has sprung from Lockwood's poor observant skill. However, Lockwoord does not get to know more about Heathcliff till he visits him for a second time. Lockwood is clearly blind to the reality of the situation, although the extent of his misinterpretations is not fully realized. He is the first of many narrators (later in the story) to tell the story from a point of view that is neither omniscient nor unbiased. In fact, one could have mistaken him as the protagonist of the whole story.    On the second visit to Wuthering Heights, Lockwood gets a better sense of its strange inhabitants. Stranded at Heathcliff's home during a snowstorm, Lockwood finds his host anything but hospitable. Zillah, one of Heathcliff's servants, escorts Lockwood to a bedroom. In the bedroom, Lockwood first encounters the name of Catherine as he peruses her books. Later in the night, he experiences a nightmare or a ghostly vision, which elicits an odd response from Heathcliff. Heathcliff begs the ghost to enter Lockwood's bedroom-a plea that Lockwood does not understand at all. The next day, Heathcliff agrees to guide Lockwood back to the Grange, and Lockwood is more than happy to leave Wuthering Heights at last.    Lockwood is the one who first presents the readers with a slice of Heathcliff's heinous and brutal nature. Through the events unfolded in their encounters, the readers get to see their relationship as one which is unadmirable and that which will eventually end in disaster. When Lockwood is attacked by some violent dogs at the Heights, Heathcliff blames him for not minding his business rather than sympathizing with him or scolding the horrible dogs.    The way Heathcliff relates with Lockwood in the first and second encounters makes him to be interested in persuading Nelly to tell him everything about Heathcliff. Heathcliff's past is totally revealed and Lockwoord comes to understand the reasons behind his actions.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "John K. Kargbo: Let me Die Alone     How do men behave towards women in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The play criticises the gender roles assigned to women in the traditional society. In Senehun and Mendeland at large, women are not treated as equals of men. Women are considered fragile, vulnerable and incapable of managing crises. From the beginning of the play, Chief Gbanya  tries to relegate Madam Yoko's duties to dancing and satisfying him in bed, and not to interfere in state affairs. To Chief Gbanya such responsibility is meant for men alone. Chief Gbanya shares the same sentiment with his Chief Warrior Ndapi who beats and pounds on his wife – Jilo, at any slightest opportunity. He beats Jilo for not always serving him his food at the right time, being lazy and not looking after their daughter. Initially, Gbanya has promised Yoko she would be his successor. However, with troubles around, he feels reluctant to handover the throne to her because he believes women cannot handle a land at war. This is the same stance of Lamboi. The excuse he gives for wanting to kill Gbanya is because he does not want the latter to appoint Yoko as his successor. However, the women protest in different ways. Jilo protests by having an affair with Lansana who takes her as a human being by showers her love, admires her good looks, qualities and praises her alluring waist which is in contrast to Ndapi who rarely appreciates her food, beauty and skills in bed. Obviously, if not for Yoko's doggedness and insistence, a woman would not have become the chief of Mendeland; talk more of expanding the chiefdom.  In Mendeland, women usually are not allowed into the Poro cult. Yoko is the only exception. In the village, there is a certain prejudice held against women. They are considered inferior and except for Yoko who forges ahead, women are not assigned ruling positions.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "John K. Kargbo: Let me Die Alone   Discuss Gbanya as a remarkable character", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Chief Gbanya is a great leader and warrior who chooses his wars carefully. He does not keep his promise to choose Yoko as his successor. He foresees his death and hopes he doesn't die a humiliating death. Hence, he decides not to ambush the Governor and his envoy instead he receives the Governor with a fun fare which leads to his humiliation in the presence of his chiefs. Chief Gbanya was poisoned and he died knowing that his most trusted person betrayed him and handed leadership of Senehun to Yoko.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA:  The Lion and the Jewel     How is the contest between tradition and modernity presented in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "One of the primary conflicts of the play pits traditional Yoruba customs against a western conception of progress and modernity, as represented by the conflict between Baroka and Lakunle for Sidi's hand in marriage.  Lakunle represents the modern Nigerian man. He wears western clothing, has been educated in a presumably British school, and wants to turn his village into a modern paradise like the city of Lagos. Lakunle doesn't just admire and idolize western society; he actively and loudly despises the traditional customs of his village and the people who support them. This is best illustrated by Lakunle's refusal to pay Sidi's bride price.   For much of the play, other characters describe Baroka as being directly opposed to modernity and extremely concerned with preserving his village's traditional way of life. Lakunle, in particular, finds Baroka's lifestyle abhorrent. He describes how Baroka paid off a surveyor to not route train tracks through the outskirts of Ilujinle, thereby robbing the village of a link to the modern world that would modernize the village. However, when Baroka himself speaks, it becomes apparent that he doesn't actually hate modernity or progress. While he obviously delights in the joys and customs of village life, when it comes to modernity he simply hates having it forced upon him. He sees more value in bringing modern customs to the village on his own terms. For example, he argues that creating a postal system for the village will begin to bring it into the modern world without entirely upending the village's way of life.   The competition between Baroka and Lakunle for Sidi's hand in marriage brings the conflict between tradition and modernity to life. Baroka wishes to add Sidi to his harem of wives, while Lakunle dreams of having one wife who, in theory at least, is his equal. Both men promise Sidi a different version of power and fulfillment. When Baroka dies, Sidi will become the head wife of the new Bale, a position that would make her one of the most powerful women in the village. Lakunle, on the other hand, offers Sidi the possibility of an equal partnership in which she's not required to serve her husband as is traditional. The presence of Lakunle represents the British Colonial Government forcing their culture on Nigeria's traditional belief system which downgrades the personality of Africa as primitive and barabaric. Lakunle, in his show of modern romance kisses Sidi and she describes that as unclean and he never denies that yet calls Sidi's dressing and mannerism as barbaric.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "WOLE SOYINKA:  The Lion and the Jewel   Discuss the significance of the use of play-within-a play technique.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This is stressed again by the recollection of the Stranger's entry into Ilujinle. The characters in The Lion and the Jewel (notably the Girls, Lakunle, Sidi, and much later Baroka) enact a play within the play, assigning themselves roles.    Play-within-a play is one of the device commonly employed by playwrights in which the characters of a play perform brief dramatic sketches in the course of the play. In this play, it is used as a form of flashback in \"The dance of the lost traveler\" to enact the experience of the Lagos visitor. Through the play, the audience gains an insight into the ordeal of the Lagos visitor during his first visit who has problems with his car and has to abandon it to continue his exploration on foot.    The second play is dramatized to illustrate how Baroka bribes the surveyor to divert the railway track from llujinle.  The third play is called \"The dance of virility employed to mock Baroka which involves a combination of music, mime, and movement meant to entertain the characters themselves.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN, OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger     Consider Jimmy's views about the Victorian society of his time.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jimmy Porter is illustrative of an entire culture wistful for past glory. He romanticizes the past even while mocking those who could not understand the change in times. In a time of crucial transition from Britain's Victorian past into the modern twentieth century, Jimmy's rage is an expression of pent-up emotion in an inert and dull world. That anger became a symbol of the rebellion against the political and social malaise of British culture.  Class disparity, troubled childhood and social imbalance all contribute to Jimmy's anger. Jimmy Porter is from the lower class but hates the higher class because of his not being able to be like them or enjoy their privileges. Coincidentally, he married a girl from the upper class (Alison that is) and it is only logical that he would unleash his hatred, anger and frustration on Alison who in this context is an effigy of the higher class he hates. Besides, he has been through a lot. He lost his father when he was five. The latter died in his arms. Despite having a university degree, he still could not find his way into the upper class. Instead, he finds himself working in a small candy stall. These, to a large extent, make for his anger in the play.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "JOHN, OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger   Comment on Alison's reactions to Jimmy's attacks on her family.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Alison Porter, Jimmy's wife. A woman of upper-middle-class background, she is perceptive enough to understand that her husband resents everything in her that reminds him of the social differences between them. After three years of marriage, she is miserable. The only way that she can survive Jimmy's constant verbal attacks on her and on her family is to conceal her feelings and remain silent. Although she says that Jimmy is the only man she has ever loved, Alison so yearns for peace that, with the encouragement of her friend Helena, she finally leaves him without telling him that she is pregnant. After losing the baby, she returns to Jimmy, begs his forgiveness for betraying him, and promises that because she has experienced suffering, she can now be the kind of wife he wants and needs.  Alison is aware of the fact that Jimmy is trying to make her angry. She knows that if she give any reaction to his attacks he will be triumphant. Alison's submissive and silent manner against Jimmy's assaults is also a way of expressing aggression because of the fact that she reach  passive aggressively.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AUGUST, WILSON:  Fences     How does Troy's upbringing influence his relationship with his children?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The theme of \"fathers and sons\" is one of the pillars of the play \"Fences\", connecting the stories of three generations of the Maxson family. Troy's difficult relationship with his own father shapes him as a parent and his relationship with Lyon and Cory. Maxson man's path to manhood include the act of defiance against their fathers, fleeing their home and finally internalizing them. Troy's struggles as a father and son is a representation of the importance of the father-son relationship and how that shapes the character of the sons.   Troy and his father's relationship is influenced by the times, because Troy's father grew up in the 1800s after slavery was abolished, and for him to be raised in that environment ultimatley influenced how he painted his children and how he showed affection to them. Troy's perception of what is right and what is wrong for Cory, based on Troy's refusal to perceive a historical change in the acceptance of Black people, tragically causes Cory to experience a disappointing fate similar to Troy's. Troy passes his personal history on to his family in other ways throughout the play with sayings that represent his philosophies of life like, \"You gotta take the crookeds with the straights.\" His children also inherit Troy's past by learning songs he sings like, \"Hear It Ring! Hear It Ring!\" a song Troy's own father taught him. Cory tells Rose in Act Two, scene five, \"Papa was like a shadow that followed you everywhere.\" Troy's songs and sayings link his family to the difficult life in the south that his generation was free to run away from, though penniless and without roots in the north. Troy's purposefully and inadvertently passes on his life experience to his children.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "AUGUST, WILSON:  Fences   To what extent does Gabriel provide comic relief in the play?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Gabriel, or Gabe, is Troy's brother. He's the only sibling Troy is still in touch with, though they grew up in a large family. Gabe suffered a traumatic head injury in World War II that left a metal plate in his head. Gabriel wanders around the Maxson family's neighbourhood carrying a basket and singing. He often thinks he is not a person, but the angel Gabriel who opens the gates of heaven with his trumpet for Saint Peter on Judgment Day.   Gabriel is the wise fool, a character who often sounds silly or nonsensical, but who often knows more about the characters around him than they know about themselves. When he talks to his brother Troy in riddles about hellhounds and St. Peter in Act I, Scene Two, Gabe seems to observe Troy's fates with clarity. He tries, in his playful language, to warn Troy of his tragic fate. When Troy dies, Gabriel prays for his brother to be received in heaven.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How effective is the use of contrast in  The Song of the Women of my Land ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Sesay's \"Song of the Women of my Land'' examines the human condition, the suffering of women, oppression, pain, the ravages of time and death. Social criticism is at the heart of this poem. The poem further underscores the point that people die but artists or poets have the ability to preserve them in their art, for all eternity. Contrast is dominant in the poem and encompasses more in the use of metaphors and similes.  \"They ploughed the terrain of their mindscape/ for a song\" – This metaphor describes their minds as a garden or farmland that is ploughed in preparation for the sowing of seeds. This figure of speech suggests how they thought very seriously about the most appropriate song that can capture or describe their pathetic situation.  \"They sponged off their anguish.\" -This is a very powerful metaphor that compares the way people mop floors or swab wounds to the way the women use their song to ease their anguish. This is almost therapeutic. This metaphor conveys not only what the women have in their lives (they do have a song) but more importantly, what they do not have in their lives – men. That is, they lack men who can champion their cause, or heal their pain and they now use their song as a balm for their agony.    The above excerpts are examples of how the poet uses vivid differences to show similarities and emphasize the central idea of the poem.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine  The Leader and the led as a criticism of leadership in Africa", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"The Leader and the Led\" by Professor Niyi Osundare is an allegorical poem that avers the kind of leadership in Africa and what leadership ought to be. The poem establishes the cat and mice relationship that exists between African leaders and their followers.    The poet's African origin and the siting of the tropics as the meeting place of the animals unmistakably point Africa as the point of reference in the poem. The poet no doubt addresses the eyesore of leadership deficiency Africa as a continent is plagued with. Osundare first addresses the issues of bad leadership, leadership ineptitude, and gross misgovernance which have become the rallying cries for many short-changed African followers. The poet, as he does, examines the kind of relationship that exists between African leaders and their followers. He then typifies the type of leadership peculiar to African countries since their purported independence from European colonialists.    The poet uses the attributes, bodily features and predatory ability of some of the contending animals as proofs of the leadership inadequacies Africa is beset with. In \"the lion\" and \"the hyena\", Osundare shows African leaders as exploiters and oppressors. With their powers, they exploit Africa and its citizenry of resources and oppress the people they are supposed to lead. This makes them ideal replacements of their equally exploiting colonial masters. In the the typical ways of \"the lion\" and \"the hyena\", these leaders endanger the lives of those whom they have sworn to protect. In \"the lion\", the poet uses \"the ferocious pounce of his paws\" on antelopes as an analogy of the deliberate and calculated oppression of the citizenry by the machinery of the state. The poet also portrays the elitism of African leaders typified by the farness of the giraffe's eyes from the ground. African leaders are only close to the people before assuming power or when they are seeking for votes into elective posts. Once they assume power, they distance themselves from the masses. In \"the zebra\", the poet references the dubiousness and deceptiveness of African leaders. Using \"the duplicity of his stripes\" as a focal point, the poet posits that African leaders can not be trusted to do anything right or taken for what they say or on the face value because behind their sugar-coated lies are several ulterior motives. Like \"the pack\" of animals, the people are justifiably suspicious of their leaders' \"duplicity\".    No doubt, Niyi Osundare's \"The Leader and the Led\" has done justice in its depiction of the type of leadership in Africa. The poem figuratively describes African leaders as \"ferocious\", \"lethal\" in appetite, duplicitous, greedy, \"riotous\" and \"trampling\". The poem, however, offers insights on what ideal leadership is. It says ideal leadership embodies transparency, compassion, humility, legitimacy, the will to govern, the readiness to listen to the followers, and a balance between ideas on the opposite sides of the fringe.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Consider the mood of the person in  The Good Morrow .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The subject matter of the poem circles around the nature and completeness of the lovers' world. Donne takes the everyday idea that lovers are engulfed in a world of their own; thus, they are oblivious to reality as it appears as though the outside world is not real. The intensity of their love is sufficient to create its own reality. The poem depicts love as a feeling that surpasses other feelings and one that thrives against odds.In typical Donne's fashion, the poem takes the reader right into the bedroom which is the crucible of passion and thought.  In this poem, Donne employs a dramatic and ecstatic tone. He begins on a note of restraining excitement in the expression of the feeling of love shared between himself and his lover. He marginalizes their feelings and places them above all and against odds. He compares their love to two hemispheres of the world and theirs is perfect. This, thus, evokes a romantic mood through the poem.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2022>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Discuss the theme of regret in  The Journey of the Magi .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"Journey of the Magi\", is one of the four Ariel Poems written by Eliot during 1927 and 1930. It is in the form of a monologue in which a magus, one of the Three Wise Men who came from the East to Bethlehem to see the infant Jesus, narrates their journey long after the event, and analyses its impact on their imagination. It was written by Eliot soon after his conversion to Catholicism. The agony of parting with one faith and embracing another is therefore the theme of the poem. In order to express this feeling, Eliot, according to his poetic practice, chooses the biblical alibi of the journey of the three Wise Men f rom the East to Bethlehem to see the Incarnation. Eliot believes that \"poetry is not a turning loose of emotion, but an escape from emotion; it is not the expression of personality, but an escape from personality' So to escape from his emotion of agony and his personality, he dissolves himself in the emotion and personality of the Magi placed in a similar situation.  The poem is in the form of a monologue. One of the Magi, long after their journey, narrates the event in the end he analyses with uneasiness the impact of the journey on their imagination. He accepts the birth of the new faith. But he does not understand its significance. He is also unwilling to relinguish his pagan way of life which Christ has come to destroy. His \"hard and bitter agony is as painful as that of the poet who is enchained to the past and unable to submit to a transition.  The Magi began journey during the worst time of the year. It was the very dead of winter. The journey was long and the ways were deep and hard. The camels on which they travelled were galled, sore-footed and refractory. They often lay down in the melting snow. The Wise Men felt sorry for leaving their summer palaces and the silken girls bringing sherbet. The camel men cursed complained and ran far away for want of liquor and women. They had no nightfires or shelter. The cities were hostile and the towns unfriendly. The villages were dirty and changed his sprices. At last they decided to travel by night sleeping only in snatches. All along, their voice of reason was reminding them that their action was foolish. The last part of the poem is more blatantly the Magus reminiscing about the story (\"all this was a long time ago, I remember\"), and in his recollection, he seems to be doubtful about whether or not the birth was a good or bad, replacing as it would his own religion and culture. In fact, at the end of the poem, he seems to regard it as a bad thing indeed, with the Magus wishing for his own death alongside the death of his peoples' conventional beliefs; hence, regret.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: SECOND CLASS CITIZEN    Examine the contributions of Adah's first day at the Methodist school to the development of the plot.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Adah's first day at the Methodist school is a significant event in the plot development of 'Second Class Citizen'. It marks the beginning of Adah's journey towards self-discovery and independence. The school serves as a platform for Adah to escape from her oppressive home environment and to explore her intellectual capabilities. Her experiences at the school, including her interactions with her teachers and peers, shape her character and influence her future decisions. The school also exposes Adah to the harsh realities of gender and class discrimination, which further fuels her determination to overcome societal barriers. Therefore, Adah's first day at the Methodist school contributes significantly to the development of the plot.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: SECOND CLASS CITIZEN  Why does Mr Noble find it difficult to evict his tenants?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Second Class Citizen', Mr. Noble finds it difficult to evict his tenants due to several reasons. Firstly, he is bound by the legal and contractual obligations that protect the rights of the tenants. Evicting them without a valid reason could lead to legal consequences. Secondly, Mr. Noble is also influenced by his moral and ethical considerations. Despite his personal discomfort with the tenants, he recognizes their right to shelter and is reluctant to render them homeless. Lastly, Mr. Noble is also aware of the social implications of eviction. He fears the potential backlash from the community and the damage to his reputation. Therefore, these legal, ethical, and social factors make it difficult for Mr. Noble to evict his tenants.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: UNEXPECTED JOY AT DAWN    What impression do you form of Mama Orojo?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Unexpected Joy at Dawn', Mama Orojo is portrayed as a strong, resilient, and compassionate woman. Despite her personal hardships, she remains committed to her family and community. She is a source of strength and support for her children, often sacrificing her own needs for their well-being. Her resilience is evident in her ability to endure adversity and maintain her optimism. Mama Orojo's compassion is reflected in her interactions with the less fortunate members of her community. She is often seen helping others and advocating for social justice. Therefore, the impression formed of Mama Orojo is that of a strong, resilient, and compassionate woman.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: UNEXPECTED JOY AT DAWN  Consider the contribution of Massa and Marshak to the development of the plot?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Unexpected Joy at Dawn', Massa and Marshak play crucial roles in the development of the plot. Massa, as the protagonist's friend, serves as a catalyst for the protagonist's transformation. His experiences and perspectives challenge the protagonist's beliefs and prompt him to question his own values. Marshak, on the other hand, represents the oppressive forces in society. His actions and attitudes towards the protagonist highlight the societal barriers that the protagonist must overcome. Both characters, through their interactions with the protagonist, contribute to his character development and the progression of the plot.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: INVISIBLE MAN    How does the advive of the narrator's grandfather influence his actions?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Invisible Man', the narrator's grandfather's advice significantly influences his actions. The advice, which encourages the narrator to 'overcome 'em with yeses, undermine 'em with grins, agree 'em to death and destruction', serves as a guiding principle for the narrator. It shapes his approach towards dealing with racial discrimination and societal expectations. The narrator often finds himself resorting to deception and subversion, as suggested by his grandfather, to navigate the oppressive society. However, the advice also causes internal conflict within the narrator, as he struggles to reconcile his personal identity with the societal roles imposed upon him. Therefore, the grandfather's advice plays a pivotal role in influencing the narrator's actions and his journey towards self-discovery.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: INVISIBLE MAN  Examine the ideology of the Brotherhood in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the novel 'Invisible Man' by Ralph Ellison, the Brotherhood represents a socialist organization that aims to fight for the rights of the oppressed and marginalized. The ideology of the Brotherhood is based on the principles of equality, justice, and fraternity. They believe in the power of collective action and the importance of unity in achieving their goals. However, the protagonist becomes disillusioned with the Brotherhood as he realizes that they are using him as a tool for their own political agenda. The Brotherhood's ideology is revealed to be flawed as they are willing to sacrifice individuals for the sake of their cause. This critique of the Brotherhood reflects Ellison's critique of ideological rigidity and the dangers of losing one's individuality in the pursuit of collective action.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: WUTHERING HEIGHTS    Consider Heathcliff's marriage to Isabella.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Wuthering Heights' by Emily Bronte, Heathcliff's marriage to Isabella is a complex and tragic affair. Heathcliff, driven by his desire for revenge against Edgar Linton, marries Isabella, Edgar's sister. This marriage is not based on love but on Heathcliff's need to hurt Edgar and gain control over Thrushcross Grange. Isabella, who is infatuated with Heathcliff, is unaware of his true intentions and is ultimately victimized by him. Heathcliff's treatment of Isabella reveals his cruel and vindictive nature. The marriage serves as a tool for Heathcliff's revenge and highlights his destructive and self-destructive tendencies.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2023>SECTION B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: WUTHERING HEIGHTS  Discuss the use of \"the weather' \"the window\" and \"the setting\" as symbols in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 'Wuthering Heights', Emily Bronte uses various symbols to enhance the themes and emotions of the novel. The weather, the window, and the setting are significant symbols in the novel. The weather often mirrors the emotional state of the characters and the intensity of their experiences. Stormy weather often accompanies moments of emotional turmoil. The window is a symbol of separation and longing, as characters often look through windows longing for what they cannot have. The setting of the novel, the Yorkshire moors, symbolizes the wild and untamed nature of the love between Catherine and Heathcliff. The harsh and rugged landscape reflects the tumultuous and passionate relationship between the two characters.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: Second Class Citizen    How is conflict in marriage portrayed in the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen, the portrayal of marital conflict is a central theme that underscores the struggles of the protagonist, Adah, and highlights broader issues of gender, identity, and cultural clash. The novel provides a examination of marriage through the lens of Adah's experiences, revealing the complexities and often harsh realities faced by women in traditional and expatriate settings.    The marital conflict in Second Class Citizen is deeply intertwined with traditional gender roles and expectations. Adah's marriage to Francis is emblematic of the patriarchal norms that dictate the dynamics between husband and wife. Francis embodies the traditional male authority figure who expects to dominate the relationship. His behavior is reflective of the societal norms that see women as subordinate and primarily responsible for domestic duties. This dynamic is evident in his disregard for Adah's aspirations and his insistence on her adhering to his demands, such as prioritizing domestic chores over her personal ambitions.    Adah's struggle against these traditional roles forms the backbone of the marital conflict. Her desire for education and personal growth is continually stifled by Francis's expectations and control. The conflict escalates as Adah's growing independence and ambition clash with Francis's rigid adherence to traditional roles, leading to frequent arguments and emotional distress. The portrayal of this conflict highlights the oppressive nature of gender roles within marriage and the personal sacrifices women often make to fit these roles.    The novel also explores the conflict arising from cultural differences and its impact on marital relations. Adah and Francis's move to England introduces a new layer of complexity to their relationship. The clash between Nigerian cultural expectations and the realities of life in a Western society creates additional strains. In England, Adah faces the challenges of racial discrimination, economic hardship, and the struggle to adapt to a new cultural environment. Francis's inability to adapt and his refusal to support Adah's efforts further exacerbate the marital discord.  The cultural clash is particularly evident in Francis's disdain for Adah's attempts to integrate into British society and her desire to pursue a career. His attitude reflects a broader resistance to change and a lack of understanding of the challenges Adah faces as a woman of color in a foreign land. This conflict reveals the tension between personal identity and cultural expectations, as Adah struggles with maintaining her Nigerian identity while navigating the demands of her new environment.  Economic factors play a significant role in the marital conflict portrayed in the novel. The financial difficulties faced by the family contribute to the power imbalance between Adah and Francis. Adah's efforts to contribute economically and improve their situation are often undermined by Francis's reluctance to support her ambitions or share in the responsibility of family finances. This economic strain not only adds to the stress of the relationship but also reinforces the power dynamics, with Francis exerting control over the family's resources and decisions.  Adah's struggle to assert her independence despite the economic constraints highlights the intersection of gender and economic power. Her attempts to improve their financial situation and gain financial autonomy are met with resistance from Francis, reflecting the broader societal issues related to women's economic empowerment and their role within the family unit.  The emotional and psychological impact of the marital conflict is depicted in Adah's experiences. The constant strain and friction in her marriage lead to feelings of isolation, inadequacy, and frustration. Adah's internal conflict is mirrored in her external struggles, and the novel captures the emotional toll of living in a dysfunctional and oppressive relationship.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: Second Class Citizen    Examine the relationship between Adah and Bill", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen, the relationship between Adah and Bill is an important aspect of the story that reveals much about Adah's evolving personal identity and her struggle for independence. Adah's interaction with Bill provides a contrast to her troubled marriage with Francis and highlights her quest for autonomy in a foreign land.    Bill enters Adah's life as a colleague at a local school where Adah works. Unlike Francis, who is controlling and dismissive of Adah's ambitions, Bill treats her with respect and admiration. This new dynamic offers Adah a glimpse of how relationships can be built on mutual respect and support. Bill's professional and personal interest in Adah provides her with a sense of validation and recognition that she has been missing in her marriage. The relationship between Adah and Bill starkly contrasts with her relationship with Francis. While Francis is often domineering and unsupportive, Bill represents a more egalitarian approach to relationships. Bill's genuine interest in Adah's well-being and career aspirations stands in direct opposition to Francis's disregard for her goals. This contrast highlights the significant issues within Adah's marriage and underscores her feelings of entrapment and disillusionment.    Adah's interactions with Bill help her reassess her own life and choices. The respect and kindness she receives from Bill make her reflect on the possibilities of a different kind of relationship—one where she is valued and not merely constrained by traditional roles. Bill's support and encouragement contribute to Adah's growing sense of self-worth and autonomy, making her question the sustainability of her relationship with Francis.    The relationship with Bill also plays a role in Adah's personal growth. Bill's presence in her life encourages her to think about her own needs and desires, separate from her obligations to Francis and the constraints of her marriage. This relationship becomes a catalyst for Adah's journey toward self-discovery and independence. Bill's support acts as a mirror, reflecting the possibilities of a life where Adah's ambitions and individuality are not only recognized but nurtured.    In summary, the relationship between Adah and Bill in Second Class Citizen highlights the contrast between Adah's restrictive marriage with Francis and the potential for a more supportive and respectful relationship. Bill's positive influence serves as a turning point for Adah, pushing her toward self-realization and challenging the constraints imposed by her marriage. Through this relationship, Adah begins to envision a different future for herself, one that aligns more closely with her aspirations and sense of self.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: Unexpected Joy at Dawn    Discuss the meeting between Ni Tackie and Tally O", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Alex Agyiri's Unexpected Joy at Dawn, the meeting between Ni Tackie and Tally O is a significant moment that highlights themes of identity, perception, and the clash between tradition and modernity. This encounter is pivotal in illustrating the contrasting worlds that the characters inhabit and the impact of these differences on their interactions.    Ni Tackie, a traditionalist and a wealthy landowner, embodies the values and customs of his upbringing. He is portrayed as a man deeply rooted in traditional practices and social hierarchies. His demeanor and attitudes reflect a life that values social status and adherence to established norms. On the other hand, Tally O represents the modern, progressive elements of society. His character is marked by a more liberal outlook, one that embraces change and challenges conventional beliefs.    When Ni Tackie and Tally O first meet, their interaction is charged with tension due to their differing worldviews. Ni Tackie, with his deep respect for tradition, views Tally O's modern approach and attitudes with suspicion. He perceives Tally O as a threat to the established order, seeing his progressive views as disruptive to the traditional values that Ni Tackie holds dear.    Tally O, conversely, is critical of Ni Tackie's rigid adherence to tradition. He challenges the status quo and questions the relevance of Ni Tackie's old-fashioned beliefs in a rapidly changing world. This conflict of perspectives is evident in their conversation, where each character attempts to assert their own values while dismissing the other's as outdated or irrelevant.    The meeting between the two is not merely a clash of personalities but also a reflection of broader societal shifts. Ni Tackie's resistance to change and Tally O's embrace of modernity symbolize the generational and ideological divide present in their society. Their interaction underscores the difficulties in bridging this divide and finding common ground.    Despite the initial hostility, the meeting also reveals underlying similarities between Ni Tackie and Tally O. Both characters are driven by strong convictions and a desire to shape their world according to their beliefs. This common ground hints at the possibility of understanding and reconciliation, even amidst their apparent differences.    In conclusion, the meeting between Ni Tackie and Tally O in Unexpected Joy at Dawn serves as a microcosm of the broader conflict between tradition and modernity.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "AFRICAN PROSE: Unexpected Joy at Dawn    Examine Nii's rejection of Linda's advances", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Alex Agyiri's Unexpected Joy at Dawn, Nii's rejection of Linda's advances is a pivotal moment that reveals deep-seated social and personal dynamics. This rejection is not merely a personal choice but is intricately tied to broader themes of societal expectations, personal values, and the struggle between tradition and modernity.    Nii's decision to reject Linda stems primarily from his adherence to traditional values and cultural expectations. In the context of the novel, Nii represents a character grounded in cultural and societal norms. His rejection of Linda's advances is a manifestation of his commitment to these norms, which dictate that relationships and courtships should follow a certain decorum and respectability. Linda's advances, which are seen as bold and untraditional, challenge these norms, putting Nii in a position where he must choose between his personal desires and his adherence to societal expectations.    This conflict is further complicated by Nii's own personal values and self-concept. Nii's rejection is not solely based on external pressures but also reflects his internal struggle with his sense of identity and propriety. He perceives Linda's actions as a threat to his self-image and the image he wishes to project within his community. By rejecting Linda, Nii is not only adhering to societal expectations but also protecting his own sense of dignity and personal integrity. The rejection thus becomes a means for Nii to assert control over his life and preserve his self-respect.    Furthermore, Nii's rejection highlights the broader theme of traditional versus modern values within the novel. Linda's advances symbolize a departure from traditional norms, representing modernity and a shift in social dynamics. Nii's refusal to engage with Linda's advances underscores his resistance to these changes and his desire to maintain a connection with the traditional values that he feels are integral to his identity and social standing. This clash between the traditional and the modern is central to the novel's exploration of societal change and personal values.    In addition, Nii's rejection of Linda can be seen as a reflection of the broader societal pressures and expectations placed upon individuals in the context of relationships and social interactions. The pressure to conform to traditional norms and the fear of social judgment play a significant role in shaping Nii's decision. His rejection of Linda's advances is not just a personal choice but a response to the societal forces that dictate appropriate behavior and relationships.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: Invisible Man  How is the epilogue significant to the structure of the novel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Ralph Ellison's Invisible Man, the epilogue plays a crucial role in shaping the novel's structure and thematic development. This concluding section is significant for several reasons: it provides closure to the protagonist's journey, reinforces key themes, and offers a reflective perspective on the narrative.    The epilogue brings the protagonist's journey full circle, offering a sense of resolution to the story. Throughout the novel, the protagonist grapples with issues of identity, invisibility, and self-discovery. The epilogue reveals that he has retreated into a basement, where he reflects on his experiences and the lessons learned. This retreat is symbolic of his desire for introspection and understanding. By revisiting his earlier experiences and recognizing his invisibility, the protagonist achieves a deeper understanding of his place in society and his own identity. The epilogue thus provides a concluding moment of self-realization and acceptance, completing the arc of his personal growth.    The epilogue underscores several central themes of the novel. One of the most prominent themes is the concept of invisibility, which is explored throughout the text. The protagonist's retreat into the basement represents his acknowledgment of his invisibility and the ways it has affected his life. It highlights the ongoing struggle of finding visibility and recognition in a society that often ignores or marginalizes individuals. Additionally, the epilogue reinforces the theme of identity, as the protagonist's reflections reveal his understanding of how his identity has been shaped by external forces and his own experiences.    The epilogue offers a reflective perspective on the entire narrative, allowing readers to see the protagonist's journey from a new vantage point. It serves as a moment of contemplation, where the protagonist assesses the significance of his past actions and experiences. This reflection provides insight into the broader implications of the narrative and invites readers to consider the larger social and philosophical questions raised by the novel. By looking back on his journey, the protagonist and the readers can evaluate the impact of the events and themes explored throughout the story.    Structurally, the epilogue connects with the novel's beginning and middle sections. It mirrors the protagonist's initial sense of disconnection and invisibility, but with added depth and understanding gained from his experiences. This connection between the beginning and the end of the novel helps to unify the narrative and emphasize the protagonist's development. The epilogue's reflection on the protagonist's experiences creates a cohesive structure, linking the various themes and events of the novel.    In summary, the epilogue of Invisible Man is significant for its role in concluding the protagonist's journey, reinforcing key themes, and providing a reflective perspective on the narrative. It ties together the novel's various elements and offers a comprehensive understanding of the protagonist's experiences and the novel's overarching messages.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: Invisible Man    Comment on the use of blindness as a metaphor.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Ralph Ellison's Invisible Man, blindness functions as a powerful metaphor that explores themes of identity, invisibility, and social alienation. This metaphor goes beyond the literal sense of physical blindness to address deeper psychological and social dimensions.    One of the most significant uses of blindness in Invisible Man is its role in symbolizing social invisibility. The protagonist, who remains unnamed, experiences profound invisibility in a society that fails to recognize his individuality and humanity. This invisibility is not due to physical blindness but stems from the way society disregards him and views him only through racial stereotypes. The metaphor of blindness captures how the protagonist is overlooked and marginalized, his identity obscured by societal prejudices. His struggle to be seen and acknowledged reflects a broader critique of a society that is blind to the experiences and contributions of Black individuals.    Ellison uses blindness to highlight the racial discrimination embedded in societal structures. The protagonist's journey reveals how racial biases can render individuals invisible, making it difficult for them to achieve recognition and equality. In various scenes, the protagonist encounters people and institutions that are metaphorically blind to his humanity and worth. For instance, when he is forced to participate in a humiliating \"battle royal\" for the entertainment of white men, his individuality and dignity are disregarded. This blindness to his humanity underscores the systemic racism that dehumanizes Black individuals, reducing them to mere objects of spectacle and control.    The metaphor of blindness also reflects the protagonist's journey toward self-discovery. Throughout the novel, he grapples with his sense of identity and struggles to understand his place in a world that perceives him as invisible. His quest for self-awareness is marked by moments of figurative blindness, where he is unable to see the truth about himself and his environment. As he moves through various phases of his life, including his experiences with the Brotherhood and his time in the underground hideout, he gradually gains insight into his own identity and the nature of his invisibility. This process of enlightenment highlights the protagonist's evolving understanding of himself and his society, moving from a state of ignorance to one of greater awareness.    Ellison's use of blindness also comments on power dynamics and control. The protagonist encounters figures who wield power over him, often through manipulation and deception. These figures are metaphorically blind to his true nature and needs, focusing instead on their own agendas. For example, the Brotherhood, which initially appears to offer a path to social change, ultimately exploits the protagonist for its own purposes. This manipulation further emphasizes the theme of blindness, as those in power fail to recognize the protagonist's individual struggles and aspirations. The protagonist's eventual retreat to the underground reflects his rejection of these deceptive forms of power and his search for a more genuine and self-aware existence.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: Wuthering Heights  Why does Heathcliff hate Hindley?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Emily Brontë's Wuthering Heights, Heathcliff's hatred toward Hindley Earnshaw is a central element of the novel, driving much of the conflict and drama. This animosity is rooted in a blend of personal grievances, social inequalities, and deep-seated resentment. To understand why Heathcliff harbors such intense hatred toward Hindley, it is essential to explore their relationship and the broader social context of their interactions.    Heathcliff's resentment toward Hindley begins with their early relationship and the social status that Heathcliff occupies in the Earnshaw household. Heathcliff is introduced as an orphan taken in by Mr. Earnshaw, who treats him with kindness and affection, often favoring him over his own biological children, Hindley and Catherine. This favoritism establishes a foundation of jealousy and competition. Hindley, who feels marginalized and overshadowed by Heathcliff's presence, begins to harbor ill feelings towards him. The preferential treatment Heathcliff receives from Mr. Earnshaw fuels Hindley's animosity and sets the stage for future conflicts.    After Mr. Earnshaw's death, Hindley inherits Wuthering Heights and immediately sets about asserting his authority and reversing the previous favoritism. Hindley's resentment toward Heathcliff intensifies as he sees an opportunity to undermine and degrade him. Hindley systematically diminishes Heathcliff's status in the household, treating him as a servant rather than an equal. This shift in power dynamics transforms Heathcliff's position from a favored child to an underprivileged servant, deepening the bitterness and sense of betrayal that Heathcliff feels.    Hindley's actions include stripping Heathcliff of any status or respect and subjecting him to harsh treatment. Heathcliff's relegation to a servant's role not only humiliates him but also fuels his desire for revenge. This constant belittling and the loss of the respect and affection he once enjoyed create a deep-seated grudge against Hindley, which becomes a driving force behind Heathcliff's actions throughout the novel.    Heathcliff's hatred toward Hindley evolves into a burning desire for revenge. The mistreatment he endures under Hindley's rule motivates Heathcliff to plot his revenge meticulously. As he acquires wealth and social power, Heathcliff begins to execute his plans to reclaim his perceived lost status and dignity. He manipulates Hindley's vulnerabilities, exploits his weaknesses, and systematically dismantles the Earnshaw estate. Heathcliff's revenge is not merely about personal vindication but also about restoring a sense of balance and justice as he perceives it.    The personal grievances Heathcliff holds against Hindley are compounded by emotional trauma. Heathcliff's early experiences of favoritism followed by abrupt humiliation create a sense of betrayal and injustice. His feelings of abandonment and rejection amplify his hatred toward Hindley, transforming a personal vendetta into a consuming obsession. This emotional trauma significantly influences Heathcliff's behavior and decisions throughout the novel, contributing to his relentless quest for revenge.    The social and class issues between Heathcliff and Hindley are also critical to understanding their animosity. Heathcliff's initial status as an adopted orphan and later as a servant creates a stark contrast to Hindley's privileged position. Hindley's disdain for Heathcliff is partly rooted in class prejudice, as he sees Heathcliff as a threat to his own social superiority. Heathcliff's eventual rise to wealth and social standing challenges Hindley's sense of superiority and exacerbates their conflict.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2024>SECTION B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE: Wuthering Heights    How does the death of Mr. Earnshaw affect the fortunes of Heathcliff?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Emily Brontë's Wuthering Heights, the death of Mr. Earnshaw is a pivotal event that dramatically alters the fortunes of Heathcliff, significantly impacting his role in the narrative and his relationship with other characters. Mr. Earnshaw's death marks the beginning of a series of events that contribute to Heathcliff's transformation from a beloved adopted son into a figure driven by revenge and bitterness.    At the beginning of the novel, Mr. Earnshaw, the head of Wuthering Heights, is a kindly and generous man who adopts Heathcliff as a child. Heathcliff is treated with affection and is considered a beloved member of the Earnshaw family. Mr. Earnshaw's death, however, leads to a profound shift in Heathcliff's circumstances.    After Mr. Earnshaw dies, his son Hindley inherits Wuthering Heights and becomes the new head of the household. Unlike his father, Hindley harbors deep resentment towards Heathcliff, whom he views as an intruder and rival to his own position. Hindley's hostility towards Heathcliff is fueled by jealousy and a sense of injustice over the favoritism his father showed towards the adopted boy. This change in leadership initiates a period of severe mistreatment and marginalization for Heathcliff.    Under Hindley's rule, Heathcliff's fortunes take a dramatic downturn. Hindley degrades Heathcliff to the status of a servant, stripping him of the privileges and respect he once enjoyed as Mr. Earnshaw's adopted son. Heathcliff's new status as an underling has both social and economic repercussions. He is subjected to harsh treatment, including physical abuse and emotional degradation, which severely affects his well-being and self-worth.    The loss of Mr. Earnshaw's protection also leaves Heathcliff vulnerable to the ill-treatment of Hindley and his allies. As a result, Heathcliff is deprived of educational opportunities and social standing, which further entrenches his position as an outcast. This economic and social decline sets the stage for Heathcliff's future actions and decisions, which are heavily influenced by a desire to seek revenge on those who have wronged him.    The mistreatment Heathcliff endures under Hindley's regime has a profound impact on his character. His initial suffering and sense of betrayal foster a deep-seated resentment and a thirst for revenge. Heathcliff's experiences of injustice and degradation shape his future actions, driving him to seek retribution against those who have contributed to his misery. Heathcliff's transformation from a victim of circumstance to a vengeful and calculating individual is a direct consequence of Mr. Earnshaw's death. His once-gentle demeanor gives way to a more ruthless and determined personality, as he devises a complex scheme to exact revenge on Hindley, Catherine Earnshaw, and others who have wronged him. Heathcliff's pursuit of vengeance becomes a central theme in the novel, reflecting the profound effect Mr. Earnshaw's death has had on his life.    The death of Mr. Earnshaw not only alters Heathcliff's immediate circumstances but also has long-term implications for his life and the lives of those around him. Heathcliff's actions, driven by the injustices he faced, lead to a cycle of suffering and turmoil that affects multiple generations. His quest for revenge and the resultant consequences shape the narrative's course and impact the fates of various characters within the novel.    In summary, Mr. Earnshaw's death marks a turning point for Heathcliff, leading to his significant social and economic decline. The subsequent mistreatment by Hindley, combined with the loss of Mr. Earnshaw's protection, drives Heathcliff to seek revenge and transform into a figure driven by bitterness and resentment. This transformation is central to the novel's exploration of themes related to social injustice, revenge, and the impact of past traumas on personal development.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Comment on the use of allusion in Second Class Citizens", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Second Class Citizen, Buchi Emecheta skillfully employs allusion to enrich the narrative and anchor Adah's personal story within broader historical, cultural, and ideological frameworks. One of the most prominent forms of allusion in the novel is to colonialism. Adah's experiences in England are not isolated events but rather reflections of the residual impact of British colonial rule in Nigeria. Her sense of displacement, marginalization, and struggle for recognition in a foreign land underscores how the legacies of imperialism continue to shape the lives of formerly colonized peoples, even after the formal end of colonial rule.    Another important thread of allusion woven into the novel is the reference to the Bible. Emecheta draws upon biblical imagery and moral teachings to illustrate how Christianity—introduced during colonial times—shapes Adah's early understanding of suffering, sacrifice, and womanhood. These religious allusions explain her initial willingness to endure oppression and hardship, as she equates patience and submission with spiritual virtue. However, as the story progresses, Adah undergoes a significant transformation, moving away from passive acceptance toward a more assertive and self-aware identity, symbolizing her growing disillusionment with rigid doctrines and her development into an empowered individual.    The novel also contains implicit allusions to the Western education system, particularly in the way Adah venerates formal schooling and intellectual advancement. Her deep desire to be educated reflects the influence of colonial ideologies that positioned Western education as the primary route to success and modernity. Through Adah's admiration for schooling, Emecheta subtly critiques how colonial narratives redefined indigenous perceptions of progress, often at the expense of native knowledge systems. The tension between aspiration and alienation in Adah's pursuit of education reveals both the promises and constraints of this inherited worldview.    Furthermore, Second Class Citizen alludes to global feminist discourses through Adah's persistent struggle for autonomy, respect, and equality in a patriarchal world. Although these feminist themes are not always explicitly labeled, they resonate with broader movements advocating for women's rights and liberation. Adah's resistance against the cultural and marital constraints imposed on her mirrors the universal challenges faced by women striving to assert their voices in societies that seek to marginalize them. Through these layered allusions—to colonialism, religion, education, and feminism—Emecheta elevates Adah's personal narrative, transforming it into a powerful exploration of identity, resilience, and social transformation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Examine Adah's experience of motherhood.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Second Class Citizen, Buchi Emecheta presents motherhood as a central and deeply complex aspect of Adah's life, portraying it as a powerful blend of affection, sacrifice, resilience, and empowerment. Adah's experience as a mother is rooted in profound love and a fierce sense of responsibility. She cherishes her children deeply and views them not only as a source of joy but also as her primary motivation to persevere through life's many hardships. In a foreign environment marked by cultural alienation, systemic racism, and domestic instability, her children become her anchor—giving her emotional strength and a reason to keep striving against all odds.    Motherhood, for Adah, is also a journey of relentless sacrifice. Time and again, she puts the welfare of her children above her own needs and desires. Despite being subjected to emotional abuse and neglect by her husband, Francis—who fails to offer meaningful support—Adah takes on the full weight of providing for the family. She accepts menial and physically demanding jobs, lives in cramped and unsanitary conditions, and endures long hours of toil to ensure that her children have access to food, shelter, and education. Her determination to secure a better future for them underscores the depth of her maternal devotion.    Yet, Adah's role as a mother is not without its sorrows and emotional burdens. She experiences the devastating loss of a child, a trauma that adds to her emotional and psychological strain. She constantly battles with anxiety over her children's well-being, particularly in a society that offers little compassion or support to immigrant women. The poverty she faces, coupled with the loneliness of raising children in a largely indifferent and sometimes hostile environment, adds layers of difficulty to her journey. Nevertheless, Adah never allows these hardships to defeat her. She continues to nurture her children with remarkable strength, even when her resources—both material and emotional—are severely limited.    Ultimately, motherhood emerges not only as a challenge but also as a powerful source of empowerment for Adah. It becomes the catalyst for her growth in courage, self-awareness, and independence. Through the responsibilities and trials of raising her children, she develops a stronger sense of identity and purpose. Her desire to break the cycle of poverty and dependence fuels her resolve to live a life of dignity and to model resilience for her children. Thus, in Emecheta's narrative, motherhood transcends traditional domestic roles and becomes a profound force that shapes Adah's evolution into a self-reliant and dignified woman. It is one of the most poignant and transformative elements of her story.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "What do you find interesting about Paleo's treatment of Nii?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paleo's treatment of Nii in Unexpected Joy at Dawn offers a compelling exploration of the tension between personal ambition and human compassion. As Nii's friend and colleague, Paleo initially appears to be a figure of loyalty and camaraderie. However, when presented with opportunities for career advancement, he becomes increasingly self-serving and emotionally detached. His decision to prioritize his own survival and professional growth over the bonds of friendship reveals how the pressures of a difficult socio-economic environment can alter personal values. This shift becomes especially evident when Paleo leverages his connections at the Ghana Commercial Bank to secure a better job for himself, leaving Nii behind to grapple with hardship and uncertainty. The speed with which friendship gives way to self-interest underscores the fragility of loyalty in times of personal opportunity.    What makes Paleo's betrayal even more striking is the way he attempts to rationalize his actions. Instead of openly acknowledging that he has abandoned Nii, he cloaks his selfishness in polite excuses and manipulative language, presenting his choices as inevitable or even beyond his control. He claims he is powerless to assist Nii, despite having access to valuable information and contacts that could have made a difference. This deceptive self-justification reflects a common human tendency: the desire to protect one's conscience while acting in ways that may harm others. Paleo's behavior becomes symbolic of a broader social pattern in which individuals—pressed by external forces—resort to self-preservation at the expense of empathy and solidarity.    Moreover, Paleo's attitude toward Nii can be interpreted as a reflection of the broader societal and political climate in which they live. Set in Ghana during a time of economic hardship and political instability, the novel shows how individuals are often compelled to act out of desperation and fear. Paleo's betrayal, while personally painful, is also part of a larger systemic reality that prioritizes individual advancement over communal well-being. In such a context, his actions are not entirely surprising; they are symptomatic of a world in which people are conditioned to look after themselves first. This adds a layer of complexity to his character—he is not merely a villain, but a product of his environment, illustrating how societal pressures can corrode even the most meaningful human connections.    Ultimately, what renders Paleo's betrayal most devastating is the emotional toll it takes on Nii. Nii had placed deep trust in Paleo, relying on their friendship as a source of stability amidst his struggles. When Paleo turns away from him, the sense of abandonment intensifies Nii's feelings of isolation and despair. The emotional wound caused by betrayal from a trusted friend is portrayed as more painful than the material hardships Nii faces. In choosing personal comfort over loyalty, Paleo unwittingly contributes to Nii's psychological suffering. Though his actions may be understandable in a context of survival and limited opportunities, they starkly illustrate how easily trust can be broken—and how, in a world driven by self-interest, even the most intimate relationships can become casualties of ambition.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Examine the use of irony in the novel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Irony functions as a powerful literary device in Unexpected Joy at Dawn, enabling Alex Agyei-Agyiri to underscore themes of social injustice, broken expectations, and the dissonance between personal identity and state-imposed definitions of belonging. Throughout the novel, irony serves not only to heighten the emotional weight of the characters' struggles but also to critique the societal and political systems that perpetuate suffering under the guise of progress and national interest.    One of the most prominent and striking instances of irony lies in the title itself—Unexpected Joy at Dawn. The phrase evokes hope, renewal, and the promise of happiness at the end of a long night. It suggests that after darkness and separation, joy and unity await. Yet, the reality experienced by the protagonists, particularly Mama Orojo and Nii Tackie, starkly contrasts this hopeful imagery. Their anticipated reunion, long delayed by the forces of history and politics, is instead marred by bureaucratic red tape, economic hardship, and political hostility. Rather than joy, they encounter frustration, alienation, and deep emotional pain. The irony lies in how what is expected to be a moment of celebration becomes a narrative of struggle and sorrow. This reversal underscores the unpredictable and often cruel nature of post-colonial realities in West Africa.    Another layer of irony is found in the treatment of immigrants during the implementation of the \"Ghana Must Go\" policy. Designed as a nationalist economic measure to reclaim jobs and resources, the policy results in the expulsion of individuals who, ironically, have long considered Ghana their home. Many of those deported—including Nii Tackie, a Ghanaian by birth—are victims of the very system they helped build. Nii is forced to flee to Nigeria, the land of his ancestry, in a bid to escape harassment and political persecution. But instead of finding refuge in a \"brotherly\" African country, he encounters suspicion, rejection, and hostility. This is the bitter irony of pan-Africanism unravelled in practice—the idea of African unity is betrayed by xenophobic policies and fractured national identities. Nii's journey, meant to be a homecoming, becomes a disorienting and dangerous quest for acceptance in places that treat him as an outsider.    Situational irony also pervades Mama Orojo's narrative. As a wealthy, devout, and socially conscious woman, she assumes that her resources and goodwill will make it easy to reunite with her brother and uplift him. However, the very systems she hopes to navigate—religious institutions, charitable efforts, and formal bureaucracies—become obstacles. Her genuine desire to help is often misread as manipulation or ambition, and her piety is met with skepticism. Despite her social status, she is repeatedly thwarted by corruption, institutional inefficiency, and a general climate of mistrust. The irony here lies in the gap between noble intent and hostile reception. The values she upholds—faith, family, generosity—are rendered almost powerless in a society where distrust and exploitation prevail.    Perhaps the most profound irony in the novel is encapsulated in the concept of \"home.\" For Nii Tackie, Ghana is the land of his birth and identity, yet he is alienated and criminalized there. In fleeing to Nigeria to trace his ancestral roots, he is again treated as a stranger. What begins as a search for identity and belonging ends in greater confusion and displacement. He becomes a man without a home, caught between two nations that both reject him. The deeper irony here is that in his effort to reconnect with his heritage, Nii instead loses his sense of rootedness altogether. The narrative reveals the tragic irony that in post-colonial Africa, the very quest for unity, identity, and belonging can lead to division, rejection, and loss.    Through these richly layered ironies, Unexpected Joy at Dawn critiques the failures of state systems, the unpredictability of human behavior, and the contradictions of identity in a fractured socio-political landscape. The novel reminds us that what is expected or promised—whether joy, unity, or belonging—often turns out to be elusive or tragically inverted, especially for those navigating the margins of society.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Examine the narrator's experience at Liberty Paint.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Invisible Man, the narrator's experience at Liberty Paints stands out as one of the most symbolically rich and revealing episodes in the novel, offering a deep critique of race relations, identity, and institutional hypocrisy in American society. The Liberty Paints factory is renowned for producing \"Optic White,\" a brand of paint marketed as the purest white available—so white, in fact, that it is used by the government itself. This detail alone sets the stage for irony: a place named \"Liberty\" manufactures a product that symbolizes erasure rather than freedom, especially the erasure of Black identity under the guise of national ideals.    The narrator is initially assigned to work in the paint mixing room under a white supervisor named Kimbro, where he is instructed to add a few drops of a mysterious black liquid into the base of the white paint. This process is both paradoxical and deeply symbolic. The black chemical is essential for achieving the paint's final white color, suggesting that Blackness, though publicly denied or repressed, is secretly integral to the very fabric of the society that pretends to exclude it. The act of mixing black into white to produce a supposedly pure product reveals the hypocrisy and hidden dependencies within the racist structures of the dominant culture. It critiques a world that loudly proclaims the supremacy of whiteness while quietly depending on Black labor, culture, and presence to sustain its image.    The narrator's encounter with Mr. Brockway, the elderly Black man who works alone in the factory's basement, adds another layer to the novel's commentary on race and power. Brockway, who guards his position jealously, represents a figure who has internalized the values of the oppressive system. Though he holds little real power, he takes pride in his secret knowledge of the factory's inner workings and fiercely defends his role against any perceived intruders—including the narrator. His hostility reflects the divisive effects of systemic oppression, which pits individuals against one another even when they share common struggles. This internalized fear and suspicion culminate in a violent confrontation between the two men, leading to a literal explosion—a moment that powerfully symbolizes the destructive potential of a system that fosters competition among the oppressed rather than solidarity.    Following the explosion, the narrator is taken to the factory hospital, where he undergoes brutal electric shock treatment under the supervision of emotionless, dehumanizing doctors. This procedure, conducted without his consent, further strips him of his identity and agency. The shock therapy—resembling a form of reprogramming—serves as a chilling metaphor for the way society erases individuality and enforces conformity, especially among those who challenge or deviate from prescribed social roles. In this scene, the narrator is treated more as a malfunctioning machine than a human being, reflecting the broader theme of dehumanization faced by Black individuals in a system that values control over compassion. His fragmented thoughts and impaired memory after the treatment represent a kind of psychic death, a forced disconnection from his past and a symbolic rebirth into a new, uncertain awareness.    The Liberty Paints episode ultimately encapsulates many of the novel's central themes. The name \"Liberty\" is revealed to be bitterly ironic: rather than standing for freedom and equality, the factory is a microcosm of racial exploitation and control. Its celebrated product—white paint—can only exist through the hidden inclusion of blackness, a contradiction that mirrors the broader American myth of racial purity and unity. Through his time at the factory, the narrator begins to see the facade of societal ideals, recognizing that beneath claims of liberty and progress lie deep contradictions, moral decay, and invisible forces that shape identity and experience.    This chapter marks a significant turning point in the narrator's journey toward self-awareness and social critique. As he endures betrayal, violence, and erasure, he starts to peel back the illusions he has long accepted. Liberty Paints is more than just a workplace—it is a potent symbol of the complex, often violent relationship between race, identity, and power in America. Through this experience, the narrator moves closer to understanding the true nature of his invisibility, and the forces that keep him unseen.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Comment on the fight between Ras and Clifton in Invisible Man", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The fight between Ras the Exhorter and Tod Clifton in Ralph Ellison's Invisible Man stands out as one of the most symbolically charged moments in the novel, revealing deep ideological divisions within the Black community and exploring the broader struggle for identity and freedom in a racially oppressive society. Far beyond a mere street altercation, their confrontation represents a clash of worldviews concerning how best to respond to racism, marginalization, and systemic injustice. Through this episode, Ellison illustrates the internal conflicts that can hinder collective progress, especially when racial solidarity is undermined by competing visions of empowerment.    Ras the Exhorter, a staunch Black nationalist, believes in racial separation and militant resistance against white domination. To him, any collaboration with white institutions is a betrayal of Black identity and dignity. His worldview is rigid, and he sees the path to liberation in complete rejection of white society. In contrast, Tod Clifton represents a more pragmatic, though ultimately conflicted, approach. As a member of the Brotherhood—a political group that claims to advocate for social justice across racial and class lines—Clifton initially believes that working within a larger political framework can bring about meaningful change. Their fight emerges from these fundamentally opposing beliefs. When Ras confronts Clifton in public, accusing him of being a puppet for white interests, Clifton refuses to submit, insisting on the validity of his own choices. This confrontation reveals the difficulty of defining loyalty and integrity in a world where survival often requires compromise.    The fight itself is highly symbolic. Ras, dressed in flamboyant African garb and wielding a spear, assumes a theatrical posture that turns him into a near-caricature of militant nationalism. His attire and rhetoric are meant to evoke pride in African heritage, but Ellison's depiction suggests that such extreme identity posturing can be performative rather than transformative. Clifton's resistance to Ras's threats and his refusal to be shamed into submission reflect his unwillingness to let ideology dictate his path. Though he works for an organization that proves to be deeply flawed, Clifton insists on his autonomy, even in the face of violence. The physical clash between the two men thus dramatizes a deeper ideological conflict: whether freedom can be pursued through collaboration and political structure or only through total rejection and confrontation.    The narrator's role as observer during this fight is also significant. Witnessing the hostility between Ras and Clifton compels him to reflect on his own position within the Brotherhood and to question the motives of those around him. He begins to realize that both Ras's extremism and the Brotherhood's false idealism fail to fully respect the individuality and humanity of Black people. The fight exposes how rigid ideologies, even those claiming to fight oppression, can become another form of control. The narrator sees the tragedy of a movement fragmented by internal suspicion, mistrust, and competition, with individuals like Clifton caught in the middle—revered one moment, discarded the next.    Moreover, the fight serves as a powerful foreshadowing of Clifton's eventual fate. Soon after the confrontation with Ras, Clifton disappears from the Brotherhood and reemerges briefly as a street vendor, ironically selling degrading Sambo dolls to make a living. This descent into disillusionment and his subsequent death at the hands of a white police officer reflect the bleak reality that no approach—militancy, cooperation, or withdrawal—offers true safety or acceptance. His demise underscores the central theme of Invisible Man: that Black identity is constantly under threat, not only from external forces but also from internal divisions and societal expectations.    In conclusion, the fight between Ras the Exhorter and Tod Clifton is a crucial moment in Invisible Man, offering a vivid portrayal of the ideological fragmentation within the Black struggle for liberation. Through this encounter, Ellison critiques both militant nationalism and blind allegiance to political organizations, exposing the dangers of allowing ideology to override individual complexity. It is a scene marked by confrontation, betrayal, and symbolic violence, illustrating how easily solidarity can fracture under pressure and how difficult it is to find a path to freedom in a world built on contradiction and control.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "In Wuthering Heights by Emily Bronte, how does Heathcliff's return affects the marriage between Edger and Catherine?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Wuthering Heights by Emily Brontë, Heathcliff's return after a mysterious absence of three years has a deeply disruptive effect on the marriage between Edgar Linton and Catherine Earnshaw. His reappearance reawakens powerful emotions in Catherine and reignites the unresolved tension from their past, ultimately undermining the stability of her relationship with Edgar.    Before Heathcliff's return, Catherine is already emotionally conflicted. Although she has chosen to marry Edgar for his social status, refinement, and security, her deep, almost elemental bond with Heathcliff remains intact. She famously describes her love for Edgar as \"like the foliage in the woods,\" temporary and changeable, while her love for Heathcliff is \"like the eternal rocks beneath,\" a force that is unchanging and inseparable from her identity. When Heathcliff returns, this dormant passion is rekindled, and Catherine is torn between the man she married and the man who mirrors her wild, untamed spirit.    Heathcliff's presence introduces jealousy and suspicion into the Linton household. Edgar, who is gentle and reserved, is both appalled and threatened by Heathcliff's crude manners and intense emotional hold over Catherine. As Heathcliff begins to insert himself into their lives—especially through his interactions with Isabella, Edgar's sister—Edgar becomes increasingly isolated from Catherine. The emotional chasm between husband and wife grows as Catherine refuses to sever ties with Heathcliff, insisting on maintaining their closeness despite the tension it causes.    Catherine's deteriorating health can be directly linked to the psychological strain caused by this triangle. Her mental and physical collapse follows heated confrontations between Edgar and Heathcliff, as well as her own sense of entrapment. She feels caught between social expectations and her passionate nature, a conflict intensified by Heathcliff's haunting return. Ultimately, her death is symbolic of the emotional destruction that Heathcliff's return inflicts—not only on her marriage but on her sense of identity and peace.    In essence, Heathcliff's return acts as a catalyst that exposes the emotional fragility of Edgar and Catherine's union. His presence reintroduces unresolved desires and bitterness from the past, revealing that Catherine's marriage to Edgar was built on compromise rather than true emotional fulfillment. The resulting emotional turmoil leads to Catherine's decline and the eventual collapse of any illusion of harmony in her marriage.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION A>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN PROSE", "question": "Compare the places Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Wuthering Heights, Emily Brontë uses the two main settings—Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange—as powerful symbols that reflect the novel's central themes, character dynamics, and emotional atmosphere. These two houses are not just physical locations but represent contrasting worlds, values, and psychological states, functioning as symbolic backdrops that mirror the inner lives of the characters who inhabit them.    Wuthering Heights, the more ancient and remote of the two, is a wild, untamed, and brooding place situated on the harsh moors. Its very name, \"Wuthering,\" refers to turbulent weather, which immediately sets the tone for the kind of life it embodies—raw, stormy, and unrefined. Architecturally, it is a strong, weather-beaten farmhouse, built to withstand the violent winds and storms of the moors. The environment around Wuthering Heights is bleak, rugged, and exposed to nature's extremes. This setting reflects the primitive passions, emotional intensity, and fierce independence of the characters associated with it, particularly Heathcliff and Catherine Earnshaw. Their love is stormy, obsessive, and often destructive, mirroring the wildness of the house itself. Life at Wuthering Heights is marked by conflict, suffering, and cruelty, especially after Hindley assumes control and later when Heathcliff returns and imposes his revenge.    In contrast, Thrushcross Grange symbolizes civilization, order, refinement, and social decorum. Located in a more sheltered and fertile valley, it offers a sharp contrast to the rugged isolation of Wuthering Heights. The Grange is elegant, warm, and well-maintained, with soft lighting and genteel furnishings. It is associated with the Linton family, who embody the values of politeness, education, and gentility. Edgar and Isabella Linton are products of this refined world, and their mannered way of life stands in opposition to the violent emotional energy of the Heights. Thrushcross Grange represents the social norms and restrictions of the Victorian upper class, a world where appearances, propriety, and rationality dominate.    The symbolic opposition between the two houses also extends to the characters' emotional development and moral struggles. Catherine Earnshaw herself is torn between these two worlds. Her spiritual and emotional connection lies with Wuthering Heights and Heathcliff—wild, passionate, and instinctive. However, she chooses to marry Edgar Linton of Thrushcross Grange for social advancement and security, a decision that leads to her internal conflict and ultimate downfall. Her famous declaration that she is Heathcliff emphasizes how deeply Wuthering Heights is tied to her identity, even as she tries to live within the confines of Thrushcross Grange. The resulting tension between her passionate self and her socially acceptable role reveals the conflict between nature and culture, between authentic emotion and societal expectations.    As the novel progresses, the two estates also reflect changes in character and generational evolution. The second generation—young Catherine (Cathy), Hareton, and Linton Heathcliff—inherit both the emotional legacies and the physical spaces of the first. Initially, Wuthering Heights remains a place of cruelty and ignorance, especially under Heathcliff's domination. But as love and education slowly take root through Cathy and Hareton's relationship, the house begins to change, suggesting the possibility of redemption and harmony. Meanwhile, Thrushcross Grange, though more elegant, begins to lose its vitality after Edgar's death and Cathy's removal to the Heights. By the novel's end, the symbolic roles of the two estates are reversed—Wuthering Heights becomes a place of renewal and emotional growth, while Thrushcross Grange is emptied out and eventually rented to the narrator, Lockwood.    In conclusion, Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange are more than mere settings; they serve as symbolic opposites that shape the characters and themes of the novel. Wuthering Heights represents untamed passion, elemental nature, and raw emotion, while Thrushcross Grange stands for social order, refinement, and repression of desire. The interplay between these two spaces captures the novel's exploration of human duality—between passion and reason, freedom and control, chaos and order. Through them, Brontë creates a landscape that is not just physical but psychological, mapping the emotional terrain of her characters and the moral ambiguities of their world.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>1", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "How does Governor Samuel Rowe contribute to the fall of Yoko?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Let Me Die Alone by John Kargbo, the character of Governor Samuel Rowe plays a pivotal role in advancing the central theme of colonialism and its devastating effects on traditional African societies. Through his actions and policies, the narrative vividly portrays the deep tensions and cultural dissonance between colonial authorities and indigenous communities. The novel serves as a powerful critique of foreign domination, emphasizing how colonial interference disrupts established systems of governance, identity, and cultural cohesion.    Governor Samuel Rowe, a representative of British imperial power, is depicted as the embodiment of colonial arrogance and exploitation. His administrative decisions are consistently motivated by the interests of the British Crown, with little to no regard for the socio-political structures of the local people. By systematically undermining Queen Yoko's leadership and authority, Rowe imposes foreign ideals and legal frameworks that displace indigenous customs. His disregard for local autonomy intensifies the disintegration of traditional systems, heightening the cultural conflict within the play.    Rowe's character is not merely an antagonist to Yoko but also a symbolic force representing the broader machinery of colonial domination. His manipulation of local leadership structures and strategic imposition of colonial governance illustrate the insidious ways colonialism entrenches itself into the fabric of indigenous society. The eventual downfall of Yoko, a proud and capable female ruler, is intricately linked to Rowe's calculated actions, thereby dramatizing the destructive nature of imperial conquest and the erosion of native leadership.    Moreover, Rowe's impact extends beyond personal antagonism to Yoko—it serves as a narrative device that underscores the widespread consequences of colonial rule. Through his character, the play exposes how colonial powers co-opt traditional institutions, exploit divisions, and systematically strip local populations of their autonomy and cultural heritage. This portrayal functions as a powerful commentary on the enduring scars of colonialism and calls attention to the importance of cultural preservation, resistance, and self-determination in post-colonial societies.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>2", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Examine the significance of Lamboi's ambition on Yoko's reign.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Lamboi's ambition casts a long and ultimately corrosive shadow over Yoko's reign in Let Me Die Alone, shaping both the political landscape of the kingdom and the personal trajectory of its queen. His relentless drive for power and prestige undermines the stability Yoko seeks to build, exacerbates factionalism at court, and exposes the limits of her authority in a patriarchal context. By tracing the arc of Lamboi's ascent—from trusted advisor to overreaching usurper—we can see how his personal ambitions become inseparable from the larger themes of loyalty, governance, and cultural survival that animate the play.    From the earliest scenes in which Lamboi counsels Queen Yoko, his ambition is evident in the way he frames every decision as an opportunity for expansion—of wealth, territory, or influence. Though Yoko initially welcomes his strategic acumen, she remains guided by a holistic vision of rulership: one that balances military strength with respect for tradition and the well‑being of her people. Lamboi, by contrast, prioritizes short‑term gains. He advocates aggressive policies—new taxes, preemptive strikes on neighboring chiefdoms, and alliances with foreign merchants—that strain the kingdom's resources and clash with Yoko's more cautious, consensus‑building instincts. His proposals gradually shift the focus of the court from preserving harmony to maximizing advantage, and in doing so they fuel dissent among traditionalists who fear the loss of cultural identity.    As Lamboi accumulates successes—new revenues from expanded trade routes, spoil from military raids, and personal prestige at court—he begins to slip the reins of loyalty. He subtly undermines Yoko's decisions by privately courting key nobles, whispering that the queen is too \"soft\" to maintain security in an era of colonial encroachment. These machinations erode the unity that Yoko has painstakingly crafted among her counselors. When a diplomatic mission to the colonial governor goes awry, it is Lamboi's faction that blames Yoko's hesitation rather than the governor's bad faith. By sowing doubt in her judgment, Lamboi not only advances his own standing but also diminishes the standing of the monarchy itself, leaving Yoko vulnerable to both internal and external threats.    The full extent of Lamboi's ambition becomes clear in the play's climactic act, when he attempts to depose Yoko by exploiting her moment of personal weakness—her grief over a major military setback. Seizing on her isolation, Lamboi forges alliances with rival chiefs and even reaches out to the colonial administration, offering to serve as their proxy ruler in exchange for formal recognition and military backing. His betrayal is a dramatic inversion of the loyalty he once professed, and it forces Yoko to confront the limits of her power: she must choose between open conflict with a trusted confidant or acquiescence to a lesser, compromised sovereignty. Her eventual resistance—calling on the people and the old ways of communal council—is both a rejection of Lamboi's methods and a reaffirmation of her own vision of leadership.    In the end, Lamboi's ambition serves as the catalyst for Yoko's most decisive assertion of authority. By laying bare the dangers of unchecked personal ambition within the structures of traditional rule, the play argues that true sovereignty requires more than force or cunning—it demands moral legitimacy and the consent of the governed. Yoko's triumph in rallying her supporters against Lamboi underscores the play's enduring message: that a ruler's strength lies not in coercion or opportunism but in fidelity to communal values and the courage to stand against those who would exploit those values for private gain. Lamboi's rise and fall thus illuminates the fragile balance between ambition and duty, and the ways in which personal desires can both propel and imperil a nation.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>3", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Consider the use of music and dance Wole Soyinka's 'The Lion and the Jewel'.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In The Lion and the Jewel, Wole Soyinka masterfully blends elements of traditional African performance with Western dramatic techniques to create a uniquely vibrant theatrical experience. Among the most significant features of this fusion are music and dance, which Soyinka does not treat as mere ornamentation but rather as essential components of the play's structure, meaning, and cultural authenticity. Music and dance in The Lion and the Jewel perform multiple roles: they serve as tools of storytelling, expressions of cultural identity, reflections of ideological conflict, and devices for character development. Through these performative elements, Soyinka celebrates African traditions while also critically exploring the tensions between modernity and tradition.    One of the most important functions of music and dance in the play is their role in upholding and transmitting traditional African culture. Set in the fictional Yoruba village of Ilujinle, The Lion and the Jewel draws heavily on the oral and performative traditions of African societies, where storytelling is closely intertwined with singing, drumming, mime, and dancing. This cultural authenticity is reflected in episodes such as the \"Dance of the Lost Traveller,\" in which villagers reenact the comical story of a foreigner who wandered into their village. Through dance and mime, the villagers not only recall past events but also ridicule the outsider, thus preserving collective memory while asserting cultural pride. Soyinka uses these sequences to show how music and dance function as repositories of communal history and wisdom, reinforcing the African worldview and challenging Western narrative forms.    Beyond their cultural value, music and dance serve as narrative devices that enhance the dramatic structure of the play. Instead of relying on lengthy dialogue or expository monologues to relay past events, Soyinka employs choreographed performances that bring history to life. The villagers' dramatization of past events—such as the arrival of the stranger or Baroka's past triumphs—allows the audience to witness the village's past through movement and rhythm. These performances help bridge the temporal gaps between past and present, offering a dynamic and engaging way to communicate memory and legend. As such, dance functions as a storytelling technique that both entertains and informs, drawing the audience into the cultural and emotional life of the community.    Music and dance also serve as symbolic representations of the ideological conflict at the heart of the play: the clash between tradition and modernity. The central rivalry between Baroka, the cunning and tradition-bound Bale, and Lakunle, the Western-educated schoolteacher, is not only verbal but also expressed through their relationship to performance culture. Baroka is deeply immersed in the rituals and dances of the village; he uses music and traditional ceremonies to assert his authority and charisma. His ease with these cultural expressions underscores his enduring connection to the people and their customs. In contrast, Lakunle disdains traditional dance and village festivals, viewing them as backward and unrefined. His inability to engage with these communal expressions marks him as alienated and disconnected from the very society he wishes to reform. Thus, music and dance highlight the characters' ideologies and expose the limits of Lakunle's vision of progress.    In addition to their symbolic and narrative value, music and dance help reveal the emotional landscape of the play and the inner lives of its characters. Moments of joy, mockery, celebration, and transformation are often communicated not through dialogue, but through performance. The satirical dances used to mock outsiders or celebrate village traditions express the villagers' pride and playfulness. Furthermore, the closing scenes of the play are filled with jubilant music and dance, reflecting Sidi's transformation and her acceptance of Baroka's proposal. Her participation in dance underscores her growth from a naive girl into a woman who understands and embraces her role within the traditional structure of her society.    In conclusion, music and dance are central to the thematic and structural richness of The Lion and the Jewel. They function as vital tools for storytelling, cultural affirmation, emotional expression, and ideological debate. Through these elements, Soyinka reaffirms the power and beauty of African theatrical traditions while also critiquing the tensions that arise from the imposition of Western values. In doing so, he creates a play that not only entertains but also educates and provokes reflection, using music and dance as instruments of both artistic and cultural significance.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>4", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "What does Sidi bring out in Baroka and Lakunle?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Wole Soyinka's satirical comedy The Lion and the Jewel, Sidi, the beautiful and confident village girl, plays a central role not only as the object of desire but also as a character whose presence and actions reveal the true nature of the two competing male characters—Baroka and Lakunle. Through her interactions with them, Sidi becomes a mirror that exposes their personal traits, beliefs, and limitations. While both men attempt to win her over, they are, in the process, unmasked by her responses. Sidi brings out Baroka's cunning, calculated leadership and traditional masculinity, while she exposes Lakunle's immaturity, hypocrisy, and alienation from cultural values. Thus, Sidi serves as a dramatic and thematic instrument in Soyinka's exploration of tradition versus modernity and the complexities of gender and power in African society.    One of the most significant aspects of Sidi's relationship with Baroka is how it brings out the Bale's strategic intelligence and traditional charm. Baroka is portrayed as an aging leader who is fully aware of his waning physical prowess but refuses to be irrelevant. When Sidi's beauty is publicly celebrated in a foreign magazine, Baroka feels threatened—not only because she becomes more admired than he is, but also because her fame represents a changing era where the traditional authority of men like him might lose its grip. In response to her rejection of his marriage proposal, Baroka does not confront her directly or display anger; rather, he pretends to be impotent, a ruse designed to provoke Sidi's curiosity and sympathy. This act of manipulation reveals Baroka's patience and ability to use subtlety over confrontation, demonstrating his wisdom in navigating social situations. Sidi's importance to him thus brings out his inner fears and his reliance on cunning to maintain influence.    Additionally, Sidi's interaction with Baroka highlights his strong connection to tradition and his role as the custodian of culture. Unlike Lakunle, Baroka never undermines Sidi's values. Instead, he affirms them by approaching her with gestures consistent with Yoruba courtship traditions—offering gifts, praising her beauty through poetic language, and respecting her pride. These elements of his courtship reveal a man deeply in tune with the customs of his people. Sidi's initial resistance to Baroka's advances further shows that the Bale is not used to being denied, but he adapts and schemes rather than dominates, revealing his tactical ability to bend situations in his favor.    In contrast, Sidi's relationship with Lakunle reveals a completely different dynamic—one that exposes the schoolteacher's contradictions, insecurities, and intellectual arrogance. Lakunle claims to be a modern man, guided by progressive ideals and Western education. He often criticizes village traditions and speaks of freeing Sidi from what he calls \"barbaric customs,\" especially the payment of bride price. However, Sidi sees through his façade. She refuses to marry Lakunle without the bride price, not because she values money over love, but because she recognizes that Lakunle's refusal stems from pride, not principle. This exchange brings out Lakunle's failure to understand or respect the very culture he wishes to reform.    Moreover, Sidi's presence reveals Lakunle's hypocrisy. Although he preaches gender equality, he often contradicts himself by describing women as intellectually and physically inferior. He says that women have smaller brains and should be guided by men. These statements clearly undermine the very ideals he claims to uphold. Sidi's witty retorts and sharp observations expose these contradictions, making it evident to the audience that Lakunle is not the enlightened hero he imagines himself to be. In fact, through Sidi's rejections and ridicule, Lakunle is shown to be emotionally immature, socially awkward, and disconnected from both the people and the values of Ilujinle.    Furthermore, Sidi's growing self-awareness throughout the play also serves to emphasize the shortcomings of both suitors. When she first hears of her pictures in the foreign magazine, she becomes obsessed with her own image and worth. This vanity puts her in a position of power, enabling her to resist both men's advances temporarily. However, by the end of the play, her acceptance of Baroka—after he tricks her into visiting his bedroom and seduces her—reveals not only her transformation from innocence to experience but also the ultimate triumph of traditional wisdom over youthful pride and empty modernity. Her decision indirectly justifies Baroka's strategic patience and undermines Lakunle's ineffectual idealism, solidifying her role as a character who exposes the deeper truths of the other two.    In conclusion, Sidi plays a crucial role in The Lion and the Jewel, not merely as a love interest but as a dramatic force that reveals the essential characteristics of Baroka and Lakunle. Through her eyes and reactions, the audience comes to understand Baroka's calculated intelligence, his cultural confidence, and his manipulative charm. Conversely, Sidi's interactions with Lakunle expose his arrogance, emotional immaturity, and failure to bridge the gap between Western ideas and traditional African values. Through her relationships with both men, Sidi becomes a tool through which Soyinka explores broader themes such as generational conflict, gender roles, and the clash between tradition and modernity. In this way, her role is both personal and symbolic, making her central to the play's narrative and ideological structure.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>5", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "5", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Comment on the view that Jimmy is at heart a caring person.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "John Osborne's Look Back in Anger presents Jimmy Porter as one of the most polarising characters in post-war British drama. Often seen as a mouthpiece of the \"Angry Young Man\" movement, Jimmy is characterised by verbal aggression, social resentment, and an almost relentless barrage of emotional and intellectual abuse directed at those around him. At first glance, he appears bitter, cruel, and intolerably arrogant. Yet, beneath this turbulent surface lies a deeply wounded and emotionally complex individual. A close reading of the play suggests that, at heart, Jimmy is a caring person—one who struggles to reconcile his emotional sensitivity with a world that he believes is indifferent to genuine feeling.    Jimmy's caring nature is most vividly revealed through his emotional vulnerability. One of the central traumas that shapes his character is the death of his father, who had fought on the losing side of the Spanish Civil War and returned to England disillusioned and broken. Jimmy speaks of this loss with quiet reverence: \"He died when he was fifty. He was worn out with rage and despair.\" This moment is not just a historical reference—it reveals the deep admiration Jimmy felt for a man of ideals, and the pain of watching someone he loved die in obscurity and helplessness. His father's suffering haunts him, and his anger toward the world is, in many ways, an extension of that unresolved grief. Jimmy's capacity to feel so deeply about the suffering of his father suggests a tenderness and emotional investment that runs contrary to his aggressive exterior.    Moreover, Jimmy's relationship with his friend and lodger, Cliff Lewis, offers further insight into his capacity for affection. In a world where Jimmy seems constantly at odds with everyone else, Cliff represents stability and warmth. The affectionate bond between the two men is demonstrated through their physical closeness and mutual respect. Cliff even goes as far as defending Jimmy to Alison and Helena, describing him as someone with a \"big mouth\" but \"a heart.\" Their interactions are often laced with humour and camaraderie, suggesting that Jimmy is capable of intimacy, loyalty, and affection—when he feels safe and understood. Cliff's tolerance of Jimmy's many outbursts indicates that he sees, and appreciates, the caring man beneath the fury.    Perhaps the most symbolic and emotionally revealing aspect of Jimmy's caring nature lies in the recurring \"bear and squirrel game\" he shares with Alison. This private fantasy, in which they imagine themselves as two small woodland creatures, represents a world of emotional safety and childlike intimacy. It is a sanctuary from the harshness of reality and a testament to a time when their love was pure and undamaged. When Jimmy reverts to this game, it is not an act of mockery or childishness but a desperate yearning for closeness and unconditional acceptance. That he returns to this game—particularly at the end of the play after Alison's miscarriage—shows that he is not incapable of love or affection. Rather, he clings to that emotional connection as proof that he once knew, and can still reclaim, a more tender version of himself.    One of the most powerful moments in the play that reveals Jimmy's emotional depth and caring heart is his reaction to Alison's miscarriage. Up until that point, his treatment of Alison had been harsh, filled with verbal abuse and emotional distance. Yet when Helena informs him of Alison's loss, Jimmy's response is devastatingly human. He confesses, \"I was waiting for something to happen... and now it has... I feel older than I ever was.\" This quiet, reflective grief stands in stark contrast to his usual bombastic anger. It is a moment of sincere heartbreak, in which the audience sees a man who has hoped, feared, and now mourns deeply. The rawness of his reaction suggests that he had invested emotionally in the possibility of fatherhood, even if he never openly expressed it. His loss reveals the true cost of his emotional isolation and confirms that his outward hostility was always a defence mechanism for his vulnerability.    It is also worth noting that Jimmy's bitterness often stems not from indifference, but from caring too much. He rails against a society that, in his view, has lost its moral and emotional compass. His dissatisfaction with Alison, for instance, comes not just from class resentment, but from a belief that she does not engage with life as deeply as he does. He accuses her of being \"impassive,\" of not feeling deeply enough. While his criticism is cruel, it stems from a desire for genuine emotional connection. He wants to share life with someone who burns with the same intensity as he does. This intense longing for emotional authenticity, even if misguided, shows that Jimmy is driven by the need to love and be loved in return.    By the end of the play, after all the conflict and loss, Alison returns to Jimmy. Their final interaction—marked by a renewed version of the bear and squirrel game—symbolises a return to emotional vulnerability and reconciliation. Jimmy says, \"I may be a lost cause, but I thought if you loved me, it needn't matter.\" In this final scene, his defences are down. He is no longer the angry young man berating the world, but a broken soul reaching out for healing. That Alison accepts this gesture confirms that she too recognises the caring man behind the fury.    In conclusion, while Jimmy Porter is undoubtedly abrasive, emotionally explosive, and often cruel, these traits cannot be taken at face value. His character is a tragic embodiment of a man who feels deeply but cannot express those feelings in socially acceptable ways. Beneath his harsh exterior lies a passionate and caring individual whose vulnerability makes him lash out at the very people he loves. His grief over his father, his tender bond with Cliff, his longing for intimacy with Alison, and his devastating reaction to loss all point to a man whose rage is fuelled by a profound capacity to care. Jimmy Porter may be angry, but he is not heartless. At his core, he is a deeply caring individual—one whose love, however imperfect, is genuine and intensely felt.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>6", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Trace the transformation of Helena in the play.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In John Osborne's Look Back in Anger, Helena Charles begins as a poised and moralistic woman rooted in conventional upper middle class values. Initially presented as a cold outsider who passes judgment on the lives of others, Helena experiences a significant transformation that reveals her emotional vulnerability and moral contradictions. Through her character development from a self righteous moral enforcer to a conflicted lover and eventually a remorseful realist, Osborne portrays the complexity of human emotions and the collapse of rigid social values in the face of personal passion. This essay will trace Helena's transformation across the play, using textual evidence to demonstrate her moral shift and emotional awakening.    At her introduction in Act Two, Helena arrives at the Porters' home to support her friend Alison, who is enduring a difficult and emotionally abusive marriage to Jimmy. Helena is sharply contrasted with Jimmy from the beginning. She is calm, elegant and composed, whereas Jimmy is chaotic, impulsive and rude. Helena does not hesitate to express her moral disdain for Jimmy's behavior. She describes him as \"a crude, rude little man\" and tells Alison, \"He's not your equal. You're not his kind. Don't try to fool yourself.\" This early declaration of moral superiority is reinforced when she secretly writes to Alison's father to come and take Alison away. Her justification is clear: \"You're being hurt, and I can't let it happen.\" At this point, Helena firmly positions herself as the rational and principled character who acts for her friend's well being and believes in doing what is right.    However, her moral posture begins to crumble after Alison's departure. Alone with Jimmy, Helena unexpectedly finds herself drawn to him, despite previously condemning him. Her transformation begins when she kisses Jimmy, the very man she had described as \"evil.\" Her line, \"I'm not ashamed. It's what I want,\" marks a dramatic shift from a voice of judgment to someone overtaken by emotion. This confession reveals her emotional longing and inner conflict. The woman who once scorned Jimmy now desires him. She has not necessarily changed her view of his cruelty, but she is overwhelmed by her need for intimacy and intensity.    This marks the beginning of Helena's emotional compromise. Her relationship with Jimmy, based not on shared values but on passion and rebellion, pulls her deeper into the emotional turmoil she had once sought to correct. She becomes part of the same emotional cycle that she had judged in Alison. Helena's decision to stay and pursue a romantic relationship with Jimmy reveals the breakdown of her rigid principles. Her earlier stance of control and morality is now replaced by emotional confusion. Osborne uses this phase of her journey to show that no one is truly immune to desire, and that even the most disciplined person can be swept away by personal need.    Helena's most important transformation comes with the return of Alison in Act Three. Alison, now visibly grieving the loss of her unborn child, silently exposes the cost of the emotional wreckage left behind. Helena's immediate response is guilt and discomfort. She realizes the wrongness of her affair with Jimmy and the pain it has caused. Her words to Alison are honest and heartfelt: \"I know I've done wrong. I know it in my heart.\" This admission signals the return of her moral consciousness, not through self righteousness, but through deep personal regret. She recognizes that she has betrayed her friend and violated the very values she once claimed to defend.    Her final decision to leave Jimmy is the completion of her transformation. She tells him, \"I don't think I'm very much of a lady, but I'm going.\" This statement is filled with quiet humility. She does not attempt to justify her actions, nor does she accuse Jimmy of anything. Instead, she accepts her moral failure and removes herself from the situation. Unlike her earlier intervention to remove Alison from Jimmy's life, this departure is not triumphant or judgmental. It is a quiet and sincere act of remorse.    In conclusion, Helena Charles undergoes a profound emotional and moral transformation in Look Back in Anger. She begins as a firm defender of traditional values, judging others for their perceived failures. Yet, as the play progresses, she becomes emotionally involved with the very man she condemned. Her relationship with Jimmy reveals her capacity for passion, contradiction and personal weakness. Ultimately, her remorseful exit shows growth and self awareness. Through Helena's transformation, Osborne explores the tension between morality and emotion, and the difficult choices individuals face when confronted with personal desire and guilt. Helena's journey is a powerful reminder that even the most morally certain people can fall, reflect and change.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>7", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "How does Alberta's death affect Troy?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In August Wilson's Fences, the character of Troy Maxson is portrayed as a deeply flawed yet profoundly human figure whose internal conflicts drive much of the play's emotional intensity. One of the most pivotal moments in the narrative is the death of Alberta, the woman with whom Troy has had an extramarital affair. While Alberta is never seen on stage, her presence looms large over the characters and their relationships. Her death marks a turning point for Troy both emotionally and morally. It forces him to confront the consequences of his actions, exacerbates his isolation, and brings his responsibilities into sharper focus. Let us examine how Alberta's death affects Troy by exploring his emotional reaction, his altered relationship with his family, and his evolving sense of guilt and responsibility.    At the time of Alberta's death, Troy is already under great emotional strain. His relationship with Rose, his wife of eighteen years, is fractured following the revelation of his infidelity. When he delivers the news of Alberta's death, the audience sees a rare moment of emotional vulnerability in a man who is otherwise guarded and proud. He tells Rose, \"Alberta died having the baby.\" This short, direct statement is not just informational but carries a heavy emotional burden. Although Troy tries to appear strong and unemotional, it is clear from the tone of the scene that Alberta's death has left him shaken. The woman who brought him temporary escape and joy is suddenly gone, and he must now face the long term consequences of that relationship.    Troy's emotional response is further revealed in his conversation with Rose. He says, \"She's gone. She's gone and I got to be the one to tell you.\" This statement is layered with sorrow, not just because Alberta has died, but because he knows the pain he is causing Rose by having to deliver this news. It is a moment of reckoning for Troy. The weight of his betrayal, compounded by Alberta's death, forces him into an emotional corner where he can no longer hide behind his usual bravado. He is now fully exposed as a man who has made irreversible choices, and the emotional burden begins to erode his sense of pride and control.    The most profound consequence of Alberta's death is the arrival of her child, Raynell. This baby becomes the physical embodiment of Troy's infidelity. However, it also provides an opportunity for growth. When Troy brings Raynell home and asks Rose to help raise the child, he says, \"This child got to have a mother. I can't do nothing but try and do right by her.\" This is a moment of humility. Troy acknowledges that while he has failed as a husband, he cannot abandon his duty as a father. Alberta's death thus forces Troy into a new role, one that demands emotional maturity and personal sacrifice.    Rose's response to Troy further highlights the impact Alberta's death has on him. She agrees to raise Raynell, but she says firmly, \"I'll take care of your baby for you... but you a womanless man.\" With these words, Rose draws a clear boundary. She will take responsibility for the child, but she will not continue as Troy's wife in the emotional sense. This moment isolates Troy further, making Alberta's death the event that severs his last emotional connection to Rose. The comfort and companionship he once found in both women is gone. Alberta is dead, and Rose has withdrawn from the intimacy of their marriage.    Troy's psychological state continues to deteriorate after Alberta's death. As the years pass, he becomes more isolated and alienated from his family, especially from his son Cory. His inner guilt and sorrow manifest not as open repentance but as increased defensiveness and stubbornness. He builds the fence not just as a physical barrier but as a symbol of his desire to contain the chaos in his life. Alberta's death has left a void that Troy cannot fill, and he tries to compensate by clinging to the remnants of control he has left.    In Act Two, Scene Four, Troy confronts death symbolically by speaking directly to it, saying, \"Come on! It's between you and me now! Come on!\" This outburst reveals how Troy now views death as a personal opponent. Alberta's sudden and tragic passing has brought death to his doorstep, and he can no longer avoid thinking about his own mortality. He challenges death in an effort to regain power, but the challenge is filled with fear and pain. Alberta's death has transformed Troy's relationship with life and death itself, making him more aware of his own vulnerability and moral failures.    In conclusion, Alberta's death is a turning point in Fences that deeply affects Troy Maxson on emotional, relational and psychological levels. It forces him to confront the consequences of his infidelity, pushes him further into emotional isolation, and changes his relationship with his wife and children. Through this tragedy, August Wilson reveals the heavy toll of personal choices and the fragile nature of human connections. Alberta's death does not bring Troy redemption, but it brings him clarity. It strips away his illusions and compels him to face the life he has built with all its cracks and regrets. In this way, Alberta's death serves not only as a plot device but as a powerful mirror that reflects the internal collapse of a man who tried to fence out the pain but could not escape the consequences of his own actions.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>8", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "8", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN DRAMA", "question": "Comment on the portrayal of African-American life in the play 'Fences'.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "August Wilson's Fences provides a powerful and authentic portrayal of African-American life in mid-twentieth century America. Set in the 1950s, the play centers on Troy Maxson, a working-class African-American man, and his family as they navigate personal struggles, racial injustices, and generational divides. Wilson does not idealize African-American life; instead, he presents it as a complex blend of resilience, frustration, love, and hardship. Through his vivid characters, cultural references, and emotionally charged dialogue, Wilson captures the realities of black life during a time of racial inequality and social limitation.    One of the most striking portrayals in Fences is the economic struggle faced by African Americans. Troy works as a garbage collector and is proud to have broken a color barrier by becoming the first black man allowed to drive a garbage truck. However, this advancement is minimal when compared to the limitations he has endured throughout his life. Earlier in his youth, Troy had the talent to become a professional baseball player but was denied the opportunity due to racial discrimination. This bitter disappointment defines much of his worldview and is symbolic of the dashed dreams many African Americans experienced during this era. Wilson uses Troy's story to reflect the broader frustration felt by black men who were repeatedly denied access to economic and professional growth.    In addition to economic hardship, Wilson highlights the emotional and psychological toll of systemic racism on black families. Troy's bitterness often manifests in his strained relationships with his wife, Rose, and his son, Cory. He is stern and emotionally distant, fearing that nurturing dreams will only lead to heartbreak. For instance, when Cory wants to pursue a football scholarship, Troy denies him the chance, stating, \"The white man ain't gonna let you get nowhere with that football now.\" While his actions are harsh, they are rooted in his desire to protect Cory from the same disappointment he endured. This generational conflict reveals how racism not only hinders progress but also breeds distrust and emotional disconnect within black families.    The role of African-American women is also carefully portrayed through Rose, Troy's wife. Rose represents the emotional backbone of the family. She is loyal, nurturing, and deeply grounded in her faith. Yet, her role also reflects the sacrifices black women were often expected to make. When Troy has an affair and fathers a child with another woman, Rose is devastated but agrees to raise the child, Raynell, saying, \"I'll take care of your baby for you... but you a womanless man.\" Through Rose, Wilson explores themes of endurance, forgiveness, and the silent strength of African-American women who often held families together despite personal betrayal and disappointment.    Moreover, Fences reveals the richness of African-American culture through its dialogue, music, and storytelling traditions. Characters frequently engage in storytelling, boasting, and sharing folk wisdom, which preserves oral history and cultural identity. Troy's brother Gabriel, who believes he is the angel Gabriel, brings a spiritual dimension to the play, highlighting the presence of religion and mystical belief in African-American communities. Additionally, the blues motif—especially in the final scene when Troy's brother sounds his trumpet to \"open the gates of heaven\"—underscores the cultural and spiritual resilience of African Americans, even in the face of suffering.    In conclusion, Fences is a moving and multi-layered portrayal of African-American life that captures both the pain and dignity of a people struggling against systemic barriers. August Wilson presents characters who are flawed, real, and emotionally resonant. He addresses racial inequality, generational conflict, economic hardship, and the quiet heroism found in everyday black families. Rather than offering simple answers or idealized narratives, Wilson gives voice to a community shaped by history, grounded in culture, and determined to find meaning within its own fences. The result is a timeless and powerful depiction of African-American life that continues to speak to audiences across generations.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>9", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Examine the effects of colonialism in \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Agostinho Neto's The Grieved Lands of Africa is a passionate lamentation that captures the deep wounds inflicted by colonialism on the African continent. Through the use of vivid imagery, powerful symbolism, and emotionally charged language, Neto conveys the pain, dehumanization, and cultural devastation brought upon Africans by colonial powers. The poem does not merely speak of physical occupation but goes further to unveil the spiritual, psychological, and historical consequences of colonial domination. Neto, who was both a revolutionary and a poet, draws from his personal experience as an Angolan under Portuguese rule, and through this poem, gives voice to a continent that has been deeply scarred.    One of the most evident effects of colonialism in the poem is the dehumanization of African people. Neto writes of \"the grieved lands of Africa / in the limpidity of the waters,\" a line that juxtaposes the natural beauty of the continent with the pain it bears. The people are not described as proud or free, but as \"deformed by the rule of strangers,\" which reflects the way colonialism reshaped African identity by imposing foreign values, languages, and systems. This phrase clearly suggests that African societies were forcefully remade to serve the needs and desires of the colonizers, stripping people of their dignity and cultural heritage.    Another effect of colonialism revealed in the poem is the psychological trauma and cultural disorientation experienced by the colonized. Neto refers to the people who \"live on the razor's edge of destitution,\" indicating how colonial rule led to economic exploitation and left Africans in a constant state of poverty and insecurity. Furthermore, the line \"the children who are the eternal heirs of hunger\" highlights the generational impact of colonial exploitation. Hunger here is not just physical but also symbolic of spiritual and cultural starvation. By robbing Africans of their traditional systems and values, colonialism left behind a broken sense of self and community.    The poem also addresses the violent repression and suffering that accompanied colonial rule. Neto speaks of \"the dead without a name,\" evoking the countless Africans who were murdered, enslaved, or made invisible by colonial history. This line captures the silencing and erasure of African lives and voices. The colonizers not only ruled with violence but also denied the humanity of those they ruled. The \"lands grieved\" are not just mourning their occupation—they are mourning their sons and daughters who were erased from memory and denied the dignity of identity and history.    In addition, the poem suggests the resilience and unyielding spirit of the African people in the face of colonial suffering. Even while portraying grief and pain, Neto's voice carries a quiet strength. He writes, \"the grieved lands of Africa / continue to bear flowers,\" a powerful metaphor that shows that despite the destruction, beauty and life persist. The land, though violated, continues to bloom. This image captures the hope that Africa will rise again and that its people will eventually reclaim their stolen history, identity, and destiny. This reflects Neto's political activism and his belief in the liberation of the continent.    In conclusion, Agostinho Neto's The Grieved Lands of Africa paints a sorrowful yet powerful portrait of the effects of colonialism. Through its vivid language and striking imagery, the poem reveals how colonial rule brought dehumanization, cultural destruction, economic despair, and violent repression. Yet, within the poem's grief lies a resilient hope—a belief in the survival of African identity and the eventual triumph over oppression. Neto's poem serves not only as a lament but also as a historical testimony and a cry for justice, capturing the emotional and historical wounds of colonialism while honoring the endurance of the African spirit.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>10", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "", "topic": "AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the effect of time on the memory of the women in \"The Song of the Women of My Land\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In \"The Song of the Women of My Land,\" Oumar Farouk Sesay crafts a poignant reflection on how the passage of time affects memory, particularly the memory preserved and transmitted by women through oral traditions. The poet reveres the songs of these women, which serve as vessels of history, identity, and communal experience. However, time emerges as a silent force that gradually erodes these powerful memories. As modernity encroaches and cultural continuity weakens, the memory once carried in the women's songs begins to fade, leading to a loss of both heritage and identity.    One of the most significant effects of time in the poem is the erosion of oral tradition, which has historically been maintained by women. The poet speaks of the songs \"that echo through the corridors of memory,\" suggesting that these songs once served as active reminders of collective struggle and survival. However, with the passing of time, this echo grows fainter, and the once-vibrant oral tradition is at risk of being forgotten. The image of songs reverberating only in memory implies that they are no longer sung with the same passion or frequency. Time, therefore, functions as a distancing mechanism, separating the present generation from the cultural practices of the past.    In addition to eroding tradition, time also transforms memory into silence or abstraction. The poet refers to the voices of the women as being \"lost in the whirl of urban noise,\" indicating how modern life and its distractions drown out the echoes of the past. The women's songs, once integral to cultural preservation, are now reduced to distant memories or, worse, completely silenced. The poem laments this transformation, portraying it as a form of cultural death. The lines \"those voices / that rose in cadences of pain and joy\" reveal the emotional depth of the songs, which are no longer heard. Time, in this context, is depicted as an agent that turns living memory into historical shadow.    Moreover, the poet's tone is infused with nostalgia and longing, underscoring the emotional effect of time on memory. The speaker yearns for a time when the songs of women were not just remembered, but actively performed and lived. \"I strain my ears / to pick the strands / of a forgotten song,\" the poet says, conveying a desperate attempt to reconnect with the past. This longing is intensified by the realization that the memory is slipping away beyond recovery. Through this, time is shown not only as a destructive force but also as one that induces sorrow and loss for what can no longer be reclaimed in its original form.    Time's passage also leads to cultural amnesia, where the heritage carried by these songs risks total erasure. The women's songs once served as repositories of history, tradition, and moral instruction, but in the absence of active remembrance, this legacy is endangered. The poet speaks of \"songs that once mapped our existence,\" a metaphor that shows how these oral traditions were vital in shaping the community's identity. With time, if such maps are no longer read or sung, the people lose their sense of direction and belonging. Thus, the poem warns of the devastating effect time can have on collective memory if it is not safeguarded.    In conclusion, \"The Song of the Women of My Land\" is a lyrical lamentation of how time gradually effaces memory, particularly the memory held and shared by women through song. The poem portrays time as a corrosive force—erasing oral traditions, silencing ancestral voices, and inducing a sense of longing and cultural dislocation. Through vivid imagery and emotional resonance, Sesay highlights the urgent need to preserve memory and resist the cultural amnesia brought about by time. The poet's reverence for the women's songs is ultimately a call to action—to listen, remember, and revive the songs before they are completely lost to time.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>11", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "How does the poet treat the two types of love in 'The Good Morrow'?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "John Donne's poem \"The Good Morrow\" explores the development and transformation of love from its immature, sensual form to a deeper, more spiritual and transcendent union. As a metaphysical poet, Donne is deeply concerned with intellectual and emotional complexity, and in this poem, he contrasts the superficial pleasures of youthful love with the profound connection of a mature relationship. The poem progresses from a recollection of a past marked by physical desire to the celebration of an awakened, soul-deep companionship. Through vivid imagery and philosophical reflection, Donne distinguishes between these two types of love to elevate true affection as both sacred and eternal.    In the opening stanza, Donne reflects on the first kind of love—a youthful, earthly or physical love characterized by ignorance and sensual pleasure. He begins with rhetorical questions: \"I wonder, by my troth, what thou and I / Did, till we loved?\" This suggests that the speaker and his lover had lived in a state of emotional or spiritual unconsciousness before discovering true love. He refers to this previous phase as \"childish\" and imagines that they were indulging in \"country pleasures\" or meaningless affairs. The term \"snorted we in the Seven Sleepers' den\" is a biblical allusion implying that they were metaphorically asleep, unaware of the depth of love that was possible. This immature love, then, is marked by bodily satisfaction without intellectual or spiritual awareness.    The second type of love—mature, awakened, and spiritual love—is introduced in the second stanza, and it is celebrated as the moment of true consciousness and emotional rebirth. With the line \"And now good morrow to our waking souls,\" Donne marks a turning point where the lovers have moved from sleep to wakefulness, from illusion to reality. This \"good morrow\" is both literal and metaphorical—a new day and a new phase in their relationship. The poet sees their love as complete and self-sufficient, describing the room they inhabit as \"an everywhere,\" a space so whole and fulfilling that they need no other world. The treatment of this love is deeply idealistic; it is mutual, soul-connected, and transcendent.    Donne further emphasizes the perfection of this mature love by using metaphysical imagery, particularly the idea of mirrored souls and equal worlds. He writes, \"My face in thine eye, thine in mine appears,\" showing how the lovers reflect one another, suggesting unity and equality. He compares their joined love to two hemispheres that form one globe, \"Where can we find two better hemispheres / Without sharp North, without declining West?\" This imagery reflects a world of harmony, without division, decay, or geographical separation. Unlike the fleeting pleasures of bodily love, this spiritual love is whole and timeless. It transcends physical limitations and aspires to eternal perfection.    In the final lines, Donne presents the ultimate affirmation of spiritual love by suggesting its immortality. He says, \"If our two loves be one, or thou and I / Love so alike that none can slacken, none can die,\" implying that perfect, equal love cannot perish. This is the climax of the poet's treatment of love—he exalts the love that is mutual and constant as something that defeats time and death. This marks the final distinction between the two types of love: the first is temporal and incomplete, while the second is eternal and divine.    In conclusion, John Donne treats the two types of love in \"The Good Morrow\" by first acknowledging the shallow, physical desires of youth and then contrasting them with a higher, spiritual love that unites both body and soul. He celebrates the latter as the ideal form of love—reciprocal, complete, and everlasting. Through intellectual conceits, emotional sincerity, and metaphysical imagery, Donne presents love not just as passion, but as a powerful force that brings about personal awakening and spiritual fulfillment.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>Literature>2025>SECTION B>12", "subject": "Literature", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "", "topic": "NON-AFRICAN POETRY", "question": "Comment on the diction of Binsey Poplars.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Gerard Manley Hopkins' poem \"Binsey Poplars\" is renowned for its emotional intensity and lyrical sensitivity, much of which is achieved through his carefully chosen diction. Hopkins, a devout Jesuit priest and innovator of poetic language, selects words that are deeply expressive, richly musical, and thematically loaded. In this elegy for the felled poplar trees of Binsey, the diction reflects his deep sorrow, ecological awareness, and reverence for the natural world. Through his use of compound adjectives, alliteration, neologisms, and emotionally charged language, Hopkins crafts a powerful lament that elevates a local environmental loss into a universal expression of grief and reverence.    One of the most striking features of Hopkins' diction is his use of compound words and coinages, which allow him to compress complex images and ideas into single, expressive units. Words like \"all felled,\" \"unselved,\" and \"boon\" are particularly charged. The phrase \"All felled, felled, are all felled\" is not only repetitive but also rhythmically forceful, mimicking the sound of trees crashing to the ground. The repetition of \"felled\" in quick succession conveys a sense of violence and irrevocability. The invented word \"unselved\" conveys more than just destruction—it suggests a loss of identity, spirit, or essence. Such diction enables Hopkins to convey deep philosophical concerns about how human actions can unmake the divine beauty and selfhood of nature.    Hopkins also employs sensuous and textured language to describe the natural landscape before and after its destruction. Before the felling, the trees are described with words like \"airy,\" \"angel-mild,\" and \"fresh,\" all evoking gentleness and vitality. These adjectives not only suggest the visual and tactile qualities of the poplars but also attribute to them a kind of spiritual or sacred character. The image of the trees \"quelled or quenched in leaves the leaping sun\" captures how the foliage filtered sunlight in a delicate interplay of movement and shadow. Such diction reveals Hopkins' awe at the intricacy of nature's design.    After the destruction, however, the diction shifts dramatically to reflect loss and desecration. Words like \"hack and rack,\" \"stark,\" and \"stroke\" convey violence and brutality. The phrase \"after-comers cannot guess the beauty been\" emphasizes the finality of the destruction and the inability of future generations to appreciate what once was. The term \"stroke\" in the line \"O if we but knew what we do / When we delve or hew— / Hack and rack the growing green!\" suggests not just a physical blow, but also a spiritual and moral wound. This shift in diction underscores the contrast between the life-giving force of nature and the careless destructiveness of human activity.    Hopkins' diction also reveals his religious and moral sensibilities. His reverence for nature is closely tied to his view of it as a manifestation of divine beauty. Words like \"sweet especial rural scene,\" \"boon,\" and \"dear\" are emotionally tender and spiritually rich. The poem is not just mourning trees but lamenting the desecration of God's creation. The diction often carries a tone of moral warning, as seen in the line, \"We stroke our own / The mere mould of man, reck his rod.\" Here, Hopkins uses somewhat obscure but forceful terms to warn against the human tendency to destroy the very world that nurtures us—possibly foreshadowing ecological crisis long before it became a mainstream concern.    Lastly, Hopkins' use of alliteration, assonance, and rhythmical stress enhances the expressive power of his diction. Phrases such as \"strokes of havoc,\" \"fresh and following folded rank,\" and \"beauty been\" exhibit his attention to sound and musicality. These choices heighten the lyrical mournfulness of the poem and demonstrate how diction in \"Binsey Poplars\" is not merely about meaning, but also about feeling. The soundscape created by Hopkins' diction immerses the reader in both the beauty of the past and the violence of the present.    In conclusion, Gerard Manley Hopkins' diction in \"Binsey Poplars\" is a deliberate and potent instrument that conveys his deep ecological and spiritual concerns. Through inventive vocabulary, vivid imagery, emotional contrasts, and sonic beauty, Hopkins transforms a local environmental event into a profound meditation on loss, responsibility, and reverence for creation. His diction serves not just to describe nature, but to mourn it, defend it, and urge a more compassionate relationship between humanity and the natural world.", "marks": "25", "difficulty": "3"}];